on!\'94 So, Robert Wilson thought to himself, she is giving him a ride, isn\'92t she? Or do you suppose that\'92s her idea of putting up a good show? How should a woman act when she discovers her husband is a bloody coward? She\'92s damn cruel but they\'92re all cruel. They govern, of course, and to govern one has to be cruel sometimes. Still, I\'92ve seen enough of their damn terrorism. \'93Have some more eland,\'94 he said to her politely. That afternoon, late, Wilson and Macomber went out in the motor car with the native driver and the two gun-bearers. Mrs. Macomber stayed in the camp. It was too hot to go out, she said, and she was going with them in the early morning. As they drove off Wilson saw her standing under the big tree, looking pretty rather than beautiful in her faintly rosy khaki, her dark hair drawn back off her forehead and gathered in a knot low on her neck, her face as fresh, he thought, as though she were in England. She waved to them as the car went off through the swale of high grass and curved around through the trees into the small hills of orchard bush. In the orchard bush they found a herd of impala, and leaving the car they stalked one old ram with long, wide-spread horns and Macomber killed it with a very creditable shot that knocked the buck down at a good two hundred yards and sent the herd off bounding wildly and leaping over one another\'92s backs in long, leg-drawn-up leaps as unbelievable and as floating as those one makes sometimes in dreams. \'93That was a good shot,\'94 Wilson said. \'93They\'92re a small target.\'94 \'93Is it a worth-while head?\'94 Macomber asked. \'93It\'92s excellent,\'94 Wilson told him. \'93You shoot like that and you\'92ll have no trouble.\'94 \'93Do you think we\'92ll find buffalo tomorrow?\'94 \'93There\'92s a good chance of it. They feed out early in the morning and with luck we may catch them in the open.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to clear away that lion business,\'94 Macomber said. \'93It\'92s not very pleasant to have your wife see you do something like that.\'94 I should think it would be even more unpleasant to do it, Wilson thought, wife or no wife, or to talk about it having done it. But he said, \'93I wouldn\'92t think about that any more. Any one could be upset by his first lion. That\'92s all over.\'94 But that night after dinner and a whisky and soda by the fire before going to bed, as Francis Macomber lay on his cot with the mosquito bar over him and listened to the night noises it was not all over. It was neither all over nor was it beginning. It was there exactly as it happened with some parts of it indelibly emphasized and he was miserably ashamed at it. But more than shame he felt cold, hollow fear in him. The fear was still there like a cold slimy hollow in all the emptiness where once his confidence had been and it made him feel sick. It was still there with him now. It had started the night before when he had wakened and heard the lion roaring somewhere up along the river. It was a deep sound and at the end there were sort of coughing grunts that made him seem just outside the tent, and when Francis Macomber woke in the night to hear it he was afraid. He could hear his wife breathing quietly, asleep. There was no one to tell he was afraid, nor to be afraid with him, and, lying alone, he did not know the Somali proverb that says a brave man is always frightened three times by a lion; when he first sees his track, when he first hears him roar and when he first confronts him. Then while they were eating breakfast by lantern light out in the dining tent, before the sun was up, the lion roared again and Francis thought he was just at the edge of camp. \'93Sounds like an old-timer,\'94 Robert Wilson said, looking up from his kippers and coffee. \'93Listen to him cough.\'94 \'93Is he very close?\'94 \'93A mile or so up the stream.\'94 \'93Will we see him?\'94 \'93We\'92ll have a look.\'94 \'93Does his roaring carry that far? It sounds as though he were right in camp.\'94 \'93Carries a hell of a long way,\'94 said Robert Wilson. \'93It\'92s strange the way it carries. Hope he\'92s a shootable cat. The boys said there was a very big one about here.\'94 \'93If I get a shot, where should I hit him,\'94 Macomber asked, \'93to stop him?\'94 \'93In the shoulders,\'94 Wilson said. \'93In the neck if you can make it. Shoot for bone. Break him down.\'94 \'93I hope I can place it properly,\'94 Macomber said. \'93You shoot very well,\'94 Wilson told him. \'93Take your time. Make sure of him. The first one in is the one that counts.\'94 \'93What range will it be?\'94 \'93Can\'92t tell. Lion has something to say about that. Don\'92t shoot unless it\'92s close enough so you can make sure.\'94 \'93At under a hundred yards?\'94 Macomber asked. Wilson looked at him quickly. \'93Hundred\'92s about right. Might have to take him a bit under. Shouldn\'92t chance a shot at much over that. A hundred\'92s a decent range. You can hit him wherever you want at that. Here comes the Memsahib.\'94 \'93Good morning,\'94 she said. \'93Are we going after that lion?\'94 \'93As soon as you deal with your breakfast,\'94 Wilson said. \'93How are you feeling?\'94 \'93Marvellous,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92m very excited.\'94 \'93I\'92ll just go and see that everything is ready.\'94 Wilson went off. As he left the lion roared again. \'93Noisy beggar,\'94 Wilson said. \'93We\'92ll put a stop to that.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter, Francis?\'94 his wife asked him. \'93Nothing,\'94 Macomber said. \'93Yes, there is,\'94 she said. \'93What are you upset about?\'94 \'93Nothing,\'94 he said. \'93Tell me,\'94 she looked at him. \'93Don\'92t you feel well?\'94 \'93It\'92s that damned roaring,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s been going on all night, you know.\'94 \'93Why didn\'92t you wake me,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92d love to have heard it.\'94 \'93I\'92ve got to kill the damned thing,\'94 Macomber said, miserably. \'93Well, that\'92s what you\'92re out here for, isn\'92t it?\'94 \'93Yes. But I\'92m nervous. Hearing the thing roar gets on my nerves.\'94 \'93Well then, as Wilson said, kill him and stop his roaring.\'94 \'93Yes, darling,\'94 said Francis Macomber. \'93It sounds easy, doesn\'92t it?\'94 \'93You\'92re not afraid, are you?\'94 \'93Of course not. But I\'92m nervous from hearing him roar all night.\'94 \'93You\'92ll kill him marvellously,\'94 she said. \'93I know you will. I\'92m awfully anxious to see it.\'94 \'93Finish your breakfast and we\'92ll be starting.\'94 \'93It\'92s not light yet,\'94 she said. \'93This is a ridiculous hour.\'94 Just then the lion roared in a deep-chested moaning, suddenly guttural, ascending vibration that seemed to shake the air and ended in a sigh and a heavy, deep-chested grunt. \'93He sounds almost here,\'94 Macomber\'92s wife said. \'93My God,\'94 said Macomber. \'93I hate that damned noise.\'94 \'93It\'92s very impressive.\'94 \'93Impressive. It\'92s frightful.\'94 Robert Wilson came up then carrying his short, ugly, shockingly big-bored .505 Gibbs and grinning. \'93Come on,\'94 he said. \'93Your gun-bearer has your Springfield and the big gun. Everything\'92s in the car. Have you solids?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93I\'92m ready,\'94 Mrs. Macomber said. \'93Must make him stop that racket,\'94 Wilson said. \'93You get in front. The Memsahib can sit back here with me.\'94 They climbed into the motor car and, in the gray first daylight, moved off up the river through the trees. Macomber opened the breech of his rifle and saw he had metal-cased bullets, shut the bolt and put the rifle on safety. He saw his hand was trembling. He felt in his pocket for more cartridges and moved his fingers over the cartridges in the loops of his tunic front. He turned back to where Wilson sat in the rear seat of the doorless, box-bodied motor car beside his wife, them both grinning with excitement, and Wilson leaned forward and whispered, \'93See the birds dropping. Means the old boy has left his kill.\'94 On the far bank of the stream Macomber could see, above the trees, vultures circling and plummeting down. \'93Chances are he\'92ll come to drink along here,\'94 Wilson whispered. \'93Before he goes to lay up. Keep an eye out.\'94 They were driving slowly along the high bank of the stream which here cut deeply to its boulderfilled bed, and they wound in and out through big trees as they drove. Macomber was watching the opposite bank when he felt Wilson take hold of his arm. The car stopped. \'93There he is,\'94 he heard the whisper. \'93Ahead and to the right. Get out and take him. He\'92s a marvellous lion.\'94 Macomber saw the lion now. He was standing almost broadside, his great head up and turned toward them. The early morning breeze that blew toward them was just stirring his dark mane, and the lion looked huge, silhouetted on the rise of bank in the gray morning light, his shoulders heavy, his barrel of a body bulking smoothly. \'93How far is he?\'94 asked Macomber, raising his rifle. \'93About seventy-five. Get out and take him.\'94 \'93Why not shoot from where I am?\'94 \'93You don\'92t shoot them from cars,\'94 he heard Wilson saying in his ear. \'93Get out. He\'92s not going to stay there all day.\'94 Macomber stepped out of the curved opening at the side of the front seat, onto the step and down onto the ground. The lion still stood looking majestically and coolly toward this object that his eyes only showed in silhouette, bulking like some super-rhino. There was no man smell carried toward him and he watched the object, moving his great head a little from side to side. Then watching the object, not afraid, but hesitating before going down the bank to drink with such a thing opposite him, he saw a man figure detach itself from it and he turned his heavy head and swung away toward the cover of the trees as he heard a cracking crash and felt the slam of a .30-06 220-grain solid bullet that bit his flank and ripped in sudden hot scalding nausea through his stomach. He trotted