ould hide a hare. You can\'92t very well send boys in there to that sort of a show. Somebody bound to get mauled.\'94 \'93What about the gun-bearers?\'94 \'93Oh, they\'92ll go with us. It\'92s their shauri. You see, they signed on for it. They don\'92t look too happy though, do they?\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to go in there,\'94 said Macomber. It was out before he knew he\'92d said it. \'93Neither do I,\'94 said Wilson very cheerily. \'93Really no choice though.\'94 Then, as an afterthought, he glanced at Macomber and saw suddenly how he was trembling and the pitiful look on his face. \'93You don\'92t have to go in, of course,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s what I\'92m hired for, you know. That\'92s why I\'92m so expensive.\'94 \'93You mean you\'92d go in by yourself? Why not leave him there?\'94 Robert Wilson, whose entire occupation had been with the lion and the problem he presented, and who had not been thinking about Macomber except to note that he was rather windy, suddenly felt as though he had opened the wrong door in a hotel and seen something shameful. \'93What do you mean?\'94 \'93Why not just leave him?\'94 \'93You mean pretend to ourselves he hasn\'92t been hit?\'94 \'93No. Just drop it.\'94 \'93It isn\'92t done.\'94 \'93Why not?\'94 \'93For one thing, he\'92s certain to be suffering. For another, some one else might run onto him.\'94 \'93I see.\'94 \'93But you don\'92t have to have anything to do with it.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to,\'94 Macomber said. \'93I\'92m just scared, you know.\'94 \'93I\'92ll go ahead when we go in,\'94 Wilson said, \'93with Kongoni tracking. You keep behind me and a little to one side. Chances are we\'92ll hear him growl. If we see him we\'92ll both shoot. Don\'92t worry about anything. I\'92ll keep you backed up. As a matter of fact, you know, perhaps you\'92d better not go. It might be much better. Why don\'92t you go over and join the Memsahib while I just get it over with?\'94 \'93No, I want to go.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 said Wilson