u glad?\'94 \'93Yes. Now.\'94 \'93Will you go back to the States?\'94 \'93I guess so.\'94 \'93Do you want to?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Does Helen?\'94 \'93No.\'94 George sat silent. He looked at the empty bottle and the empty glasses. \'93It\'92s hell, isn\'92t it?\'94 he said. \'93No. Not exactly,\'94 Nick said. \'93Why not?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Nick said. \'93Will you ever go skiing together in the States?\'94 George said. \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said Nick. \'93The mountains aren\'92t much,\'94 George said. \'93No,\'94 said Nick. \'93They\'92re too rocky. There\'92s too much timber and they\'92re too far away.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said George, \'93that\'92s the way it is in California.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 Nick said, \'93that\'92s the way it is everywhere I\'92ve ever been.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said George, \'93that\'92s the way it is.\'94 The Swiss got up and paid and went out. \'93I wish we were Swiss,\'94 George said. \'93They\'92ve all got goiter,\'94 said Nick. \'93I don\'92t believe it,\'94 George said. \'93Neither do I,\'94 said Nick. They laughed. \'93Maybe we\'92ll never go skiing again, Nick,\'94 George said. \'93We\'92ve got to,\'94 said Nick. \'93It isn\'92t worth while if you can\'92t.\'94 \'93We\'92ll go, all right,\'94 George said. \'93We\'92ve got to,\'94 Nick agreed. \'93I wish we could make a promise about it,\'94 George said. Nick stood up. He buckled his wind jacket tight. He leaned over George and picked up the two ski poles from against the wall. He stuck one of the ski poles into the floor. \'93There isn\'92t any good in promising,\'94 he said. They opened the door and went out. It was very cold. The snow had crusted hard. The road ran up the hill into the pine trees. They took down their skis from where they leaned against the wall in the inn. Nick put on his gloves. George was already started up the road, his skis on his shoulder. Now they would have the run home together. CHAPTER XIII I heard the drums coming down the street and then the fifes and the pipes and then they came around the corner, all dancing. The street was full of them. Maera saw him and then I saw him. When they stopped the music for the crouch he hunched down in the street with them all and when they started it again he jumped up and went dancing down the street with them. He was drunk all right. You go down after him, said Maera, he hates me. So I went down and caught up with them and grabbed him while he was crouched down waiting for the music to break loose and said, Come on Luis. For Christ\'92s sake you\'92ve got bulls this afternoon. He didn\'92t listen to me, he was listening so hard for the music to start. I said, Don\'92t be a damn fool Luis. Come on back to the hotel. Then the music started up again and he jumped up and twisted away from me and started dancing. I grabbed his arm and he pulled loose and said, Oh leave me alone. You\'92re not my father. I went back to the hotel and Maera was on the balcony looking out to see if I\'92d be bringing him back. He went inside when he saw me and came downstairs disgusted. Well, I said, after all he\'92s just an ignorant Mexican savage. Yes, Maera said, and who will kill his bulls after he gets a cogida? We, I suppose, I said. Yes, we, said Maera. We kills the savages \'92 bulls, and the drunkards\'92 bulls, and the riau-riau dancers\'92 bulls. Yes. We kill them. We kill them all right. Yes. Yes. Yes. My Old Man I GUESS LOOKING AT IT, NOW, MY OLD man was cut out for a fat guy, one of those regular little roly fat guys you see around, but he sure never got that way, except a little toward the last, and then it wasn\'92t his fault, he was riding over the jumps only and he could afford to carry plenty of weight then. I remember the way he\'92d pull on a rubber shirt over a couple of jerseys and a big sweat shirt over that, and get me to run with him in the forenoon in the hot sun. He\'92d have, maybe, taken a trial trip with one of Razzo\'92s skins early in the morning after just getting in from Torino at four o\'92clock in the morning and beating it out to the stables in a cab and then with the dew all over everything and the sun just starting to get going, I\'92d help him pull off his boots and he\'92d get into a pair of sneakers and all these sweaters and we\'92d start out. \'93Come on, kid,\'94 he\'92d say, stepping up and down on his toes in front of the jock\'92s dressing room, \'93let\'92s get moving.\'94 Then we\'92d start off jogging around the infield once, maybe, with him ahead, running nice, and then turn out the gate and along one of those roads with all the trees along both sides of them that run out from San Siro. I\'92d go ahead of him when we hit the road and I could run pretty good and I\'92d look around and he\'92d be jogging easy just behind me and after a little while I\'92d look around again and he\'92d begun to sweat. Sweating heavy and he\'92d just be dogging it along with his eyes on my back, but when he\'92d catch me looking at him he\'92d grin and say, \'93Sweating plenty?\'94 When my old man grinned, nobody could help but grin too. We\'92d keep right on running out toward the mountains and then my old man would yell, \'93Hey, Joe!\'94 and I\'92d look back and he\'92d be sitting under a tree with a towel he\'92d had around his waist wrapped around his neck. I\'92d come back and sit down beside him and he\'92d pull a rope out of his pocket and start skipping rope out in the sun with the sweat pouring off his face and him skipping rope out in the white dust with the rope going cloppetty, cloppetty, clop, clop, clop, and the sun hotter, and him working harder up and down a patch of the road. Say, it was a treat to see my old man skip rope, too. He could whirr it fast or lop it slow and fancy. Say, you ought to have seen wops look at us sometimes, when they\'92d come by, going into town walking along with big white steers hauling the cart. They sure looked as though they thought the old man was nuts. He\'92d start the rope whirring till they\'92d stop dead still and watch him, then give the steers a cluck and a poke with the goad and get going again. When I\'92d sit watching him working out in the hot sun I sure felt fond of him. He sure was fun and he done his work so hard and he\'92d finish up with a regular whirring that\'92d drive the sweat out on his face like water and then sling the rope at the tree and come over and sit down with me and lean back against the tree with the towel and a sweater wrapped around his neck. \'93Sure is hell keeping it down, Joe,\'94 he\'92d say and lean back and shut his eyes and breathe long and deep, \'93it ain\'92t like when you\'92re a kid.\'94 Then he\'92d get up and before he started to cool we\'92d jog along back to the stables. That\'92s the way it was keeping down to weight. He was worried all the time. Most jocks can just about ride off all they want to. A jock loses about a kilo every time he rides, but my old man was sort of dried out and he couldn\'92t keep down his kilos without all that running. I remember once at San Siro, Regoli, a little wop, that was riding for Buzoni, came out across the paddock going to the bar for something cool; and flicking his boots with his whip, after he\'92d just weighed in and my old man had just weighed in too, and came out with the saddle under his arm looking red-faced and tired and too big for his silks and he stood there looking at young Regoli standing up to the outdoors bar, cool and kid-looking, and I said, \'93What\'92s the matter, Dad?\'94 cause I thought maybe Regoli had bumped him or something and he just looked at Regoli and said, \'93Oh, to hell with it,\'94 and went on to the dressing room. Well, it would have been all right, maybe, if we\'92d stayed in Milan and ridden at Milan and Torino/cause if there ever were any easy courses, it\'92s those two. \'93Pianola, Joe,\'94 my old man said when he dismounted in the winning stall after what the wops thought was a hell of a steeplechase. I asked him once. \'93This course rides itself. It\'92s the pace you\'92re going at, that makes riding the jumps dangerous, Joe. We ain\'92t going any pace here, and they ain\'92t really bad jumps either. But it\'92s the pace always\'97not the jumps\'97that makes the trouble.\'94 San Siro was the swellest course I\'92d ever seen but the old man said it was a dog\'92s life. Going back and forth between Mirafiore and San Siro and riding just about every day in the week with a train ride every other night. I was nuts about the horses, too. There\'92s something about it, when they come out and go up the track to the post. Sort of dancy and tight looking with the jock keeping a tight hold on them and maybe easing off a little and letting them run a little going up. Then once they were at the barrier it got me worse than anything. Especially at San Siro with that big green infield and the mountains way off and the fat wop starter with his big whip and the jocks fiddling them around and then the barrier snapping up and that bell going off and them all getting off in a bunch and then commencing to string out. You know the way a bunch of skins gets off. If you\'92re up in the stand with a pair of glasses all you see is them plunging off and then that bell goes off and it seems like it rings for a thousand years and then they come sweeping round the turn. There wasn\'92t ever anything like it for me. But my old man said one day, in the dressing room, when he was getting into his street clothes, \'93None of these things are horses, Joe. They\'92d kill that bunch of skates for their hides and hoofs up at Paris.\'94 That was the day he\'92d won the Premio Commercio with Lantorna shooting her out of the field the last hundred meters like pulling a cork out of a bottle. It was right after the Premio Commercio that we pulled out and left Italy. My old man and Holbrook and a fat wop in a straw hat that kept wiping his face with a handkerchief were having an argument at a table in the Galleria. They were all talking French and the two of them was after my old man about something. Finally he didn\'92t say anything any more but just sat there and looked at Holbrook, and the two of them kept after him, first one talking and then the other, and the fat wop always butting in on Holbrook. \'93You go out and buy me a Sportsman, will you, Joe?\'94 my old man said, and handed me a couple of soldi without looking away from Holbrook. So I went out of the Galleria and walked over to in front of the Scala and bought a paper, and came back and stood a little way away because I didn\'92t want to butt in and my old man was sitting back in his chair looking down at his coffee and fooling with a spoon and Holbrook and the big wop were standing and the big wop was wiping his face and shaking his head. And I came up and my old man acted just as though the two of them weren\'92t standing there and said, \'93Want an ice, Joe?\'94 Holbrook looked down at my old man and said slow and careful, \'93You son of a bitch,\'94 and he and the fat wop went out through the tables. My old man sat there and son of smiled at me, but his face was white and he looked sick as hell and I was scared and felt sick inside because I knew something had happened and I didn\'92t see how anybody could call my old man a son of a bitch, and get away with it. My old man opened up the Sportsman and studied the handicaps for a while and then he said, \'93You got to take a lot of things in this world, Joe.\'94 And three days later we left Milan for good on the Turin train for Paris, after an auction sale out in front of Turner\'92s stables of everything we couldn\'92t get into a trunk and a suit case. We got into Paris early in the morning in a long, dirty station the old man told me was the Gare de Lyon. Paris was an awful big town after Milan. Seems like in Milan everybody is going somewhere and all the trams run somewhere and there ain\'92t any sort of a mix-up, but Paris is all balled up and they never do straighten it out. I got to like it, though, part of it, anyway, and say, it\'92s got the best race courses in the world. Seems as though that were the thing that keeps it all going and about the only thing you can figure on is that every day the buses will be going out to whatever track they\'92re running at, going right out through everything to the track. I never really got to know Paris well, because I just came in about once or twice a week with the old man from Maisons and he always sat at the Caf\'e9 de la Paix on the Opera side with the rest of the gang from Maisons and I guess that\'92s one of the busiest parts of the town. But, say, it is funny that a big town like Paris wouldn\'92t have a Galleria, isn\'92t it? Well, we went out to live at Maisons-Lafitte, where just about everybody lives except the gang at Chantilly, with a Mrs. Meyers that runs a boarding house. Maisons is about the swellest place to live I\'92ve ever seen in all my life. The town ain\'92t so much, but there\'92s a lake and a swell forest that we used to go off bumming in all day, a couple of us kids, and my old man made me a sling shot and we got a lot of things with it but the best one was a magpie. Young Dick Atkinson shot a rabbit with it one day and we put it under a tree and were all sitting around and Dick had some cigarettes and all of a sudden the rabbit jumped up and beat it into the brush and we chased it but we couldn\'92t find it. Gee, we had fun at Maisons. Mrs. Meyers used to give me lunch in the morning and I\'92d be gone all day. I learned to talk French quick. It\'92s an easy language. As soon as we got to Maisons, my old man wrote to Milan for his license and he was pretty worried till it came. He used to sit around the Caf\'e9 de Paris in Maisons with the gang, there were lots of guys he\'92d known when he rode up at Paris, before the war, lived at Maisons, and there\'92s a lot of time to sit around because the work around a racing stable, for the jocks, that is, is all cleaned up by nine o\'92clock in the morning. They take the first bunch of skins out to gallop them at 5:30 in the morning and they work the second lot at 8 o\'92clock. That means getting up early all right and going to bed early, too. If a jock\'92s riding for somebody too, he can\'92t go boozing around because the trainer always has an eye on him if he\'92s a kid and if he ain\'92t a kid he\'92s always got an eye on himself. So mostly if a jock ain\'92t working he sits around the Caf\'e9 de Paris with the gang and they can all sit around about two or three hours in front of some drink like a vermouth and seltz and they talk and tell stories and shoot pool and it\'92s sort of like a club or the Galleria in Milan. Only it ain\'92t really like the Galleria because there everybody is going by all the time and there\'92s everybody around at the tables. Well, my old man got his license all right. They sent it through to him without a word and he rode a couple of times. Amiens, up country and that sort of thing, but he didn\'92t seem to get any engagement. Everybody liked him and whenever I\'92d come into the Caf\'e9 in the forenoon I\'92d find somebody drinking with him because my old man wasn\'92t tight like most of these jockeys that have got the first dollar they made riding at the World\'92s Fair in St. Louis in nineteen ought four. That\'92s what my old man would say when he\'92d kid George Burns. But it seemed like everybody steered clear of giving my old man any mounts. We went out to wherever they were runnning every day with the car from Maisons and that was the most fun of all. I was glad when the horses came back from Deauville and the summer. Even though it meant no more bumming in the woods,\'92cause then we\'92d ride to Enghien or Tremblay or St. Cloud and watch them from the trainers\'92 and jockeys\'92 stand. I sure learned about racing from going out with that gang and the fun of it was going every day. I remember once out at St. Cloud. It was a big two hundred thousand franc race with seven entries and Kzar a big favorite. I went around to the paddock to see the horses with my old man and you never saw such horses. This Kzar is a great big yellow horse that looks like just nothing but run. I never saw such a horse. He was being led around the paddocks with his head down and when he went by me I felt all hollow inside he was so beautiful. There never was such a wonderful, lean, running built horse. And he went around the paddock putting his feet just so and quiet and careful and moving easy like he knew just what he had to do and not jerking and standing up on his legs and getting wild eyed like you see these selling platers with a shot of dope in them. The crowd was so thick I couldn\'92t see him again except just his legs going by and some yellow and my old man started out through the crowd and I followed him over to the jock\'92s dressing room back in the trees and there was a big crowd around there, too, but the man at the door in a derby nodded to my old man and we got in and everybody was sitting around and getting dressed and pulling shirts over their heads and pulling boots on and it all smelled hot and sweaty and linimenty and outside was the crowd looking in. The old man went over and sat down beside George Gardner that was getting into his pants and said, \'93What\'92s the dope, George?\'94 just in an ordinary tone of voice \'92cause there ain\'92t any use him feeling around because George either can tell him or he can\'92t tell him. \'93He won\'92t win,\'94 George says very low, leaning over and buttoning the bottoms of his breeches. \'93Who will?\'94 my old man says, leaning over close so nobody can hear. \'93Kircubbin,\'94 George says, \'93and if he does, save me a couple of tickets.\'94 My old man says something in a regular voice to George and George says, \'93Don\'92t ever bet on anything I tell you,\'94 kidding like, and we beat it out and through all the crowd that was looking in, over to the 100 franc mutuel machine. But I knew something big was up because George is Kzar\'92s jockey. On the way he gets one of the yellow odds-sheets with the starting prices on and Kzar is only paying 5 for 10, Cefisidote is next at 3 to 1 and fifth down the list this Kircubbin at 8 to 1. My old man bets five thousand on Kircubbin to win and puts on a thousand to place and we went around back of the grandstand to go up the stairs and get a place to watch the race. We were jammed in tight and first a man in a long coat with a gray tall hat and a whip folded up in his hand came out and then one after another the horses, with the jocks up and a stable boy holding the bridle on each side and walking along, followed the old guy. That big yellow horse Kzar came first. He didn\'92t look so big when you first looked at him until you saw the length of his legs and the whole way he\'92s built and the way he moves. Gosh, I never saw such a horse. George Gardner was riding him and they moved along slow, back of the old guy in the gray tall hat that walked along like he was a ring master in a circus. Back of Kzar, moving along smooth and yellow in the sun, was a good looking black with a nice head with Tommy Archibald riding him; and after the black was a string of five more horses all moving along slow in a procession past the grandstand and the pesage. My old man said the black was Kircubbin and I took a good look at him and he was a nice-looking horse, all right, but nothing like Kzar. Everybody cheered Kzar when he went by and he sure was one swell-looking horse. The procession of them went around on the other side past the pelouse and then back up to the near end of the course and the circus master had the stable boys turn them loose one after another so they could gallop by the stands on their way up to the post and let everybody have a good look at them. They weren\'92t at the post hardly any time at all when the gong started and you could see them way off across the infield all in a bunch starting on the first swing like a lot of little toy horses. I was watching them through the glasses and Kzar was running well back, with one of the bays making the pace. They swept down and around and came pounding past and Kzar was way back when they passed us and this Kircubbin horse in front and going smooth. Gee, it\'92s awful when they go by you and then you have to watch them go farther away and get smaller and smaller and then all bunched up on the turns and then come around towards into the stretch and you feel like swearing and god-damming worse and worse. Finally they made the last turn and came into the straightaway with this Kircubbin horse way out in front. Everybody was looking funny and saying \'93Kzar\'94 in sort of a sick way and them pounding nearer down the stretch, and then something came out of the pack right into my glasses like a horseheaded yellow streak and everybody began to yell \'93Kzar\'94 as though they were crazy. Kzar came on faster than I\'92d ever seen anything in my life and pulled up on Kircubbin that was going fast as any black horse could go with the jock flogging hell out of him with the gad and they were right dead neck and neck for a second but Kzar seemed going about twice as fast with those great jumps and that head out\'97but it was while they were neck and neck that they passed the winning post and when the numbers went up in the slots the first one was 2 and that meant that Kircubbin had won. I felt all trembly and funny inside, and then we were all jammed in with the people going downstairs to stand in front of the board where they\'92d post what Kircubbin paid. Honest, watching the race I\'92d forgot how much my old man had bet on Kircubbin. I\'92d wanted Kzar to win so damned bad. But now it was all over it was swell to know we had the winner. \'93Wasn\'92t it a swell race. Dad?\'94 I said to him. He looked at me sort of funny with his derby on the back of his head. \'93George Gardner\'92s a swell jockey, all right,\'94 he said. \'93It sure took a great jock to keep that Kzar horse from winning.\'94 Of course I knew it was funny all the time. But my old man saying that right out like that sure took the kick all out of it for me and I didn\'92t get the real kick back again ever, even when they posted the numbers upon the board and the bell rang to pay off and we saw that Kircubbin paid 67.50 for 10. All round people were saying, \'93Poor Kzar! Poor Kzar!\'94 And I thought, I wish I were a jockey and could have rode him instead of that son of a bitch. And that was funny, thinking of George Gardner as a son of a bitch because I\'92d always liked him and besides he\'92d given us the winner, but I guess that\'92s what he is, all right. My old man had a big lot of money after that race and he took to coming into Paris oftener. If they raced at Tremblay he\'92d have them drop him in town on their way back to Maisons and he and I\'92d sit out in front of the Caf\'e9 de la Paix and watch the people go by. It\'92s funny sitting there. There\'92s streams of people going by and all sorts of guys come up and want to sell you things, and I loved to sit there with my old man. That was when we\'92d have the most fun. Guys would come by selling funny rabbits that jumped if you squeezed a bulb and they\'92d come up to us and my old man would kid with them. He could talk French just like English and all those kind of guys knew him \'92cause you can always tell a jockey\'97and then we always sat at the same table and they got used to seeing us there. There were guys selling matrimonial papers and girls selling rubber eggs that when you squeezed them a rooster came out of them and one old wormy-looking guy that went by with post-cards of Paris, showing them to everybody, and, of course, nobody ever bought any, and then he would come back and show the under side of the pack and they would all be smutty postcards and lots of people would dig down and buy them. Gee, I remember the funny 