really an awfully simple operation, Jig,\'94 the man said. \'93It\'92s not really an operation at all.\'94 The girl looked at the ground the table legs rested on. \'93I know you wouldn\'92t mind it. Jig. It\'92s really not anything. It\'92s just to let the air in.\'94 The girl did not say anything. \'93I\'92ll go with you and I\'92ll stay with you all the time. They just let the air in and then it\'92s all perfectly natural.\'94 \'93Then what will we do afterward?\'94 \'93We\'92ll be fine afterward. Just like we were before.\'94 \'93What makes you think so?\'94 \'93That\'92s the only thing that bothers us. It\'92s the only thing that\'92s made us unhappy.\'94 The girl looked at the bead curtain, put her hand out and took hold of two of the strings of beads. \'93And you think then we\'92ll be all right and be happy.\'94 \'93I know we will. You don\'92t have to be afraid. I\'92ve known lots of people that have done it.\'94 \'93So have I,\'94 said the girl. \'93And afterward they were all so happy.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 the man said, \'93if you don\'92t want to you don\'92t have to. I wouldn\'92t have you do it if you didn\'92t want to. But I know it\'92s perfectly simple.\'94 \'93And you really want to?\'94 \'93I think it\'92s the best thing to do. But I don\'92t want you to do it if you don\'92t really want to.\'94 \'93And if I do it you\'92ll be happy and things will be like they were and you\'92ll love me?\'94 \'93I love you now. You know I love you.\'94 \'93I know. But if I do it, then it will be nice again if I say things are like white elephants, and you\'92ll like it?\'94 \'93I\'92ll love it. I love it now but I just can\'92t think about it. You know how I get when I worry.\'94 \'93If I do it you won\'92t ever worry?\'94 \'93I won\'92t worry about that because it\'92s perfectly simple.\'94 \'93Then I\'92ll do it. Because I don\'92t care about me.\'94 \'93What do you mean?\'94 \'93I don\'92t care about me.\'94 \'93Well, I care about you.\'94 \'93Oh, yes. But I don\'92t care about me. And I\'92ll do it and then everything will be fine.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want you to do it if you feel that way.\'94 The girl stood up and walked to the end of the station. Across, on the other side, were fields of grain and trees along the banks of the Ebro. Far away, beyond the river, were mountains. The shadow of a cloud moved across the field of grain and she saw the river through the trees. \'93And we could have all this,\'94 she said. \'93And we could have everything and every day we make it more impossible.\'94 \'93What did you say?\'94 \'93I said we could have everything.\'94 \'93We can have everything.\'94 \'93No, we can\'92t.\'94 \'93We can have the whole world.\'94 \'93No, we can\'92t.\'94 \'93We can go everywhere.\'94 \'93No, we can\'92t. It isn\'92t ours any more.\'94 \'93It\'92s ours.\'94 \'93No, it isn\'92t. And once they take it away, you never get it back.\'94 \'93But they haven\'92t taken it away.\'94 \'93We\'92ll wait and see.\'94 \'93Come on back in the shade,\'94 he said. \'93You mustn\'92t feel that way.\'94 \'93I don\'92t feel any way,\'94 the girl said. \'93I just know things.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want you to do anything that you don\'92t want to do\'97\'94 \'93Nor that isn\'92t good for me,\'94 she said. \'93I know. Could we have another beer?\'94 \'93All right. But you\'92ve got to realize\'97\'94 \'93I realize,\'94 the girl said. \'93Can\'92t we maybe stop talking?\'94 They sat down at the table and the girl looked across at the hills on the dry side of the valley and the man looked at her and at the table. \'93You\'92ve got to realize,\'94 he said, \'93that I don\'92t want you to do it if you don\'92t want to. I\'92m perfectly willing to go through with it if it means anything to you.\'94 \'93Doesn\'92t it mean anything to you? We could get along.\'94 \'93Of course it does. But I don\'92t want anybody but you. I don\'92t want any one else. And I know it\'92s perfectly simple.\'94 \'93Yes, you know it\'92s perfectly simple.\'94 \'93It\'92s all right for you to say that, but I do know it.\'94 \'93Would you do something for me now?\'94 \'93I\'92d do anything for you.\'94 \'93Would you please please please please please please please stop talking?\'94 He did not say anything but looked at the bags against the wall of the station. There were labels on them from all the hotels where they had spent nights. \'93But I don\'92t want you to,\'94 he said, \'93I don\'92t care anything about it.\'94 \'93I\'92ll scream,\'94 the girl said. The woman came out through the curtains with two glasses of beer and put them down on the damp felt pads. \'93The train comes in five minutes,\'94 she said. \'93What did she say?\'94 asked the girl. \'93That the train is coming in five minutes.\'94 The girl smiled brightly at the woman, to thank her. \'93I\'92d better take the bags over to the other side of the station,\'94 the man said. She smiled at him. \'93All right. Then come back and we\'92ll finish the beer.\'94 He picked up the two heavy bags and carried them around the station to the other tracks. He looked up the tracks but could not see the train. Coming back, he walked through the barroom, where people waiting for the train were drinking. He drank an Anis at the bar and looked at the people. They were all waiting reasonably for the train. He went out through the bead curtain. She was sitting at the table and smiled at him. \'93Do you feel better?\'94 he asked. \'93I feel fine,\'94 she said. \'93There\'92s nothing wrong with me. I feel fine.\'94 The Killers THE DOOR OF HENRY\'92S LUNCH-ROOM opened and two men came in. They sat down at the counter. \'93What\'92s yours?\'94 George asked them. \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 one of the men said. \'93What do you want to eat, Al?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said Al. \'93I don\'92t know what I want to eat.\'94 Outside it was getting dark. The street-light came on outside the window. The two men at the counter read the menu. From the other end of the counter Nick Adams watched them. He had been talking to George when they came in. \'93I\'92ll have a roast pork tenderloin with apple sauce and mashed potatoes,\'94 the first man said. \'93It isn\'92t ready yet.\'94 \'93What the hell do you put it on the card for?\'94 \'93That\'92s the dinner,\'94 George explained. \'93You can get that at six o\'92clock.\'94 George looked at the clock on the wall behind the counter. \'93It\'92s five o\'92clock.\'94 \'93The clock says twenty minutes past five,\'94 the second man said. \'93It\'92s twenty minutes fast.\'94 \'93Oh, to hell with the clock,\'94 the first man said. \'93What have you got to eat?\'94 \'93I can give you any kind of sandwiches,\'94 George said. \'93You can have ham and eggs, bacon and eggs, liver and bacon, or a steak.\'94 \'93Give me chicken croquettes with green peas and cream sauce and mashed potatoes.\'94 \'93That\'92s the dinner.\'94 \'93Everything we want\'92s the dinner, eh? That\'92s the way you work it.\'94 \'93I can give you ham and eggs, bacon and eggs, liver\'97\'94 \'93I\'92ll take ham and eggs,\'94 the man called Al said. He wore a derby hat and a black overcoat buttoned across the chest. His face was small and white and he had tight lips. He wore a silk muffler and gloves. \'93Give me bacon and eggs,\'94 said the other man. He was about the same size as Al. Their faces were different, but they were dressed like twins. Both wore overcoats too tight for them. They sat leaning forward, their elbows on the counter. \'93Got anything to drink?\'94 Al asked. \'93Silver beer, bevo, ginger-ale,\'94 George said. \'93I mean you got anything to drink?\'94 \'93Just those I said.\'94 \'93This is a hot town,\'94 said the other. \'93What do they call it?\'94 \'93Summit.\'94 \'93Ever hear of it?\'94 Al asked his friend. \'93No,\'94 said the friend. \'93What do you do here nights?\'94 Al asked. \'93They eat the dinner,\'94 his friend said. \'93They all come here and eat the big dinner.\'94 \'93That\'92s right,\'94 George said. \'93So you think that\'92s right?\'94 Al asked George. \'93Sure.\'94 \'93You\'92re a pretty bright boy, aren\'92t you?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said George. \'93Well, you\'92re not,\'94 said the other little man. \'93Is he, Al?\'94 \'93He\'92s dumb,\'94 said Al. He turned to Nick. \'93What\'92s your name?\'94 \'93Adams.\'94 \'93Another bright boy,\'94 Al said. \'93Ain\'92t he a bright boy, Max?\'94 \'93The town\'92s full of bright boys,\'94 Max said. George put the two platters, one of ham and eggs, the other of bacon and eggs, on the counter. He set down two side-dishes of fried potatoes and closed the wicket into the kitchen. \'93Which is yours?\'94 he asked Al. \'93Don\'92t you remember?\'94 \'93Ham and eggs.\'94 \'93Just a bright boy,\'94 Max said. He leaned forward and took the ham and eggs. Both men ate with their gloves on. George watched them eat. \'93What are you looking it?\'94 Max looked at George. \'93Nothing.\'94 \'93The hell you were. You were looking at me.\'94 \'93Maybe the boy meant it for a joke, Max,\'94 Al said. George laughed. \'93You don\'92t have to laugh,\'94 Max said to him. \'93You don\'92t have to laugh at all, see?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 said George. \'93So he thinks it\'92s all right.\'94 Max turned to Al. \'93He thinks it\'92s all right. That\'92s a good one.\'94 \'93Oh, he\'92s a thinker,\'94 Al said. They went on eating. \'93What\'92s the bright boy\'92s name down the counter?\'94 Al asked Max. \'93Hey, bright boy,\'94 Max said to Nick. \'93You go around on the other side of the counter with your boy friend.\'94 \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 Nick asked. \'93There isn\'92t any idea.\'94 \'93You better go around, bright boy,\'94 Al said. Nick went around behind the counter. \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 George asked. \'93None of your damn business,\'94 Al said. \'93Who\'92s out in the kitchen?\'94 \'93The nigger.\'94 \'93What do you mean the nigger?\'94 \'93The nigger that cooks.\'94 \'93Tell him to come in.\'94 \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 \'93Tell him to come in.\'94 \'93Where do you think you are?\'94 \'93We know damn well where we are,\'94 the man called Max said. \'93Do we look silly?\'94 \'93You talk silly,\'94 Al said to him. \'93What the hell do you argue with this kid for? Listen,\'94 he said to George, \'93tell the nigger to come out here.\'94 \'93What are you going to do to him?\'94 \'93Nothing. Use your head, bright boy. What would we do to a nigger?\'94 George opened the slit that opened back into the kitchen. \'93Sam,\'94 he called. \'93Come in here a minute.\'94 The door to the kitchen opened and the nigger came in. \'93What was it?\'94 he asked. The two men at the counter took a look at him. \'93All right, nigger. You stand right there,\'94 Al said. Sam, the nigger, standing in his apron, looked at the two men sitting at the counter. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 he said. Al got down from his stool. \'93I\'92m going back to the kitchen with the nigger and bright boy,\'94 he said. \'93Go on back to the kitchen, nigger. You go with him, bright boy.\'94 The little man walked after Nick and Sam, the cook, back into the kitchen. The door shut after them. The man called Max sat at the counter opposite George. He didn\'92t look at George but looked in the mirror that ran along back of the counter. Henry\'92s had been made over from a saloon into a lunch-counter. \'93Well, bright boy,\'94 Max said, looking into the mirror, \'93why don\'92t you say something?\'94 \'93What\'92s it all about?\'94 \'93Hey, Al,\'94 Max called, \'93bright boy wants to know what it\'92s all about.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you tell him?\'94 Al\'92s voice came from the kitchen. \'93What do you think it\'92s all about?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know.\'94 \'93What do you think?\'94 Max looked into the mirror all the time he was talking. \'93I wouldn\'92t say.\'94 \'93Hey, Al, bright boy says he wouldn\'92t say what he thinks it\'92s all about.\'94 \'93I can hear you, all right,\'94 Al said from the kitchen. He had propped open the slit that dishes passed through into the kitchen with a catsup bottle. \'93Listen, bright boy,\'94 he said from the kitchen to George. \'93Stand a little further along the bar. You move a little to the left. Max.\'94 He was like a photographer arranging for a group picture. \'93Talk to me, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93What do you trunk\'92s going to happen?\'94 George did not say anything. \'93I\'92ll tell you,\'94 Max said. \'93We\'92re going to kill a Swede. Do you know a big Swede named Ole Andreson?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93He comes here to eat every night, don\'92t he?\'94 \'93Sometimes he comes here.\'94 \'93He comes here at six o\'92clock, don\'92t he?\'94 \'93If he comes.\'94 \'93We know all that, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93Talk about something else. Ever go to the movies?\'94 \'93Once in a while.\'94 \'93You ought to go to the movies more. The movies are fine for a bright boy like you.\'94 \'93What are you going to kill Ole Andreson for? What did he ever do to you?\'94 \'93He never had a chance to do anything to us. He never even seen us.\'94 \'93And he\'92s only going to see us once,\'94 Al said from the kitchen. \'93What are you going to kill him for, then?\'94 George asked. \'93We\'92re killing him for a friend. Just to oblige a friend, bright boy.\'94 \'93Shut up,\'94 said Al from the kitchen. \'93You talk too goddam much.\'94 \'93Well, I got to keep bright boy amused. Don\'92t I, bright boy?\'94 \'93You talk too damn much,\'94 Al said. \'93The nigger and my bright boy are amused by themselves. I got them tied up like a couple of girl friends in the convent.\'94 \'93I suppose you were in a convent?\'94 \'93You never know.\'94 \'93You were in a kosher convent. That\'92s where you were.\'94 George looked up at the clock. \'93If anybody comes in you tell them the cook is off, and if they keep after it, you tell them you\'92ll go back and cook yourself. Do you get that, bright boy?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 George said. \'93What you going to do with us afterward?\'94 \'93That\'92ll depend,\'94 Max said. \'93That\'92s one of those things you never know at the time.\'94 George looked up at the clock. It was a quarter past six. The door from the street opened. A street-car motorman came in. \'93Hello, George,\'94 he said. \'93Can I get supper?\'94 \'93Sam\'92s gone out,\'94 George said. \'93He\'92ll be back in about half an hour.\'94 \'93I\'92d better go up the street,\'94 the motorman said. George looked at the clock. It was twenty minutes past six. \'93That was nice, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93You\'92re a regular little gentleman.\'94 \'93He knew I\'92d blow his head off,\'94 Al said from the kitchen. \'93No,\'94 said Max. \'93It ain\'92t that. Bright boy is nice. He\'92s a nice boy. I like him.\'94 At six-fifty-five George said: \'93He\'92s not coming.\'94 Two other people had been in the lunch-room. Once George had gone out to the kitchen and made a ham-and-egg sandwich \'93to go\'94 that a man wanted to take with him. Inside the kitchen he saw Al, his derby hat tipped back, sitting on a stool beside the wicket with the muzzle of a sawed-off shotgun resting on the ledge. Nick and the cook were back to back in the corner, a towel tied in each of their mouths. George had cooked the sandwich, wrapped it up in oiled paper, put it in a bag, brought it in, and the man had paid for it and gone out. \'93Bright boy can do everything,\'94 Max said. \'93He can cook and everything. You\'92d make some girl a nice wife, bright boy.\'94 \'93Yes?\'94 George said. \'93Your friend, Ole Andreson, isn\'92t going to come.\'94 \'93We\'92ll give him ten minutes,\'94 Max said. Max watched the mirror and the clock. The hands of the clock marked seven o\'92clock, and then five minutes past seven. \'93Come on, Al,\'94 said Max. \'93We better go. He\'92s not coming.\'94 \'93Better give him five minutes,\'94 Al said from the kitchen. In the five minutes a man came in, and George explained that the cook was sick. \'93Why the hell don\'92t you get another cook?\'94 the man asked. \'93Aren\'92t you running a lunch-counter?\'94 He went out. \'93Come on, Al,\'94 Max said. \'93What about the two bright boys and the nigger?\'94 \'93They\'92re all right.\'94 \'93You think so?\'94 \'93Sure. We\'92re through with it.\'94 \'93I don\'92t like it,\'94 said Al. \'93It\'92s sloppy. You talk too much.\'94 \'93Oh, what the hell,\'94 said Max. \'93We got to keep amused, haven\'92t we?\'94 \'93You talk too much, all the same,\'94 Al said. He came out from the kitchen. The cutoff barrels of the shotgun made a slight bulge under the waist of his too tight-fitting overcoat. He straightened his coat with his gloved hands. \'93So long, bright boy,\'94 he said to George. \'93You got a lot of luck.\'94 \'93That\'92s the truth,\'94 Max said. \'93You ought to play the races, bright boy.\'94 The two of them went out the door. George watched them, through the window, pass under the arc-light and cross the street. In their tight overcoats and derby hats they looked like a vaudeville team. George went back through the swinging-door into the kitchen and untied Nick and the cook. \'93I don\'92t want any more of that,\'94 said Sam, the cook. \'93I don\'92t want any more of that.\'94 Nick stood up. He had never had a towel in his mouth before. \'93Say,\'94 he said. \'93What the hell?\'94 He was trying to swagger it off. \'93They were going to kill Ole Andreson,\'94 George said. \'93They were going to shoot him when he came in to eat.\'94 \'93Ole Andreson?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 The cook felt the corners of his mouth with his thumbs. \'93They all gone?\'94 he asked. \'93Yeah,\'94 said George. \'93They\'92re gone now.\'94 \'93I don\'92t like it,\'94 said the cook. \'93I don\'92t like any of it at all.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 George said to Nick. \'93You better go see Ole Andreson.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 \'93You better not have anything to do with it at all,\'94 Sam, the cook, said. \'93You better stay way out of it.\'94 \'93Don\'92t go if you don\'92t want to,\'94 George said. \'93Mixing up in this ain\'92t going to get you anywhere,\'94 the cook said. \'93You stay out of it.\'94 \'93I\'92ll go see him,\'94 Nick said to George. \'93Where does he live?\'94 The cook turned away. \'93Little boys always know what they want to do,\'94 he said. \'93He lives up at Hirsch\'92s rooming-house,\'94 George said to Nick. \'93I\'92ll go up there.\'94 Outside the arc-light shone through the bare branches of a tree. Nick walked up the street beside the car-tracks and turned at the next arc-light down a side-street. Three houses up the street was Hirsch\'92s rooming-house. Nick walked up the two steps and pushed the bell. A woman came to the door. \'93Is Ole Andreson here?\'94 \'93Do you want to see him?\'94 \'93Yes, if he\'92s in.\'94 Nick followed the woman up a flight of stairs and back to the end of a corridor. She knocked on the door. \'93Who is it?\'94 \'93It\'92s somebody to see you, Mr. Andreson,\'94 the woman said. \'93It\'92s Nick Adams.\'94 \'93Come in.\'94 Nick opened the door and went into the room. Ole Andreson was lying on the bed with all his clothes on. He had been a heavyweight prizefighter and he was too long for the bed. He lay with his head on two pillows. He did not look at Nick. \'93What was it?\'94 he asked. \'93I was up at Henry\'92s,\'94 Nick said, \'93and two fellows came in and tied up me and the cook, and they said they were going to kill you.\'94 It sounded silly when he said it. Ole Andreson said nothing. \'93They put us out in the kitchen,\'94 Nick went on. \'93They were going to shoot you when you came in to supper.\'94 Ole Andreson looked at the wall and did not say anything. \'93George thought I better come and tell you about it.\'94 \'93There isn\'92t anything I can do about it,\'94 Ole Andreson said. \'93I\'92ll tell you what they were like.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to know what they were like,\'94 Ole Andreson said. He looked at the wall. \'93Thanks for coming to tell me about it.\'94 \'93That\'92s all right.\'94 Nick looked at the big man lying on the bed. \'93Don\'92t you want me to go and see the police?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Ole Andreson said. \'93That wouldn\'92t do any good.\'94 \'93Isn\'92t there something I could do?\'94 \'93No. There ain\'92t anything to do.\'94 \'93Maybe it was just a bluff.\'94 \'93No. It ain\'92t just a bluff.\'94 Ole Andreson rolled over toward the wall. \'93The only thing is,\'94 he said, talking toward the wall, \'93I just can\'92t make up my mind to go out. I been in here all day.\'94 \'93Couldn\'92t you get out of town?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Ole Andreson said. \'93I\'92m through with all that running around.\'94 He looked at the wall. \'93There ain\'92t anything to do now.\'94 \'93Couldn\'92t you fix it up some way?\'94 \'93No. I got in wrong.\'94 He talked in the same flat voice. \'93There ain\'92t anything to do. After a while I\'92ll make up my mind to go out.\'94 \'93I better go back and see George,\'94 Nick said. \'93So long,\'94 said Ole Andreson. He did not look toward Nick. \'93Thanks for coming around.\'94 Nick went out. As he shut the door he saw Ole Andreson with all his clothes on, lying on the bed looking at the wall. \'93He\'92s been in his room all day,\'94 the landlady said down-stairs. \'93I guess he don\'92t feel well. I said to him: \'91Mr. Andreson, you ought to go out and take a walk on a nice fall day like this,\'92 but he didn\'92t feel like it.\'94 \'93He doesn\'92t want to go out.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry he don\'92t feel well,\'94 the woman said. \'93He\'92s an awfully nice man. He was in the ring, you know.\'94 \'93I know it.\'94 \'93You\'92d never know it except from the way his face is,\'94 the woman said. They stood talking just inside the street door. \'93He\'92s just as gentle.\'94 \'93Well, good-night, Mrs. Hirsch,\'94 Nick said. \'93I\'92m not Mrs. Hirsch,\'94 the woman said. \'93She owns the place. I just look after it for her. I\'92m Mrs. Bell.\'94 \'93Well, good-night, Mrs. Bell,\'94 Nick said. \'93Good-night,\'94 the woman said. Nick walked up the dark street to the corner under the arc-light, and then along the car-tracks to Henry\'92s eating-house. George was inside, back of the counter. \'93Did you see Ole?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said Nick. \'93He\'92s in his room and he won\'92t go out.\'94 The cook opened the door from the kitchen when he heard Nick\'92s voice. \'93I don\'92t even listen to it,\'94 he said and shut the door. \'93Did you tell him about it?\'94 George asked. \'93Sure. I told him but he knows what it\'92s all about.\'94 \'93What\'92s he going to do?\'94 \'93Nothing.\'94 \'93They\'92ll kill him.\'94 \'93I guess they will.\'94 \'93He must have got mixed up in something in Chicago.\'94 \'93I guess so,\'94 said Nick. \'93It\'92s a hell of a thing.\'94 \'93It\'92s an awful thing,\'94 Nick said. They did not say anything. George reached down for a towel and wiped the counter. \'93I wonder what he did?\'94 Nick said. \'93Double-crossed somebody. That\'92s what they kill them for.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to get out of this town,\'94 Nick said. \'93Yes,\'94 said George. \'93That\'92s a good thing to do.\'94 \'93I can\'92t stand to think about him waiting in the room and knowing he\'92s going to get it. It\'92s too damned awful.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 said George, \'93you better not think about it.\'94 Che Ti Dice la Patria? THE ROAD OF THE PASS WAS HARD AND smooth and not yet dusty in the early morning. Below were the hills with oak and chestnut trees, and far away below was the sea. On the other side were snowy mountains. We came down from the pass through wooded country. There were bags of charcoal piled beside the road, and through the trees we saw charcoal-burners\'92 huts. It was Sunday and the road, rising and falling, but always dropping away from the altitude of the pass, went through the scrub woods and through villages. Outside the villages there were fields with vines. The fields were brown and the vines coarse and thick. The houses were white, and in the streets the men, in their Sunday clothes, were playing bowls. Against the walls of some of the houses there were pear trees, their branches candelabraed against the white walls. The pear trees had been sprayed, and the walls of the houses were stained a metallic blue-green by the spray vapor. There were small clearings around the villages where the vines grew, and then the woods. In a village, twenty kilometres above Spezia, there was a crowd in the square, and a young man carrying a suitcase came up to the car and asked us to take him in to Spezia. \'93There are only two places, and they are occupied,\'94 I said. We had an old Ford coup\'e9. \'93I will ride on the outside.\'94 \'93You will be uncomfortable.\'94 \'93That makes nothing. I must go to Spezia.\'94 \'93Should we take him?\'94 I asked Guy. \'93He seems to be going anyway,\'94 Guy said. The young man handed in a parcel through the window. \'93Look after this,\'94 he said. Two men tied his suitcase on the back of the car, above our suitcases. He shook hands with every one, explained that to a Fascist and a man as used to travelling as himself there was no discomfort, and climbed up on the running-board on the left-hand side of the car, holding on inside, his right arm through the open window. \'93You can start,\'94 he said. The crowd waved. He waved with his free hand. \'93What did he say?\'94 Guy asked me. \'93That we could start.\'94 \'93Isn\'92t he nice?\'94 Guy said. The road followed a river. Across the river were mountains. The sun was taking the frost out of the grass. It was bright and cold and the air came through the open wind-shield. \'93How do you think he likes it out there?\'94 Guy was looking up the road. His view out of his side of the car was blocked by our guest. The young man projected from the side of the car like the figurehead of a ship. He had turned his coat collar up and pulled his hat down and his nose looked cold in the wind. \'93Maybe he\'92ll get enough of it,\'94 Guy said. \'93That\'92s the side