He was too dignified to reply. We went on into Spezia. \'93That\'92s a young man that will go a long way in Italy,\'94 I said to Guy. \'93Well,\'94 said Guy, \'93he went twenty kilometres with us.\'94 A MEAL IN SPEZIA We came into Spezia looking for a place to eat. The street was wide and the houses high and yellow. We followed the tram-track into the center of town. On the walls of the houses were stencilled eyebugging portraits of Mussolini, with hand-painted \'93vivas,\'94 the double V in black paint with drippings of paint down the wall. Side-streets went down to the harbor. It was bright and the people were all out for Sunday. The stone paving had been sprinkled and there were damp stretches in the dust. We went close to the curb to avoid a tram. \'93Let\'92s eat somewhere simple,\'94 Guy said. We stopped opposite two restaurant signs. We were standing across the street and I was buying the papers. The two restaurants were side by side. A woman standing in the doorway of one smiled at us and we crossed the street and went in. It was dark inside and at the back of the room three girls were sitting at a table with an old woman. Across from us, at another table, sat a sailor. He sat there neither eating nor drinking. Further back, a young man in a blue suit was writing at a table. His hair was pomaded and shining and he was very smartly dressed and clean-cut looking. The light came through the doorway, and through the window where vegetables, fruit, steaks, and chops were arranged in a show-case. A girl came and took our order and another girl stood in the doorway. We noticed that she wore nothing under her house dress. The girl who took our order put her arm around Guy\'92s neck while we were looking at the menu. There were three girls in all, and they all took turns going and standing in the doorway. The old woman at the table in the back of the room spoke to them and they sat down again with her. There was no doorway leading from the room except into the kitchen. A curtain hung over it. The girl who had taken our order came in from the kitchen with spaghetti. She put it on the table and brought a bottle of red wine and sat down at the table. \'93Well,\'94 I said to Guy, \'93you wanted to eat some place simple.\'94 \'93This isn\'92t simple. This is complicated.\'94 \'93What do you say?\'94 asked the girl. \'93Are you Germans?\'94 \'93South Germans,\'94 I said. \'93The South Germans are a gentle, lovable people.\'94 \'93Don\'92t understand,\'94 she said. \'93What\'92s the mechanics of this place?\'94 Guy asked. \'93Do I have to let her put her arm around my neck?\'94 \'93Certainly,\'94 I said. \'93Mussolini has abolished the brothels. This is a restaurant.\'94 The girl wore a one-piece dress. She leaned forward against the table and put her hands on her breasts and smiled. She smiled better on one side than on the other and turned the good side toward us. The charm of the good side had been enhanced by some event which had smoothed the other side of her nose in, as warm wax can be smoothed. Her nose, however, did not look like warm wax. It was very cold and firmed, only smoothed in. \'93You like me?\'94 she asked Guy. \'93He adores you,\'94 I said. \'93But he doesn\'92t speak Italian.\'94 \'93Ich spreche Deutsch,\'94 she said, and stroked Guy\'92s hair. \'93Speak to the lady in your native tongue, Guy.\'94 \'93Where do you come from?\'94 asked the lady. \'93Potsdam.\'94 \'93And you will stay here now for a little while?\'94 \'93In this so dear Spezia?\'94 I asked. \'93Tell her we have to go,\'94 said Guy. \'93Tell her we are very ill, and have no money.\'94 \'93My friend is a misogynist,\'94 I said, \'93an old German misogynist.\'94 \'93Tell him I love him.\'94 I told him. \'93Will you shut your mouth and get us out of here?\'94 Guy said. The lady had placed another arm around his neck. \'93Tell him he is mine,\'94 she said. I told him. \'93Will you get us out of here?\'94 \'93You are quarrelling,\'94 the lady said. \'93You do not love one another.\'94 \'93We are Germans,\'94 I said proudly, \'93old South Germans.\'94 \'93Tell him he is a beautiful boy,\'94 the lady said. Guy is thirty-eight and takes some pride in the fact that he is taken for a travelling salesman in France. \'93You are a beautiful boy,\'94 I said. \'93Who says so?\'94 Guy asked, \'93you or her?\'94 \'93She does. I\'92m just your interpreter. Isn\'92t that what you got me in on this trip for?\'94 \'93I\'92m glad it\'92s her,\'94 said Guy. \'93I didn\'92t want to have to leave you here too.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. Spezia\'92s a lovely place.\'94 \'93Spezia,\'94 the lady said. \'93You are talking about Spezia.\'94 \'93Lovely place,\'94 I said. \'93It is my country,\'94 she said. \'93Spezia is my home and Italy is my country.\'94 \'93She says that Italy is her country.\'94 \'93Tell her it looks like her country,\'94 Guy said. \'93What have you for dessert?\'94 I asked. \'93Fruit,\'94 she said. \'93We have bananas.\'94 \'93Bananas are all right,\'94 Guy said. \'93They\'92ve got skins on.\'94 \'93Oh, he takes bananas,\'94 the lady said. She embraced Guy. \'93What does she say?\'94 he asked, keeping his face out of the way. \'93She is pleased because you take bananas.\'94 \'93Tell her I don\'92t take bananas.\'94 \'93The Signor does not take bananas.\'94 \'93Ah,\'94 said the lady, crestfallen, \'93he doesn\'92t take bananas.\'94 \'93Tell her I take a cold bath every morning,\'94 Guy said. \'93The Signor takes a cold bath every morning.\'94 \'93No understand,\'94 the lady said. Across from us, the property sailor had not moved. No one in the place paid any attention to him. \'93We want the bill,\'94 I said. \'93Oh, no. You must stay.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 the clean-cut young man said from the table where he was writing, \'93let them go. These two are worth nothing.\'94 The lady took my hand. \'93You won\'92t stay? You won\'92t ask him to stay?\'94 \'93We have to go,\'94 I said. \'93We have to get to Pisa, or if possible, Firenze, tonight. We can amuse ourselves in those cities at the end of the day. It is now the day. In the day we must cover distance.\'94 \'93To stay a little while is nice.\'94 \'93To travel is necessary during the light of day.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 the clean-cut young man said. \'93Don\'92t bother to talk with these two. I tell you they are worth nothing and I know.\'94 \'93Bring us the bill,\'94 I said. She brought the bill from the old woman and went back and sat at the table. Another girl came in from the kitchen. She walked the length of the room and stood in the doorway. \'93Don\'92t bother with these two,\'94 the clean-cut young man said in a wearied voice. \'93Come and eat. They are worth nothing.\'94 We paid the bill and stood up. All the girls, the old woman, and the clean-cut young man sat down at table together. The property sailor sat with his head in his hands. No one had spoken to him all the time we were at lunch. The girl brought us our change that the old woman counted out for her and went back to her place at the table. We left a tip on the table and went out. When we were seated in the car ready to start, the girl came out and stood in the door. We started and I waved to her. She did not wave, but stood there looking after us. AFTER THE RAIN It was raining hard when we passed through the suburbs of Genoa and, even going very slowly behind the tram-cars and the motor trucks, liquid mud splashed on to the sidewalks, so that people stepped into doorways as they saw us coming. In San Pier d\'92Arena, the industrial suburb outside of Genoa, there is a wide street with two car-tracks and we drove down the center to avoid sending the mud on to the men going home from work. On our left was the Mediterranean. There was a big sea running and waves broke and the wind blew the spray against the car. A river-bed that, when we had passed, going into Italy, had been wide, stony and dry, was running brown, and up to the banks. The brown water discolored the sea and as the waves thinned and cleared in breaking, the light came through the yellow water and the crests, detached by the wind, blew across the road. A big car passed us, going fast, and a sheet of muddy water rose up and over our wind-shield and radiator. The automatic wind-shield cleaner moved back and forth, spreading the film over the glass. We stopped and ate lunch at Sestri. There was no heat in the restaurant and we kept our hats and coats on. We could see the car outside, through the window. It was covered with mud and was stopped beside some boats that had been pulled up beyond the waves. In the restaurant you could see your breath. The pasta asciutta was good; the wine tasted of alum, and we poured water in it. Afterward the waiter brought beefsteak and fried potatoes. A man and a woman sat at the far end of the restaurant. He was middle-aged and she was young and wore black. All during the meal she would blow out her breath in the cold damp air. The man would look at it and shake his head. They ate without talking and the man held her hand under the table. She was good-looking and they seemed very sad. They had a travelling-bag with them. We had the papers and I read the account of the Shanghai fighting aloud to Guy. After the meal, he left with the waiter in search for a place which did not exist in the restaurant, and I cleaned off the wind-shield, the lights and the license plates with a rag. Guy came back and we backed the car out and started. The waiter had taken him across the road and into an old house. The people in the house were suspicious and the waiter had remained with Guy to see nothing was stolen. \'93Although I don\'92t know how, me not being a plumber, they expected me to steal anything,\'94 Guy said. As we came up on a headland beyond the town, the wind struck the car and nearly tipped it over. \'93It\'92s good it blows us away from the sea,\'94 Guy said. \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93they drowned Shelley somewhere along here.\'94 \'93That was down by Viareggio,\'94 Guy said. \'93Do you remember what we came to this country for?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said, \'93but we didn\'92t get it.\'94 \'93We\'92ll be out of it tonight.\'94 \'93If we can get past Ventimiglia.\'94 \'93We\'92ll see. I don\'92t like to drive this coast at night.\'94 It was early afternoon and the sun was out. Below, the sea was blue with whitecaps running toward Savona. Back, beyond the cape, the brown and blue water joined. Out ahead of us, a tramp steamer was going up the coast. \'93Can you still see Genoa?\'94 Guy asked. \'93Oh, yes.\'94 \'93That next big cape ought to put it out of sight.\'94 \'93We\'92ll see it a long time yet. I can still see Portofino Cape behind it.\'94 Finally we could not see Genoa. I looked back as we came out and there was only the sea, and below, in the bay, a line of beach with fishing-boats and above, on the side of the hill, a town and then capes far down the coast. \'93It\'92s gone now,\'94 I said to Guy. \'93Oh, it\'92s been gone a long time now.\'94 \'93But we couldn\'92t be sure till we got way out.\'94 There was a sign with a picture of an S-turn and Svolta Pericolosa. The road curved around the headland and the wind blew through the crack in the wind-shield. Below the cape was a flat stretch beside the sea. The wind had dried the mud and the wheels were beginning to lift dust. On the flat road we passed a Fascist riding a bicycle, a heavy revolver in a holster on his back. He held the middle of the road on his bicycle and we turned out for him. He looked up at us as we passed. Ahead there was a railway crossing, and as we came toward it the gates went down. As we waited, the Fascist came up on his bicycle. The train went by and Guy started the engine. \'93Wait,\'94 the bicycle man shouted from behind the car. \'93Your number\'92s dirty.\'94 I got out with a rag. The number had been cleaned at lunch. \'93You can read it,\'94 I said. \'93You think so?\'94 \'93Read it.\'94 \'93I cannot read it. It is dirty.\'94 I wiped it off with the rag. \'93How\'92s that?\'94 \'93Twenty-five lire.\'94 \'93What?\'94 I said. \'93You could have read it. It\'92s only dirty from the state of the roads.\'94 \'93You don\'92t like Italian roads?\'94 \'93They are dirty.\'94 \'93Fifty lire.\'94 He spat in the road. \'93Your car is dirty and you are dirty too.\'94 \'93Good. And give me a receipt with your name.\'94 He took out a receipt book, made in duplicate, and perforated, so one side could be given to the customer, and the other side filled in and kept as a stub. There was no carbon to record what the customer\'92s ticket said. \'93Give me fifty lire.\'94 He wrote in indelible pencil, tore out the slip and handed it to me. I read it. \'93This is for twenty-five lire.\'94 \'93A mistake,\'94 he said, and changed the twenty-five to fifty. \'93And now the other side. Make it fifty in the part you keep.\'94 He smiled a beautiful Italian smile and wrote something on the receipt stub, holding it so I could not see. \'93Go on,\'94 he said, \'93before your number gets dirty again.\'94 We drove for two hours after it was dark and slept in Mentone that night. It seemed very cheerful and clean and sane and lovely. We had driven from Ventimiglia to Pisa and Florence, across the Romagna to Rimini, back through Forli, Imola, Bologna, Parma, Piacenza and Genoa, to Ventimiglia again. The whole trip had taken only ten days. Naturally, in such a short trip, we had no opportunity to see how things were with the country or the people. Fifty Grand \'93HOW ARE YOU GOING YOURSELF, Jack?\'94 I asked him. \'93You seen this Walcott?\'94 he says. \'93Just in the gym.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 Jack says, \'93I\'92m going to need a lot of luck with that boy.\'94 \'93He can\'92t hit you. Jack,\'94 Soldier said. \'93I wish to hell he couldn\'92t.\'94 \'93He couldn\'92t hit you with a handful of bird-shot.\'94 \'93Bird-shot\'92d be all right,\'94 Jack says. \'93I wouldn\'92t mind bird-shot any.\'94 \'93He looks easy to hit,\'94 I said. \'93Sure,\'94 Jack says, \'93he ain\'92t going to last long. He ain\'92t going to last like you and me, Jerry. But right now he\'92s got everything.\'94 \'93You\'92ll left-hand him to death.\'94 \'93Maybe,\'94 Jack says. \'93Sure. I got a chance to.\'94 \'93Handle him like you handled Kid Lewis.\'94 \'93Kid Lewis,\'94 Jack said. \'93That kike!\'94 The three of us, Jack Brennan, Soldier Bartlett, and I were in Hanley\'92s. There were a couple of broads sitting at the next table to us. They had been drinking. \'93What do you mean, kike?\'94 one of the broads says. \'93What do you mean, kike, you big Irish bum?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 Jack says. \'93That\'92s it.\'94 \'93Kikes,\'94 this broad goes on. \'93They\'92re always talking about kikes, these big Irishmen. What do you mean, kikes?\'94 \'93Come on. Let\'92s get out of here.\'94 \'93Kikes,\'94 this broad goes on. \'93Whoever saw you ever buy a drink? Your wife sews your pockets up every morning. These Irishmen and their kikes! Ted Lewis could lick you too.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 Jack says. \'93And you give away a lot of things free too, don\'92t you?\'94 We went out. That was Jack. He could say what he wanted to when he wanted to say it. Jack started training out at Danny Hogan\'92s health farm over in Jersey. It was nice out there but Jack didn\'92t like it much. He didn\'92t like being away from his wife and the kids, and he was sore and grouchy most of the time. He liked me and we got along fine together; and he liked Hogan, but after a while Soldier Bartlett commenced to get on his nerves. A kidder gets to be an awful thing around a camp if his stuff goes sort of sour. Soldier was always kidding Jack, just sort of kidding him all the time. It wasn\'92t very funny and it wasn\'92t very good, and it began to get to Jack. It was sort of stuff like this. Jack would finish up with the weights and the bag and pull on the gloves. \'93You want to work?\'94 he\'92d say to Soldier. \'93Sure. How you want me to work?\'94 Soldier would ask. \'93Want me to treat you rough like Walcott? Want me to knock you down a few times?\'94 \'93That\'92s it,\'94 Jack would say. He didn\'92t like it any, though. One morning we were all out on the road. We\'92d been out quite a way and now we were coming back. We\'92d go along fast for three minutes and then walk a minute, and then go fast for three minutes again. Jack wasn\'92t ever what you would call a sprinter. He\'92d move around fast enough in the ring if he had to, but he wasn\'92t any too fast on the road. All the time we were walking Soldier was kidding him. We came up the hill to the farmhouse. \'93Well,\'94 says Jack, \'93you better go back to town. Soldier.\'94 \'93What do you mean?\'94 \'93You better go back to town and stay there.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 \'93I\'92m sick of hearing you talk.\'94 \'93Yes?\'94 says Soldier. \'93Yes.\'94 says Jack. \'93You\'92ll be a damn sight sicker when Walcott gets through with you.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 says Jack, \'93maybe I will. But I know I\'92m sick of you.\'94 So Soldier went off on the train to town that same morning. I went down with him to the train. He was good and sore. \'93I was just kidding him,\'94 he said. We were waiting on the platform. \'93He can\'92t pull that stuff with me, Jerry.\'94 \'93He\'92s nervous and crabby,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s a good fellow, Soldier.\'94 \'93The hell he is. The hell he\'92s ever been a good fellow.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93so long, Soldier.\'94 The train had come in. He climbed up with his bag. \'93So long, Jerry,\'94 he says. \'93You be in town before the fight?\'94 \'93I don\'92t think so.\'94 \'93See you then.\'94 He went in and the conductor swung up and the train went out. I rode back to the farm in the cart. Jack was on the porch writing a letter to his wife. The mail had come and I got the papers and went over on the other side of the porch and sat down to read. Hogan came out the door and walked over to me. \'93Did he have a jam with Soldier?\'94 \'93Not a jam,\'94 I said. \'93He just told him to go back to town.\'94 \'93I could see it coming,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He never liked Soldier much.\'94 \'93No. He don\'92t like many people.\'94 \'93He\'92s a pretty cold one,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Well, he\'92s always been fine to me.\'94 \'93Me too,\'94 Hogan said. \'93I got no kick on him. He\'92s a cold one, though.\'94 Hogan went in through the screen door and I sat there on the porch and read the papers. It was just starting to get fall weather and it\'92s nice country there in Jersey, up in the hills, and after I read the paper through I sat there and looked out at the country and the road down below against the woods with cars going along it, lifting the dust up. It was fine weather and pretty nice-looking country. Hogan came to the door and I said, \'93Say, Hogan, haven\'92t you got anything to shoot out here?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Only sparrows.\'94 \'93Seen the paper?\'94 I said to Hogan. \'93What\'92s in it?\'94 \'93Sande booted three of them in yesterday.\'94 \'93I got that on the telephone last night.\'94 \'93You follow them pretty close, Hogan?\'94 I asked. \'93Oh, I keep in touch with them,\'94 Hogan said. \'93How about Jack?\'94 I says. \'93Does he still play them?\'94 \'93Him?\'94 said Hogan. \'93Can you see him doing it?\'94 Just then Jack came around the corner with the letter in his hand. He\'92s wearing a sweater and an old pair of pants and boxing shoes. \'93Got a stamp, Hogan?\'94 he asks. \'93Give me the letter,\'94 Hogan said. \'93I\'92ll mail it for you.\'94 \'93Say, Jack,\'94 I said, \'93didn\'92t you used to play the ponies?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93I knew you did. I knew I used to see you out at Sheepshead.\'94 \'93What did you lay off them for?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93Lost money.\'94 Jack sat down on the porch by me. He leaned back against a post. He shut his eyes in the sun. \'93Want a chair?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93No,\'94 said Jack. \'93This is fine.\'94 \'93It\'92s a nice day,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s pretty nice out in the country.\'94 \'93I\'92d a damn sight rather be in town with the wife.\'94 \'93Well, you only got another week.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 Jack says. \'93That\'92s so.\'94 We sat there on the porch. Hogan was inside at the office. \'93What do you think about the shape I\'92m in?\'94 Jack asked me. \'93Well, you can\'92t tell,\'94 I said. \'93You got a week to get around into form.\'94 \'93Don\'92t stall me.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93you\'92re not right.\'94 \'93I\'92m not sleeping,\'94 Jack said. \'93You\'92ll be all right in a couple of days.\'94 \'93No,\'94 says Jack, \'93I got the insomnia.\'94 \'93What\'92s on your mind?\'94 \'93I miss the wife.\'94 \'93Have her come out.\'94 \'93No. I\'92m too old for that.\'94 \'93We\'92ll take a long walk before you turn in and get you good and tired.\'94 \'93Tired!\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m tired all the time.\'94 He was that way all week. He wouldn\'92t sleep at night and he\'92d get up in the morning feeling that way, you know, when you can\'92t shut your hands. \'93He\'92s stale as poorhouse cake,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He\'92s nothing.\'94 \'93I never seen Walcott,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92ll kill him,\'94 said Hogan. \'93He\'92ll tear him in two.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93everybody\'92s got to get it sometime.\'94 \'93Not like this, though,\'94 Hogan said. \'93They\'92ll think he never trained. It gives the farm a black eye.\'94 \'93You hear what the reporters said about him?\'94 \'93Didn\'92t I! They said he was awful. They said they oughtn\'92t to let him fight.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93they\'92re always wrong, ain\'92t they?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said Hogan. \'93But this time they\'92re right.\'94 \'93What the hell do they know about whether a man\'92s right or not?\'94 \'93Well,\'94 said Hogan, \'93they\'92re not such fools.\'94 \'93All they did was pick Willard at Toledo. This Lardner, he\'92s so wise now, ask him about when he picked Willard at Toledo.\'94 \'93Aw, he wasn\'92t out,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He only writes the big fights.\'94 \'93I don\'92t care who they are,\'94 I said. \'93What the hell do they know? They can write maybe, but what the hell do they know?\'94 \'93You don\'92t think Jack\'92s in any shape, do you?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93No. He\'92s through. All he needs is to have Corbett pick him to win for it to be all over.\'94 \'93Well, Corbett\'92ll pick him,\'94 Hogan says. \'93Sure. He\'92ll pick him.\'94 That night Jack didn\'92t sleep any either. The next morning was the last day before the fight. After breakfast we were out on the porch again. \'93What do you think about, Jack, when you can\'92t sleep?\'94 I said. \'93Oh, I worry,\'94 Jack says. \'93I worry about property I got up in the Bronx, I worry about property I got in Florida. I worry about the kids. I worry about the wife. Sometimes I think about fights. I think about that kike Ted Lewis and I get sore. I got some stocks and I worry about them. What the hell don\'92t I think about?\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93tomorrow night it\'92ll all be over.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said Jack. \'93That always helps a lot, don\'92t it? That just fixes everything all up, I suppose. Sure.\'94 He was sore all day. We didn\'92t do any work. Jack just moved around a little to loosen up. He shadow-boxed a few rounds. He didn\'92t even look good doing that. He skipped the rope a little while. He couldn\'92t sweat. \'93He\'92d be better not to do any work at all,\'94 Hogan said. We were standing watching him skip rope. \'93Don\'92t he ever sweat at all any more?\'94 \'93He can\'92t sweat.\'94 \'93Do you suppose he\'92s got the con? He never had any trouble making weight did he?\'94 \'93No, he hasn\'92t got any con. He just hasn\'92t got anything inside any more.\'94 \'93He ought to sweat,\'94 said Hogan. Jack came over, skipping the rope. He was skipping up and down in front of us, forward and back, crossing his arms every third time. \'93Well,\'94 he says. \'93What are you buzzards talking about?\'94 \'93I don\'92t think you ought to work any more,\'94 Hogan says. \'93You\'92ll be stale.\'94 \'93Wouldn\'92t that be awful?\'94 Jack says and skips away down the floor, slapping the rope hard. That afternoon John Collins showed up out at the farm. Jack was up in his room. John came out in a car from town. He had a couple of friends with him. The car stopped and they all got out. \'93Where\'92s Jack?\'94 John asked me. \'93Up in his room, lying down.\'94 \'93Lying down?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93How is he?\'94 I looked at the two fellows that were with John. \'93They\'92re friends of his,\'94 John said. \'93He\'92s pretty bad,\'94 I said. \'93What\'92s the matter with him?\'94 \'93He don\'92t sleep.\'94 \'93Hell,\'94 said John. \'93That Irishman could never sleep.\'94 \'93He isn\'92t right,\'94 I said. \'93Hell,\'94 John said. \'93He\'92s never right. I\'92ve had him for ten years and he\'92s never been right yet.\'94 The fellows who were with him laughed. \'93I want you to shake hands with Mr. Morgan and Mr. Steinfelt,\'94 John said. \'93This is Mr. Doyle. He\'92s been training Jack.\'94 \'93Glad to meet you,\'94 I said. \'93Let\'92s go up and see the boy,\'94 the fellow called Morgan said. \'93Let\'92s have a look at him,\'94 Steinfelt said. We all went upstairs. \'93Where\'92s Hogan?\'94 John asked. \'93He\'92s out in the barn with a couple of his customers,\'94 I said. \'93He got many people out here now?\'94 John asked. \'93Just two.\'94 \'93Pretty quiet, ain\'92t it?\'94 Morgan said. \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s pretty quiet.\'94 We were outside Jack\'92s room. John knocked on the door. There wasn\'92t any answer. \'93Maybe he\'92s asleep,\'94 I said. \'93What the hell\'92s he sleeping in the daytime for?\'94 John turned the handle and we all went in. Jack was lying asleep on the bed. He was face down and his face was in the pillow. Both his arms were around the pillow. \'93Hey, Jack!\'94 John said to him. Jack\'92s head moved a little on the pillow. \'93Jack!\'94 John says, leaning over him. Jack just dug a little deeper in the pillow. John touched him on the shoulder. Jack sat up and looked at us. He hadn\'92t shaved and he was wearing an old sweater. \'93Christ! Why can\'92t you let me sleep?\'94 he says to John. \'93Don\'92t be sore,\'94 John says. \'93I didn\'92t mean to wake you up.\'94 \'93Oh no,\'94 Jack says. \'93Of course not.\'94 \'93You know Morgan and Steinfelt,\'94 John said. \'93Glad to see you,\'94 Jack says. \'93How do you feel, Jack?\'94 Morgan asks him. \'93Fine,\'94 Jack says. \'93How the hell would I feel?\'94 \'93You look fine,\'94 Steinfelt says. \'93Yes, don\'92t 11,\'94 says Jack. \'93Say,\'94 he says to John. \'93You\'92re my manager. You get a big enough cut. Why the hell don\'92t you come out here when the reporters was out! You want Jerry and me to talk to them?\'94 \'93I had Lew fighting in Philadelphia,\'94 John said. \'93What the hell\'92s that to me?\'94 Jack says. \'93You\'92re my manager. You get a big enough cut, don\'92t you? You aren\'92t making me any money in Philadelphia, are you? Why the hell aren\'92t you out here when I ought to have you?\'94 \'93Hogan was here.\'94 \'93Hogan,\'94 Jack says. \'93Hogan\'92s as dumb as I am.\'94 \'93Soldier Bahtlett was out here wukking with you for a while, wasn\'92t he?\'94 Steinfelt said to change the subject. \'93Yes, he was out here,\'94 Jack says. \'93He was out here all right.\'94 \'93Say, Jerry,\'94 John said to me. \'93Would you go and find Hogan and tell him we want to see him in about half an hour?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93Why the hell can\'92t he stick around?\'94 Jack says. \'93Stick around, Jerry.\'94 Morgan and Steinfelt looked at each other. \'93Quiet down, Jack,\'94 John said to him. \'93I better go find Hogan,\'94 I said. \'93All right, if you want to go,\'94 Jack says. \'93None of these guys are going to send you away, though.\'94 \'93I\'92ll go find Hogan,\'94 I said. Hogan was out in the gym in the barn. He had a couple of his health-farm patients with the gloves on. They neither one wanted to hit the other, for fear the other would come back and hit him. \'93That\'92ll do,\'94 Hogan said when he saw me come in. \'93You can stop the slaughter. You gentlemen take a shower and Bruce will rub you down.\'94 They climbed out through the ropes and Hogan came over to me. \'93John Collins is out with a couple of friends to see Jack,\'94 I said. \'93I saw them come up in the car.\'94 \'93Who are the two fellows with John?\'94 \'93They\'92re what you call wise boys,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Don\'92t you know them two?\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s Happy Steinfelt and Lew Morgan. They got a pool-room.\'92 \'93I been away a long time,\'94 I said. \'93Sure,\'94 said Hogan. \'93That Happy Steinfelt\'92s a big operator.\'94 \'93I\'92ve heard his name,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s a pretty smooth boy,\'94 Hogan said. \'93They\'92re a couple of sharpshooters.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said. \'93They want to see us in half an hour.\'94 \'93You mean they don\'92t want to see us until a half an hour?\'94 \'93That\'92s it.\'94 \'93Come on in the office,\'94 Hogan said. \'93To hell with those sharpshooters.\'94 After about thirty minutes or so Hogan and I went upstairs. We knocked on Jack\'92s door. They were talking inside the room. \'93Wait a minute,\'94 somebody said. \'93To hell with that stuff,\'94 Hogan said. \'93When you want to see me I\'92m down in the office.\'94 We heard the door unlock. Steinfelt opened it. \'93Come on in, Hogan,\'94 he says. \'93We\'92re all going to have a drink.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 says Hogan. \'93That\'92s something.\'94 We went in. Jack was sitting on the bed. John and Morgan were sitting on a couple of chairs. Steinfelt was standing up. \'93You\'92re a pretty mysterious lot of boys,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Hello, Danny,\'94 John says. \'93Hello, Danny,\'94 Morgan says and shakes hands. Jack doesn\'92t say anything. He just sits there on the bed. He ain\'92t with the others. He\'92s all by himself. He was wearing an old blue jersey and pants and had on boxing shoes. He needed a shave. Steinfelt and Morgan were dressers. John was quite a dresser too. Jack sat there looking Irish and tough. Steinfelt brought out a bottle and Hogan brought in some glasses and everybody had a drink. Jack and I took one and the rest of them went on and had two or three each. \'93Better save some for your ride back,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Don\'92t you worry. We got plenty,\'94 Morgan said. Jack hadn\'92t drunk anything since the one drink. He was standing up and looking at them. Morgan was sitting on the bed where Jack had sat. \'93Have a drink. Jack,\'94 John said and handed him the glass and the bottle. \'93No,\'94 Jack said, \'93I never liked to go to these wakes.\'94 They all laughed. Jack didn\'92t laugh. They were all feeling pretty good when they left. Jack stood on the porch when they got into the car. They waved to him. \'93So long,\'94 Jack said. We had supper. Jack didn\'92t say anything all during the meal except, \'93Will you pass me this?\'94 or \'93Will you pass me that?\'94 The two health-farm patients ate at the same table with us. They were pretty nice fellows. After we finished eating we went out on the porch. It was dark early. \'93Like to take a walk, Jerry?\'94 Jack asked. \'93Sure,\'94 I said. We put on our coats and started out. It was quite a way down to the main road and then we walked along the main road about a mile and a half. Cars kept going by and we would pull out to the side until they were past. Jack didn\'92t say anything. After we had stepped out into the bushes to let a big car go by Jack said, \'93To hell with this walking. Come on back to Hogan\'92s.\'94 We went along a side road that cut up over the hill and cut across the fields back to Hogan\'92s. We could see the lights of the house up on the hill. We came around to the front of the house and there standing in the doorway was Hogan. \'93Have a good walk?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93Oh, fine,\'94 Jack said. \'93Listen, Hogan. Have you got any liquor?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 says Hogan. \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 \'93Send it up to the room,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m going to sleep tonight.\'94 \'93You\'92re the doctor,\'94 Hogan says. \'93Come on up to the room, Jerry,\'94 Jack says. Upstairs Jack sat on the bed with his head in his hands. \'93Ain\'92t it a life?\'94 Jack says. Hogan brought in a quart of liquor and two glasses. \'93Want some ginger ale?\'94 \'93What do you think I want to do, get sick?\'94 \'93I just asked you,\'94 said Hogan. \'93Have a drink?\'94 said Jack. \'93No, thanks,\'94 said Hogan. He went out. \'93How about you, Jerry?\'94 \'93I\'92ll have one with you,\'94 I said. Jack poured out a couple of drinks. \'93Now,\'94 he said, \'93I want to take it slow and easy.\'94 \'93Put some water in it,\'94 I said. \'93Yes,\'94 Jack said. \'93I guess that\'92s better.\'94 We had a couple of drinks without saying anything. Jack started to pour me another. \'93No,\'94 I said, \'93that\'92s all I want.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Jack said. He poured himself out another big shot and put water in it. He was lighting up a little. \'93That was a fine bunch out here this afternoon,\'94 he said. \'93They don\'92t take any chances, those two.\'94 Then a little later, \'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93they\'92re right. What the hell\'92s the good in taking chances?\'94 \'93Don\'92t you want another. Jerry?\'94 he said. \'93Come on, drink along with me.\'94 \'93I don\'92t need it, Jack,\'94 I said. \'93I feel all right.\'94 \'93Just have one more,\'94 Jack said. It was softening him up. \'93All right,\'94 I said. Jack poured one for me and another big one for himself. \'93You know,\'94 he said, \'93I like liquor pretty well. If I hadn\'92t been boxing I would have drunk quite a lot.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93You know,\'94 he said, \'93I missed a lot, boxing.\'94 \'93You made plenty of money.\'94 \'93Sure, that\'92s what I\'92m after. You know I miss a lot. Jerry.\'94 \'93How do you mean?\'94 \'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93like about the wife. And being away from home so much. It don\'92t do my girls any good. \'91Who\'92s your old man?\'92 some of those society kids\'92ll say to them. \'91My old man\'92s Jack Brennan.\'92 That don\'92t do them any good.\'94 \'93Hell,\'94 I said, \'93all that makes a difference is if they got dough.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 says Jack, \'93I got the dough for them all right.\'94 He poured out another drink. The bottle was about empty. \'93Put some water in it,\'94 I said. Jack poured in some water. \'93You know,\'94 he says, \'93you ain\'92t got any idea how I miss the wife.\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93You ain\'92t got any idea. You can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like.\'94 \'93It ought to be better out in the country than in town.\'94 \'93With me now,\'94 Jack said, \'93it don\'92t make any difference where I am. You can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like.\'94 \'93Have another drink.\'94 \'93Am I getting soused? Do I talk funny?\'94 \'93You\'92re coming on all right.\'94 \'93You can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like. They ain\'92t anybody can have an idea what it\'92s like.\'94 \'93Except the wife,\'94 I said. \'93She knows,\'94 Jack said. \'93She knows all right. She knows. You bet she knows.\'94 \'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said. \'93Jerry,\'94 says Jack, \'93you can\'92t have an idea what it gets to be like.\'94 He was good and drunk. He was looking at me steady. His eyes were sort of too steady. \'93You\'92ll sleep all right,\'94 I said. \'93Listen Jerry,\'94 Jack says. \'93You want to make some money? Get some money down on Walcott.\'94 \'93Yes?\'94 \'93Listen, Jerry,\'94 Jack put down the glass. \'93I\'92m not drunk now, see? You know what I\'92m betting on him? Fifty grand.\'94 \'93That\'92s a lot of dough.\'94 \'93Fifty grand,\'94 Jack says, \'93at two to one. I\'92ll get twenty-five thousand bucks. Get some money on him, Jerry.\'94 \'93It sounds good,\'94 I said. \'93How can I beat him?\'94 Jack says. \'93It ain\'92t crooked. How can I beat him? Why not make money on it?\'94 \'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m through after this fight,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m through with it. I got to take a beating. Why shouldn\'92t I make money on it?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93I ain\'92t slept for a week,\'94 Jack says. \'93All night I lay awake and worry my can off. I can\'92t sleep, Jerry. You ain\'92t got an idea what it\'92s like when you can\'92t sleep.\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93I can\'92t sleep. That\'92s all. I just can\'92t sleep. What\'92s the use of taking care of yourself all these years when you can\'92t sleep?\'94 \'93It\'92s bad.\'94 \'93You ain\'92t got an idea what it\'92s like, Jerry, when you can\'92t sleep.\'94 \'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said. Well, about eleven o\'92clock Jack passes out and I put him to bed. Finally he\'92s so he can\'92t keep from sleeping. I helped him get his clothes off and got him into bed. \'93You\'92ll sleep all right. Jack,\'94 I said. \'93Sure,\'94 Jack says, \'93I\'92ll sleep now.\'94 \'93Good night, Jack,\'94 I said. \'93Good night, Jerry,\'94 Jack says. \'93You\'92re the only friend I got.\'94 \'93Oh, hell,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92re the only friend I got,\'94 Jack says, \'93the only friend I got.\'94 \'93Go to sleep,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ll sleep,\'94 Jack says. Downstairs Hogan was sitting at the desk in the office reading the papers. He looked up. \'93Well, you get your boy friend to sleep?\'94 he asks. \'93He\'92s off.\'94 \'93It\'92s better for him than not sleeping,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Sure.\'94 \'93You\'92d have a hell of a time explaining that to these sport writers though,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Well, I\'92m going to bed myself,\'94 I said. \'93Good night,\'94 said Hogan. In the morning I came downstairs about eight o\'92clock and got some breakfast. Hogan had his two customers out in the barn doing exercises. I went out and watched them. \'93One! Two! Three! Four!\'94 Hogan was counting for them. \'93Hello, Jerry,\'94 he said. \'93Is Jack up yet?\'94 \'93No. He\'92s still sleeping.\'94 I went back to my room and packed up to go in to town. About nine-thirty I heard Jack getting up in the next room. When I heard him go downstairs I went down after him. Jack was sitting at the breakfast table. Hogan had come in and was standing beside the table. \'93How do you feel, Jack?\'94 I asked him. \'93Not so bad.\'94 \'93Sleep well?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93I slept all right,\'94 Jack said. \'93I got a thick tongue but I ain\'92t got a head.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 said Hogan. \'93That was good liquor.\'94 \'93Put it on the bill,\'94 Jack says. \'93What time you want to go into town?\'94 Hogan asked. \'93Before lunch,\'94 Jack says. \'93The eleven o\'92clock train.\'94 \'93Sit down, Jerry,\'94 Jack said. Hogan went out. I sat down at the table. Jack was eating a grapefruit. When he\'92d find a seed he\'92d spit it out in the spoon and dump it on the plate. \'93I guess I was pretty stewed last night,\'94 he started. \'93You drank some liquor.\'94 \'93I guess I said a lot of fool things.\'94 \'93You weren\'92t bad.\'94 \'93Where\'92s Hogan?\'94 he asked. He was through with the grapefruit. \'93He\'92s out in front in the office.\'94 \'93What did I say about betting on the fight?\'94 Jack asked. He was holding the spoon and sort of poking at the grapefruit with it. The girl came in with some ham and eggs and took away the grapefruit. \'93Bring me another glass of milk,\'94 Jack said to her. She went out. \'93You said you had fifty grand on Walcott,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s right,\'94 Jack said. \'93That\'92s a lot of money.\'94 \'93I don\'92t feel too good about it,\'94 Jack said. \'93Something might happen.\'94 \'93No,\'94 Jack said. \'93He wants the title bad. They\'92ll be shooting with him all right.\'94 \'93You can\'92t ever tell.\'94 \'93No. He wants the title. It\'92s worth a lot of money to him.\'94 \'93Fifty grand is a lot of money,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s business,\'94 said Jack. \'93I can\'92t win. You know I can\'92t win anyway.\'94 \'93As long as you\'92re in there you got a chance.\'94 \'93No,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m all through. It\'92s just business.\'94 \'93How do you feel?\'94 \'93Pretty good,\'94 Jack said. \'93The sleep was what I needed.\'94 \'93You might go good.\'94 \'93I\'92ll give them a good show,\'94 Jack said. After breakfast Jack called up his wife on the long-distance. He was inside the booth telephoning. \'93That\'92s the first time he\'92s called her up since he\'92s out here,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He writes her every day.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 Hogan says, \'93a letter only costs two cents.\'94 Hogan said good-by to us and Brace, the nigger rubber, drove us down to the train in the cart. \'93Good-by, Mr. Brennan,\'94 Bruce said at the train, \'93I sure hope you knock his can off.\'94 \'93So long,\'94 Jack said. He gave Bruce two dollars. Bruce had worked on him a lot. He looked kind of disappointed. Jack saw me looking at Bruce holding the two dollars. \'93It\'92s all in the bill,\'94 he said. \'93Hogan charged me for the rubbing.\'94 On the train going into town Jack didn\'92t talk. He sat in the corner of the seat with his ticket in his hat-band and looked out of the window. Once he turned and spoke to me. \'93I told the wife I\'92d take a room at the Shelby tonight,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s just around the corner from the Garden. I can go up to the house tomorrow morning.\'94 \'93That\'92s a good idea,\'94 I said. \'93Your wife ever see you fight, Jack?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Jack says. \'93She never seen me fight.\'94 I thought he must be figuring on taking an awful beating if he doesn\'92t want to go home afterward. In town we took a taxi up to the Shelby. A boy came out and took our bags and we went in to the desk. \'93How much are the rooms?\'94 Jack asked. \'93We only have double rooms,\'94 the clerk says. \'93I can give you a nice double room for ten dollars.\'94 \'93That\'92s too steep.\'94 \'93I can give you a double room for seven dollars.\'94 \'93With a bath?\'94 \'93Certainly.\'94 \'93You might as well bunk with me, Jerry,\'94 Jack says. \'93Oh,\'94 I said, \'93I\'92ll sleep down at my brother-in-law\'92s.\'94 \'93I don\'92t mean for you to pay it,\'94 Jack says. \'93I just want to get my money\'92s worth.\'94 \'93Will you register, please?\'94 the clerk says. He looked at the names. \'93Number 238, Mr. Brennan.\'94 We went up in the elevator. It was a nice big room with two beds and a door opening into a bath-room. \'93This is pretty good,\'94 Jack says. The boy who brought us up pulled up the curtains and brought in our bags. Jack didn\'92t make any move, so I gave the boy a quarter. We washed up and Jack said we better go out and get something to eat. We ate a lunch at Jimmy Hanley\'92s place. Quite a lot of the boys were there. When we were about half through eating, John came in and sat down with us. Jack didn\'92t talk much. \'93How are you on the weight. Jack?\'94 John asked him. Jack was putting away a pretty good lunch. \'93I could make it with my clothes on,\'94 Jack said. He never had to worry about taking off weight. He was a natural welterweight and he\'92d never gotten fat. He\'92d lost weight out at Hogan\'92s. \'93Well, that\'92s one thing you never had to worry about,\'94 John said. \'93That\'92s one thing,\'94 Jack says. We went around to the Garden to weigh in after lunch. The match was made at a hundred fortyseven pounds at three o\'92clock. Jack stepped on the scales with a towel around him. The bar didn\'92t move. Walcott had just weighed and was standing with a lot of people around him. \'93Let\'92s see what you weigh, Jack,\'94 Freedman, Walcott\'92s manager said. \'93All right, weigh him then,\'94 Jack jerked his head toward Walcott. \'93Drop the towel,\'94 Freedman said. \'93What do you make it?\'94 Jack asked the fellows who were weighing. \'93One hundred and forty-three pounds,\'94 the fat man who was weighing said. \'93You\'92re down fine, Jack,\'94 Freedman says. \'93Weigh him,\'94 Jack says. Walcott came over. He was a blond with wide shoulders and arms like a heavyweight. He didn\'92t have much legs. Jack stood about half a head taller than he did. \'93Hello, Jack,\'94 he said. His face was plenty marked up. \'93Hello,\'94 said Jack. \'93How you feel?\'94 \'93Good,\'94 Walcott says. He dropped the towel from around his waist and stood on the scales. He had the widest shoulders and back you ever saw. \'93One hundred and forty-six pounds and twelve ounces.\'94 Walcott stepped off and grinned at Jack. \'93Well,\'94 John says to him, \'93Jack\'92s spotting you about four pounds.\'94 \'93More than that when I come in, kid,\'94 Walcott says. \'93I\'92m going to go and eat now.\'94 We went back and Jack got dressed. \'93He\'92s a pretty tough-looking boy,\'94 Jack says to me. \'93He looks as though he\'92d been hit plenty of times.\'94 \'93Oh, yes,\'94 Jack says. \'93He ain\'92t hard to hit.\'94 \'93Where are you going?\'94 John asked when Jack was dressed. \'93Back to the hotel,\'94 Jack says. \'93You looked after everything?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 John says. \'93It\'92s all looked after.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to lie down a while,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92ll come around for you about a quarter to seven and we\'92ll go and eat.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 Up at the hotel Jack took off his shoes and his coat and lay down for a while. I wrote a letter. I looked over a couple of times and Jack wasn\'92t sleeping. He was lying perfectly still but every once in a while his eyes would open. Finally he sits up. \'93Want to play some cribbage, Jerry?\'94 he says. \'93Sure,\'94 I said. He went over to his suitcase and got out the cards and the cribbage board. We played cribbage and he won three dollars off me. John knocked at the door and came in. \'93Want to play some cribbage, John?\'94 Jack asked him. John put his hat down on the table. It was all wet. His coat was wet too. \'93Is it raining?\'94 Jack asks. \'93It\'92s pouring,\'94 John says. \'93The taxi I had got tied up in the traffic and I got out and walked.\'94 \'93Come on, play some cribbage,\'94 Jack says. \'93You ought to go and eat.\'94 \'93No,\'94 says Jack. \'93I don\'92t want to eat yet.\'94 So they played cribbage for about half an hour and Jack won a dollar and a half off him. \'93Well, I suppose we got to go eat,\'94 Jack says. He went to the window and looked out. \'93Is it still raining?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93Let\'92s eat in the hotel,\'94 John says. \'93All right,\'94 Jack says, \'93I\'92ll play you once more to see who pays for the meal.\'94 After a little while Jack gets up and says, \'93You buy the meal, John,\'94 and we went downstairs and ate in the big dining-room. After we ate we went upstairs and Jack played cribbage with John again and won two dollars and a half off him. Jack was feeling pretty good. John had a bag with him with all his stuff in it. Jack took off his shirt and collar and put on a jersey and a sweater, so he wouldn\'92t catch cold when he came out, and put his ring clothes and his bathrobe in a bag. \'93You all ready?\'94 John asks him. \'93I\'92ll call up and have them get a taxi.\'94 Pretty soon the telephone rang and they said the taxi was waiting. We rode down in the elevator and went out through the lobby, and got in a taxi and rode around to the Garden. It was raining hard but there was a lot of people outside on the streets. The Garden was sold out. As we came in on our way to the dressing-room I saw how full it was. It looked like half a mile down to the ring. It was all dark. Just the lights over the ring. \'93It\'92s a good thing, with this rain, they didn\'92t try and pull this fight in the ball park,\'94 John said. \'93They got a good crowd,\'94 Jack says. \'93This is a fight that would draw a lot more than the Garden could hold.\'94 \'93You can\'92t tell about the weather,\'94 Jack says. John came to the door of the dressing-room and poked his head in. Jack was sitting there with his bathrobe on, he had his arms folded and was looking at the floor. John had a couple of handlers with him. They looked over his shoulder. Jack looked up. \'93Is he in?\'94 he asked. \'93He\'92s just gone down,\'94 John said. We started down. Walcott was just getting into the ring. The crowd gave him a big hand. He climbed through between the ropes and put his two fists together and smiled, and shook them at the crowd, first at one side of the ring, then at the other, and then sat down. Jack got a good hand coming down through the crowd. Jack is Irish and the Irish always get a pretty good hand. An Irishman don\'92t draw in New York like a Jew or an Italian but they always get a good hand. Jack climbed up and bent down to go through the ropes and Walcott came over from his corner and pushed the rope down for Jack to go through. The crowd thought that was wonderful. Walcott put his hand on Jack\'92s shoulder and they stood there just for a second. \'93So you\'92re going to be one of these popular champions,\'94 Jack says to him. \'93Take your goddam hand off my shoulder.\'94 \'93Be yourself,\'94 Walcott says. This is all great for the crowd. How gentlemanly the boys are before the fight. How they wish each other luck. Solly Freedman came over to our comer while Jack is bandaging his hands and John is over in Walcott\'92s corner. Jack puts his thumb through the slit in the bandage and then wrapped his hand nice and smooth. I taped it around the wrist and twice across the knuckles. \'93Hey,\'94 Freedman says. \'93Where do you get all that tape?\'94 \'93Feel of it,\'94 Jack says. \'93It\'92s soft, ain\'92t it? Don\'92t be a hick.\'94 Freedman stands there all the time while Jack bandages the other hand, and one of the boys that\'92s going to handle him brings the gloves and I pull them on and work them around. \'93Say, Freedman,\'94 Jack asks, \'93what nationality is this Walcott?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Solly says. \'93He\'92s some sort of a Dane.\'94 \'93He\'92s a Bohemian,\'94 the lad who brought the gloves said. The referee called them out to the center of the ring and Jack walks out. Walcott comes out smiling. They met and the referee put his arm on each of their shoulders. \'93Hello, popularity,\'94 Jack says to Walcott. \'93Be yourself.\'94 \'93What do you call yourself \'91Walcott\'92 for?\'94 Jack says. \'93Didn\'92t you know he was a nigger?\'94 \'93Listen\'97\'94 says the referee, and he gives them the same old line. Once Walcott interrupts him. He grabs Jack\'92s arm and says, \'93Can I hit when he\'92s got me like this?\'94 \'93Keep your hands off me,\'94 Jack says. \'93There ain\'92t no moving-pictures of this.\'94 They went back to their corners. I lifted the bathrobe off Jack and he leaned on the ropes and flexed his knees a couple of times and scuffed his shoes in the rosin. The gong rang and Jack turned quick and went out. Walcott came toward him and they touched gloves and as soon as Walcott dropped his hands Jack jumped his left into his face twice. There wasn\'92t anybody ever boxed better than Jack. Walcott was after him, going forward all the time with his chin on his chest. He\'92s a hooker and he carries his hands pretty low. All he knows is to get in there and sock. But every time he gets in there close. Jack has the left hand in his face. It\'92s just as though it\'92s automatic. Jack just raises the left hand up and it\'92s in Walcott\'92s face. Three or four times Jack brings the right over but Walcott gets it on the shoulder or high up on the head. He\'92s just like all these hookers. The only thing he\'92s afraid of is another one of the same kind. He\'92s covered everywhere you can hurt him. He don\'92t care about a left hand in his face. After about four rounds Jack has him bleeding bad and his face all cut up, but every time Walcott\'92s got in close he\'92s socked so hard he\'92s got two big red patches on both sides just below Jack\'92s ribs. Every time he gets in close, Jack ties him up, then gets one hand loose and uppercuts him, but when Walcott gets his hands loose he socks Jack in the body so they can hear it outside in the street. He\'92s a socker. It goes along like that for three rounds more. They don\'92t talk any. They\'92re working all the time. We worked over Jack plenty too, in between the rounds. He don\'92t look good at all but he never does much work in the ring. He don\'92t move around much and that left hand is just automatic. It\'92s just like it was connected with Walcott\'92s face and Jack just had to wish it in every time. Jack is always calm in close and he doesn\'92t waste any juice. He knows everything about working in close too and he\'92s getting away with a lot of stuff. While they were in our corner I watched him tie Walcott up, get his right hand loose, turn it and come up with an uppercut that got Walcott\'92s nose with the heel of the glove. Walcott was bleeding bad and leaned his nose on Jack\'92s shoulder so as to give Jack some of it too, and Jack sort of lifted his shoulder sharp and caught him against the nose, and then brought down the right hand and did the same thing again. Walcott was sore as hell. By the time they\'92d gone five rounds he hated Jack\'92s guts. Jack wasn\'92t sore; that is, he wasn\'92t any sorer than he always was. He certainly did used to make the fellows he fought hate boxing. That was why he hated Kid Lewis so. He never got the Kid\'92s goat. Kid Lewis always had about three new dirty things Jack couldn\'92t do. Jack was as safe as a church all the time he was in there, as long as he was strong. He certainly was treating Walcott rough. The funny thing was it looked as though Jack was an open classic boxer. That was because he had all that stuff too. After the seventh round Jack says, \'93My left\'92s getting heavy.\'94 From then he started to take a beating. It didn\'92t show at first. But instead of him running the fight it was Walcott was running it