tood up, took the saucer of oil and went into the small room of the hut where he slept. \'93I\'92m going to take a little sleep,\'94 he said to the adjutant. In that army an adjutant is not a commissioned officer. \'93You will finish up.\'94 \'93Yes, signor maggiore,\'94 the adjutant answered. He leaned back in his chair and yawned. He took a paper-covered book out of the pocket of his coat and opened it; then laid it down on the table and lit his pipe. He leaned forward on the table to read and puffed at his pipe. Then he closed the book and put it back in his pocket. He had too much paper-work to get through. He could not enjoy reading until it was done. Outside, the sun went behind a mountain and there was no more light on the wall of the hut. A soldier came in and put some pine branches, chopped into irregular lengths, into the stove. \'93Be soft, Pinin,\'94 the adjutant said to him. \'93The major is sleeping.\'94 Pinin was the major\'92s orderly. He was a dark-faced boy, and he fixed the stove, putting the pine wood in carefully, shut the door, and went into the back of the hut again. The adjutant went on with his papers. \'93Tonani,\'94 the major called. \'93Signor maggiore?\'94 \'93Send Pinin in to me.\'94 \'93Pinin!\'94 the adjutant called. Pinin came into the room. \'93The major wants you,\'94 the adjutant said. Pinin walked across the main room of the hut toward the major\'92s door. He knocked on the halfopened door. \'93Signor maggiore?\'94 \'93Come in,\'94 the adjutant heard the major say, \'93and shut the door.\'94 Inside the room the major lay on his bunk. Pinin stood beside the bunk. The major lay with his head on the rucksack that he had stuffed with spare clothing to make a pillow. His long, burned, oiled face looked at Pinin. His hands lay on the blankets. \'93You are nineteen?\'94 he asked. \'93Yes, signor maggiore.\'94 \'93You have ever been in love?\'94 \'93How do you mean, signor maggiore?\'94 \'93In love\'97with a girl?\'94 \'93I have been wit