m the big lamp. Nick opened the door and went in. \'93Well, Nickie,\'94 his father said, \'93was it a good day?\'94 \'93I had a swell time. Dad. It was a swell Fourth of July.\'94 \'93Are you hungry?\'94 \'93You bet.\'94 \'93What did you do with your shoes?\'94 \'93I left them in the wagon at Garner\'92s.\'94 \'93Come on out to the kitchen.\'94 Nick\'92s father went ahead with the lamp. He stopped and lifted the lid of the ice-box. Nick went on into the kitchen. His father brought in a piece of cold chicken on a plate and a pitcher of milk and put them on the table before Nick. He put down the lamp. \'93There\'92s some pie too,\'94 he said. \'93Will that hold you?\'94 \'93It\'92s grand.\'94 His father sat down in a chair beside the oil-cloth-covered table. He made a big shadow on the kitchen wall. \'93Who won the ball game?\'94 \'93Petoskey. Five to three.\'94 His father sat watching him eat and filled his glass from the milk-pitcher. Nick drank and wiped his mouth on his napkin. His father reached over to the shelf for the pie. He cut Nick a big piece. It was huckleberry pie. \'93What did you do, Dad?\'94 \'93I went out fishing in the morning.\'94 \'93What did you get?\'94 \'93Only perch.\'94 His father sat watching Nick eat the pie. \'93What did you do this afternoon?\'94 Nick asked. \'93I went for a walk up by the Indian camp.\'94 \'93Did you see anybody?\'94 \'93The Indians were all in town getting drunk.\'94 \'93Didn\'92t you see anybody at all?\'94 \'93I saw your friend, Prudie.\'94 \'93Where was she?\'94 \'93She was in the woods with Frank Washburn. I ran onto them. They were having quite a time.\'94 His father was not looking at him. \'93What were they doing?\'94 \'93I didn\'92t stay to find out.\'94 \'93Tell me what they were doing.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 his father said. \'93I just heard them threshing around.\'94 \'93How did you know it was them?\'94 \'93I saw them.\'94 \'93I thought you said you didn\'92t see them.\'94 \'93Oh, yes, I saw them.\'94 