me, from where he lives, on skis until the snow melts. So today he brought her in to be buried and the priest, when he looked at her face, didn\'92t want to bury her. You go on and tell it,\'94 he said to the sexton. \'93Speak German, not dialect.\'94 \'93It was very funny with the priest,\'94 said the sexton. \'93In the report to the commune she died of heart trouble. We knew she had heart trouble here. She used to faint in church sometimes. She did not come for a long time. She wasn\'92t strong to climb. When the priest uncovered her face he asked Olz, \'91Did your wife suffer much?\'92 \'91No\'92 said Olz. \'91When I came in the house she was dead across the bed.\'92 \'93The priest looked at her again. He didn\'92t like it. \'93 \'91How did her face get that way?\'92 \'93\'91don\'92t know,\'92 Olz said. \'93\'91You\'92d better find out,\'92 the priest said, and put the blanket back. Olz didn\'92t say anything. The priest looked at him. Olz looked back at the priest. \'91You want to know?\'92 \'93\'91must know,\'92 the priest said.\'94 \'93This is where it\'92s good,\'94 the innkeeper said. \'93Listen to this. Go on Franz.\'94 \'93\'91Well,\'92 said Olz, \'91when she died I made the report to the commune and I put her in the shed across the top of the big wood. When I started to use the big wood she was stiff and I put her up against the wall. Her mouth was open and when I came into the shed at night to cut up the big wood, I hung the lantern from it.\'92 \'93\'91Why did you do that?\'92 asked the priest. \'93\'91don\'92t know,\'92 said Olz. \'93\'91Did you do that many times?\'92 \'93\'91Every time I went to work in the shed at night.\'92 \'93\'91It was very wrong,\'92 said the priest. \'91Did you love your wife?\'92 \'93\'91Ja, I loved her,\'92 Olz said. \'91I loved her fine.\'92\'94 \'93Did you understand it all?\'94 asked the innkeeper. \'93You understand it all about his wife?\'94 \'93I heard it.\'94 \'93How about eating?\'94 John asked. \'93You order,\'94 I said. \'93Do you think it\'92s true?\'94 I asked the innkeeper. \'93Sure it\'92s true,\'94 he said. \'93These peasants are beasts.\'94 \'93Where did he go now?\'94 \'93He\'92s gone to drink at my colleague\'92s, the L\'f6wen.\'94 \'93He didn\'92t want to drink with me,\'94 said the sexton. \'93He didn\'92t want to drink with me, after he knew about his wife,\'94 said the innkeeper. \'93Say,\'94 said John. \'93How about eating?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. A Pursuit Race WILLIAM CAMPBELL HAD BEEN IN A PUR suit race with a burlesque show ever since Pittsburgh. In a pursuit race, in bicycle racing, riders start at equal intervals to ride after one another. They ride very fast because the race is usually limited to a short distance and if they slow their riding another rider who maintains his pace will make up the space that separated them equally at the start. As soon as a rider is caught and passed he is out of the race and must get down from his bicycle and leave the track. If none of the riders are caught the winner of the race is the one who has gained the most distance. In most pursuit races, if there are only two riders, one of the riders is caught inside of six miles. The burlesque show caught William Campbell at Kansas City. William Campbell had hoped to hold a slight lead over the burlesque show until they reached the Pacific coast. As long as he preceded the burlesque show as advance man he was being paid. When the burlesque show caught up with him he was in bed. He was in bed when the manager of the burlesque troupe came into his room and after the manager had gone out he decided that he might as well stay in bed. It was very cold in Kansas City and he was in no hurry to go out. He did not like Kansas City. He reached under the bed for a bottle and drank. It made his stomach feel better. Mr. Turner, the manager of the burlesque show, had refused a drink. William Campbell\'92s interview with Mr. Turner had been a little strange. Mr. Turner had knocked on the door. Campbell had said: \'93Come in!\'94 When Mr. Turner came into the room he saw clothing on a chair, an open suitcase, the bottle on a chair beside the bed, and some one lying in the bed completely covered by the bed-clothes. \'93Mister Campbell,\'94 Mr. Turner said. \'93You can\'92t fire me,\'94 William Campbell said from underneath the covers. It was warm and white and close under the covers. \'93You can\'92t fire me because I\'92ve got down off my bicycle.\'94 \'93You\'92re drunk,\'94 Mr. Turner said. \'93Oh, yes,\'94 William Campbell said, speaking directly against the sheet and feeling the texture with his lips. \'93You\'92re a fool,\'94 Mr. Turner said. He turned off the electric light. The electric light had been burning all night. It was now ten o\'92clock in the morning. \'93You\'92re a drunken fool. When did you get into this town?\'94 \'93I got into this town last night,\'94 William Campbell said, speaking against the sheet. He found he liked to talk through a sheet. \'93Did you ever talk through a sheet?\'94 \'93Don\'92t try to be funny. You aren\'92t funny.\'94 \'93I\'92m not being funny. I\'92m just talking through a sheet.\'94 \'93You\'92re talking through a sheet all right.\'94 \'93You can go now, Mr. Turner,\'94 Campbell said. \'93I don\'92t work for you any more.\'94 \'93You know that anyway.\'94 \'93I know a lot,\'94 William Campbell said. He pulled down the sheet and looked at Mr. Turner. \'93I know enough so I don\'92t mind looking at you at all. Do you want to hear what I know?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 said William Campbell. \'93Because really I don\'92t know anything at all. I was just talking.\'94 He pulled the sheet up over his face again. \'93I love it under a sheet,\'94 he said. Mr. Turner stood beside the bed. He was a middle-aged man with a large stomach and a bald head and he had many things to do. \'93You ought to stop off here, Billy, and take a cure,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92ll fix it up if you want to do it.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to take a cure,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93I don\'92t want to take a cure at all. I am perfectly happy. All my life I have been perfectly happy.\'94 \'93How long have you been this way?\'94 \'93What a question!\'94 William Campbell breathed in and out through the sheet. \'93How long have you been stewed, Billy?\'94 \'93Haven\'92t I done my work?\'94 \'93Sure. I just asked you how long you\'92ve been stewed, Billy.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. But I\'92ve got my wolf back,\'94 he touched the sheet with his tongue. \'93I\'92ve had him for a week.\'94 \'93The hell you have.\'94 \'93Oh, yes. My dear wolf. Every time I take a drink he goes outside the room. He can\'92t stand alcohol. The poor little fellow.\'94 He moved his tongue round and round on the sheet. \'93He\'92s a lovely wolf. He\'92s just like he always was.\'94 William Campbell shut his eyes and took a deep breath. \'93You got to take a cure, Billy,\'94 Mr. Turner said. \'93You won\'92t mind the Keeley. It isn\'92t bad.\'94 \'93The Keeley,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93It isn\'92t far from London.\'94 He shut his eyes and opened them, moving the eyelashes against the sheet. \'93I just love sheets,\'94 he said. He looked at Mr. Turner. \'93Listen, you think I\'92m drunk.\'94 \'93You are drunk.\'94 \'93No, I\'92m not.\'94 \'93You\'92re drunk and you\'92ve had D.T.\'92s.\'94 \'93No.\'94 William Campbell held the sheet around his head. \'93Dear sheet,\'94 he said. He breathed against it gently. \'93Pretty sheet. You love me, don\'92t you, sheet? It\'92s all in the price of the room. Just like in Japan. No,\'94 he said. \'93Listen Billy, dear Sliding Billy, I have a surprise for you. I\'92m not drunk. I\'92m hopped to the eyes.\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Mr. Turner. \'93Take a look.\'94 William Campbell pulled up the right sleeve of his pyjama jacket under the sheet, then shoved the right forearm out. \'93Look at that.\'94 On the forearm, from just above the wrist to the elbow, were small blue circles around tiny dark blue punctures. The circles almost touched one another. \'93That\'92s trie new development,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93I drink a little now once in a while, just to drive the wolf out of the room.\'94 \'93They got a cure for that,\'94 \'93Sliding Billy\'94 Turner said. \'93No,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93They haven\'92t got a cure for anything.\'94 \'93You can\'92t just quit like that, Billy,\'94 Turner said. He sat on the bed. \'93Be careful of my sheet,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93You can\'92t just quit at your age and take to pumping yourself full of that stuff just because you got in a jam.\'94 \'93There\'92s a law against it. If that\'92s what you mean.\'94 \'93No, I mean you got to fight it out.\'94 Billy Campbell caressed the sheet with his lips and his tongue. \'93Dear sheet,\'94 he said. \'93I can kiss this sheet and see right through it at the same time.\'94 \'93Cut it out about the sheet. You can\'92t just take to that stuff, Billy.\'94 William Campbell shut his eyes. He was beginning to feel a slight nausea. He knew that this nausea would increase steadily, without there ever being the relief of sickness, until something were done against it. It was at this point that he suggested that Mr. Turner have a drink. Mr. Turner declined. William Campbell took a drink from the bottle. It was a temporary measure. Mr. Turner watched him. Mr. Turner had been in this room much longer than he should have been, he had many things to do; although living in daily association with people who used drugs, he had a horror of drugs, and he was very fond of William Campbell; he did not wish to leave him. He was very sorry for him and he felt a cure might help. He knew there were good cures in Kansas City. But he had to go. He stood up. \'93Listen, Billy,\'94 William Campbell said, \'93I want to tell you something. You\'92re called \'91Sliding Billy.\'92 That\'92s because you can slide. I\'92m called just Billy. That\'92s because I never could slide at all. I