n,\'94 said the adjutant stiffly. \'93I fought in Tripoli.\'94 \'93It\'92s quite something to have met you,\'94 Nick put out his hand. \'93Those must have been trying days. I noticed the ribbons. Were you, by any chance, on the Carso?\'94 \'93I have just been called up for this war. My class was too old.\'94 \'93At one time I was under the age limit,\'94 Nick said. \'93But now I am reformed out of the war.\'94 \'93But why are you here now?\'94 \'93I am demonstrating the American uniform,\'94 Nick said. \'93Don\'92t you think it is very significant? It is a little tight in the collar but soon you will see untold millions wearing this uniform swarming like locusts. The grasshopper, you know, what we call the grasshopper in America, is really a locust. The true grasshopper is small and green and comparatively feeble. You must not, however, make a confusion with the seven-year locust or cicada which emits a peculiar sustained sound which at the moment I cannot recall. I try to recall it but I cannot. I can almost hear it and then it is quite gone. You will pardon me if I break off our conversation?\'94 \'93See if you can find the major,\'94 the adjutant said to one of the two runners. \'93I can see you have been wounded,\'94 he said to Nick. \'93In various places,\'94 Nick said. \'93If you are interested in scars I can show you some very interesting ones but I would rather talk about grasshoppers. What we call grasshoppers that is; and what are, really, locusts. These insects at one time played a very important part in my life. It might interest you and you can look at the uniform while I am talking.\'94 The adjutant made a motion with his hand to the second runner who went out. \'93Fix your eyes on the uniform. Spagnolini made it, you know. You might as well look, too,\'94 Nick said to the signallers. \'93I really have no rank. We\'92re under the American consul. It\'92s perfectly all right for you to look. You can stare, if you like. I will tell you about the American