ike to have you remember. One thing I would like you to take with you as you leave this room. Gentlemen, either you must govern\'97or you must be governed. That is all, gentlemen. Good-day.\'94 He removed his cloth-covered helmet, put it on again and, stooping, went out the low entrance of the dugout. Para, accompanied by the two runners, was coming down the line of the sunken road. It was very hot in the sun and Nick removed the helmet. \'93There ought to be a system for wetting these things,\'94 he said. \'93I shall wet this one in the river.\'94 He started up the bank. \'93Nicolo,\'94 Paravicini called. \'93Nicolo. Where are you going?\'94 \'93I don\'92t really have to go.\'94 Nick came down the slope, holding the helmet in his hands. \'93They\'92re a damned nuisance wet or dry. Do you wear yours all the time?\'94 \'93All the time,\'94 said Para. \'93It\'92s making me bald. Come inside.\'94 Inside Para told him to sit down. \'93You know they\'92re absolutely no damned good,\'94 Nick said. \'93I remember when they were a comfort when we first had them, but I\'92ve seen them full of brains too many times.\'94 \'93Nicolo,\'94 Para said. \'93I think you should go back. I think it would be better if you didn\'92t come up to the line until you had those supplies. There\'92s nothing here for you to do. If you move around, even with something worth giving away, the men will group and that invites shelling. I won\'92t have it.\'94 \'93I know it\'92s silly,\'94 Nick said. \'93It wasn\'92t my idea. I heard the brigade was here so I thought I would see you or some one else I knew. I could have gone to Zenzon or to San Dona. I\'92d like to go to San Dona to see the bridge again.\'94 \'93I won\'92t have you circulating around to no purpose,\'94 Captain Paravicini said. \'93All right,\'94 said Nick. He felt it coming on again. \'93You understand?\'94 \'93Of course,\'94 said Nick. He was trying to hold it in. \'93Anything of that sort should be done at night.\'94 \'93Naturally,\