2t like the smell of the hops in the carts. Nor in the fields. Je n\'92aime pas les houblons. No, my God, not a bit. The man that owns the brewery said to me and my sister to go to the brewery and drink the beer, and then we\'92d like the hops. That\'92s true. Then we liked them all right. He had them give us the beer. We liked them all right then. But Fontan, il est crazy pour le vin. One time he killed a jack-rabbit and he wanted me to cook it with a sauce with wine, make a black sauce with wine and butter and mushrooms and onion and everything in it, for the jack. My God, I make the sauce all right, and he eat it all and said, \'91La sauce est meilleure que le jack.\'92 Dans son pays c\'92est comme \'e7a. Il y a beaucoup de gibier et de vin. Moi, j\'92aime les pommes de terre, le saucisson, et la bi\'e8re. C\'92est bon, la bi\'e8re. C\'92est tr\'e8s bon pour la sant\'e9.\'94 \'93It\'92s good,\'94 I said. \'93It and wine too.\'94 \'93You\'92re like Fontan. But there was a thing here that I never saw. I don\'92t think you\'92ve ever seen it either. There were Americans came here and they put whiskey in the beer.\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93Oui. My God, yes, that\'92s true. Et aussi une femme qui a vomis sur la table!\'94 \'93Comment?\'94 \'93C\'92est vrai. Elle a vomis sur la table. Et apr\'e8s elle a vomis dans ses shoes. And afterward they come back and say they want to come again and have another party the next Saturday, and I say no, my God, no! When they came I locked the door.\'94 \'93They\'92re bad when they\'92re drunk.\'94 \'93In the winter-time when the boys go to the dance they come in the cars and wait outside and say to Fontan, \'91Hey, Sam, sell us a bottle wine,\'92 or they buy the beer, and then they take the moonshine out of their pockets in a bottle and pour it in the beer and drink it. My God, that\'92s the first time I ever saw that in my life. They put whiskey in the beer. My God, I don\'92t understand that!\'94 \'93They want to get sick, so they\'92ll know they\'92re drunk.\'94 \'93One time a fellow comes here came to me and said he wanted me to cook them a big supper and they drink one two bottles of wine, and their girls come too, and then they go to the dance. All right, I said. So I made a big supper, and when they come already they drank a lot. Then they put whiskey in the wine. My God, yes. I said to Fontan, \'91On va \'eatre malade!\'92 \'91Oui,\'92 il dit. Then these girls were sick, nice girls too, all-right girls. They were sick right at the table. Fontan tried to take them by the arm and show them where they could be sick all right in the cabinet, but the fellows said no, they were all right right there at the table.\'94 Fontan had come in. \'93When they come again I locked the door. \'91No,\'92 I said. \'91Not for hundred fifty dollars.\'92 My God, no.\'94 \'93There is a word for such people when they do like that, in French,\'94 Fontan said. He stood looking very old and tired from the heat. \'93What?\'94 \'93Cochon,\'94 he said delicately, hesitating to use such a strong word. \'93They were like the cochon. C\'92est un mot tr\'e8s fort,\'94 he apologized, \'93mais vomir sur la table\'97\'94 he shook his head sadly. \'93Cochons,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s what they are\'97cochons. Salauds.\'94 The grossness of the words was distasteful to Fontan. He was glad to speak of something else. \'93Il y a des gens tr\'e8s gentils, tr\'e8s sensibles, qui viennent aussi,\'94 he said. \'93There are officers from the fort. Very nice men. Good fellas. Everybody that was ever in France they want to come and drink wine. They like wine all right.\'94 \'93There was one man,\'94 Madame Fontan said, \'93and his wife never lets him get out. So he tells her he\'92s tired, and goes to bed, and when she goes to the show he comes straight down here, sometimes in his pyjamas just with a coat over them. \'91Maria, some beer,\'92 he says, \'91for God\'92s sake.\'92 He sits in his pyjamas and drinks the beer, and then he goes up to the fort and gets back in bed before his wife comes home from the show.\'94 \'93C\'92est un original,\'94 Fontan said, \'93mais vraiment gentil. He\'92s a nice fella.\'94 \'93My God, yes, nice fella all right,\'94 Madame Fontan said. \'93He\'92s always in bed when his wife gets back from the show.\'94 \'93I have to go away tomorrow,\'94 I said. \'93To the Crow Reservation. We go there for the opening of the prairie-chicken season.\'94 \'93Yes? You come back here before you go away. You come back here all right?\'94 \'93Absolutely.\'94 \'93Then the wine will be done,\'94 Fontan said. \'93We\'92ll drink a bottle together.\'94 \'93Three bottles,\'94 Madame Fontan said. \'93I\'92ll be back,\'94 I said. \'93We count on you,\'94 Fontan said. \'93Good night,\'94 I said. We got in early in the afternoon from the shooting-trip. We had been up that morning since five o\'92clock. The day before we had had good shooting, but that morning we had not seen a prairiechicken. Riding in the open car, we were very hot and we stopped to eat our lunch out of the sun, under a tree beside the road. The sun was high and the patch of shade was very small. We ate sandwiches and crackers with sandwich filling on them, and were thirsty and tired, and glad when we finally were out and on the main road back to town. We came up behind a prairie-dog town and stopped the car to shoot at the prairie-dogs with the pistol. We shot two, but then stopped, because the bullets that missed glanced off the rocks and the dirt, and sung off across the fields, and beyond the fields there were some trees along a watercourse, with a house, and we did not want to get in trouble from stray bullets going toward the house. So we drove on, and finally were on the road coming down-hill toward the outlying houses of the town. Across the plain we could see the mountains. They were blue that day, and the snow on the high mountains shone like glass. The summer was ending, but the new snow had not yet come to stay on the high mountains; there was only the old sun-melted snow and the ice, and from a long way away it shone very brightly. We wanted something cool and some shade. We were sun-burned and our lips blistered from the sun and alkali dust. We turned up the side road to Fontan\'92s, stopped the car outside the house, and went in. It was cool inside the dining-room. Madame Fontan was alone. \'93Only two bottles beer,\'94 she said. \'93It\'92s all gone. The new is no good yet.\'94 I gave her some birds. \'93That\'92s good,\'94 she said. \'93All right. Thanks. That\'92s good.\'94 She went out to put the birds away where it was cooler. When we finished the beer I stood up. \'93We have to go,\'94 I said. \'93You come back tonight all right? Fontan he\'92s going to have the wine.\'94 \'93We\'92ll come back before we go away.\'94 \'93You go away?\'94 \'93Yes. We have to leave in the morning.\'94 \'93That\'92s too bad you go away. You come tonight. Fontan will have the wine. We\'92ll make a f\'eate before you go.\'94 \'93We\'92ll come before we go.\'94 But that afternoon there were telegrams to send, the car to be gone over\'97a tire had been cut by a stone and needed vulcanizing\'97and, without the car, I walked into the town, doing things that had to be done before we could go. When it was supper-time I was too tired to go out. We did not want a foreign language. All we wanted was to go early to bed. As I lay in bed before I went to sleep, with all the things of the summer piled around ready to be packed, the windows open and the air coming in cool from the mountains, I thought it was a shame not to have gone to Fontan\'92s\'97but in a little while I was asleep. The next day we were busy all morning packing and ending the summer. We had lunch and were ready to start by two o\'92clock. \'93We must go and say good-by to the Fontans,\'94 I said. \'93Yes, we must.\'94 \'93I\'92m afraid they expected us last night.\'94 \'93I suppose we could have gone.\'94 \'93I wish we\'92d gone.\'94 We said good-by to the man at the desk at the hotel, and to Larry and our other friends in the town, and then drove out to Fontan\'92s. Both Monsieur and Madame were there. They were glad to see us. Fontan looked old and tired. \'93We thought you would come last night,\'94 Madame Fontan said. \'93Fontan had three bottles of wine. When you did not come he drank it all up.\'94 \'93We can only stay a minute,\'94 I said. \'93We just came to say good-by. We wanted to come last night. We intended to come, but we were too tired after the trip.\'94 \'93Go get some wine,\'94 Fontan said. \'93There is no wine. You drank it all up.\'94 Fontan looked very upset. \'93I\'92ll go get some,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92ll just be gone a few minutes. I drank it up last night. We had it for you.\'94 \'93I knew you were tired. \'91My God,\'92 I said, \'91they\'92re too tired all right to come,\'92\'94 Madame Fontan said. \'93Go get some wine, Fontan.\'94 \'93I\'92ll take you in the car,\'94 I said. \'93All right,\'94 Fontan said. \'93That way we\'92ll go faster.\'94 We drove down the road in the motor-car and turned up a side road about a mile away. \'93You\'92ll like that wine,\'94 Fontan said. \'93It\'92s come out well. You can drink it for supper tonight.\'94 We stopped in front of a frame house. Fontan knocked on the door. There was no answer. We went around to the back. The back door was locked too. There were empty tin cans around the back door. We looked in the window. There was nobody inside. The kitchen was dirty and sloppy, but all the doors and windows were tight shut.\'94 \'93That son of a bitch. Where is she gone out?\'94 Fontan said. He was desperate. \'93I know where I can get a key,\'94 he said. \'93You stay here.\'94 I watched him go down to the next house down the road, knock on the door, talk to the woman who came out, and finally come back. He had a key. We tried it on the front door and the back, but it wouldn\'92t work. \'93That son of a bitch,\'94 Fontan said. \'93She\'92s gone away somewhere.\'94 Looking through the window I could see where the wine was stored. Close to the window you could smell the inside of the house. It smelled sweet and sickish like an Indian house. Suddenly Fontan took a loose board and commenced digging at the earth beside the back door. \'93I can get in,\'94 he said. \'93Son of a bitch, I can get in.\'94 There was a man in the back yard of the next house doing something to one of the front wheels of an old Ford. \'93You better not,\'94 I said. \'93That man will see you. He\'92s watching.\'94 Fontan straightened up. \'93We\'92ll try the key once more,\'94 he said. We tried the key and it did not work. It turned half-way in either direction. \'93We can\'92t get in,\'94 I said. \'93We better go back.\'94 \'93I\'92ll dig up the back,\'94 Fontan offered. \'93No, I wouldn\'92t let you take the chance.\'94 \'93I\'92ll do it.\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93That man would see. Then they would seize it.\'94 We went out to the car and drove back to Fontan\'92s, stopping on the way to leave the key. Fontan did not say anything but swear in English. He was incoherent and crushed. We went in the house. \'93That son of a bitch!\'94 he said. \'93We couldn\'92t get the wine. My own wine that I made.\'94 All the happiness went from Madame Fontan\'92s face. Fontan sat down in a corner with his head in his hands. \'93We must go,\'94 I said. \'93It doesn\'92t make any difference about the wine. You drink to us when we\'92re gone.\'94 \'93Where did that crazy go?\'94 Madame Fontan asked. \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Fontan said. \'93I don\'92t know where she go. Now you go away without any wine.\'94 \'93That\'92s all right,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s no good,\'94 Madame Fontan said. She shook her head. \'93We have to go,\'94 I said. \'93Good-by and good luck. Thank you for the fine times.\'94 Fontan shook his head. He was disgraced. Madame Fontan looked sad. \'93Don\'92t feel bad about the wine,\'94 I said. \'93He wanted you to drink his wine,\'94 Madame Fontan said. \'93You can come back next year?\'94 \'93No. Maybe the year after.\'94 \'93You see?\'94 Fontan said to her. \'93Good-by,\'94 I said. \'93Don\'92t think about the wine. Drink some for us when we\'92re gone.\'94 Fontan shook his head. He did not smile. He knew when he was ruined. \'93That son of a bitch,\'94 Fontan said to himself. \'93Last night he had three bottles,\'94 Madame Fontan said to comfort him. He shook his head. \'93Good-by,\'94 he said. Madame Fontan had tears in her eyes. \'93Good-by,\'94 she said. She felt badly for Fontan. \'93Good-by,\'94 we said. We all felt very badly. They stood in the doorway and we got in, and I started the motor. We waved. They stood together sadly on the porch. Fontan looked very old, and Madame Fontan looked sad. She waved to us and Fontan went in the house. We turned up the road. \'93They felt so badly. Fontan felt terribly.\'94 \'93We ought to have gone last night.\'94 \'93Yes, we ought to have.\'94 We were through the town and out on the smooth road beyond, with the stubble of grain-fields on each side and the mountains off to the right. It looked like Spain, but it was Wyoming. \'93I hope they have a lot of good luck.\'94 \'93They won\'92t,\'94 I said, \'93and Schmidt won\'92t be President either.\'94 The cement road stopped. The road was gravelled now and we left the plain and started up between two foot-hills; the road in a curve and commencing to climb. The soil of the hills was red, the sage grew in gray clumps, and as the road rose we could see across the hills and away across the plain of the valley to the mountains. They were farther away now and they looked more like Spain than ever. The road curved and climbed again, and ahead there were some grouse dusting in the road. They flew as we came toward them, their wings beating fast, then sailing in long slants, and lit on the hillside below. \'93They are so big and lovely. They\'92re bigger than European patridges.\'94 \'93It\'92s a fine country for la chasse, Fontan says.\'94 \'93And when the chasse is gone?\'94 \'93They\'92ll be dead then.\'94 \'93The boy won\'92t.\'94 \'93There\'92s nothing to prove he won\'92t be,\'94 I said. \'93We ought to have gone last night.\'94 \'93Oh, yes,\'94 I said. \'93We ought to have gone.\'94 The Gambler, The Nun, and the Radio THEY BROUGHT THEM IN AROUND MID -night and then, all night long, every one along the corridor heard the Russian. \'93Where is he shot?\'94 Mr. Frazer asked the night nurse. \'93In the thigh, I think.\'94 \'93What about the other one?\'94 \'93Oh, he\'92s going to die, I\'92m afraid.\'94 \'93Where is he shot?\'94 \'93Twice in the abdomen. They only found one of the bullets.\'94 They were both beet workers, a Mexican and a Russian, and they were sitting drinking coffee in an all-night restaurant when some one came in the door and started shooting at the Mexican. The Russian crawled under a table and was hit, finally, by a stray shot fired at the Mexican as he lay on the floor with two bullets in his abdomen. That was what the paper said. The Mexican told the police he had no idea who shot him. He believed it to be an accident. \'93An accident that he fired eight shots at you and hit you twice, there?\'94 \'93S\'ed, se\'f1or,\'94 said the Mexican, who was named Cayetano Ruiz. \'93An accident that he hit me at all, the cabr\'f3n,\'94 he said to the interpreter. \'93What does he say?\'94 asked the detective sergeant, looking across the bed at the interpreter. \'93He says it was an accident.\'94 \'93Tell him to tell the truth, that he is going to die,\'94 the detective said. \'93Na,\'94 said Cayetano. \'93But tell him that I feel very sick and would prefer not to talk so much.\'94 \'93He says that he is telling the truth,\'94 the interpreter said. Then, speaking confidently, to the detective, \'93He don\'92t know who shot him. They shot him in the back.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said the detective. \'93I understand that, but why did the bullets all go in the front?\'94 \'93Maybe he is spinning around,\'94 said the interpreter. \'93Listen,\'94 said the detective, shaking his finger almost at Cayetano\'92s nose, which projected, waxen yellow, from his dead-man\'92s face in which his eyes were alive as a hawk\'92s. \'93I don\'92t give a damn who shot you, but I\'92ve got to clear this thing up. Don\'92t you want the man who shot you to be punished? Tell him that,\'94 he said to the interpreter. \'93He says to tell who shot you.\'94 \'93Mandarlo al carajo,\'94 said Cayetano, who was very tired. \'93He says he never saw the fellow at all,\'94 the interpreter said. \'93I tell you straight they shot him in the back.\'94 \'93Ask him who shot the Russian.\'94 \'93Poor Russian,\'94 said Cayetano. \'93He was on the floor with his head enveloped in his arms. He started to give cries when they shoot him and he is giving cries ever since. Poor Russian.\'94 \'93He says some fellow that he doesn\'92t know. Maybe the same fellow that shot him.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 the detective said. \'93This isn\'92t Chicago. You\'92re not a gangster. You don\'92t have to act like a moving picture. It\'92s all right to tell who shot you. Anybody would tell who shot them. That\'92s all right to do. Suppose you don\'92t tell who he is and he shoots somebody else. Suppose he shoots a woman or a child. You can\'92t let him get away with that. You tell him,\'94 he said to Mr. Frazer. \'93I don\'92t trust that damn interpreter.\'94 \'93I am very reliable,\'94 the interpreter said. Cayetano looked at Mr. Frazer. \'93Listen, amigo,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93The policeman says that we are not in Chicago but in Hailey, Montana. You are not a bandit and this has nothing to do with the cinema.\'94 \'93I believe him,\'94 said Cayetano softly. \'93Ya lo creo.\'94 \'93One can, with honor, denounce one\'92s assailant. Every one does it here, he says. He says what happens if after shooting you, this man shoots a woman or a child?\'94 \'93I am not married,\'94 Cayetano said. \'93He says any woman, any child.\'94 \'93The man is not crazy,\'94 Cayetano said. \'93He says you should denounce him,\'94 Mr. Frazer finished. \'93Thank you,\'94 Cayetano said. \'93You are of the great translators. I speak English, but badly. I understand it all right. How did you break your leg?\'94 \'93A fall off a horse.\'94 \'93What bad luck. I am very sorry. Does it hurt much?\'94 \'93Not now. At first, yes.\'94 \'93Listen, amigo,\'94 Cayetano began, \'93I am very weak. You will pardon me. Also I have much pain; enough pain. It is very possible that I die. Please get this policeman out of here because I am very tired.\'94 He made as though to roll to one side; then held himself still. \'93I told him everything exactly as you said and he said to tell you, truly, that he doesn\'92t know who shot him and that he is very weak and wishes you would question him later on,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93He\'92ll probably be dead later on.\'94 \'93That\'92s quite possible.\'94 \'93That\'92s why I want to question him now.\'94 \'93Somebody shot him in the back, I tell you,\'94 the interpreter said. \'93Oh, for Chrisake,\'94 the detective sergeant said, and put his notebook in his pocket. Outside in the corridor the detective sergeant stood with the interpreter beside Mr. Frazer\'92s wheeled chair. \'93I suppose you think somebody shot him in the back too?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 Frazer said. \'93Somebody shot him in the back. What\'92s it to you?\'94 \'93Don\'92t get sore,\'94 the sergeant said. \'93I wish I could talk spick.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you learn?\'94 \'93You don\'92t have to get sore. I don\'92t get any fun out of asking that spick questions. If I could talk spick it would be different.\'94 \'93You don\'92t need to talk Spanish,\'94 the interpreter said. \'93I am a very reliable interpreter.\'94 \'93Oh, for Chrisake,\'94 the sergeant said. \'93Well, so long. I\'92ll come up and see you.\'94 \'93Thanks. I\'92m always in.\'94 \'93I guess you are all right. That was bad luck all right. Plenty bad luck.\'94 \'93It\'92s coming along good now since he spliced the bone.\'94 \'93Yes, but it\'92s a long time. A long, long time.\'94 \'93Don\'92t let anybody shoot you in the back.\'94 \'93That\'92s right,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s right. Well, I\'92m glad you\'92re not sore.\'94 \'93So long,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. Mr. Frazer did not see Cayetano again for a long time, but each morning Sister Cecilia brought news of him. He was so uncomplaining she said and he was very bad now. He had peritonitis and they thought he could not live. Poor Cayetano, she said. He had such beautiful hands and such a fine face and he never complains. The odor, now, was really terrific. He would point toward his nose with one finger and smile and shake his head, she said. He felt badly about the odor. It embarrassed him, Sister Cecilia said. Oh, he was such a fine patient. He always smiled. He wouldn\'92t go to confession to Father but he promised to say his prayers, and not a Mexican had been to see him since he had been brought in. The Russian was going out at the end of the week. I could never feel anything about the Russian, Sister Cecilia said. Poor fellow, he suffered too. It was a greased bullet and dirty and the wound infected, but he made so much noise and then I always like the bad ones. That Cayetano, he\'92s a bad one. Oh, he must really be a bad one, a thoroughly bad one, he\'92s so fine and delicately made and he\'92s never done any work with his hands. He\'92s not a beet worker. I know he\'92s not a beet worker. His hands are as smooth and not a callous on them. I know he\'92s a bad one of some sort. I\'92m going down and pray for him now. Poor Cayetano, he\'92s having a dreadful time and he doesn\'92t make a sound. What did they have to shoot him for? Oh, that poor Cayetano! I\'92m going right down and pray for him. She went right down and prayed for him. In that hospital a radio did not work very well until it was dusk. They said it was because there was so much ore in the ground or something about the mountains, but anyway it did not work well at all until it began to get dark outside; but all night it worked beautifully and when one station stopped you could go farther west and pick up another. The last one that you could get was Seattle, Washington, and due to the difference in time, when they signed off at four o\'92clock in the morning it was five o\'92clock in the morning in the hospital; and at six o\'92clock you could get the morning revellers in Minneapolis. That was on account of the difference in time, too, and Mr. Frazer used to like to think of the morning revellers arriving at the studio and picture how they would look getting off a street-car before daylight in the morning carrying their instruments. Maybe that was wrong and they kept their instruments at the place they revelled, but he always pictured them with their instruments. He had never been in Minneapolis and believed he probably would never go there, but he knew what it looked like that early in the morning. Out of the window of the hospital you could see a field with tumbleweed coming out of the snow, and a bare clay butte. One morning the doctor wanted to show Mr. Frazer two pheasants that were out there in the snow, and pulling the bed toward the window, the reading light fell off the iron bedstead and hit Mr. Frazer on the head. This does not sound so funny now but it was very funny then. Every one was looking out the window, and the doctor, who was a most excellent doctor, was pointing at the pheasants and pulling the bed toward the window, and then, just as in a comic section, Mr. Frazer was knocked out by the leaded base of the lamp hitting the top of his head. It seemed the antithesis of healing or whatever people were in the hospital for, and every one thought it was very funny, as a joke on Mr. Frazer and on the doctor. Everything is much simpler in a hospital, including the jokes. From the other window, if the bed was turned, you could see the town, with a little smoke above it, and the Dawson mountains looking like real mountains with the winter snow on them. Those were the two views since the wheeled chair had proved to be premature. It is really best to be in bed if you are in a hospital; since two views, with time to observe them, from a room the temperature of which you control, are much better than any number of views seen for a few minutes from hot, empty rooms that are waiting for some one else, or just abandoned, which you are wheeled in and out of. If you stay long enough in a room the view, whatever it is, acquires a great value and becomes very important and you would not change it, not even by a different angle. Just as, with the radio, there are certain things that you become fond of, and you welcome them and resent the new things. The best tunes they had that winter were \'93Sing Something Simple,\'94 \'93Singsong Girl,\'94 and \'93Little White Lies.\'94 No other tunes were as satisfactory, Mr. Frazer felt. \'93Betty Co-ed\'94 was a good tune too, but the parody of the words which came unavoidably into Mr. Frazer\'92s mind, grew so steadily and increasingly obscene that there being no one to appreciate it, he finally abandoned it and let the song go back to football. About nine o\'92clock in the morning they would start using the X-ray machine, and then the radio, which, by then, was only getting Hailey, became useless. Many people in Hailey who owned radios protested about the hospital\'92s X-ray machine which ruined their morning reception, but there was never any action taken, although many felt it was a shame the hospital could not use their machine at a time when people were not using their radios. About the time when it became necessary to turn off the radio Sister Cecilia came in. \'93How\'92s Cayetano, Sister Cecilia?\'94 Mr. Frazer asked. \'93Oh, he\'92s very bad.\'94 \'93Is he out of his head?\'94 \'93No, but I\'92m afraid he\'92s going to die.\'94 \'93How are you?\'94 \'93I\'92m very worried about him, and do you know that absolutely no one has come to see him? He could die just like a dog for all those Mexicans care. They\'92re really dreadful.\'94 \'93Do you want to come up and hear the game this afternoon?\'94 \'93Oh, no,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92d be too excited. I\'92ll be in the chapel praying.\'94 \'93We ought to be able to hear it pretty well,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93They\'92re playing out on the coast and the difference in time will bring it late enough so we can get it all right.\'94 \'93Oh, no. I couldn\'92t do it. The world series nearly finished me. When the Athletics were at bat I was praying right out loud: \'91Oh, Lord, direct their batting eyes! Oh, Lord, may he hit one! Oh, Lord, may he hit safely!\'92 Then when they filled the bases in the third game, you remember, it was too much for me. \'91Oh, Lord, may he hit it out of the lot! Oh, Lord, may he drive it clean over the fence!\'92 Then you know when the Cardinals would come to bat it was simply dreadful. \'91Oh, Lord, may they not see it! Oh, Lord, don\'92t let them even catch a glimpse of it! Oh, Lord, may they fan!\'92And this game is even worse. It\'92s Notre Dame. Our Lady. No, I\'92ll be in the chapel. For Our Lady. They\'92re playing for Our Lady. I wish you\'92d write something sometime for Our Lady. You could do it. You know you could do it, Mr. Frazer.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know anything about her that I could write. It\'92s mostly been written already,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93You wouldn\'92t like the way I write. She wouldn\'92t care for it either.\'94 \'93You\'92ll write about her sometime,\'94 Sister said. \'93I know you will. You must write about Our Lady.\'94 \'93You\'92d better come up and hear the game.\'94 \'93It would be too much for me. No, I\'92ll be in the chapel doing what I can.\'94 That afternoon they had been playing about five minutes when a probationer came into the room and said, \'93Sister Cecilia wants to know how the game is going?\'94 \'93Tell her they have a touchdown already.\'94 In a little while the probationer came into the room again. \'93Tell her they\'92re playing them off their feet,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. A little later he rang the bell for the nurse who was on floor duty. \'93Would you mind going down to the chapel or sending word down to Sister Cecilia that Notre Dame has them fourteen to nothing at the end of the first quarter and that it\'92s all right. She can stop praying.\'94 In a few minutes Sister Cecilia came into the room. She was very excited. \'93What does fourteen to nothing mean? I don\'92t know anything about this game. That\'92s a nice safe lead in baseball. But I don\'92t know anything about football. It may not mean a thing. I\'92m going right back down to the chapel and pray until it\'92s finished.\'94 \'93They have them beaten,\'94 Frazer said. \'93I promise you. Stay and listen with me.\'94 \'93No. No. No. No. No. No. No,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92m going right down to the chapel to pray.\'94 Mr. Frazer sent down word whenever Notre Dame scored, and finally, when it had been dark a long time, the final result. \'93How\'92s Sister Cecilia?\'94 \'93They\'92re all at chapel,\'94 she said. The next morning Sister Cecilia came in. She was very pleased and confident. \'93I knew they couldn\'92t beat Our Lady,\'94 she said. \'93They couldn\'92t. Cayetano\'92s better too. He\'92s much better. He\'92s going to have visitors. He can\'92t see them yet, but they are going to come and that will make him feel better and know he\'92s not forgotten by his own people. I went down and saw that O\'92Brien boy at Police Headquarters and told him that he\'92s got to send some Mexicans up to see poor Cayetano. He\'92s going to send some this afternoon. Then that poor man will feel better. It\'92s wicked the way no one has come to see him.\'94 That afternoon about five o\'92clock three Mexicans came into the room. \'93Can one?\'94 asked the biggest one, who had 