eve it.\'94 \'93From me,\'94 said the smallest one, \'93he won one hundred and eighty dollars. Now there is no longer one hundred and eighty dollars in the world.\'94 \'93From me,\'94 said the thin one, \'93he won two hundred and eleven dollars. Fix yourself on that figure.\'94 \'93I never played with him,\'94 said the fat one. \'93He must be very rich,\'94 Mr. Frazer suggested. \'93He is poorer than we,\'94 said the little Mexican. \'93He has no more than the shirt on his back.\'94 \'93And that shirt is of little value now,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93Perforated as it is.\'94 \'93Clearly.\'94 \'93The one who wounded him was a card-player?\'94 \'93No, a beet worker. He has had to leave town.\'94 \'93Fix yourself on this,\'94 said the smallest one. \'93He was the best guitar player ever in this town. The finest.\'94 \'93What a shame.\'94 \'93I believe it,\'94 said the biggest one. \'93How he could touch the guitar.\'94 \'93There are no good guitar players left?\'94 \'93Not the shadow of a guitar player.\'94 \'93There is an accordion player who is worth something,\'94 the thin man said. \'93There are a few who touch various instruments,\'94 the big one said. \'93You like music?\'94 \'93How would I not?\'94 \'93We will come one night with music? You think the sister would allow it? She seems very amiable.\'94 \'93I am sure she would permit it when Cayetano is able to hear it.\'94 \'93Is she a little crazy?\'94 asked the thin one. \'93Who?\'94 \'93That sister.\'94 \'93No,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93She is a fine woman of great intelligence and sympathy.\'94 \'93I distrust all priests, monks, and sisters,\'94 said the thin one. \'93He had bad experiences when a boy,\'94 the smallest one said. \'93I was acolyte,\'94 the thin one said proudly. \'93Now I believe in nothing. Neither do I go to mass.\'94 \'93Why? Does it mount to your head?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said the thin one. \'93It is alcohol that mounts to my head. Religion is the opium of the poor.\'94 \'93I thought marijuana was the opium of the poor,\'94 Frazer said. \'93Did you ever smoke opium?\'94 the big one asked. \'93No.\'94 \'93Nor I,\'94 he said. \'93It seems it is very bad. One commences and cannot stop. It is a vice.\'94 \'93Like religion,\'94 said the thin one. \'93This one,\'94 said the smallest Mexican, \'93is very strong against religion.\'94 \'93It is necessary to be very strong against something,\'94 Mr. Frazer said politely. \'93I respect those who have faith even though they are ignorant,\'94 the thin one said. \'93Good,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93What can we bring you?\'94 asked the big Mexican. \'93Do you lack for anything?\'94 \'93I would be glad to buy some beer if there is good beer.\'94 \'93We will bring beer.\'94 \'93Another copita before you go?\'94 \'93It is very good.\'94 \'93We are robbing you.\'94 \'93I can\'92t take it. It goes to my head. Then I have a bad headache and sick at the stomach.\'94 \'93Good-by, gentlemen.\'94 \'93Good-by and thanks.\'94 They went out and there was supper and then the radio, turned to be as quiet as possible and still be heard, and the stations finally signing off in this order: Denver, Salt Lake City, Los Angeles, and Seattle. Mr. Frazer received no picture of Denver from the radio. He could see Denver from the Denver Post, and correct the picture from The Rocky Mountain News. Nor did he ever have any feel of Salt Lake City or Los Angeles from what he heard from those places. All he felt about Salt Lake City was that it was dean, but dull, and there were too many ballrooms mentioned in too many big hotels for him to see Los Angeles. He could not feel it for the ballrooms. But Seattle he came to know very well, the taxicab company with the big white cabs (each cab equipped with radio itself) he rode in every night out to the roadhouse on the Canadian side where he followed the course of parties by the musical selections they phoned for. He lived in Seattle from two o\'92clock on, each night, hearing the pieces that all the different people asked for, and it was as real as Minneapolis, where the revellers left their beds each morning to make that trip down to the studio. Mr. Frazer grew very fond of Seattle, Washington. The Mexicans came and brought beer but it was not good beer. Mr. Frazer saw them but he did not feel like talking, and when they went he knew they would not come again. His nerves had become tricky and he disliked seeing people while he was in this condition. His nerves went bad at the end of five weeks, and while he was pleased they lasted that long yet he resented being forced to make the same experiment when he already knew the answer. Mr. Frazer had been through this all before. The only thing which was new to him was the radio. He played it all night long, turned so low he could barely hear it, and he was learning to listen to it without thinking. Sister Cecilia came into the room about ten o\'92clock in the morning on that day and brought the mail. She was very handsome, and Mr. Frazer liked to see her and to hear her talk, but the mail, supposedly coming from a different world, was more important. However, there was nothing in the mail of any interest. \'93You look so much better,\'94 she said. \'93You\'92ll be leaving us soon.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93You look very happy this morning.\'94 \'93Oh, I am. This morning I feel as though I might be a saint.\'94 Mr. Frazer was a little taken aback at this. \'93Yes,\'94 Sister Cecilia went on. \'93That\'92s what I want to be. A saint. Ever since I was a little girl I\'92ve wanted to be a saint. When I was a girl I thought if I renounced the world and went into the convent I would be a saint. That was what I wanted to be and that was what I thought I had to do to be one. I expected I would be a saint. I was absolutely sure I would be one. For just a moment I thought I was one. I was so happy and it seemed so simple and easy. When I awoke in the morning I expected I would be a saint, but I wasn\'92t. I\'92ve never become one. I want so to be one. All I want is to be a saint. That is all I\'92ve ever wanted. And this morning I feel as though I might be one. Oh, I hope I will get to be one.\'94 \'93You\'92ll be one. Everybody gets what they want. That\'92s what they always tell me.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know now. When I was a girl it seemed so simple. I knew I would be a saint. Only I believed it took time when I found it did not happen suddenly. Now it seems almost impossible.\'94 \'93I\'92d say you had a good chance.\'94 \'93Do you really think so? No, I don\'92t want just to be encouraged. Don\'92t just encourage me. I want to be a saint. I want so to be a saint.\'94 \'93Of course you\'92ll be a saint,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93No, probably I won\'92t be. But, oh, if I could only be a saint! I\'92d be perfectly happy.\'94 \'93You\'92re three to one to be a saint.\'94 \'93No, don\'92t encourage me. But, oh, if I could only be a saint! If I could only be a saint!\'94 \'93How\'92s your friend Cayetano?\'94 \'93He\'92s going to get well but he\'92s paralyzed. One of the bullets hit the big nerve that goes down through his thigh and that leg is paralyzed. They only found it out when he got well enough so that he could move.\'94 \'93Maybe the nerve will regenerate.\'94 \'93I\'92m praying that it will,\'94 Sister Cecilia said. \'93You ought to see him.\'94 \'93I don\'92t feel like seeing anybody.\'94 \'93You know you\'92d like to see him. They could wheel him in here.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 They wheeled him in, thin, his skin transparent, his hair black and needing to be cut, his eyes very laughing, his teeth bad when he smiled. \'93Hola, amigo! Qu\'e9 tal?\'94 \'93As you see,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93And thou?\'94 \'93Alive and with the leg paralyzed.\'94 \'93Bad,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93But the nerve can regenerate and be as good as new.\'94 \'93So they tell me.\'94 \'93What about the pain?\'94 \'93Not now. For a while I was crazy with it in the belly. I thought the pain alone would 