ght he shot you first and the Russian after.\'94 \'93No, the Russian first, me after. The paper was mistaken.\'94 \'93Why didn\'92t you shoot him?\'94 \'93I never carry a gun. With my luck, if I carried a gun I would be hanged ten times a year. I am a cheap card player, only that.\'94 He stopped, then continued. \'93When I make a sum of money I gamble and when I gamble I lose. I have passed at dice for three thousand dollars and crapped out for the six. With good dice. More than once.\'94 \'93Why continue?\'94 \'93If I live long enough the luck will change. I have bad luck now for fifteen years. If I ever get any good luck I will be rich.\'94 He grinned. \'93I am a good gambler, really I would enjoy being rich.\'94 \'93Do you have bad luck with all games?\'94 \'93With everything and with women.\'94 He smiled again, showing his bad teeth. \'93Truly?\'94 \'93Truly.\'94 \'93And what is there to do?\'94 \'93Continue, slowly, and wait for luck to change.\'94 \'93But with women?\'94 \'93No gambler has luck with women. He is too concentrated. He works nights. When he should be with the woman. No man who works nights can hold a woman if the woman is worth anything.\'94 \'93You are a philosopher.\'94 \'93No, hombre. A gambler of the small towns. One small town, then another, another, then a big town, then start over again.\'94 \'93Then shot in the belly.\'94 \'93The first time,\'94 he said. \'93That has only happened once.\'94 \'93I tire you talking?\'94 Mr. Frazer suggested. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I must tire you.\'94 \'93And the leg?\'94 \'93I have no great use for the leg. I am all right with the leg or not. I will be able to circulate.\'94 \'93I wish you luck, truly, and with all my heart,\'94 Mr. Frazer said. \'93Equally,\'94 he said. \'93And that the pain stops.\'94 \'93It will not last, certainly. It is passing. It is of no importance.\'94 \'93That it passes quickly.\'94 \'93Equally.\'94 That night the Mexicans played the accordion and other instruments in the ward and it was cheerful and the noise of the inhalations and exhalations of the accordion, and of the bells, the traps, and the drum came down the corridor. In that ward there was a rodeo rider who had come out of the chutes on Midnight on a hot dusty afternoon with the big crowd watching, and now, with a broken back, was going to learn to work in leather and to cane chairs when he got well enough to leave the hospital. There was a carpenter who had fallen with a scaffolding and broken both ankles and both wrists. He had lit like a cat but without a cat\'92s resiliency. They could fix him up so that he could work again but it would take a long time. There was a boy from a farm, about sixteen years old, with a broken leg that had been badly set and was to be rebroken. There was Cayetano Ruiz, a small-town gambler with a paralyzed leg. Down the corridor Mr. Frazer could hear them all laughing and merry with the music made by the Mexicans who had been sent by the police. The Mexicans were having a good time. They came in, very excited, to see Mr. Frazer and wanted to know if there was anything he wanted them to play, and they came twice more to play at night of their own accord. The last time they played Mr. Frazer lay in his room with the door open and listened to the noisy, bad music and could not keep from thinking. When they wanted to know what he wished played, he asked for the Cucaracha, which has the sinister lightness and deftness of so many of the tunes men have gone to die to. They played noisily and with emotion. The tune was better than most of such tunes, to Mr. Frazer\'92s mind, but the effect was all the same. In spite of this introduction of emotion, Mr. Frazer went on thinking. Usually he avoided thinking all he could, except when he was writing, but now he was thinking about those who were playing and what the little one had said. Religion is the opium of the people. He believed that, that dyspeptic little joint-keeper. Yes, and music is the opium of the people. Old mount-to-the-head hadn\'92t thought of that. And now economics is the opium of the people; along with patriotism the opium of the people in Italy and Germany. What about sexual intercourse; was that an opium of the people? Of some of the people. Of some of the best of the people. But drink was a sovereign opium of the people, oh, an excellent opium. Although some prefer the radio, another opium of the people, a cheap one he had just been using. Along with these went gambling, an opium of the people if there ever was one, one of the oldest. Ambition was another, an opium of the people, along with a belief in any new form of government. What you wanted was the minimum of government, always less government. Liberty, what we believed in, now the name of a MacFadden publication. We believed in that although they had not found a new name for it yet. But what was the real one? What was the real, the actual, opium of the people? He knew it very well. It was gone just a little way around the corner in that well-lighted part of his mind that was there after two or more drinks in the evening; that he knew was there (it was not really there of course). What was it? He knew very well. What was it? Of course; bread was the opium of the people. Would he remember that and would it make sense in the daylight? Bread is the opium of the people. \'93Listen,\'94 Mr. Frazer said to the nurse when she came. \'93Get that little thin Mexican in here, will you, please?\'94 \'93How do you like it?\'94 the Mexican said at the door. \'93Very much.\'94 \'93It is a historic tune,\'94 the Mexican said. \'93It is the tune of the real revolution.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93Why should the people be operated on without an an\'e6sthetic?\'94 \'93I do not understand.\'94 \'93Why are not all the opiums of the people good? What do you want to do with the people?\'94 \'93They should be rescued from ignorance.\'94 \'93Don\'92t talk nonsense. Education is an opium of the people. You ought to know that. You\'92ve had a little.\'94 \'93You do not believe in education?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93In knowledge, yes.\'94 \'93I do not follow you.\'94 \'93Many times I do not follow myself with pleasure.\'94 \'93You want to hear the Cucaracha another time?\'94 asked the Mexican worriedly. \'93Yes,\'94 said Mr. Frazer. \'93Play the Cucaracha another time. It\'92s better than the radio.\'94 Revolution, Mr. Frazer thought, is no opium. Revolution is a catharsis; an ecstasy which can only be prolonged by tyranny. The opiums are for before and for after. He was thinking well, a little too well. They would go now in a little while, he thought, and they would take the Cucaracha with them. Then he would have a little spot of the giant killer and play the radio, you could play the radio so that you could hardly hear it. Fathers and Sons THERE HAD BEEN A SIGN TO DETOUR IN the center of the main street of this town, but cars had obviously gone through, so, believing it was some repair which had been completed, Nicholas Adams drove on through the town along the empty, brick-paved street, stopped by traffic lights that flashed on and off on this traffic-less Sunday, and would be gone next year when the payments on the system were not met; on under the heavy trees of the small town that are a part of your heart if it is your town and you have walked under them, but that are only too heavy, that shut out the sun and that dampen the houses for a stranger; out past the last house and onto the highway that rose and fell straight away ahead with banks of red dirt sliced cleanly away and the second-growth timber on both sides. It was not his country but it was the middle of fall and all of this country was good to drive through and to see. The cotton was picked and in the clearings there were patches of corn, some cut with streaks of red sorghum, and, driving easily, his son asleep on the seat by his side, the day\'92s run made, knowing the town he would reach for the night, Nick noticed which corn fields had soy beans or peas in them, how the thickets and the cut-over land lay, where the cabins and houses were in relation to the fields and the thickets; hunting the country in his mind as he went by; sizing up each clearing as to feed and cover and figuring where you would find a covey and which way they would fly. In shooting quail you must not get between them and their habitual cover, once the dogs have found them, or when they flush they will come pouring at you, some rising steep, some skimming by your ears, whirring into a size you have never seen them in the air as they pass, the only way being to turn and take them over your shoulder as they go, before they set their wings and angle down into the thicket. Hunting this country for quail as his father had taught him, Nicholas Adams started thinking about his father. When he first thought about him it was always the eyes. The big frame, the quick movements, the wide shoulders, the hooked, hawk nose, the beard that covered the weak chin, you never thought about\'97it was always the eyes. They were protected in his head by the formation of the brows; set deep as though a special protection had been devised for some very valuable instrument. They saw much farther and much quicker than the human eye sees and they were the great gift his father had. His father saw as a big-horn ram or as an eagle sees, literally. He would be standing with his father on one shore of the lake, his own eyes were very good then, and his father would say, \'93They\'92ve run up the flag.\'94 Nick could not see the flag or the flag pole. \'93There,\'94 his father would say, \'93it\'92s your sister Dorothy. She\'92s got the flag up and she\'92s walking out onto the dock.\'94 Nick would look across the lake and he could see the long wooded shore-line, the higher timber behind, the point that guarded the bay, the clear hills of the farm and the white of their cottage in the trees but he could not see any flag pole, or any dock, only the white of the beach and the curve of the shore. \'93Can you see the sheep on the hillside toward the point?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 They were a whitish patch on the gray-green of the hill. \'93I can count them,\'94 his father said. Like all men with a faculty that surpasses human requirements, his father was very nervous. Then, too, he was sentimental, and, like most sentimental people, he was both cruel and abused. Also, he had much bad luck, and it was not all of it his own. He had died in a trap that he had helped only a little to set, and they had all betrayed him in their various ways before he died. All sentimental people are betrayed so many times. Nick could not write about him yet, although he would, later, but the quail country made him remember him as he was when Nick was a boy and he was very grateful to him for two things: fishing and shooting. His father was as sound on those two things as he was unsound on sex, for instance, and Nick was glad that it had been that way; for some one has to give you your first gun or the opportunity to get it and use it, and you have to live where there is game or fish if you are to learn about them, and now, at thirty-eight, he loved to fish and to shoot exactly as much as when he first had gone with his father. It was a passion that had never slackened and he was very grateful to his father for bringing him to know it. While for the other, that his father was not sound about, all the equipment you will ever have is provided and each man learns all there is for him to know about it without advice; and it makes no difference where you live. He remembered very clearly the only two pieces of information his father had given him about that. Once when they were out shooting together Nick shot a red squirrel out of a hemlock tree. The squirrel fell, wounded, and when Nick picked him up bit the boy clean through the ball of the thumb. \'93The dirty little bugger,\'94 Nick said and smacked the squirrel\'92s head against the tree. \'93Look how he bit me.\'94 His father looked and said, \'93Suck it out clean and put some iodine on when you get home.\'94 \'93The little bugger,\'94 Nick said. \'93Do you know what a bugger is?\'94 his father asked him. \'93We call anything a bugger,\'94 Nick said. \'93A bugger is a man who has intercourse with animals.\'94 \'93Why?\'94 Nick said. \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 his father said. \'93But it is a heinous crime.\'94 Nick\'92s imagination was both stirred and horrified by this and he thought of various animals but none seemed attractive or practical and that was the sum total of direct sexual knowledge bequeathed him by his father except on one other subject. One morning he read in the paper that Enrico Caruso had been arrested for mashing. \'93What is mashing?\'94 \'93It is one of the most heinous of crimes,\'94 his father answered. Nick\'92s imagination pictured the great tenor doing something strange, bizarre, and heinous with a potato masher to a beautiful lady who looked like the pictures of Anna Held on the inside of cigar boxes. He resolved, with considerable horror, that when he was old enough he would try mashing at least once. His father had summed up the whole matter by stating that masturbation produced blindness, insanity, and death, while a man who went with prostitutes would contract hideous venereal diseases and that the thing to do was to keep your hands off of people. On the other hand his father had the finest pair of eyes he had ever seen and Nick had loved him very much and for a long time. Now, knowing how it had all been, even remembering the earliest times before things had gone badly was not good remembering. If he wrote it he could get rid of it. He had gotten rid of many things by writing them. But it was still too early for that. There were still too many people. So he decided to think of something else. There was nothing to do about his father and he had thought it all through many times. The handsome job the undertaker had done on his father\'92s face had not blurred in his mind and all the rest of it was quite clear, including the responsibilities. He had complimented the undertaker. The undertaker had been both proud and smugly pleased. But it was not the undertaker that had given him that last face. The undertaker had only made certain dashingly executed repairs of doubtful artistic merit. The face had been making itself and being made for a long time. It had modelled fast in the last three years. It was a good story but there were still too many people alive for him to write it. Nick\'92s own education in those earlier matters had been acquired in the hemlock woods behind the Indian camp. This was reached by a trail which ran from the cottage through the woods to the farm and then by a road which wound through the slashings to the camp. Now if he could still feel all of that trail with bare feet. First there was the pine-needle loam through the hemlock woods behind the cottage where the fallen logs crumbled into wood dust and long splintered pieces of wood hung like javelins in the tree that had been struck by lightning. You crossed the creek on a log and if you stepped off there was the black muck of the swamp. You climbed a fence out of the woods and the trail was hard in the sun across the field with cropped grass and sheep sorrel and mullen growing and to the left the quaky bog of the creek bottom where the killdeer plover fed. The spring house was in that creek. Below the barn there was fresh warm manure and the other older manure that was caked dry on top. Then there was another fence and the hard, hot trail from the barn to the house and the hot sandy road that ran down to the woods, crossing the creek, on a bridge this time, where the cat-tails grew that you soaked in kerosene to make jack-lights with for spearing fish at night. Then the main road went off to the left, skirting the woods and climbing the hill, while you went into the woods on the wide clay and shale road, cool under the trees, and broadened for them to skid out the hemlock bark the Indians cut. The hemlock bark was piled in long rows of stacks, roofed over with more bark, like houses, and the peeled logs lay huge and yellow where the trees had been felled. They left the logs in the woods to rot, they did not even clear away or burn the tops. It was only the bark they wanted for the tannery at Boyne City; hauling it across the lake on the ice in winter, and each year there was less forest and more open, hot, shadeless, weed-grown slashing. But there was still much forest then, virgin forest where the trees grew high before there were any branches and you walked on the brown, clean, springy-needled ground with no undergrowth and it was cool on the hottest days and they three lay against the trunk of a hemlock wider than two beds are long, with the breeze high in the tops and the cool light that came in patches, and Billy said: \'93You want Trudy again?\'94 \'93You want to?\'94 \'93Un Huh.\'94 \'93Come on.\'94 \'93No, here.\'94 \'93But Billy\'97\'94 \'93I no mind Billy. He my brother.\'94 Then afterwards they sat, the three of them, listening for a black squirrel that was in the top branches where they could not see him. They were waiting for him to bark again because when he barked he would jerk his tail and Nick would shoot where he saw any movement. His father gave him only three cartridges a day to hunt with and he had a single-barrel twenty-gauge shotgun with a very long barrel. \'93Son of a bitch never move,\'94 Billy said. \'93You shoot, Nickie. Scare him. We see him jump. Shoot him again,\'94 Trudy said. It was a long speech for her. \'93I\'92ve only got two shells,\'94 Nick said. \'93Son of a bitch,\'94 said Billy. They sat against the tree and were quiet. Nick was feeling hollow and happy. \'93Eddie says he going to come some night sleep in bed with you sister Dorothy.\'94 \'93What?\'94 \'93He said.\'94 Trudy nodded. \'93That\'92s all he want do,\'94 she said. Eddie was their older half-brother. He was seventeen. \'93If Eddie Gilby ever comes at night and even speaks to Dorothy you know what I\'92d do to him? I\'92d kill him like this.\'94 Nick cocked the gun and hardly taking aim pulled the trigger, blowing a hole as big as your hand in the head or belly of that half-breed bastard Eddie Gilby. \'93Like that. I\'92d kill him like that.\'94 \'93He better not come then,\'94 Trudy said. She put her hand in Nick\'92s pocket. \'93He better watch out plenty,\'94 said Billy. \'93He\'92s big bluff,\'94 Trudy was exploring with her hand in Nick\'92s pocket. \'93But don\'92t you kill him. You get plenty trouble.\'94 \'93I\'92d kill him like that,\'94 Nick said. Eddie Gilby lay on the ground with all his chest shot away. Nick put his foot on him proudly. \'93I\'92d scalp him,\'94 he said happily. \'93No,\'94 said Trudy. \'93That\'92s dirty.\'94 \'93I\'92d scalp him and send it to his mother.\'94 \'93His mother dead,\'94 Trudy said. \'93Don\'92t you kill him, Nickie. Don\'92t you kill him for me.\'94 \'93After I scalped him I\'92d throw him to the dogs.\'94 Billy was very depressed. \'93He better watch out,\'94 he said gloomily. \'93They\'92d tear him to pieces,\'94 Nick said, pleased with the picture. Then, having scalped that halfbreed renegade and standing, watching the dogs tear him, his face unchanging, he fell backward against the tree, held tight around the neck, Trudy holding, choking him, and crying, \'93No kill him! No kill him! No kill him! No. No. No. Nickie. Nickie. Nickie!\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94 \'93No kill him.\'94 \'93I got to kill him.\'94 \'93He just a big bluff.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nickie said. \'93I won\'92t kill him unless he comes around the house. Let go of me.\'94 \'93That\'92s good,\'94 Trudy said. \'93You want to do anything now? I feel good now.\'94 \'93If Billy goes away.\'94 Nick had killed Eddie Gilby, then pardoned him his life, and he was a man now. \'93You go, Billy. You hang around all the time. Go on.\'94 \'93Son a bitch,\'94 Billy said. \'93I get tired this. What we come? Hunt or what?\'94 \'93You can take the gun. There\'92s one shell.\'94 \'93All right. I get a big black one all right.\'94 \'93I\'92ll holler,\'94 Nick said. Then, later, it was a long time after and Billy was still away. \'93You think we make a baby?\'94 Trudy folded her brown legs together happily and rubbed against him. Something inside Nick had gone a long way away. \'93I don\'92t think so,\'94 he said. \'93Make plenty baby what the hell.\'94 They heard Billy shoot. \'93I wonder if he got one.\'94 \'93Don\'92t care,\'94 said Trudy. Billy came through the trees. He had the gun over his shoulder and he held a black squirrel by the front paws. \'93Look,\'94 he said. \'93Bigger than a cat. You all through?\'94 \'93Where\'92d you get him?\'94 \'93Over there. Saw him jump first.\'94 \'93Got to go home,\'94 Nick said. \'93No,\'94 said Trudy. \'93I got to get there for supper.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 \'93Want to hunt tomorrow?\'94 \'93All right.\'94 \'93You can have the squirrel.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 \'93Come out after supper?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93How you feel?\'94 \'93Good.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 \'93Give me kiss on the face,\'94 said Trudy. Now, as he rode along the highway in the car and it was getting dark, Nick was all through thinking about his father. The end of the day never made him think of him. The end of the day had always belonged to Nick alone and he never felt right unless he was alone at it. His father came back to him in the fall of the year, or in the early spring when there had been jacksnipe on the prairie, or when he saw shocks of corn, or when he saw a lake, or if he ever saw a horse and buggy, or when he saw, or heard, wild geese, or in a duck blind; remembering the time an eagle dropped through the whirling snow to strike a canvas-covered decoy, rising, his wings beating, the talons caught in the canvas. His father was with him, suddenly, in deserted orchards and in new-plowed fields, in thickets, on small hills, or when going through dead grass, whenever splitting wood or hauling water, by grist mills, cider mills and dams and always with open fires. The towns he lived in were not towns his father knew. After he was fifteen he had shared nothing with him. His father had frost in his beard in cold weather and in hot weather he sweated very much. He liked to work in the sun on the farm because he did not have to and he loved manual work, which Nick did not. Nick loved his father but hated the smell of him and once when he had to wear a suit of his father\'92s underwear that had gotten too small for his father it made him feel sick and he took it off and put it under two stones in the creek and said that he had lost it. He had told his father how it was when his father had made him put it on but his father had said it was freshly washed. It had been, too. When Nick had asked him to smell of it his father sniffed at it indignantly and said that it was clean and fresh. When Nick came home from fishing without it and said he lost it he was whipped for lying. Afterwards he had sat inside the woodshed with the door open, his shotgun loaded and cocked, looking across at his father sitting on the screen porch reading the paper, and thought, \'93I can blow him to hell. I can kill him.\'94 Finally he felt his anger go out of him and he felt a little sick about it being the gun that his father had given him. Then he had gone to the Indian camp, walking there in the dark, to get rid of the smell. There was only one person in his family that he liked the smell of; one sister. All the others he avoided all contact with. That sense blunted when he started to smoke. It was a good thing. It was good for a bird dog but it did not help a man. \'93What was it like, Papa, when you were a little boy and used to hunt with the Indians?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Nick was startled. He had not even noticed the boy was awake. He looked at him sitting beside him on the seat. He had felt quite alone but this boy had been with him. He wondered for how long. \'93We used to go all day to hunt black squirrels,\'94 he said. \'93My father only gave me three shells a day because he said that would teach me to hunt and it wasn\'92t good for a boy to go banging around. I went with a boy named Billy Gilby and his sister Trudy. We used to go out nearly every day all one summer.\'94 \'93Those are funny names for Indians.\'94 \'93Yes, aren\'92t they,\'94 Nick said. \'93But tell me what they were like.\'94 \'93They were Ojibways,\'94 Nick said. \'93And they were very nice.\'94 \'93But what were they like to be with?\'94 \'93It\'92s hard to say,\'94 Nick Adams said. Could you say she did first what no one has ever done better and mention plump brown legs, flat belly, hard little breasts, well holding arms, quick searching tongue, the flat eyes, the good taste of mouth, then uncomfortably, tightly, sweetly, moistly, lovely, tightly, achingly, fully, finally, unendingly, never-endingly, never-to-endingly, suddenly ended, the great bird flown like an owl in the twilight, only it was daylight in the woods and hemlock needles stuck against your belly. So that when you go in a place where Indians have lived you smell them gone and all the empty pain killer bottles and the flies that buzz do not kill the sweetgrass smell, the smoke smell and that other like a fresh cased marten skin. Nor any jokes about them nor old squaws take that away. Nor the sick sweet smell they get to have. Nor what they did finally. It wasn\'92t how they ended. They all ended the same. Long time ago good. Now no good. And about the other. When you have shot one bird flying you have shot all birds flying. They are all different and they fly in different ways but the sensation is the same and the last one is as good as the first. He could thank his father for that. \'93You might not like them,\'94 Nick said to the boy. \'93But I think you would.\'94 \'93And my grandfather lived with them too when he was a boy, didn\'92t he?\'94 \'93Yes. When I asked him what they were like he said that he had many friends among them.\'94 \'93Will I ever live with them?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Nick said. \'93That\'92s up to you.\'94 \'93How old will I be when I get a shotgun and can hunt by myself?\'94 \'93Twelve years old if I see you are careful.\'94 \'93\'92I wish I was twelve now.\'94 \'93You will be, soon enough.\'94 \'93What was my grandfather like? I can\'92t remember him except that he gave me an air rifle and an American flag when I came over from France that time. What was he like?\'94 \'93He\'92s hard to describe. He was a great hunter and fisherman and he had wonderful eyes.\'94 \'93\'92Was he greater than you?\'94 \'93He was a much better shot and his father was a great wing shot too.\'94 \'93I\'92ll bet he wasn\'92t better than you.\'94 \'93Oh, yes he was. He shot very quickly and beautifully. I\'92d rather see him shoot than any man I ever knew. He was always very disappointed in the way I shot.\'94 \'93Why do we never go to pray at the tomb of my grandfather?\'94 \'93We live in a different pan of the country. It\'92s a long way from here.\'94 \'93In France that wouldn\'92t make any difference. In France we\'92d go. I think I ought to go to pray at the tomb of my grandfather.\'94 \'93Sometime we\'92ll go.\'94 \'93I hope we won\'92t live somewhere so that I can never go to pray at your tomb when you are dead.\'94 \'93We\'92ll have to arrange it.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you think we might all be buried at a convenient place? We could all be buried in France. That would be fine.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to be buried in France,\'94 Nick said. \'93Well, then, we\'92ll have to get some convenient place in America. Couldn\'92t we all be buried out at the ranch?\'94 \'93That\'92s an idea.\'94 \'93Then I could stop and pray at the tomb of my grandfather on the way to the ranch.\'94 \'93You\'92re awfully practical.\'94 \'93Well, I don\'92t feel good never to have even visited the tomb of my grandfather.\'94 \'93We\'92ll have to go,\'94 Nick said. \'93I can see we\'92ll have to go.\'94 Part II Short Stories Published in Books or Magazines Subsequent to \'93The First Forty-nine\'94 One Trip Across YOU KNOW HOW IT IS THERE EARLY IN the morning in Havana with the bums still asleep against the walls of the buildings; before even the ice wagons come by with ice for the bars? Well, we came across the square from the dock to the Pearl of San Francisco Caf\'e9 to get coffee and there was only one beggar awake in the square and he was getting a drink out of the fountain. But when we got inside the caf\'e9 and sat down, there were the three of them waiting for us. We sat down and one of them came over. \'93Well,\'94 he said. \'93I can\'92t do it,\'94 I told him. \'93I\'92d like to do it as a favor. But I told you last night I couldn\'92t.\'94 \'93You can name your own price.\'94 \'93It isn\'92t that. I can\'92t do it. That\'92s all.\'94 The two others had come over and they stood there looking sad. They were nice-looking fellows all right and I would have liked to have done them the favor. \'93A thousand apiece,\'94 said the one who spoke good English. \'93Don\'92t make me feel bad,\'94 I told him. \'93I tell you true I can\'92t do it.\'94 \'93Afterwards, when things are changed, it would mean a good deal to you.\'94 \'93I know it. I\'92m all for you. But I can\'92t do it.\'94 \'93Why not?\'94 \'93I make my living with the boat. If I lose her I lose my living.\'94 \'93With the money you buy another boat.\'94 \'93Not in jail.\'94 They must have thought I just needed to be argued into it because the one kept on. \'93You would have three thousand dollars and it could mean a great deal to you later. All this will not last, you know.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93I don\'92t care who is President here. But I don\'92t carry anything to the States that can talk.\'94 \'93You mean we would talk?\'94 one of them who hadn\'92t spoken said. He was angry. \'93I said anything that can talk.\'94 \'93Do you think we are lenguas largas?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Do you know what a lengua larga is?\'94 \'93Yes. One with a long tongue.\'94 \'93Do you know what we do with them?\'94 \'93Don\'92t be tough with me,\'94 I said. \'93You propositioned me. I didn\'92t offer you anything.\'94 \'93Shut up, Pancho,\'94 the one who had done the talking before said to the angry one. \'93He said we would talk,\'94 Pancho said. \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93I told you I didn\'92t carry anything that can talk. Sacked liquor can\'92t talk. Demijohns can\'92t talk. There\'92s other things that can\'92t talk. Men can talk.\'94 \'93Can Chinamen talk?\'94 Pancho said, pretty nasty. \'93They can talk, but I can\'92t understand them,\'94 I told him. \'93So you won\'92t?\'94 \'93It\'92s just like I told you last night. I can\'92t.\'94 \'93But you won\'92t talk?\'94 Pancho said. The one thing that he hadn\'92t understood right had made him nasty. I guess it was disappointment, too. I didn\'92t even answer him. \'93You\'92re not a lengua larga, are you?\'94 he asked, still nasty. \'93I don\'92t think so.\'94 \'93What\'92s that? A threat?\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I told him. \'93Don\'92t be so tough so early in the morning. I\'92m sure you\'92ve cut plenty people\'92s throats. I haven\'92t even had my coffee yet.\'94 \'93So you\'92re sure I\'92ve cut people\'92s throats?\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93And I don\'92t give a damn. Can\'92t you do business without getting angry?\'94 \'93I am angry now,\'94 he said. \'93I would like to kill you.\'94 \'93Oh, hell,\'94 I told him, \'93don\'92t talk so much.\'94 \'93Come on, Pancho, the first one said. Then, to me, \'93I am very sorry. I wish you would take us.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry, too. But I can\'92t.\'94 The three of them started for the door, and I watched them go. They were good-looking young fellows, wore good clothes; none of them wore hats, and they looked like they had plenty of money. They talked plenty of money, anyway, and they spoke the kind of English Cubans with money speak. Two of them looked like brothers and the other one, Pancho, was a little taller but the same sort of looking kid. You know, slim, good clothes, and shiny hair. I didn\'92t figure he was as mean as he talked. I figured he was plenty nervous. As they turned out of the door to the right, I saw a closed car come across the square toward them. The first thing a pane of glass went and the bullet smashed into the row of bottles on the showcase wall to the right. I heard the gun going and, bop, bop, bop, there were bottles smashing all along the wall. I jumped behind the bar on the left side and could see looking over the edge. The car was stopped and there were two fellows crouched down by it. One had a Thompson gun and the other had a sawed-off automatic shotgun. The one with the Thompson gun was a nigger. The other had a chauffeur\'92s white duster on. One of the boys was spread out on the sidewalk, face down, just outside the big window that was smashed. The other two were behind one of the Tropical beer ice wagons that was stopped in front of the Cunard bar next door. One of the ice-wagon horses was down in the harness, kicking, and the other was plunging his head off. One of the boys shot from the rear corner of the wagon and it ricocheted off the sidewalk. The nigger with the tommy gun got his face almost into the street and gave the back of the wagon a burst from underneath and sure enough one came down, falling toward the sidewalk with his head above the curb. He flopped there, putting his hands over his head, and the chauffeur shot at him with the shotgun while the nigger put in a fresh pan, but it was a long shot. You could see the buckshot marks all over the sidewalk like silver splatters. The other fellow pulled the one who was hit back by the legs to behind the wagon, and I saw the nigger getting his face down on the paving to give them another burst. Then I saw old Pancho come around the corner of the wagon and step into the lee of the horse that was still up. He stepped clear of the horse, his face white as a dirty sheet, and got the chauffeur with the big Luger he had, holding it in both hands to keep it steady. He shot twice over the nigger\'92s head, coming on, and once low. He hit a tire on the car because I saw dust blowing in a spurt on the street as the air came out, and at ten feet the nigger shot him in the belly with his tommy gun, with what must have been the last shot in it because I saw him throw it down, and old Pancho sat down hard and went over forward. He was trying to come up, still holding onto the Luger, only he couldn\'92t get his head up, when the nigger took the shotgun that was lying against the wheel of the car by the chauffeur and blew the side of his head off. Some nigger. I took a quick one out of the first bottle I saw open and I couldn\'92t tell you yet what it was. The whole thing made me feel pretty bad. I slipped along behind the bar and out through the kitchen in back and all the way out. I went clean around the outside of the square and never even looked over toward the crowd there was coming fast in front of the caf\'e9 and went in through the gate and out onto the dock and got on board. The fellow who had her chartered was on board waiting. I told him what had happened. \'93Where\'92s Eddy?\'94 this fellow Johnson that had her chartered asked me. \'93I never saw him after the shooting started.\'94 \'93Do you suppose he was hit?\'94 \'93Hell no. I tell you the only shots that came in the caf\'e9 were into the show case. That was when the car was coming behind them. That was when they shot the first fellow right in front of the window. They came at an angle like this\'97\'94 \'93You seem awfully sure about it,\'94 he said. \'93I was watching,\'94 I told him. Then, as I looked up, I saw Eddy coming along the dock looking taller and sloppier than ever. He walked with his joints all slung wrong. \'93There he is.\'94 Eddy looked pretty bad. He never looked too good early in the morning but he looked plenty bad now. \'93Where were you?\'94 I asked him. \'93On the floor.\'94 \'93Did you see it?\'94 Johnson asked him. \'93Don\'92t talk about it, Mr. Johnson,\'94 Eddy said to him. \'93It makes me sick to even think about it.\'94 \'93You better have a drink,\'94 Johnson told him. Then he said to me, \'93Well, are we going out?\'94 \'93That\'92s up to you.\'94 \'93What sort of a day will it be?\'94 \'93Just about like yesterday. Maybe better.\'94 \'93Let\'92s get out then.\'94 \'93All right, as soon as the bait comes.\'94 We\'92d had this bird out three weeks fishing the stream and I hadn\'92t seen any of his money yet except one hundred dollars he gave me to pay the consul and clear and get some grub and put gas in her before we came across. I was furnishing all the tackle and he had her chartered at thirty-five dollars a day. He slept at a hotel and came aboard every morning. Eddy got me the charter so I had to carry him. I was giving him four dollars a day. \'93I\'92ve got to put gas in her,\'94 I told Johnson. \'93All right.\'94 \'93I\'92ll need some money for that.\'94 \'93How much?\'94 \'93It\'92s twenty-eight cents a gallon. I ought to put in forty gallons anyway. That\'92s eleven-twenty.\'94 He got out fifteen dollars. \'93Do you want to put the rest on the beer and the ice?\'94 I asked him. \'93That\'92s fine,\'94 he said. \'93Just put it down against what I owe you.\'94 I was thinking three weeks was a long time to let him go but if he was good for it what difference was there? He should have paid every week anyway. But I\'92ve let them run a month and got the money. It was my fault but I was glad to see it run at first. It was only the last few days he made me nervous but I didn\'92t want to say anything for fear of getting him plugged at me. If he was good for it, the longer he went the better. \'93Have a bottle of beer?\'94 he asked me, opening the box. \'93No thanks.\'94 Just then this nigger we had getting bait comes down the dock and I told Eddy to get ready to cast her off. The nigger came on board with the bait and we cast off and started out of the harbor, the nigger fixing on a couple of mackerel; passing the hook through their mouth, out the gills, slitting the side and then putting the hook through the other side and out, tying the mouth shut on the wire leader and tying the hook good so it couldn\'92t slip and so the bait would troll smooth without spinning. He\'92s a real black nigger, smart and gloomy, with blue voodoo beads around his neck under his shirt and an old straw hat. What he liked to do on board was sleep and read the papers. But he put on a nice bait and he was fast. \'93Can\'92t you put on a bait like that, Captain?\'94 Johnson asked me. \'93Yes, sir.\'94 \'93Why do you carry a nigger to do it?\'94 \'93When the big fish run you\'92ll see,\'94 I told him. \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 \'93The nigger can do it faster than I can.\'94 \'93Can\'92t Eddy do it?\'94 \'93No, sir.\'94 \'93It seems an unnecessary expense to me.\'94 He\'92d been giving the nigger a dollar a day and the nigger had been on a rumba every night. I could see him getting sleepy already. \'93He\'92s necessary,\'94 I said. By then we had passed the smacks with their fish cars anchored in front of Cabanas and the skiffs anchored fishing for mutton fish on the rock bottom by the Morro, and I headed her out where the gulf made a dark line. Eddy put the two big teasers out and the nigger had baits on three rods. The stream was in nearly to soundings and as we came toward the edge you could see her running nearly purple with regular whirlpools. There was a light east breeze coming up and we put up plenty of flying fish, those big ones that look like the picture of Lindbergh crossing the Atlantic when they sail off. Those big flying fish are the best sign there is. As far as you could see, there was that faded yellow gulfweed in small patches that means the main stream is well in and there were birds ahead working over a school of little tuna. You could see them jumping; just little ones weighing a couple of pounds apiece. \'93Put out any time you want,\'94 I told Johnson. He put on his belt and his harness and put out the big rod with the Hardy reel with six hundred yards of thirty-six thread. I looked back and his bait was trolling nice, just bouncing along on the swell and the two teasers were diving and jumping. We were going just about the right speed and I headed her into the stream. \'93Keep the rod butt in the socket on the chair,\'94 I told him. \'93Then the rod won\'92t be as heavy. Keep the drag off so you can slack to him when he hits. If one ever hits with the drag on he\'92ll jerk you overboard.\'94 Every day I\'92d have to tell him the same thing but I didn\'92t mind that. One out of fifty parties you get know how to fish. Then when they do know, half the time they\'92re goofy and want to use line that isn\'92t strong enough to hold anything big. \'93How does the day look?\'94 he asked me. \'93It couldn\'92t be better,\'94 I told him. It was a pretty day all right. I gave the nigger the wheel and told him to work along the edge of the stream to the eastward and went back to where Johnson was sitting watching his bait bouncing along. \'93Want me to put out another rod?\'94 I asked him. \'93I don\'92t think so,\'94 he said. \'93I want to hook, fight, and land my fish myself.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 I said. \'93Do you want Eddy to put it out and hand it to you if one strikes so you can hook him?\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I prefer to have only one rod out.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 The nigger was still taking her out and I looked and saw he had seen a patch of flying fish burst out ahead and up the stream a little. Looking back, I could see Havana looking fine in the sun and a ship just coming out of the harbor past the Morro. \'93I think you\'92re going to have a chance to fight one today, Mr. Johnson,\'94 I told him. \'93It\'92s about time,\'94 he said. \'93How long have we been out?\'94 \'93Three weeks today.\'94 \'93That\'92s a long time to fish.\'94 \'93They\'92re a funny fish,\'94 I told him. \'93They aren\'92t here until they come. But when they come there\'92s plenty of them. And they\'92ve always come. If they don\'92t come now they\'92re never coming. The moon is right. There\'92s a good stream and we\'92re going to have a good breeze.\'94 \'93There were some small ones when we first came.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93Like I told you. The small ones thin out and stop before the big ones come.\'94 \'93You party-boat captains always have the same line. Either it\'92s too early or too late or the wind isn\'92t right or the moon is wrong. But you take the money just the same.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I told him, \'93the hell of it is that it usually is too early or too late and plenty of time the wind is wrong. Then when you get a day that\'92s perfect you\'92re ashore without a party.\'94 \'93But you think today\'92s a good day?\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I told him, \'93I\'92ve had action enough for me already today. But I\'92d like to bet you\'92re going to have plenty.\'94 \'93I hope so,\'94 he said. We settled down to troll. Eddy went forward and lay down. I was standing up watching for a tail to show. Every once in a while the nigger would doze off and I was watching him, too. I bet he had some nights. \'93Would you mind getting me a bottle of beer, Captain?\'94 Johnson asked me. \'93No, sir,\'94 I said, and I dug down in the ice to get him a cold one. \'93Won\'92t you have one?\'94 he asked. \'93No, sir,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ll wait till tonight.\'94 I opened the bottle and was reaching it toward him when I saw this big brown bugger with a spear on him longer than your arm burst head and shoulders out of the water and smash at that mackerel. He looked as big around as a saw log. \'93Slack it to him!\'94 I yelled. \'93He hasn\'92t got it,\'94 Johnson said. \'93Hold it, then.\'94 He\'92d come up from deep down and missed it. I knew he\'92d turn and come for it again. \'93Get ready to turn it loose to him the minute he grabs it.\'94 Then I saw him coming from behind under water. You could see his fins out wide like purple wings and the purple stripes across the brown. He came on like a submarine and his top fin came out and you could see it slice the water. Then he came right behind the bait and his spear came out too, sort of wagging clean out of water. \'93Let it go into his mouth,\'94 I said. Johnson took his hand off the reel spool and it started to whiz and the old marlin turned and went down and I could see the whole length of him shine bright silver as he turned broadside and headed off fast toward shore. \'93Put on a little drag,\'94 I said. \'93Not much.\'94 He screwed down on the drag. \'93Not too much,\'94 I said. I could see the line slant up. \'93Shut her down hard and sock him,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92ve got to sock him. He\'92s going to jump anyway.\'94 Johnson screwed the drag down and came back on the rod. \'93Sock him,\'94 I told him. \'93Stick it into him. Hit him half a dozen times.\'94 He hit him pretty hard a couple of times more, and then the rod bent double and the reel commenced to screech and out he came, boom, in a long straight jump, shining silver in the sun and making a splash like throwing a horse off a cliff. \'93Ease up on the drag,\'94 I told him. \'93He\'92s gone,\'94 said Johnson. \'93The hell he is,\'94 I told him. \'93Ease up on the drag quick.\'94 I could see the curve in the line and the next time he jumped he was astern and headed out to sea. Then he came out again and smashed the water white and I could see he was hooked in the side of his mouth. The stripes showed clear on him. He was a fine fish, bright silver now, barred with purple and as big around as a log. \'93He\'92s gone,\'94 Johnson said. The line was slack. \'93Reel on him,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s hooked good. Put her ahead with all the machine!\'94 I yelled to the nigger. Then once, twice, he came out stiff as a post, the whole length of him jumping straight toward us, throwing the water high each time he landed. The line came taut and I saw he was headed inshore again and I could see he was turning. \'93Now he\'92ll make his run,\'94 I said. \'93If he hooks up I\'92ll chase him. Keep your drag light. There\'92s plenty of line.\'94 The old marlin headed out to the nor\'92west like all the big ones go, and brother, did he hook up. He started jumping in those long lopes and every splash would be like a speed boat in a sea. We went after him, keeping him on the quarter once I\'92d made the turn. I had the wheel and I kept yelling to Johnson to keep his drag light and reel fast. All of a sudden I see his rod jerk and the line go slack. It wouldn\'92t look slack unless you knew about it because of the pull of the belly of the line in the water. But I knew. \'93He\'92s gone,\'94 I told him. The fish was still jumping and he went on jumping until he was out of sight. He was a fine fish all right. \'93I can still feel him pull,\'94 Johnson said. \'93That\'92s the weight of the line.\'94 \'93I can hardly reel it. Maybe he\'92s dead.\'94 \'93Look at him,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s still jumping.\'94 You could see him out a half a mile, still throwing spouts of water. I felt his drag. He had it screwed down tight. You couldn\'92t pull out any line. It had to break. \'93Didn\'92t I tell you to keep your drag light?\'94 \'93But he kept taking out line.\'94 \'93So what?\'94 \'93So I tightened it.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I told him. \'93If you don\'92t give them line when they hook up like that they break it. There isn\'92t any line will hold them. When they want it you\'92ve got to give it to them. You have to keep a light drag. The market fishermen can\'92t hold them tight when they do that even with a harpoon line. What we have to do is use the boat to chase them so they don\'92t take it all when they make their run. After they make their run they\'92ll sound and you can tighten up the drag and get it back.\'94 \'93Then if it hadn\'92t broken I would have caught him?\'94 \'93You\'92d have had a chance.\'94 \'93He couldn\'92t have kept that up, could he?\'94 \'93He can do plenty of other things. It isn\'92t until after he\'92s made his run that the fight starts.\'94 \'93Well, let\'92s catch one,\'94 he said. \'93You have to reel that line in first,\'94 I told him. We\'92d hooked that fish and lost him without waking Eddy up. Now old Eddy came back astern. \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 he said. Eddy was a good man on a boat once, before he got to be a rummy, but he isn\'92t any good now. I looked at him standing there tall and hollowcheeked with his mouth loose and that white stuff in the corners of his eyes and his hair all faded in the sun. I knew he woke up dead for a drink. \'93You\'92d better drink a bottle of beer,\'94 I told him. He took one out of the box and drank it. \'93Well, Mr. Johnson,\'94 he said, \'93I guess I better finish my nap. Much obliged for the beer, sir.\'94 Some Eddy. The fish didn\'92t make any difference to him. Well, we hooked another one around noon and he jumped off. You could see the hook go thirty feet in the air when he threw it. \'93What did I do wrong then?\'94 Johnson asked. \'93Nothing,\'94 I said. \'93He just threw it.\'94 \'93Mr. Johnson,\'94 said Eddy, who\'92d waked up to have another bottle of beer\'97 \'93Mr. Johnson, you\'92re just unlucky. Now maybe you\'92re lucky with women. Mr. Johnson, what do you say we go out tonight?\'94 Then he went back and lay down again. About four o\'92clock when we\'92re coming back close in to shore against the stream, it going like a mill race, us with the sun at our backs, the biggest black marlin I ever saw in my life hit Johnson\'92s bait. We\'92d put out a feather squid and caught four of those little tuna and the nigger put one on his hook for bait. It trolled pretty heavy but it made a big splash in the wake. Johnson took the harness off the reel so he could put the rod across his knees because his arms got tired holding it in position all the time. Because his hands got tired holding the spool of the reel against the drag of the big bait, he screwed the drag down when I wasn\'92t looking. I never knew he had it down. I didn\'92t like to see him hold the rod that way but I hated to be crabbing at him all the time. Besides, with the drag off, line would go out so there wasn\'92t any danger. But it was a sloppy way to fish. I was at the wheel and was working the edge of the stream opposite that old cement factory where it makes deep so close in to shore and where it makes a son of eddy where there is always lots of bait. Then I saw a splash like a depth bomb and the sword and eye and open lower jaw and huge purple-black head of a black marlin. The whole top fin was up out of water looking as high as a fullrigged ship, and the whole scythe tall was out as he smashed at that tuna. The bill was as big around as a baseball bat and slanted up, and as he grabbed the bait he sliced the ocean wide open. He was solid purple-black and he had an eye as big as a soup bowl. He was huge. I bet he\'92d go a thousand pounds. I yelled to Johnson to let him have line but before I could say a word I saw Johnson rise up in the air off the chair as though he was being derricked, and him holding just for a second onto that rod and the rod bending like a bow, and then the butt caught him in the belly and the whole works went overboard. He\'92d screwed the drag tight, and when the fish struck, it lifted Johnson right out of the chair and he couldn\'92t hold it. He\'92d had the butt under one leg and the rod across his lap. If he\'92d had the harness on it would have taken him along, too. I cut out the engine and went back to the stern. He was sitting there holding onto his belly where the rod butt had hit him. \'93I guess that\'92s enough for today,\'94 I said. \'93What was it?\'94 he said to me. \'93Black marlin,\'94 I said. \'93How did it happen?\'94 \'93You figure it out,\'94 I said. \'93The reel cost two hundred and fifty dollars. It costs more now. The rod cost me forty-five. There was a little under six hundred yards of thirty-six thread.\'94 Just then Eddy slaps him on the back. \'93Mr. Johnson,\'94 he says, \'93you\'92re just unlucky. You know I never saw that happen before in my life.\'94 \'93Shut up, you rummy,\'94 I said to him. \'93I tell you, Mr. Johnson,\'94 Eddy said, \'93that\'92s the rarest occurrence I ever saw in my life.\'94 \'93What would I do if I was hooked to a fish like that?\'94 Johnson said. \'93That\'92s what you wanted to fight all by yourself,\'94 I told him. I was plenty sore. \'93They\'92re too big,\'94 Johnson said. \'93Why, it would just be punishment.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93A fish like that would kill you.\'94 \'93They catch them.\'94 \'93People who know how to fish catch them. But don\'92t think they don\'92t take punishment.\'94 \'93I saw a picture of a girl who caught one.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93Still fishing. He swallowed the bait and they pulled his stomach out and he came to the top and died. I\'92m talking about trolling them when they\'92re hooked in the mouth.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 said Johnson, \'93they\'92re too big. If it isn\'92t enjoyable, why do it?\'94 \'93That\'92s right, Mr. Johnson,\'94 Eddy said. \'93If it isn\'92t enjoyable, why do it? Listen, Mr. Johnson. You hit the nail on the head there. If it isn\'92t enjoyable\'97why do it?\'94 I was still shaky from seeing that fish and feeling plenty sick about the tackle and I couldn\'92t listen to them. I told the nigger to head her for the Morro. I didn\'92t say anything to them and there they sat, Eddy in one of the chairs with a bottle of beer and Johnson with another. \'93Captain,\'94 he said to me after a while, \'93could you make me a highball?\'94 I made him one without saying anything, and then I made myself a real one. I was thinking to myself that this Johnson had fished fifteen days, finally he hooks into a fish a fisherman would give a year to tie into, he loses him, he loses my heavy tackle, he makes a fool of himself and he sits there perfectly content drinking with a rummy. When we got in to the dock and the nigger was standing there waiting, I said, \'93What about tomorrow?\'94 \'93I don\'92t think so,\'94 Johnson said. \'93I\'92m about fed up with this kind of fishing.\'94 \'93You want to pay off the nigger?\'94 \'93How much do I owe him?\'94 \'93A dollar. You can give him a tip if you want.\'94 So Johnson gave the nigger a dollar and two Cuban twenty-cent pieces. \'93What\'92s this for?\'94 the nigger asks me, showing the coins. \'93A tip,\'94 I told him in Spanish. \'93You\'92re through. He gives you that.\'94 \'93Don\'92t come tomorrow?\'94 \'93No.\'94 The nigger gets his ball of twine he used for tying baits and his dark glasses, puts on his straw hat and goes without saying good-bye. He was a nigger that never thought much of any of us. \'93When do you want to settle up, Mr. Johnson?\'94 I asked him. \'93I\'92ll go to the bank in the morning,\'94 Johnson said. \'93We can settle up in the afternoon.\'94 \'93Do you know how many days there are?\'94 \'93Fifteen.\'94 \'93No. There\'92s sixteen with today and a day each way makes eighteen. Then there\'92s the rod and reel and the line from today.\'94 \'93The tackle\'92s your risk.\'94 \'93No, sir. Not when you lose it that way.\'94 \'93I\'92ve paid every day for the rent of it. It\'92s your risk.\'94 \'93No, sir,\'94 I said. \'93If a fish broke it and it wasn\'92t your fault, that would be something else. You lost that whole outfit by carelessness.\'94 \'93The fish pulled it out of my hands.\'94 \'93Because you had the drag on and didn\'92t have the rod in the socket.\'94 \'93You have no business to charge for that.\'94 \'93If you hired a car and ran it off a cliff, don\'92t you think you\'92d have to pay for it?\'94 \'93Not if I was in it,\'94 Johnson said. \'93That\'92s pretty good, Mr. Johnson,\'94 Eddy said. \'93You see it, don\'92t you, Cap? If he was in it he\'92d be killed. So he wouldn\'92t have to pay. That\'92s a good one.\'94 I didn\'92t pay any attention to the rummy. \'93You owe two hundred and ninety five dollars for that rod and reel and line,\'94 I told Johnson. \'93Well, it\'92s not right,\'94 he said. \'93But if that\'92s the way you feel about it why not split the difference?\'94 \'93I can\'92t replace it for under three hundred and sixty. I\'92m not charging you for the line. A fish like that could get all your line and it not be your fault. If there was anyone here but a rummy they\'92d tell you how square I\'92m being with you. I know it seems like a lot of money but it was a lot of money when I bought the tackle, too. You can\'92t fish like that without the best tackle you can buy.\'94 \'93Mr. Johnson, he says I\'92m a rummy. Maybe I am. But I tell you he\'92s right. He\'92s right and he\'92s reasonable,\'94 Eddy told him. \'93I don\'92t want to make any difficulties,\'94 Johnson said finally. \'93I\'92ll pay for it, even though I don\'92t see it. That\'92s eighteen days at thirty-five dollars and two ninety-five extra.\'94 \'93You gave me a hundred,\'94 I told him. \'93I\'92ll give you a list of what I spent and I\'92ll deduct what grub there is left. What you bought for provisions going over and back.\'94 \'93That\'92s reasonable,\'94 Johnson said. \'93Listen, Mr. Johnson,\'94 Eddy said. \'93If you knew the way they usually charge a stranger you\'92d know it was more than reasonable. Do you know what it is? It\'92s exceptional. The cap is treating you like you were his own mother.\'94 \'93I\'92ll go to the bank tomorrow and come down in the afternoon. Then I\'92ll get the boat day after tomorrow.\'94 \'93You can go back with us and save the boat fare.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92ll save time with the boat.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 I said. \'93What about a drink?\'94 \'93Fine,\'94 said Johnson. \'93No hard feelings now, are there?\'94 \'93No, sir,\'94 I told him. So the three of us sat there in the stern and drank a highball together. The next day I worked around her all morning, changing the oil in her base and one thing and another. At noon I went uptown and ate at a Chink place where you get a good meal for forty cents, and then I bought some things to take home to my wife and our three girls. You know, perfume, a couple of fans and two of those high combs. When I finished I stopped in at Donovan\'92s and had a beer and talked with the old man and then walked back to the San Francisco docks, stopping in at three or four places for a beer on the way. I bought Frankie a couple at the Cunard bar and I came on board feeling pretty good. When I came on board I had just forty cents left. Frankie came on board with me, and while we sat and waited for Johnson I drank a couple of cold ones out of the ice box with Frankie. Eddy hadn\'92t shown up all night or all day but I knew he would be around sooner or later, as soon as his credit ran out. Donovan told me he\'92d been in there the night before a little while with Johnson, and Eddy had been setting them up on credit. We waited and I began to wonder about Johnson not showing up. I\'92d left word at the dock for them to tell him to go on board and wait for me but they said he hadn\'92t come. Still, I figured he had been out late and probably didn\'92t get up till around noon. The banks were open until three-thirty. We saw the plane go out, and about five-thirty I was all over feeling good and was getting plenty worried. At six o\'92clock I sent Frankie up to the hotel to see if Johnson was there. I still thought he might be out on a time or he might be there at the hotel feeling too bad to get up. I kept waiting and waiting until it was late. But I was getting plenty worried because he owed me eight hundred and twenty-five dollars. Frankie was gone about a little over half an hour. When I saw him coming he was walking fast and shaking his head. \'93He went on the plane,\'94 he said. All right. There it was. The consulate was closed. I had forty cents, and anyhow the plane was in Miami by now. I couldn\'92t even send a wire. Some Mr. Johnson, all right. It was my fault. I should have known better. \'93Well,\'94 I said to Frankie, \'93we might as well have a cold one. Mr. Johnson bought them.\'94 There were three bottles of Tropical left. Frankie felt as bad as I did. I don\'92t know how he could but he seemed to. He just kept slapping me on the back and shaking his head. So there it was. I was broke. I\'92d lost five hundred and thirty dollars of the charter, and tackle I couldn\'92t replace for three hundred and fifty more. How some of that gang that hangs around the dock would be pleased at that, I thought. It certainly would make some conchs happy. And the day before I turned down three thousand dollars to land three aliens on the Keys. Anywhere, just to get them out of the country. All right, what was I going to do now? I couldn\'92t bring in a load because you have to have money to buy the booze and besides there\'92s no money in it any more. The town is flooded with it and there\'92s nobody to buy it. But I was damned if I was going home broke and starve a summer in that town. Besides I\'92ve got a family. The clearance was paid when we came in. You usually pay the broker in advance and he enters you and clears you. Hell, I didn\'92t even have enough money to put in gas. It was a hell of a note, all right. Some Mr. Johnson. \'93I\'92ve got to carry something, Frankie,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ve got to make some money.\'94 \'93I\'92ll see,\'94 said Frankie. He hangs around the water front and does odd jobs and is pretty deaf and drinks too much every night. But you never saw a fellow more loyal nor with a better heart. I\'92ve known him since I first started to run over there. He used to help me load plenty of times. Then when I got handling stuff and went party-boating and broke out this swordfishing in Cuba I used to see him a lot around the dock and around the caf\'e9. He seems dumb and he usually smiles instead of talking but that\'92s because he\'92s deaf. \'93You carry anything?\'94 Frankie asked. \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93I can\'92t choose now.\'94 \'93Anything?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93I\'92ll see,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Where will you be?\'94 \'93I\'92ll be at the Perla,\'94 I told him. \'93I have to eat.\'94 You can get a good meal at the Perla for twenty-five cents. Everything on the menu is a dime except soup, and that is a nickel. I walked as far as there with Frankie, and I went in and he went on. Before he went he shook me by the hand and clapped me on the back again. \'93Don\'92t worry,\'94 he said. \'93Me Frankie much politics. Much business. Much drinking. No money. But big friend. Don\'92t worry.\'94 \'93So long, Frankie,\'94 I said. \'93Don\'92t you worry either, boy.\'94 I went in the Perla and sat down at a table. They had a new pane of glass in the window that had been shot up and the show case was all fixed up. There were a lot of gallegos drinking at the bar and some eating. One table was playing dominoes already. I had black bean soup and a beef stew with boiled potatoes for fifteen cents. A bottle of Hatuey beer brought it up to a quarter. When I spoke to the waiter about the shooting he wouldn\'92t say anything. They were all plenty scared. I finished the meal and sat back and smoked a cigarette and worried my head off. Then I saw Frankie coming in the door with someone behind him. Yellow stuff, I thought to myself. So it\'92s yellow stuff. \'93This is Mr. Sing,\'94 Frankie said, and he smiled. He\'92d been pretty fast all right and he knew it. \'93How do you do?\'94 said Mr. Sing. Mr. Sing was about the smoothest-looking thing I\'92d ever seen. He was a Chink all right, but he talked like an Englishman and he was dressed in a white suit with a silk shirt and black tie and one of those hundred-and-twenty-five-dollar Panama hats. \'93You will have some coffee?\'94 he asked me. \'93If you do.\'94 \'93Thank you,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93We are quite alone here?\'94 \'93Except for everybody in the caf\'e9,\'94 I told him. \'93That is all right,\'94 Mr. Sing said. \'93You have a boat?\'94 \'93Thirty-eight feet,\'94 I said. \'93Hundred horse Kermath.\'94 \'93Ah,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93I had imagined it was a lugger.\'94 \'93It can carry two hundred and sixty-five cases without being loaded.\'94 \'93Would you care to charter it to me?\'94 \'93On what terms?\'94 \'93You need not go. I will provide a captain and a crew.\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I go on her wherever she goes.\'94 \'93I see,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Would you mind leaving us?\'94 he said to Frankie. Frankie looked as interested as ever and smiled at him. \'93He\'92s deaf,\'94 I said. \'93He doesn\'92t understand much English.\'94 \'93I see,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93You speak Spanish. Tell him to rejoin us later.\'94 I motioned to Frankie with my thumb. He got up and went over to the bar. \'93You don\'92t speak Spanish?\'94 I said. \'93Oh, yes,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Now what are the circumstances that would\'97that have made you consider \'85\'94 \'93I\'92m broke.\'94 \'93I see,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Does the boat owe any money? Can she be libeled?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Quite so,\'94 Mr. Sing said. \'93How many of my unfortunate compatriots could your boat accommodate?\'94 \'93You mean carry?\'94 \'93That\'92s it.\'94 \'93How far?\'94 \'93A day\'92s voyage.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 I said. \'93She can take a dozen if they didn\'92t have any baggage.\'94 \'93They would not have baggage.\'94 \'93Where do you want to carry them?\'94 \'93I\'92d leave that to you,\'94 Mr. Sing said. \'93You mean where to land them?\'94 \'93You would embark them for the Tortugas where a schooner would pick them up.\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93There\'92s a lighthouse at the Tortugas on Loggerhead Key with a radio that works both ways.\'94 \'93Quite,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93It would certainly be very silly to land them there.\'94 \'93Then what?\'94 \'93I said you would embark them for there. That is what their passage calls for.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93You would land them wherever your best judgment dictated.\'94 \'93Will the schooner come to Tortugas to get them?\'94 \'93Of course not,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93How silly.\'94 \'93How much are they worth a head?\'94 \'93Fifty dollars,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93No.\'94 \'93How would seventy-five do?\'94 \'93What do you get a head?\'94 \'93Oh, that\'92s quite beside the point. You see, there are a great many facets, or shall we say angles, to my issuing the tickets. It doesn\'92t stop there.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93And what I\'92m supposed to do doesn\'92t have to be paid for, either. Eh?\'94 \'93I see your point absolutely,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Should we say a hundred dollars apiece?\'94 \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93Do you know how long I would go to jail if they pick me up on this?\'94 \'93Ten years,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Ten years at least. But there is no reason to go to jail, my dear Captain. You run only one risk\'97when you load your passengers. Everything else is left to your discretion.\'94 \'93And if they come back on your hands?\'94 \'93That\'92s quite simple. I would accuse you to them of having betrayed me. I will make a partial refund and ship them out again. They realize, of course, that it is a difficult voyage.\'94 \'93What about me?\'94 \'93I suppose I should send some word to the consulate.\'94 \'93I see.\'94 \'93Twelve hundred dollars, Captain, is not to be despised at present.\'94 \'93When would I get the money?\'94 \'93Two hundred when you agree and a thousand when you load.\'94 \'93If I would go off with the two hundred?\'94 \'93I could do nothing, of course,\'94 he smiled. \'93But I know you wouldn\'92t do such a thing, Captain.\'94 \'93Have you got the two hundred with you?\'94 \'93Of course.\'94 \'93Put it under the plate.\'94 He did. \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ll clear in the morning and pull out at dark. Now, where do we load?\'94 \'93How would Bacuranao be?\'94 \'93All right. Have you got it fixed?\'94 \'93Of course.\'94 \'93Now, about the loading,\'94 I said. \'93You show two lights, one above the other, at the point. I\'92ll come in when I see them. You come out in a boat and load from the boat. You come yourself and you bring the money. I won\'92t take one on board until I have it.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said; \'93one-half when you start to load and the other when you are finished.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s reasonable.\'94 \'93So everything is understood?\'94 \'93I guess so,\'94 I said. \'93There\'92s no baggage and no arms. No guns, knives, or razors; nothing. I have to know about that.\'94 \'93Captain,\'94 said Mr. Sing, \'93have you no trust in me? Don\'92t you see our interests are identical?\'94 \'93You\'92ll make sure?\'94 \'93Please do not embarrass me,\'94 he said. \'93Do you not see how our interests coincide?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I told him. \'93What time will you be there?\'94 \'93Before midnight.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93I guess that\'92s all.\'94 \'93How do you want the money?\'94 \'93In hundreds is all right.\'94 He stood up and I watched him go out. Frankie smiled at him as he went. He was a smooth- looking Chink all right. Some Chink. Frankie came over to the table. \'93Well?\'94 he said. \'93Where did you know Mr. Sing?\'94 \'93He ships Chinamen,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Big business.\'94 \'93How long you know him?\'94 \'93He\'92s here about two years,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Another one ship them before him. Somebody kill him.\'94 \'93Somebody will kill Mr. Sing, too.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said Frankie. \'93Why not? Plenty big business.\'94 \'93Some business,\'94 I said. \'93Big business,\'94 said Frankie. \'93Ship Chinamen never come back. Other Chinamen write letters say everything fine.\'94 \'93Wonderful,\'94 I said. \'93This kind of Chinamen no understand write. Chinamen can write all rich. Eat nothing. Live on rice. Hundred thousand Chinamen here. Only three Chinese women.\'94 \'93Why?\'94 \'93Government no let.\'94 \'93Hell of a situation,\'94 I said. \'93You do business him?\'94 \'93Maybe.\'94 \'93Good business,\'94 said Frankie. \'93Better than politics. Much money. Plenty big business.\'94 \'93Have a bottle of beer,\'94 I told him. \'93You not worry any more?\'94 \'93Hell no,\'94 I said. \'93Plenty big business. Much obliged.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 said Frankie and patted me on the back. \'93Make me happier than nothing. All I want is you happy. Chinamen good business, eh?\'94 \'93Wonderful.\'94 \'93Make me happy,\'94 said Frankie. I saw he was about ready to cry because he was so pleased everything was all right, so I patted him on the back. Some Frankie. First thing in the morning I got hold of the broker and told him to clear us. He wanted the crew list and I told him nobody. \'93You\'92re going to cross alone, Captain?\'94 \'93That\'92s right.\'94 \'93What\'92s become of your mate?\'94 \'93He\'92s on a drunk,\'94 I told him. \'93It\'92s very dangerous to go alone.\'94 \'93It\'92s only ninety miles,\'94 I said. \'93Do you think having a rummy on board makes any difference?\'94 I ran her over to the Standard Oil dock across the harbor and filled up both the tanks. She held nearly two hundred gallons when I had her full. I hated to buy it at twenty-eight cents a gallon but I didn\'92t know where we might go. Ever since I\'92d seen the Chink and taken the money I\'92d been worrying about the business. I don\'92t think I slept all night. I brought her back to the San Francisco dock, and there was Eddy waiting on the dock for me. \'93Hello, Harry,\'94 he said to me and waved. I threw him the stern line and he made her fast, and then came aboard; longer, blearier, drunker than ever. I didn\'92t say anything to him. \'93What do you think about that fellow Johnson going off like that, Harry?\'94 he asked me. \'93What do you know about that?\'94 \'93Get out of here,\'94 I told him. \'93You\'92re poison to me.\'94 \'93Brother, don\'92t I feel as bad about it as you do?\'94 \'93Get off of her,\'94 I told him. He just settled back in the chair and stretched his legs out. \'93I hear we\'92re going across today,\'94 he said. \'93Well, I guess there isn\'92t any use to stay around.\'94 \'93You\'92re not going.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter, Harry? There\'92s no sense to get plugged with me.\'94 \'93No? Get off her.\'94 \'93Oh, take it easy.\'94 I hit him in the face and he stood up and then climbed up onto the dock. \'93I wouldn\'92t do a thing like that to you, Harry,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m not going to carry you,\'94 I told him. \'93That\'92s all.\'94 \'93Well, what did you have to hit me for?\'94 \'93So you\'92d believe it.\'94 \'93What do you want me to do? Stay here and starve?\'94 \'93Starve, hell,\'94 I said. \'93You can get work on the ferry. You can work your way back.\'94 \'93You aren\'92t treating me square,\'94 he said. \'93Who did you treat square, you rummy?\'94 I told him. \'93You\'92d double-cross your own mother.\'94 That was true, too. But I felt bad about hitting him. You know how you feel when you hit a drunk. But I wouldn\'92t carry him the way things were now, not even if I wanted to. He started to walk off down the dock looking longer than a day without breakfast. Then he turned and came back. \'93How\'92s to let me take a couple of dollars, Harry?\'94 I gave him a five-dollar bill of the Chink\'92s. \'93I always knew you were my pal. Harry, why don\'92t you carry me?\'94 \'93You\'92re bad luck.\'94 \'93You\'92re just plugged,\'94 he said. \'93Never mind, old pal. You\'92ll be glad to see me yet.\'94 Now he had money he went off a good deal faster but I tell you it was poison to see him walk, even. He walked just like his joints were backwards. I went up to the Perla and met the broker and he gave me the papers and I bought him a drink. Then I had lunch and Frankie came in. \'93Fellow gave me this for you,\'94 he said and handed me a rolled-up sort of tube wrapped in paper and tied with a piece of red string. It looked like a photograph when I unwrapped it and I unrolled it thinking it was maybe a picture someone around the dock had taken of the boat. All right. It was a close-up picture of the head and chest of a dead nigger with his throat cut clear across from ear to ear and then stitched up neat and a card on his chest saying in Spanish: \'93This is what we do to lenguas largas.\'94 \'93Who gave it to you?\'94 I asked Frankie. He pointed out a Spanish boy that works around the docks who is just about gone with the con. This kid was standing at the lunch counter. \'93Ask him to come over.\'94 The kid came over. He said two young fellows gave it to him about eleven o\'92clock. They asked him if he knew me and he said yes. Then he gave it to Frankie for me. They gave him a dollar to see that I got it. They were well dressed, he said. \'93Politics,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Oh, yes,\'94 I said. \'93They think you told the police you were meeting those boys here that morning.\'94 \'93Oh, yes.\'94 \'93Bad politics,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Good thing you go.\'94 \'93Did they leave any message?\'94 I asked the Spanish boy. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93Just to give you that.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to have to leave now,\'94 I said to Frankie. \'93Bad politics,\'94 Frankie said. \'93Very bad politics.\'94 I had all the papers in a bunch that the broker had given me and I paid the bill and walked out of that caf\'e9 and across the square and through the gate and I was plenty glad to come through the warehouse and get out on the dock. Those kids had me spooked all right. They were just dumb enough to think I\'92d tipped somebody off about that other bunch. Those kids were like Pancho. When they were scared they got excited, and when they got excited they wanted to kill somebody. I got on board and warmed up the engine. Frankie stood on the dock watching. He was smiling that funny deaf smile. I went back to him. \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93Don\'92t you get in any trouble about this.\'94 He couldn\'92t hear me. I had to yell it at him. \'93Me good politics,\'94 Frankie said. He cast her off. I waved to Frankie, who\'92d thrown the bowline on board, and I headed her out of the slip and dropped down the channel with her. A British freighter was going out and I ran along beside her and passed her. I went out the harbor and past the Morro and put her on the course for Key West; due north. I left the wheel and went forward and coiled up the bowline and then came back and held her on her course, spreading Havana out astern and then dropping it off behind us as we brought the mountains up. I dropped the Morro out of sight after a while and then the National Hotel and finally I could just see the dome of the Capitol. There wasn\'92t much current compared to the last day we had fished and there was only a light breeze. I saw a couple of smacks headed in toward Havana and they were coming from the westward so I knew the current was light. I cut the switch and killed the motor. There wasn\'92t any sense in wasting gas. I\'92d let her drift. When it got dark I could always pick up the light of the Morro or, if she drifted up too far, the lights of Cojimar, and steer in and run along to Bacuranao. I figured the way the current looked she would drift the twelve miles up to Bacuranao by dark and I\'92d see the lights of Barac\'f3a. Well, I killed the engine and climbed up forward to have a look around. All there was to see was the two smacks off to the westward headed in, and way back the dome of the Capitol standing up white out of the edge of the sea. There was some gulfweed on the stream and a few birds working, but not many. I sat up there awhile on top of the house and watched, but the only fish I saw were those little brown ones that rise around the gulfweed. Brother, don\'92t let anybody tell you there isn\'92t plenty of water between Havana and Key West. I was just on the edge of it. After a while I went down into the cockpit again and there was Eddy! \'93What\'92s the matter? What\'92s the matter with the engine?\'94 \'93She broke down.\'94 \'93Why haven\'92t you got the hatch up?\'94 \'93Oh, hell!\'94 I said. Do you know what he\'92d done? He\'92d come back again and slipped the forward hatch and gone down into the cabin and gone to sleep. He had two quarts with him. He\'92d gone into the first bodega he\'92d seen and bought it and come aboard. When I started out he woke up and went back to sleep again. When I stopped her out in the gulf and she began to roll a little with the swell it woke him up. \'93I knew you\'92d carry me, Harry,\'94 he said. \'93Carry you to hell,\'94 I said. \'93You aren\'92t even on the crew list. I\'92ve got a good mind to make you jump overboard now.\'94 \'93You\'92re an old joker, Harry,\'94 he said. \'93Us conchs ought to stick together when we\'92re in trouble.\'94 \'93You,\'94 I said, \'93with your mouth. Who\'92s going to trust your mouth when you\'92re hot?\'94 \'93I\'92m a good man, Harry. You put me to the test and see what a good man I am.\'94 \'93Get me the two quarts,\'94 I told him. I was thinking of something else. He brought them out and I took a drink from the open one and put them forward by the wheel. He stood there and I looked at him. I was sorry for him and for what I knew I\'92d have to do. Hell, I knew him when he was a good man. \'93What\'92s the matter with her, Harry?\'94 \'93She\'92s all right.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter, then? What are you looking at me like that for?\'94 \'93Brother,\'94 I told him, and I was sorry for him, \'93you\'92re in plenty of trouble.\'94 \'93What do you mean, Harry?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know yet,\'94 I said. \'93I haven\'92t got it all figured out yet.\'94 We sat there awhile and I didn\'92t feel like talking to him any more. Once I knew it, it was hard to talk to him. Then I went below and got out the pump-gun and the Winchester thirty-thirty that I always had below in the cabin and hung them up in their cases from the top of the house where we hung the rods usually, right over the wheel where I could reach them. I keep them in those full-length clipped sheep\'92s-wool cases soaked in oil. That\'92s the only way you can keep them from rusting on a boat. I loosened up the pump and worked her a few times, and then filled her up and pumped one into the barrel. I put a shell in the chamber of the Winchester and filled up the magazine. I got out the Smith and Wesson thirty-eight special I had when I was on the police force up in Miami from under the mattress and cleaned and oiled it and filled it up and put it on my belt. \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 Eddy said. \'93What the hell\'92s the matter?\'94 \'93Nothing,\'94 I told him. \'93What\'92s all the damn guns for?\'94 \'93I always carry them on board,\'94 I said. \'93To shoot birds that bother the baits or to shoot sharks cruising along the keys.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter, damn it?\'94 said Eddy. \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 \'93Nothing,\'94 I told him. I sat there with the old thirty-eight flopping against my leg when she rolled, and I looked at him. I thought, there\'92s no sense to do it now. I\'92m going to need him now. \'93We\'92re going to do a little job,\'94 I said. \'93In at Bacuranao. I\'92ll tell you what to do when it\'92s time.\'94 I didn\'92t want to tell him too far ahead because he would get to worrying and get so spooked he wouldn\'92t be any use. \'93You couldn\'92t have anybody better than me. Harry,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m the man for you. I\'92m with you on anything.\'94 I looked at him, tall and bleary and shaky, and I didn\'92t say anything. \'93Listen, Harry. Would you give me just one?\'94 he asked me. \'93I don\'92t want to get the shakes.\'94 I gave him one and we sat and waited for it to get dark. It was a fine sunset and there was a nice light breeze, and when the sun got pretty well down I started the engine and headed her in slow toward land. We lay offshore about a mile in the dark. The current had freshened up with the sun down and I noticed it running in. I could see the Morro light way down to the westward and the glow of Havana, and the lights opposite us were Rinc\'f3n and Barac\'f3a. I headed her up against the current until I was past Bacuranao and nearly to Cojimar. Then I let her drift down. It was plenty dark but I could tell good where we were. I had all the lights out. \'93What\'92s it going to be, Harry?\'94 Eddy asked me. He was beginning to be spooked again. \'93What do you think?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 he said. \'93You\'92ve got me worried.\'94 He was pretty close to the shakes and when he came near me he had a breath like a buzzard. \'93What time is it?\'94 \'93I\'92ll go down and see,\'94 he said. He came back up and said it was half past nine. \'93Are you hungry?\'94 I asked him. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93You know I couldn\'92t eat, Harry.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I told him. \'93You can have one.\'94 After he had it I asked him how he felt. He said he felt fine. \'93I\'92m going to give you a couple more in a little while,\'94 I told him. \'93I know you haven\'92t got any guts unless you\'92ve got rum and there isn\'92t much on board. So you\'92d better go easy.\'94 \'93Tell me what\'92s up,\'94 said Eddy. \'93Listen,\'94 I said, talking to him in the dark. \'93We\'92re going in to Bacuranao and pick up twelve Chinks. You take the wheel when I tell you to and do what I tell you to. We\'92ll take the twelve Chinks on board and we\'92ll lock them below forward. Go on forward now and fasten the hatch from the outside.\'94 He went up and I saw him shadowed against the dark. He came back and he said, \'93Harry, can I have one of those now?\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I want you rum-brave. I don\'92t want you useless.\'94 \'93I\'92m a good man, Harry. You\'92ll see.\'94 \'93You\'92re a rummy,\'94 I said. \'93Listen. One Chink is going to bring those twelve out. He\'92s going to give me some money at the start. When they\'92re all on board he\'92s going to give me some more money. When you see him start to hand me money the second time you put her ahead and hook her up and head her out to sea. Don\'92t you pay any attention to what happens. You keep her going out no matter what happens. Do you understand?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93If any Chink starts bursting out of the cabin or coming through the hatch, once we\'92re out and under way, you take that pump-gun and blow them back as fast as they come out. Do you know how to use the pump-gun?\'94 \'93No. But you can show me.\'94 \'93You\'92d never remember. Do you know how to use the Winchester?\'94 \'93Just pump the lever and shoot it.\'94 \'93That\'92s right,\'94 I said. \'93Only don\'92t shoot any holes in the hull.\'94 \'93You\'92d better give me that other drink,\'94 Eddy said. \'93All right. I\'92ll give you a little one.\'94 I gave him a real one. I knew they wouldn\'92t make him drunk now; not pouring into all that fear. But each one would work for a little while. After he drank this Eddy said, just as though he was happy, \'93So we\'92re going to run Chinks. Well, by God, I always said I\'92d run Chinamen if I was ever broke.\'94 \'93But you never got broke before, eh?\'94 I said to him. He was funny all right. I gave him three more drinks to keep him brave before it was half past ten. It was funny watching him and it kept me from thinking about it myself. I hadn\'92t figured on all this wait. I\'92d planned to leave after dark, run out, just out of the glare, and coast along to Cojimar. At a little before eleven I saw the two lights show on the point. I waited a little while and then I took her in slow. Bacuranao is a cove where there used to be a big dock for loading sand. There is a little river that comes in when the rains open the bar across the mouth. The northers, in the winter, pile the sand up and close it. They used to go in with schooners and load guavas from the river and there used to be a town. But the hurricane took it and it is all gone now except one house that some gallegos built out of the shacks the hurricane blew down and that they use for a clubhouse on Sundays when they come out to swim and picnic from Havana. There is one other house where the delegate lives but it is back from the beach. Each little place like that all down the coast has a government delegate, but I figured the Chink must use his own boat and have him fixed. As we came in I could smell the sea grape and that sweet smell from the brush you get off the land. \'93Get up forward,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93You can\'92t hit anything on that side,\'94 he said. \'93The reef\'92s on the other side as you go in.\'94 You see, he\'92d been a good man once. \'93Watch her,\'94 I said, and I took her in to where I knew they could see us. With no surf they could hear the engine. I didn\'92t want to wait around, not knowing whether they saw us or not, so I flashed the running lights on once, just the green and red, and turned them off. Then I turned her and headed her out and let her lay there, just outside, with the engine just ticking. There was quite a little swell that close in. \'93Come on back here,\'94 I said to Eddy and I gave him a real drink. \'93Do you cock it first with your thumb?\'94 he whispered to me. He was sitting at the wheel now, and I had reached up and had both the cases open and the butts pulled out about six inches. \'93That\'92s right.\'94 \'93Oh boy,\'94 he said. It certainly was wonderful what a drink would do to him and how quick. We lay there and I could see a light from the delegate\'92s house back through the bush. I saw the two lights on the point go down, and one of them moving off around the point. They must have blown the other one out. Then, in a little while, coming out of the cove, I see a boat come toward us with a man sculling. I could tell by the way he swung back and forth. I knew he had a big oar. I was pretty pleased. If they were sculling that meant one man. They came alongside. \'93Good evening. Captain,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93Come astern and put her broadside,\'94 I said to him. He said something to the man who was sculling but he couldn\'92t scull her backwards, so I took hold of the gunwale and passed her astern. There were eight men in the boat. The six Chinks, Mr. Sing, and the kid sculling. While I was pulling her astern I was waiting for something to hit me on top of the head but nothing did. I straightened up and let Mr. Sing hold onto the stern. \'93Let\'92s see what it looks like,\'94 I said. He handed it to me and I took it up to where Eddy was at the wheel and put on the binnacle light. I looked at it carefully. It looked all right to me and I turned off the light. Eddy was trembling. \'93Pour one yourself,\'94 I said. I saw him reach for the bottle and tip it up. I went back to the stern. \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93Let six come on board.\'94 Mr. Sing and the Cuban that sculled were having a job holding their boat from knocking in what little swell there was. I heard Mr. Sing say something in Chink and all the Chinks in the boat started to climb onto the stern. \'93One at a time,\'94 I said. He said something again, and then one after another six Chinks came over the stern. They were all lengths and sizes. \'93Show them forward,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93Right this way, gentlemen,\'94 said Eddy. By God, I knew he had taken a big one. \'93Lock the cabin,\'94 I said, when they were all in. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 said Eddy. \'93I will return with the others,\'94 said Mr. Sing. \'93O.K.,\'94 I told him. I pushed them clear and the boy with him started sculling off. \'93Listen,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93You lay off that bottle. You\'92re brave enough now.\'94 \'93O.K., chief,\'94 said Eddy. \'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94 \'93This is what I like to do,\'94 said Eddy. \'93You say you just pull it backward with your thumb?\'94 \'93You lousy rummy,\'94 I told him. \'93Give me a drink out of that.\'94 \'93All gone,\'94 said Eddy. \'93Sorry, chief.\'94 \'93Listen. What you have to do now is watch her when he hands me the money and put her ahead.\'94 \'93O.K., chief,\'94 said Eddy. I reached up and took the other bottle and got the corkscrew and drew the cork. I took a good drink and went back to the stem, putting the cork in tight and laying the bottle behind two wicker jugs full of water. \'93Here comes Mr. Sing,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 said Eddy. The boat came out sculling toward us. He brought her astern and I let them do the holding in. Mr. Sing had hold of the roller we had across the stern to slide a big fish on board. \'93Let them come aboard,\'94 I said, \'93one at a time.\'94 Six more assorted Chinks came on board over the stern. \'93Open up and show them forward,\'94 I told Eddy. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 said Eddy. \'93Lock the cabin.\'94 \'93Yes, sir.\'94 I saw he was at the wheel. \'93All right, Mr. Sing,\'94 I said. \'93Let\'92s see the rest of it.\'94 He put his hand in his pocket and reached the money out toward me. I reached for it and grabbed his wrist with the money in his hand, and as he came forward on the stern I grabbed his throat with the other hand. I felt her start and then churn ahead as she hooked up and I was plenty busy with Mr. Sing but I could see the Cuban standing in the stem of the boat holding the sculling oar through all the flopping and bouncing Mr. Sing was doing. He was flopping and bouncing worse than any dolphin on a gaff. I got his arm around behind him and came up on it but I brought it too far because I felt it go. When it went he made a funny little noise and came forward, me holding him throat and all, and bit me on the shoulder. But when I felt the arm go I dropped it. It wasn\'92t any good to him any more and I took him by the throat with both hands, and brother, that Mr. Sing would flop just like a fish, true, his loose arm flailing, but I got him forward onto his knees and had both thumbs well in behind his talk box and I bent the whole thing back until she cracked. Don\'92t think you can\'92t hear it crack, either. I held him quiet just a second, and then I laid him down across the stem. He lay there, face up, quiet, in his good clothes, with his feet in the cockpit, and I left him. I picked up the money off the cockpit floor and took it up and put it on the binnacle and counted it. Then I took the wheel and told Eddy to look under the stem for some pieces of iron that I used for anchoring whenever we fished bottom fishing on patches or rocky bottom where you wouldn\'92t want to risk an anchor. \'93I can\'92t find anything,\'94 he said. He was scared being down there by Mr. Sing. \'93Take the wheel,\'94 I said. \'93Keep her out.\'94 There was a certain amount of moving around going on below but I wasn\'92t spooked about them. I found a couple of pieces of what I wanted\'97iron from the old coaling dock at Tortugas\'97and I took some snapper line and made a couple of good big pieces fast to Mr. Sing\'92s ankles. Then when we were about two miles offshore I slid him over. He slid over smooth off the roller. I never even looked in his pockets. I didn\'92t feel like fooling with him. He\'92d bled a little on the stern from his nose and his mouth, and I dipped a bucket of water that nearly pulled me overboard the way we were going, and cleaned her off good with a scrub brush from under the stern. \'93Slow her down,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93What if he floats up?\'94 Eddy said. \'93I dropped him in about seven hundred fathoms,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s going down all that way. That\'92s a long way, brother. He won\'92t float till the gas brings him up and all the time he\'92s going with the current and baiting up fish. Hell,\'94 I said, \'93you don\'92t have to worry about Mr. Sing.\'94 \'93What did you have against him?\'94 Eddy asked me. \'93Nothing,\'94 I said. \'93He was the easiest man to do business with I ever met. I thought there must be something wrong all the time.\'94 \'93What did you kill him for?\'94 \'93To keep from killing twelve other Chinks,\'94 I told him. \'93Harry,\'94 he said, \'93you\'92ve got to give me one because I can feel them coming on. It made me sick to see his head all loose like that.\'94 So I gave him one. \'93What about the Chinks?\'94 Eddy said. \'93I want to get them out as quick as I can,\'94 I told him. \'93Before they smell up the cabin.\'94 \'93Where are you going to put them?\'94 \'93We\'92ll run them right in to the long beach,\'94 I told him. \'93Take her in now?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93Take her in slow.\'94 We came in slow over the reef and to where I could see the beach shine. There is plenty of water over the reef and inside it\'92s all sandy bottom and slopes right in to shore. \'93Get up forward and give me the depth.\'94 He kept sounding with a grains pole, motioning me on with the pole. He came back and motioned me to stop. I came astern on her. \'93You\'92ve got about five feet.\'94 \'93We\'92ve got to anchor,\'94 I said. \'93If anything happens so we haven\'92t time to get her up, we can cut loose or break her off.\'94 Eddy paid out rope and when finally she didn\'92t drag he made her fast. She swung stern in. \'93It\'92s sandy bottom, you know,\'94 he said. \'93How much water have we got at the stern?\'94 \'93Not over five feet.\'94 \'93You take the rifle,\'94 I said. \'93And be careful,\'94 \'93Let me have one,\'94 he said. He was plenty nervous. I gave him one and took down the pump-gun. I unlocked the cabin door, opened it, and said: \'93Come on out.\'94 Nothing happened. Then one Chink put his head out and saw Eddy standing there with a rifle and ducked back. \'93Come on out. Nobody\'92s going to hurt you,\'94 I said. Nothing doing. Only lots of talk in Chink. \'93Come on out, you!\'94 Eddy said. My God, I knew he\'92d had the bottle. \'93Put that bottle away,\'94 I said to him, \'93or I\'92ll blow you out of the boat.\'94 \'93Come on out,\'94 I said to them, \'93or I\'92ll shoot in at you.\'94 I saw one of them looking at the corner of the door and he saw the beach evidently because he begins to chatter. \'93Come on,\'94 I said, \'93or I\'92ll shoot.\'94 Out they came. Now I tell you it would take a hell of a mean man to butcher a bunch of Chinks like that and I\'92ll bet there would be plenty of trouble, too, let alone mess. They came out and they were scared and they didn\'92t have any guns but there were twelve of them. I walked backwards down to the stem holding the pump gun. \'93Get overboard,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s not over your heads.\'94 Nobody moved. \'93Over you go.\'94 Nobody moved. \'93You yellow rat-eating aliens,\'94 Eddy said, \'93get overboard.\'94 \'93Shut your drunken mouth,\'94 I told him. \'93No swim,\'94 one Chink said. \'93No need swim,\'94 I said. \'93No deep.\'94 \'93Come on, get overboard,\'94 Eddy said. \'93Come astern here,\'94 I said. \'93Take your gun in one hand and your grains pole in the other and show them how deep it is.\'94 He showed them. \'93No need swim?\'94 the one asked me. \'93No.\'94 \'93True?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93Where we?\'94 \'93Cuba.\'94 \'93You damn crook,\'94 he said and went over the side, hanging on and then letting go. His head went under but he came up and his chin was out of water. \'93Damn crook,\'94 he said. \'93Damn crook.\'94 He was mad and he was plenty brave. He said something in Chink and the others started going into the water off the stern. \'93All right,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93Get the anchor up.\'94 As we headed her out, the moon started to come up and you could see the Chinks with just their heads out of water walking ashore, and the shine of the beach and the brush behind. We got out past the reef and I looked back once and saw the beach and the mountains starting to show up; then I put her on her course for Key West. \'93Now you can take a sleep,\'94 I said to Eddy. \'93No, wait, go below and open up all the ports to get the stink out and bring me the iodine.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 he said when he brought it. \'93I cut my finger.\'94 \'93Do you want me to steer?\'94 \'93Get a sleep,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ll wake you up.\'94 He lay down on the built-in bunk in the cockpit, over the gas tank, and in a little while he was asleep. I held the wheel with my knee and opened up my shirt and saw where Mr. Sing bit me. It was quite a bite and I put iodine on it, and then I sat there steering and wondering whether a bite from a Chinaman was poisonous and listened to her running nice and smooth and the water washing along her and I figured, Hell no, that bite wasn\'92t poisonous. A man like that Mr. Sing probably scrubbed his teeth two or three times a day. Some Mr. Sing. He certainly wasn\'92t much of a business man. Maybe he was. Maybe he just trusted me. I tell you I couldn\'92t figure him. Well, now it was all simple except for Eddy. Because he\'92s a rummy he\'92ll talk when he gets hot. I sat there steering and I looked at him and I thought, Hell, he\'92s as well off dead as the way he is, and then I\'92m all clear. When I found he was on board I decided I\'92d have to do away with him but then when everything had come out so nice I didn\'92t have the heart. But looking at him lying there it certainly was a temptation. But then I thought there\'92s no sense spoiling it by doing something you\'92d be sorry for afterwards. Then I started to think he wasn\'92t even on the crew list and I\'92d have a fine to pay for bringing him in and I didn\'92t know how to consider him. Well, I had plenty of time to think about it and I held her on her course and every once in a while I\'92d take a drink out of the bottle he\'92d brought on board. There wasn\'92t much in it, and when I\'92d finished it, I opened up the only one I had left, and I tell you I felt pretty good steering, and it was a pretty night to cross. It had turned out a good trip all right, finally, even though it had looked plenty bad plenty of times. When it got daylight Eddy woke up. He said he felt terrible. \'93Take the wheel a minute,\'94 I told him. \'93I want to look around.\'94 I went back to the stem and threw a little water on her. But she was perfectly clean. I scrubbed the brush over the side. I unloaded the guns and stowed them below. But I still kept the gun on my belt. It was fresh and nice as you want it below, no smell at all. A little water had come in through the starboard port onto one of the bunks was all; so I shut the ports. There wasn\'92t a customhouse officer in the world could smell Chink in her now. I saw the clearance papers in the net bag hanging up under her framed license where I\'92d shoved them when I came on board and I took them out to look them over. Then I went up to the cockpit. \'93Listen,\'94 I said. \'93How did you get on the crew list?\'94 \'93I met the broker when he was leaving for the consulate and told him I was going.\'94 \'93God looks after rummies,\'94 I told him and I took the thirty-eight off and stowed it down below. I made some coffee down below and then I came up and took the wheel. \'93There\'92s coffee below,\'94 I told him. \'93Brother, coffee wouldn\'92t do me any good.\'94 You knew you had to be sorry for him. He certainly looked bad. About nine o\'92clock we saw the Sand Key light just about dead ahead. We\'92d seen tankers going up the gulf for quite a while. \'93We\'92ll be in now,\'94 I said to him. \'93I\'92m going to give you the same four dollars a day just as if Johnson had paid.\'94 \'93How much did you get out of last night?\'94 he asked me. \'93Only six hundred,\'94 I told him. I don\'92t know whether he believed me or not. \'93Don\'92t I share in it?\'94 \'93That\'92s your share,\'94 I told him. \'93What I just told you, and if you ever open your mouth about last night I\'92ll hear of it and I\'92ll do away with you.\'94 \'93You know I\'92m no squealer, Harry.\'94 \'93You\'92re a rummy. But no matter how rum dumb you get, if you ever talk about that, I promise you.\'94 \'93I\'92m a good man,\'94 he said. \'93You oughtn\'92t to talk to me like that.\'94 \'93They can\'92t make it fast enough to keep you a good man,\'94 I told him. But I didn\'92t worry about him any more, because who was going to believe him? Mr. Sing wouldn\'92t make any complaints. The Chinks weren\'92t going to. You know the boy that sculled them out wasn\'92t. Eddy would mouth about it sooner or later, maybe, but who believes a rummy? Why, who could prove anything? Naturally it would have made plenty more talk when they saw his name on the crew list. That was luck for me, all right. I could have said he fell overboard, but it makes plenty talk. Plenty of luck for Eddy, too. Plenty of luck, all right. Then we came to the edge of the stream and the water quit being blue and was light and greenish and inside I could see the stakes on the Long Reef and on the Western Dry Rocks and the wireless masts at Key West and the La Concha hotel up high out of all the low houses and plenty smoke from out where they\'92re burning garbage. Sand Key light was plenty close now and you could see the boathouse and the little dock alongside the light and I knew we were only forty minutes away now and I felt good to be getting back and I had a good stake now for the summertime. \'93What do you say about a drink, Eddy?\'94 I said to him. \'93Ah, Harry,\'94 he said, \'93I always knew you were my pal.\'94 The Tradesman\'92s Return THEY CAME ON ACROSS IN THE NIGHT AND it blew a big breeze from the northwest. When the sun was up he sighted a tanker coming down the gulf and she stood up so high and white with the sun on her in that cold air that it looked like tall buildings rising out of the sea and he said to the nigger, \'93Where the hell are we?\'94 The nigger raised himself up to look. \'93Ain\'92t nothing like that this side of Miami.\'94 \'93You know damn well we ain\'92t been carried up to no Miami,\'94 he told the nigger. \'93All I say ain\'92t no buildings like that on no Florida keys.\'94 \'93We\'92ve been steering for Sand Key.\'94 \'93We\'92ve got to see it then. It or American shoals.\'94 Then in a little while he saw it was a tanker and not buildings and then in less than an hour he saw Sand Key light, straight, thin and brown, rising out of the sea right where it ought to be. \'93You got to have confidence steering,\'94 he told the nigger. \'93I got confidence,\'94 the nigger said. \'93But the way this trip gone I ain\'92t got confidence no more.\'94 \'93How\'92s your leg?\'94 \'93It hurts me all the time.\'94 \'93It ain\'92t nothing,\'94 the man said. \'93You keep it clean and wrapped up and it\'92ll heal by itself.\'94 He was steering to the westward now to go in to lay up for the day in the mangroves by Woman Key where he would not see anybody and where the boat was to come out to meet them. \'93You\'92re going to be all right,\'94 he told the Negro. \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 the nigger said. \'93I hurt bad.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to fix you up good when we get in to the place,\'94 he told him. \'93You aren\'92t shot bad. Quit worrying.\'94 \'93I\'92m shot,\'94 he said. \'93I ain\'92t never been shot before. Anyway I\'92m shot is bad.\'94 \'93You\'92re just scared.\'94 \'93No sir. I\'92m shot. And I\'92m hurting bad. I\'92ve been throbbing all night.\'94 The nigger went on grumbling like that and he could not keep from taking the bandage off to look at it. \'93Leave it alone,\'94 the man who was steering told him. The nigger lay on the floor of the cockpit and there were sacks of liquor, shaped like hams, piled everywhere. He had made himself a place in them to lie down in. Every time he moved there was the noise of broken glass in the sacks and there was the odor of spilled liquor. The liquor had run all over everything. The man was steering in for Woman Key now. He could see it now plainly. \'93I hurt,\'94 the nigger said. \'93I hurt worse all the time.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry, Wesley,\'94 the man said. \'93But I got to steer.\'94 \'93You treat a man no better than a dog,\'94 the nigger said. He was getting ugly now, but the man was still sorry for him. \'93I\'92m going to make you comfortable, Wesley,\'94 he said. \'93You lay quiet now.\'94 \'93You don\'92t care what happens to a man,\'94 the nigger said. \'93You ain\'92t hardly human.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to fix you up good,\'94 the man said. \'93You just lay quiet.\'94 \'93You ain\'92t going to fix me up,\'94 the nigger said. The man, whose name was Harry, said nothing then because he liked the nigger and there was nothing to do now but hit him, and he couldn\'92t hit him. The nigger kept on talking. \'93Why we didn\'92t stop when they started shooting?\'94 The man did not answer. \'93Ain\'92t a man\'92s life worth more than a load of liquor?\'94 The man was intent on his steering. \'93All we have to do is stop and let them take the liquor.\'94 \'93No,\'94 the man said. \'93They take the liquor and the boat and you go to jail.\'94 \'93I don\'92t mind jail,\'94 the nigger said. \'93But I never wanted to get shot.\'94 He was getting on the man\'92s nerves now and the man was becoming tired of hearing him talk. \'93Who the hell\'92s shot worse?\'94 he asked him. \'93You or me?\'94 \'93You\'92re shot worse,\'94 the nigger said. \'93But I ain\'92t never been shot. I didn\'92t figure to get shot. I ain\'92t paid to get shot. I don\'92t want to be shot.\'94 \'93Take it easy, Wesley,\'94 the man told him. \'93It don\'92t do you any good to talk like that.\'94 They were coming up on the key now. They were inside the shoals and as he headed her into the channel it was hard to see with the sun on the water. The nigger was going out of his head, or becoming religious because he was hurt; anyway he was talking all the time. \'93Why they 