he motion of the big sea they had been in all night in the gulf. \'93I\'92m going to make some coffee,\'94 he told the nigger. \'93Then I\'92ll fix you up again.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want no coffee.\'94 \'93I do,\'94 the man told him. But down below he began to feel dizzy so he came out on deck again. \'93I guess we won\'92t have coffee,\'94 he said. \'93I want some water.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 He gave the Negro a cup of water out of a demijohn. \'93Why you want to keep on running for when they started to shoot?\'94 \'93Why they want to shoot?\'94 the man answered. \'93I want a doctor,\'94 the nigger told him. \'93What\'92s a doctor going to do that I ain\'92t done for you?\'94 \'93Doctor going to cure me.\'94 \'93You\'92ll have a doctor tonight when the boat comes out.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to wait for no boat.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 the man said. \'93We\'92re going to dump this liquor now.\'94 He started to dump it and it was hard work one-handed. A sack of liquor only weighs about forty pounds but he had not dumped very many of them before he became dizzy again. He sat down in the cockpit and then he lay down. \'93You going to kill yourself,\'94 the nigger said. The man lay quietly in the cockpit with his head against one of the sacks. The branches of the mangroves had come into the cockpit and they made a shadow over him where he lay. He could hear the wind above the mangroves and looking out at the high, cold sky see the thin brown clouds of the norther. \'93Nobody going to come out with this breeze,\'94 he thought. \'93They won\'92t look for us to have started with this blowing.\'94 \'93You think they\'92ll come out?\'94 the nigger asked. \'93Sure,\'94 the man said. \'93Why not?\'94 \'93It\'92s blowing too hard.\'94 \'93They\'92re looking for us.\'94 \'93Not with it like this. What you want to lie to me for?\'94 The nigger was talking with his mouth almost against a sack. \'93Take it easy, Wesley,\'94 the man told him. \'93Take it easy, the man says,\'94 the 