\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I know he is not.\'94 \'93I have never denounced anyone.\'94 \'93It is your problem. Maybe one of the other waiters will denounce him.\'94 \'93No. Only the old waiters know him and the old waiters do not denounce.\'94 \'93Bring another of the yellow gins and some bitters,\'94 I said. \'93There is tonic water still in the bottle.\'94 \'93What\'92s he talk about?\'94 asked John. \'93I only understand little bit.\'94 \'93There is a man here that we both knew in the old days. He used to be a marvelous pigeon shot and I used to see him at shoots. He is a fascist and for him to come here now, no matter what his reasons, is very foolish. But he was always very brave and very foolish.\'94 \'93Show him to me.\'94 \'93There at that table with the flyers.\'94 \'93Which one?\'94 \'93With the very brown face; the cap over one eye. Who is laughing now.\'94 \'93He is fascist?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93That\'92s a closest I see fascist since Fuentes del Ebro. Is a many fascist here?\'94 \'93Quite a few from time to time.\'94 \'93Is drink the same drink as you,\'94 said John. \'93We drink that other people think we fascists, eh? Listen you ever been South America, West Coast, Magallanes?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Is all right. Only too many oc-toe-pus.\'94 \'93Too many what?\'94 \'93Oc-toe-pus.\'94 He pronounced it with the accent on the toe as oc-toepus. \'93You know with the eight arms.\'94 \'93Oh,\'94 I said. \'93Octopus.\'94 \'93Oc-toe-pus,\'94 said John. \'93You see I am diver too. Is a good place to work all right make plenty money only too many oc-toe-pus.\'94 \'93Did they bother you?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know about that. First time I go down in Magallanes harbor I see oc-toe-pus. He is stand on his feet like this.\'94 John pointed his fingers on the table and brought his hands up, at the same time bringing up his shoulders and raising his eyebrows. \'93He is stand up taller than I am and he is look me right in the eye. I jerk cord for them to bring me up.\'94 \'93How big was he, John?\'94 \'93I cannot say absolutely because the glass in the helmet make distort a little. But the head was big around more than four feet anyway. And he was stand on his feet like on tip-toes and look at me like this.\'94 (He peered in my face.) \'93So when I get up out of water they take off the helmet and so I say I don\'92t go down there any more. Then the man of the job says, \'91What a matter with you, John? The octoe-pus is more afraid of you than you afraid of oc-toe-pus.\'92 So I say to him \'91Impossible!\'92 What you say we drink some more this fascist drink?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. I was watching the man at the table. His name was Luis Delgado and the last time I had seen him had been in 1933 shooting pigeons at Saint Sebastian and I remembered standing with him up on top of the stand watching the final of the big shoot. We had a bet, more than I could afford to bet, and I believed a good deal more than he could afford to lose that year, and when he paid coming down the stairs, I remembered how pleasant he was and how he made it seem a great privilege to pay. Then I remembered our standing at the bar having a martini, and I had that wonderful feeling of relief that comes when you have bet yourself out of a bad hole and I was wondering how badly the bet had hit him. I had shot rottenly all week and he had shot beautifully but drawn almost impossible birds and he had bet on himself steadily. \'93Should we match a duro?\'94 he asked. \'93You really want to?\'94 \'93Yes, if you like.\'94 \'93For how much?\'94 He took out a notecase and looked in it and laughed. \'93I\'92d say for anything you like,\'94 he said. \'93But suppose we say for eight thousand pesetas. That\'92s what seems to be there.\'94 That was close to a thousand dollars then. \'93Good,\'94 I said, all the fine inner quiet gone now and the hollow that gambling makes come back again. \'93Who\'92s matching who?\'94 \'93I\'92ll match you.\'94 We shook the heavy five-peseta pieces in our cupped hands; then each man laid his coin on the back of his left hand, each coin covered with the right hand. \'93What\'92s yours?\'94 he asked. I uncovered the big silver piece with the profile of Alfonso XIII as a baby showing. \'93Heads,\'94 I said. \'93Take these damned things and be a good man and buy me a drink.\'94 He emptied out the notecase. \'93You wouldn\'92t like to buy a good Purdey gun would you?\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93But look, Luis, if you need some money\'97\'94 I was holding the stiffly folded, shiny-heavy-paper, green thousandpeseta notes toward him. \'93Don\'92t be silly, Enrique,\'94 he said. \'93We\'92ve been gambling, haven\'92t we?\'94 \'93Yes. But we know each other quite well.\'94 \'93Not that well.\'94 \'93Right,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92re the judge of that. Then what will you drink?\'94 \'93What about a gin and tonic? That\'92s a marvelous drink you know.\'94 So we had a gin and tonic and I felt very badly to have broken him and I felt awfully good to have won the money, and a gin and tonic never tasted better to me in all my life. There is no use to lie about these things or pretend you do not enjoy winning; but this boy Luis Delgado was a very pretty gambler. \'93I don\'92t think if people gambled for what they could afford it would be very interesting. Do you, Enrique?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. I\'92ve never been able to afford it.\'94 \'93Don\'92t be silly. You have lots of money.\'94 \'93No I haven\'92t,\'94 I said. \'93Really.\'94 \'93Oh, everyone has money,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s just a question of selling something or other to get hold of it.\'94 \'93I don\'92t have much. Really.\'94 \'93Oh, don\'92t be silly. I\'92ve never known an American who wasn\'92t rich.\'94 I guess that was the truth all right. He wouldn\'92t have met them at the Ritz bar or at Chicote\'92s either in those days. And now he was back in Chicote\'92s and all the Americans he would meet there now were the kind he would never have met; except me, and I was a mistake. But I would have given plenty not to have seen him in there. Still, if he wanted to do an absolutely damn fool thing like that it was his own business. But as I looked at the table and remembered the old days I felt badly about him and I felt very badly too that I had given the waiter the number of the counterespionage bureau in Seguridad headquarters. He could have had Seguridad by simply asking on the telephone. But I had given him the shortest cut to having Delgado arrested in one of those excesses of impartiality, righteousness and Pontius Pilatry, and the always-dirty desire to see how people act under an emotional conflict, that makes writers such attractive friends. The waiter came over. \'93What do you think?\'94 he asked. \'93I would never denounce him myself,\'94 I said, now trying to undo for myself what I had done with the number. \'93But I am a foreigner and it is your war and your problem.\'94 \'93But you are with us.\'94 \'93Absolutely and always. But it does not include denouncing old friends.\'94 \'93But for me?\'94 \'93For you it is different.\'94 I knew this was true and there was nothing else to say, only I wished I had never heard of any of it. My curiosity as to how people would act in this case had been long ago, and shamefully, satisfied. I turned to John and did not look at the table where Luis Delgado was sitting. I knew he had been flying with the fascists for over a year, and here he was, in a loyalist uniform, talking to three young loyalist flyers of the last crop that had been trained in France. None of those new kids would know him and I wondered whether he had come to try to steal a plane or for what. Whatever he was there for, he was a fool to come to Chicote\'92s now. \'93How do you feel, John?\'94 I asked. \'93Feel good,\'94 said John. \'93Is a good drink hokay. Makes me feel little bit drunk maybe. Is a good for the buzzing in the head.\'94 The waiter came over. He was very excited. \'93I have denounced him,\'94 he said. \'93Well then,\'94 I said, \'93now you haven\'92t any problem.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said proudly. \'93I have denounced him. They are on their way now to get him.\'94 \'93Let\'92s go,\'94 I said to John. \'93There is going to be some trouble here.\'94 \'93Is best go then,\'94 said John. \'93Is a plenty trouble always come, even if you do best to avoid. How much we owe?\'94 \'93You aren\'92t going to stay?\'94 the waiter asked. \'93No.\'94 \'93But you gave me the telephone number.\'94 \'93I know it. You get to know too many telephone numbers if you stay around in this town.\'94 \'93But it was my duty.\'94 \'93Yes. Why not? Duty is a very strong thing.\'94 \'93But now?\'94 \'93Well, you felt good about it just now, didn\'92t you? Maybe you will feel good about it again. Maybe you will get to like it.\'94 \'93You have forgotten the package,\'94 the waiter said. He handed me the meat which was wrapped in two envelopes which had brought copies of the Spur to the piles of magazines which accumulated in one of the office rooms of the Embassy. \'93I understand,\'94 I said to the waiter. \'93Truly.\'94 \'93He was an old client and a good client. Also I have never denounced anyone before. I did not denounce for pleasure.\'94 \'93Also I should not speak cynically or brutally. Tell him that I denounced him. He hates me anyway by now for differences in politics. He\'92d feel badly if he knew it was you.\'94 \'93No. Each man must take his responsibility. But you understand?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. Then lied. \'93I understand and I approve.\'94 You have to lie very often in a war and when you have to lie you should do it quickly and as well as you can. We shook hands and I went out the door with John. I looked back at the table where Luis Delgado sat as I went out. He had another gin and tonic in front of him and everyone at the table was laughing at something he had said. He had a very gay, brown face, and shooter\'92s eyes, and I wondered what he was passing himself off as. He was a fool to go to Chicote\'92s. But that was exactly the sort of thing that he would do in order to be able to boast of it when he was back with his own people. As we went out of the door and turned to walk up the street, a big Seguridad car drew up in front of Chicote\'92s and eight men got out of it. Six with submachine guns took up positions outside the door. Two in plain clothes went inside. A man asked us for our papers and when I said, \'93Foreigners,\'94 he said to go along; that it was all right. In the dark going up the Gran Via there was much new broken glass on the sidewalk and much rubble under foot from the shelling. The air was still smoky and all up the street it smelled of high explosive and blasted granite. \'93Where you go eat?\'94 asked John. \'93I have some meat for all of us, and we can cook it in the room.\'94 \'93I cook it,\'94 said John. \'93I cook good. I remember one time when I cook on ship\'97\'94 \'93It will be pretty tough,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s just been freshly butchered.\'94 \'93Oh no,\'94 said John. \'93Is a no such thing as a touch meat in a war.\'94 People were hurrying by in the dark on their way home from the cinemas where they had stayed until the shelling was over. \'93What\'92s a matter that fascist he come to that caf\'e9 where they know him?\'94 \'93He was crazy to do it.\'94 \'93Is a trouble with a war,\'94 John said. \'93Is a too many people crazy.\'94 \'93John,\'94 I said, \'93I think you\'92ve got something there.\'94 Back at the hotel we went in the door past the sandbags piled to protect the porter\'92s desk and I asked for the key, but the porter said there were two comrades upstairs in the room taking a bath. He had given them the keys. \'93Go on up, John,\'94 I said. \'93I want to telephone.\'94 I went over to the booth and called the same number I had given the waiter. \'93Hello? Pep\'e9?\'94 A thin-lipped voice came over the phone. \'93\'bfQu\'e9 tal Enrique?\'94 \'93Listen, Pep\'e9, did you pick up a certain Luis Delgado at Chicote\'92s?\'94 \'93S\'ed, hombre, s\'ed. Sin novedad. Without trouble.\'94 \'93He doesn\'92t know anything about the waiter?\'94 \'93No, hombre, no.\'94 \'93Then don\'92t tell him. Tell him I denounced him then, will you? Nothing about the waiter.\'94 \'93Why when it will make no difference? He is a spy. He will be shot. There is no choice in the matter.\'94 \'93I know,\'94 I said. \'93But it makes a difference.\'94 \'93As you want, hombre. As you want. When shall I see thee?\'94 \'93Lunch tomorrow. We have some meat.\'94 \'93And whisky before. Good, hombre, good.\'94 \'93Salud, Pep\'e9, and thank you.\'94 \'93Salud, Enrique. It is nothing. Salud.\'94 It was a strange and very deadly voice and I never got used to hearing it, but as I walked up the stairs now, I felt much better. All we old clients of Chicote\'92s had a sort of feeling about the place. I knew that was why Luis Delgado had been such a fool as to go back there. He could have done his business some place else. But if he was in Madrid he had to go there. He had been a good client as the waiter had said and we had been friends. Certainly any small acts of kindness you can do in life are worth doing. So I was glad I had called my friend Pep\'e9 at Seguridad headquarters because Luis Delgado was an old client of Chicote\'92s and I did not wish him to be disillusioned or bitter about the waiters there before he died. The Butterfly and the Tank ON THIS EVENING I WAS WALKING HOME from the censorship office to the Florida Hotel and it was raining. So about halfway home I got sick of the rain and stopped into Chicote\'92s for a quick one. It was the second winter of shelling in the siege of Madrid and everything was short including tobacco and people\'92s tempers and you were a little hungry all the time and would become suddenly and unreasonably irritated at things you could do nothing about such as the weather. I should have gone on home. It was only five blocks more, but when I saw Chicote\'92s doorway I thought I would get a quick one and then do those six blocks up the Gran Via through the mud and rubble of the streets broken by the bombardment. The place was crowded. You couldn\'92t get near the bar and all the tables were full. It was full of smoke, singing, men in uniform, and the smell of wet leather coats, and they were handing drinks over a crowd that was three deep at the bar. A waiter I knew found a chair from another table and I sat down with a thin, white-faced, Adam\'92s-appled German I knew who was working at the censorship and two other people I did not know. The table was in the middle of the room a little on your right as you go in. You couldn\'92t hear yourself talk for the singing and I ordered a gin and Angostura and put it down against the rain. The place was really packed and everybody was very jolly; maybe getting just a little bit too jolly from the newly made Catalan liquor most of them were drinking. A couple of people I did not know slapped me on the back and when the girl at our table said something to me, I couldn\'92t hear it and said, \'93Sure.\'94 She was pretty terrible looking now I had stopped looking around and was looking at our table; really pretty terrible. But it turned out, when the waiter came, that what she had asked me was to have a drink. The fellow with her was not very forceful looking but she was forceful enough for both of them. She had one of those strong, semi-classical faces and was built like a lion tamer; and the boy with her looked as though he ought to be wearing an old school tie. He wasn\'92t though. He was wearing a leather coat just like all the rest of us. Only it wasn\'92t wet because they had been there since before the rain started. She had on a leather coat too and it was becoming to the sort of face she had. By this time I was wishing I had not stopped into Chicote\'92s but had gone straight on home where you could change your clothes and be dry and have a drink in comfort on the bed with your feet up, and I was tired of looking at both of these young people. Life is very short and ugly women are very long and sitting there at the table I decided that even though I was a writer and supposed to have an insatiable curiosity about all sorts of people, I did not really care to know whether these two were married, or what they saw in each other, or what their politics were, or whether he had a little money, or she had a little money, or anything about them. I decided they must be in the radio. Any time you saw really strange looking civilians in Madrid they were always in the radio. So to say something I raised my voice above the noise and asked, \'93You in the radio?\'94 \'93We are,\'94 the girl said. So that was that. They were in the radio. \'93How are you comrade?\'94 I said to the German. \'93Fine. And you?\'94 \'93Wet,\'94 I said, and he laughed with his head on one side. \'93You haven\'92t got a cigarette?\'94 he asked. I handed him my next to the last pack of cigarettes and he took two. The forceful girl took two and the young man with the old school tie face took one. \'93Take another,\'94 I shouted. \'93No thanks,\'94 he answered and the German took it instead. \'93Do you mind?\'94 he smiled. \'93Of course not,\'94 I said. I really minded and he knew it. But he wanted the cigarettes so badly that it did not matter. The singing had died down momentarily, or there was a break in it as there is sometimes in a storm, and we could all hear what we said. \'93You been here long?\'94 the forceful girl asked me. She pronounced it bean as in bean soup. \'93Off and on,\'94 I said. \'93We must have a serious talk,\'94 the German said. \'93I want to have a talk with you. When can we have it?\'94 \'93I\'92ll call you up,\'94 I said. This German was a very strange German indeed and none of the good Germans liked him. He lived under the delusion that he could play the piano, but if you kept him away from pianos he was all right unless he was exposed to liquor, or the opportunity to gossip, and nobody had even been able to keep him away from those two things yet. Gossip was the best thing he did and he always knew something new and highly discreditable about anyone you could mention in Madrid, Valencia, Barcelona, and other political centers. Just then the singing really started in again, and you cannot gossip very well shouting, so it looked like a dull afternoon at Chicote\'92s and I decided to leave as soon as I should have bought a round myself. Just then it started. A civilian in a brown suit, a white shirt, black tie, his hair brushed straight back from a rather high forehead, who had been clowning around from table to table, squirted one of the waiters with a flit gun. Everybody laughed except the waiter who was carrying a tray full of drinks at the time. He was indignant. \'93No hay derecho,\'94 the waiter said. This means, \'93You have no right to do that,\'94 and is the simplest and the strongest protest in Spain. The flit gun man, delighted with his success, and not seeming to give any importance to the fact that it was well into the second year of the war, that he was in a city under siege where everyone was under a strain, and that he was one of only four men in civilian clothes in the place, now squirted another waiter. I looked around for a place to duck to. This waiter, also, was indignant and the flit gun man squirted him twice more, lightheartedly. Some people still thought it was funny, including the forceful girl. But the waiter stood, shaking his head. His lips were trembling. He was an old man and he had worked in Chicote\'92s for ten years that I knew of. \'93No hay derecho, \'94 he said with dignity. People had laughed, however, and the flit gun man, not noticing how the singing had fallen off, squirted his flit gun at the back of a waiter\'92s neck. The waiter turned, holding his tray. \'93No hay derecho,\'94 he said. This time it was no protest. It was an indictment and I saw three men in uniform start from a table for the flit gun man and the next thing all four of them were going out the revolving door in a rush and you heard a smack when someone hit the flit gun man on the mouth. Somebody else picked up the flit gun and threw it out the door after him. The three men came back in looking serious, tough and very righteous. Then the door revolved and in came the flit gun man. His hair was down in his eyes, there was blood on his face, his necktie was pulled to one side and his shirt was torn open. He had the flit gun again and as he pushed, wild- eyed and white-faced, into the room he made one general, unaimed, challenging squirt with it, holding it toward the whole company. I saw one of the three men start for him and I saw this man\'92s face. There were more men with him now and they forced the flit gun man back between two tables on the left of the room as you go in, the flit gun man struggling wildly now, and when the shot went off I grabbed the forceful girl by the arm and dove for the kitchen door. The kitchen door was shut and when I put my shoulder against it it did not give. \'93Get down here behind the angle of the bar,\'94 I said. She knelt there. \'93Flat,\'94 I said and pushed her down. She was furious. Every man in the room except the German, who lay behind a table, and the public-school-looking boy who stood in a corner drawn up against the wall, had a gun up. On a bench along the wall three over-blonde girls, their hair dark at the roots, were standing on tiptoe to see and screaming steadily. \'93I\'92m not afraid,\'94 the forceful one said. \'93This is ridiculous.\'94 \'93You don\'92t want to get shot in a caf\'e9 brawl,\'94 I said. \'93If that flit king has any friends here this can be very bad.\'94 But he had no friends, evidently, because people began putting their pistols away and somebody lifted down the blonde screamers and everyone who had started over there when the shot came drew back away from the flit man who lay, quietly, on his back on the floor. \'93No one is to leave until the police come,\'94 someone shouted from the door. Two policemen with rifles, who had come in off the street patrol, were standing by the door and at this announcement I saw six men form up just like the line-up of a football team coming out of a huddle and head out through the door. Three of them were the men who had first thrown the flit king out. One of them was the man who shot him. They went right through the policemen with the rifles like good interference taking out an end and a tackle. And as they went out one of the policemen got his rifle across the door and shouted, \'93No one can leave. Absolutely no one.\'94 \'93Why did those men go? Why hold us if anyone\'92s gone?\'94 \'93They were mechanics who had to return to their air field,\'94 someone said. \'93But if anyone\'92s gone it\'92s silly to old the others.\'94 \'93Everyone must wait for the Seguridad. Things must be done legally and in order.\'94 \'93But don\'92t you see that if any person has gone it is silly to hold the others?\'94 \'93No one can leave. Everyone must wait.\'94 \'93It\'92s comic,\'94 I said to the forceful girl. \'93No it\'92s not. It\'92s simply horrible.\'94 We were standing up now and she was staring indignantly at where the flit king was lying. His arms were spread wide and he had one leg drawn up. \'93I\'92m going over to help that poor wounded man. Why has no one helped him or done anything for him?\'94 \'93I\'92d leave him alone,\'94 I said. \'93You want to keep out of this.\'94 \'93But it\'92s simply inhuman. I\'92ve nurse\'92s training and I\'92m going to give him first aid.\'94 \'93I wouldn\'92t,\'94 I said. \'93Don\'92t go near him.\'94 \'93Why not?\'94 She was very upset and almost hysterical. \'93Because he\'92s dead,\'94 I said. When the police came they held everybody there for three hours. They commenced by smelling of all the pistols. In this manner they would detect one which had been fired recently. After about forty pistols they seemed to get bored with this and anyway all you could smell was wet leather coats. Then they sat at a table placed directly behind the late flit king, who lay on the floor looking like a grey wax caricature of himself, with grey wax hands and a grey wax face, and examined people\'92s papers. With his shirt ripped open you could see the flit king had no undershirt and the soles of his shoes were worn through. He looked very small and pitiful lying there on the floor. You had to step over him to get to the table where two plain clothes policemen sat and examined everyone\'92s identification papers. The husband lost and found his papers several times with nervousness. He had a safe conduct pass somewhere but he had mislaid it in a pocket and he kept on searching and perspiring until he found it. Then he would put it in a different pocket and have to go searching again. He perspired heavily while doing this and it made his hair very curly and his face red. He now looked as though he should have not only an old school tie but one of those little caps boys in the lower forms wear. You have heard how events age people. Well, this shooting had made him look about ten years younger. While we were waiting around I told the forceful girl I thought the whole thing was a pretty good story and that I would write it sometime. The way the six had lined up in single file and rushed that door was very impressive. She was shocked and said that I could not write it because it would be prejudicial to the cause of the Spanish Republic. I said that I had been in Spain for a long time and that they used to have a phenomenal number of shootings in the old days around Valencia under the monarchy, and that for hundreds of years before the Republic people had been cutting each other with large knives called navajas in Andalucia, and that if I saw a comic shooting in Chicote\'92s during the war I could write about it just as though it had been in New York, Chicago, Key West or Marseilles. It did not have anything to do with politics. She said I shouldn\'92t. Probably a lot of other people will say I shouldn\'92t too. The German seemed to think it was a pretty good story, however, and I gave him the last of the Camels. Well, anyway, finally, after about three hours the police said we could go. They were sort of worried about me at the Florida because in those days, with the shelling, if you started for home on foot and didn\'92t get there after the bars were closed at seven-thirty, people worried. I was glad to get home and I told the story while we were cooking supper on an electric stove and it had quite a success. Well, it stopped raining during the night, and the next morning it was a fine, bright, cold early winter day and at twelve forty-five I pushed open the revolving doors at Chicote\'92s to try a little gin and tonic before lunch. There were very few people there at that hour and two waiters and the manager came over to the table. They were all smiling. \'93Did they catch the murderer?\'94 I asked. \'93Don\'92t make jokes so early in the day,\'94 the manager said. \'93Did you see him shot?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I told him. \'93Me too,\'94 he said. \'93I was just here when it happened.\'94 He pointed to a comer table. \'93He placed the pistol right against the man\'92s chest when he fired.\'94 \'93How late did they hold people?\'94 \'93Oh, until past two this morning.\'94 \'93They only came for the fiambre,\'94 using the Spanish slang word for corpse, the same used on menus for cold meat, \'93at eleven o\'92clock this morning.\'94 \'93But you don\'92t know about it yet,\'94 the manager said. \'93No. He doesn\'92t know,\'94 a waiter said. \'93It is a very rare thing,\'94 another waiter said. \'93Muy raro.\'94 \'93And sad too,\'94 the manager said. He shook his head. \'93Yes. Sad and curious,\'94 the waiter said. \'93Very sad.\'94 \'93Tell me.\'94 \'93It is a very rare thing,\'94 the manager said. \'93Tell me. Come on, tell me.\'94 The manager leaned over the table in great confidence. \'93In the flit gun, you know,\'94 he said. \'93He had eau de cologne. Poor fellow.\'94 \'93It was not a joke in such bad taste, you see?\'94 the waiter said. \'93It was really just gaiety. No one should have taken offense,\'94 the manager said. \'93Poor fellow.\'94 \'93I see,\'94 I said. \'93He just wanted everyone to have a good time.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said the manager. \'93It was really just an unfortunate misunderstanding.\'94 \'93And what about the flit gun?\'94 \'93The police took it. They have sent it around to his family.\'94 \'93I imagine they will be glad to have it,\'94 I said. \'93Yes,\'94 said the manager. \'93Certainly. A flit gun is always useful.\'94 \'93Who was he?\'94 \'93A cabinet maker.\'94 \'93Married?\'94 \'93Yes, the wife was here with the police this morning.\'94 \'93What did she say?\'94 \'93She dropped down by him and said, \'91Pedro, what have they done to thee, Pedro? Who has done this to thee? Oh, Pedro.\'92 \'94 \'93Then the police had to take her away because she could not control herself,\'94 the waiter said. \'93It seems he was feeble of the chest,\'94 the manager said. \'93He fought in the first days of the movement. They said he fought in the Sierra but he was too weak in the chest to continue.\'94 \'93And yesterday afternoon he just went out on the town to cheer things up,\'94 I suggested. \'93No,\'94 said the manager. \'93You see it is very rare. Everything is muy raro. This I learn from the police who are very efficient if given time. They have interrogated comrades from the shop where he worked. This they located from the card of his syndicate which was in his pocket. Yesterday he bought the flit gun and agua de colonia to use for a joke at a wedding. He had announced this intention. He bought them across the street. There was a label on the cologne bottle with the address. The bottle was in the washroom. It was there he filled the flit gun. After buying them he must have come in here when the rain started.\'94 \'93I remember when he came in,\'94 a waiter said. \'93In the gaiety, with the singing, he became gay too.\'94 \'93He was gay all right,\'94 I said. \'93He was practically floating around.\'94 The manager kept on with the relentless Spanish logic. \'93That is the gaiety of drinking with a weakness of the chest,\'94 he said. \'93I don\'92t like this story very well,\'94 I said. \'93Listen,\'94 said the manager. \'93How rare it is. His gaiety comes in contact with the seriousness of the war like a butterfly\'97\'94 \'93Oh, very like a butterfly,\'94 I said. \'93Too much like a butterfly.\'94 \'93I am not joking,\'94 said the manager. \'93You see it? Like a butterfly and a tank.\'94 This pleased him enormously. He was getting into the real Spanish metaphysics. \'93Have a drink on the house,\'94 he said. \'93You must write a story about this.\'94 I remembered the flit gun man with his grey wax hands and his grey wax face, his arms spread wide and his legs drawn up and he did look a little like a butterfly; not too much, you know. But he did not look very human either. He reminded me more of a dead sparrow. \'93I\'92ll take gin and Schweppes quinine tonic water,\'94 I said. \'93You must write a story about it,\'94 the manager said. \'93Here. Here\'92s luck.\'94 \'93Luck,\'94 I said. \'93Look, an English girl last night told me I shouldn\'92t write about it. That it would be very bad for the cause.\'94 \'93What nonsense,\'94 the manager said. \'93It is very interesting and important, the misunderstood gaiety coming in contact with the deadly seriousness that is here always. To me it is the rarest and most interesting thing which I have seen for some time. You must write it.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93Sure. Has he any children?\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I asked the police. But you must write it and you must call it \'91The Butterfly and the Tank.\'92 \'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93Sure. But I don\'92t like the title much.\'94 \'93The title is very elegant,\'94 the manager said. \'93It is pure literature.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93Sure. That\'92s what we\'92ll call it. \'91The Butterfly and the Tank.\'92 \'94 And I sat there on that bright cheerful morning, the place smelling clean and newly aired and swept, with the manager who was an old friend and who was now very pleased with the literature we were making together and I took a sip of the gin and tonic water and looked out the sandbagged window and thought of the wife kneeling there and saying, \'93Pedro. Pedro, who has done this to thee, Pedro?\'94 And I thought that the police would never be able to tell her that even if they had the name of the man who pulled the trigger. Night Before Battle AT THIS TIME WE WERE WORKING IN A shell-smashed house that overlooked the Casa del Campo in Madrid. Below us a battle was being fought. You could see it spread out below you and over the hills, could smell it, could taste the dust of it, and the noise of it was one great slithering sheet of rifle and automatic rifle fire rising and dropping, and in it came the crack of the guns and the bubbly rumbling of the outgoing shells fired from the batteries behind us, the thud of their bursts, and then the rolling yellow clouds of dust. But it was just too far to film well. We had tried working closer but they kept sniping at the camera and you could not work. The big camera was the most expensive thing we had and if it was smashed we were through. We were making the film on almost nothing and all the money was in the cans of film and the cameras. We could not afford to waste film and you had to be awfully careful of the cameras. The day before we had been sniped out of a good place to film from and I had to crawl back holding the small camera to my belly, trying to keep my head lower than my shoulders, hitching along on my elbows, the bullets whocking into the brick wall over my back and twice spurting dirt over me. Our heaviest attacks were made in the afternoon, God knows why, as the fascists then had the sun at their backs, and it shone on the camera lenses and made them blink like a helio and the Moors would open up on the flash. They knew all about helios and officers\'92 glasses from the Riff and if you wanted to be properly sniped, all you had to do was use a pair of glasses without shading them adequately. They could shoot too, and they had kept my mouth dry all day. In the afternoon we moved up into the house. It was a fine place to work and we made a son of a blind for the camera on a balcony with the broken latticed curtains; but, as I said, it was too far. It was not too far to get the pine studded hillside, the lake and the outline of the stone farm buildings that disappeared in the sudden smashes of stone dust from the hits by high explosive shells, nor was it too far to get the clouds of smoke and dirt that thundered up on the hill crest as the bombers droned over. But at eight hundred to a thousand yards the tanks looked like small mud-colored beetles bustling in the trees and spitting tiny flashes and the men behind them were toy men who lay flat, then crouched and ran, and then dropped to run again, or to stay where they lay, spotting the hillside as the tanks moved on. Still we hoped to get the shape of the battle. We had many close shots and would get others with luck and if we could get the sudden fountainings of earth, the puffs of shrapnel, the rolling louds of smoke and dust lit by the yellow flash and white blossoming of grenades that is the very shape of battle we would have something that we needed. So when the light failed we carried the big camera down the stairs, took off the tripod, made three loads, and then, one at a time, sprinted across the fire-swept corner of the Paseo Rosales into the lee of the stone wall of the stables of the old Montana Barracks. We knew we had a good place to work and we felt cheerful. But we were kidding ourselves plenty that it was not too far. \'93Come on, let\'92s go to Chicote\'92s,\'94 I said when we had come up the hill to the Hotel Florida. But they had to repair a camera, to change film and seal up what we had made so I went alone. You were never alone in Spain and it felt good for a change. As I started to walk down the Gran Via to Chicote\'92s in the April twilight I felt happy, cheerful and excited. We had worked hard, and I thought well. But walking down the street alone, all my elation died. Now that I was alone and there was no excitement, I knew we had been too far away and any fool could see the offensive was a failure. I had known it all day but you are often deceived by hope and optimism. But remembering how it looked now, I knew this was just another blood bath like the Somme. The people\'92s army was on the offensive finally. But it was attacking in a way that could do only one thing: destroy itself. And as I put together now what I had seen all day and what I had heard, I felt plenty bad. I knew in the smoke and din of Chicote\'92s that the offensive was a failure and I knew it even stronger when I took my first drink at the crowded bar. When things are all right and it is you that is feeling low a drink can make you feel better. But when things are really bad and you are all right, a drink just makes it clearer. Now, in Chicote\'92s it was so crowded that you had to make room with your elbows to get your drink to your mouth. I had one good long swallow and then someone jostled me so that I spilled pan of the glass of whisky and soda. I looked around angrily and the man who had jostled me laughed. \'93Hello fish face,\'94 he said. \'93Hello you goat.\'94 \'93Let\'92s get a table,\'94 he said. \'93You certainly looked sore when I bumped you.\'94 \'93Where did you come from?\'94 I asked. His leather coat was dirty and greasy, his eyes were hollow and he needed a shave. He had the big Colt automatic that had belonged to three other men that I had known of, and that we were always trying to get shells for, strapped to his leg. He was very tall and his face was smoke-darkened and grease-smudged. He had a leather helment with a heavy leather padded ridge longitudinally over the top and a heavily padded leather rim. \'93Where\'92d you come from?\'94 \'93Casa del Campo,\'94 he said, pronouncing it in a sing-song mocking way we had heard a page boy use in calling in the lobby of a hotel in New Orleans one time and still kept as a private joke. \'93There\'92s a table,\'94 I said as two soldiers and two girls got up to go. \'93Let\'92s get it.\'94 We sat at this table in the middle of the room and I watched him raise his glass. His hands were greasy and the forks of both thumbs black as graphite from the back spit of the machine gun. The hand holding the drink was shaking. \'93Look at them.\'94 He put out the other hand. It was shaking too. \'93Both the same,\'94 he said in that same comic lilt. Then, seriously, \'93You been down there?\'94 \'93We\'92re making a picture of it.\'94 \'93Photograph well?\'94 \'93Not too.\'94 \'93See us?\'94 \'93Where?\'94 \'93Attack on the farm. Three twenty-five this afternoon.\'94 \'93Oh, yes.\'94 \'93Like it?\'94 \'93Nope.\'94 \'93Me either,\'94 he said. \'93Listen the whole thing is just as crazy as a bedbug. Why do they want to make a frontal attack against positions like those? Who in hell thought it up?\'94 \'93An S.O.B. named Largo Caballero,\'94 said a short man with thick glasses who was sitting at the table when we came over to it. \'93The first time they let him look through a pair of field glasses he became a general. This is his masterpiece.\'94 We both looked at the man who spoke. Al Wagner, the tank man, looked at me and raised what had been his eyebrows before they were burnt off. The little man smiled at us. \'93If anyone around here speaks English you\'92re liable to get shot, comrade,\'94 Al said to him. \'93No,\'94 said the little short man. \'93Largo Caballero is liable to be shot. He ought to be shot.\'94 \'93Listen, comrade,\'94 said Al. \'93Just speak a little quieter, will you? Somebody might overhear you and think we were with you.\'94 \'93I know what I\'92m talking about,\'94 said the short man with the very thick glasses. I looked at him carefully. He gave you a certain feeling that he did. \'93Just the same it isn\'92t always a good thing to say what you know,\'94 I said. \'93Have a drink?\'94 \'93Certainly,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s all right to talk to you. I know you. You\'92re all right.\'94 \'93I\'92m not that all right,\'94 I said. \'93And this is a public bar.\'94 \'93A public bar is the only private place there is. Nobody can hear what we say here. What is your unit, comrade?\'94 \'93I\'92ve got some tanks about eight minutes from here on foot,\'94 Al told him. \'93We are through for the day and I have the early part of this evening off.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you ever get washed?\'94 I said. \'93I plan to,\'94 said Al. \'93In your room. When we leave here. Have you got any mechanic\'92s soap?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93That\'92s all right,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92ve got a little here with me in my pocket that I\'92ve been saving.\'94 The little man with the thick-lensed glasses was looking at Al intently. \'93Are you a party member, comrade?\'94 he asked. \'93Sure,\'94 said Al. \'93I know Comrade Henry here is not,\'94 the little man said. \'93I wouldn\'92t trust him then,\'94 Al said. \'93I never do.\'94 \'93You bastid,\'94 I said. \'93Want to go?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Al said. \'93I need another drink very badly.\'94 \'93I know all about Comrade Henry,\'94 the little man said. \'93Now let me tell you something more about Largo Caballero.\'94 \'93Do we have to hear it?\'94 Al asked. \'93Remember I\'92m in the people\'92s army. You don\'92t think it will discourage me, do you?\'94 \'93You know his head is swelled so badly now he\'92s getting sort of mad. He is Prime Minister and War Minister and nobody can even talk to him any more. You know he\'92s just a good honest trade union leader somewhere between the late Sam Gompers and John L. Lewis but this man Araquistain who invented him?\'94 \'93Take it easy,\'94 said Al. \'93I don\'92t follow.\'94 \'93Oh, Araquistain invented him! Araquistain who is Ambassador in Paris now. He made him up you know. He called him the Spanish Lenin and then the poor man tried to live up to it and somebody let him look through a pair of field glasses and he thought he was Clausewitz.\'94 \'93You said that before,\'94 Al told him coldly. \'93What do you base it on?\'94 \'93Why three days ago in the Cabinet meeting he was talking about military affairs. They were talking about this business we\'92ve got now and Jesus Hernandez, just ribbing him, you know, asked him what was the difference between tactics and strategy. Do you know what the old boy said?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Al said. I could see this new comrade was getting a little on his nerves. \'93He said, \'91In tactics you attack the enemy from in front. In strategy you take him from the sides.\'92 Now isn\'92t that something?\'94 \'93You better run along, comrade,\'94 Al said. \'93You\'92re getting so awfully discouraged.\'94 \'93But we\'92ll get rid of Largo Caballero,\'94 the short comrade said. \'93We\'92ll get rid of him right after his offensive. This last piece of stupidity will be the end of him.\'94 \'93O.K., comrade,\'94 Al told him. \'93But I\'92ve got to attack in the morning.\'94 \'93Oh, you are going to attack again?\'94 \'93Listen, comrade. You can tell me any sort of crap you want because it\'92s interesting and I\'92m grown up enough to sort things out. But don\'92t ask me any questions, see? Because you\'92ll be in trouble.\'94 \'93I just meant it personally. Not as information.\'94 \'93We don\'92t know each other well enough to ask personal questions, comrade,\'94 Al said. \'93Why don\'92t you just go to another table and let Comrade Henry and me talk. I want to ask him some things.\'94 \'93Salud, comrade,\'94 the little man said, standing up. \'93We\'92ll meet another time.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 said Al. \'93Another time.\'94 We watched him go over to another table. He excused himself, some soldiers made room for him, and as we watched we could see him starting to talk. They all looked interested. \'93What do you make of that little guy?\'94 Al asked. \'93I don\'92t know.\'94 \'93Me either,\'94 Al said. \'93He certainly had this offensive sized up.\'94 He took a drink and showed his hand. \'93See? It\'92s all right now. I\'92m not any rummy either. I never take a drink before an attack.\'94 \'93How was it today?\'94 \'93You saw it. How did it look?\'94 \'93Terrible.\'94 \'93That\'92s it. That\'92s the word for it all right. It was terrible. I guess he\'92s using strategy and tactics both now because we are attacking from straight in front and from both sides. How\'92s the rest of it going?\'94 \'93Duran took the new race track. The hip\'f3dromo. We\'92ve narrowed down on the corridor that runs up into University City. Up above we crossed the Coru\'f1a road. And we\'92re stopped at the Cerro de Aguilar since yesterday morning. We were up that way this morning. Duran lost over half his brigade, I heard. How is it with you?\'94 \'93Tomorrow we\'92re going to try those farm houses and the church again. The church on the hill, the one they call the hermit, is the objective. The whole hillside is cut by those gullies and it\'92s all enfiladed at least three ways by machine-gun posts. They\'92re dug deep all through there and it\'92s well done. We haven\'92t got enough artillery to give any kind of real covering fire to keep them down and we haven\'92t heavy artillery to blow them out. They\'92ve got anti-tanks in those three houses and an antitank battery by the church. It\'92s going to be murder.\'94 \'93When\'92s it for?\'94 \'93Don\'92t ask me. I\'92ve got no right to tell you that.\'94 \'93If we have to film it, I meant,\'94 I said. \'93The money from the film all goes for ambulances. We\'92ve got the Twelfth Brigade in the counter-attack at the Argada Bridge. And we\'92ve got the Twelfth again in that attack last week by Pingarron. We got some good tank shots there.\'94 \'93The tanks were no good there,\'94 Al said. \'93I know,\'94 I said, \'93but they photographed very well. What about tomorrow?\'94 \'93Just get out early and wait,\'94 he said. \'93Not too early.\'94 \'93How you feel now?\'94 \'93I\'92m awfully tired,\'94 he said. \'93And I\'92ve got a bad headache. But I feel a lot better. Let\'92s have another one and then go up to your place and get a bath.\'94 \'93Maybe we ought to eat first.\'94 \'93I\'92m too dirty to eat. You can hold a place and I\'92ll go get a bath and join you at the Gran Via.\'94 \'93I\'92ll go up with you.\'94 \'93No. It\'92s better to hold a place and I\'92ll join you.\'94 He leaned his head forward on the table. \'93Boy I got a headache. It\'92s the noise in those buckets. I never hear it any more but it does something to your ears just the same.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you go to bed?\'94 \'93No. I\'92d rather stay up with you for a while and then sleep when I got back down there. I don\'92t want to wake up twice.\'94 \'93You haven\'92t got the horrors, have you?\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m fine. Listen, Hank. I don\'92t want to talk a lot of crap but I think I\'92m going to get killed tomorrow.\'94 I touched the table three times with my fingertips. \'93Everybody feels like that. I\'92ve felt like that plenty of times.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s not natural with me. But where we\'92ve got to go tomorrow doesn\'92t make sense. I don\'92t even know that I can get them up there. You can\'92t make them move if they won\'92t go. You can shoot them afterwards. But at the time if they won\'92t go they won\'92t go. If you shoot them they still won\'92t go.\'94 \'93Maybe it will be all right.\'94 \'93No. We\'92ve got good infantry tomorrow. They\'92ll go anyway. Not like those yellow bastids we had the first day.\'94 \'93Maybe it will be all right.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93It won\'92t be all right. But it will be just exactly as good as I can make it. I can make them start all right and I can take them up to where they will have to quit one at a time. Maybe they can make it. I\'92ve got three I can rely on. If only one of the good ones doesn\'92t get knocked out at the start.\'94 \'93Who are your good ones?\'94 \'93I\'92ve got a big Greek from Chicago that will go anywhere. He\'92s just as good as they come. I\'92ve got a Frenchman from Marseille that\'92s got his left shoulder in a cast with two wounds still draining that asked to come out of the hospital in the Palace Hotel for this show and has to be strapped in and I don\'92t know how he can do it. Just technically I mean. He\'92d break your bloody heart. He used to be a taxi driver.\'94 He stopped. \'93I\'92m talking too much. Stop me if I talk too much.\'94 \'93Who\'92s the third one?\'94 I asked. \'93The third one? Did I say I had a third one?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93Oh, yes,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s me.\'94 \'93What about the others?\'94 \'93They\'92re mechanics, but they couldn\'92t learn to soldier. They can\'92t size up what\'92s happening. And they\'92re all afraid to die. I tried to get them over it,\'94 he said. \'93But it comes back on them every attack. They look like tank men when you see them by the tanks with the helmets on. They look like tank men when they get in. But when they shut the traps down there\'92s really nothing inside. They aren\'92t tank men. And so far we haven\'92t had time to make new ones.\'94 \'93Do you want to take the bath?\'94 \'93Let\'92s sit here a little while longer,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s nice here.\'94 \'93It\'92s funny all right, with a war right down the end of the street so you can walk to it, and then leave it and come here.\'94 \'93And then walk back to it,\'94 Al said. \'93What about a girl? There\'92s two American girls at the Florida. Newspaper correspondents. Maybe you could make one.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to have to talk to them. I\'92m too tired.\'94 \'93There\'92s the two Moor girls from Ceuta at that corner table.\'94 He looked over at them. They were both dark and bushy-headed. One was large and one was small and they certainly both looked strong and active. \'93No,\'94 said Al. \'93I\'92m going to see plenty Moors tomorrow without having to fool with them tonight.\'94 \'93There\'92s plenty of girls,\'94 I said. \'93Manolita\'92s at the Florida. That Seguridad bird she lives with has gone to Valencia and she\'92s being true to him with everybody.\'94 \'93Listen, Hank, what are you trying to promote me?\'94 \'93I just wanted to cheer you up.\'94 \'93Grow up,\'94 he said. \'93What\'92s one more?\'94 \'93One more.\'94 \'93I don\'92t mind dying a bit,\'94 he said. \'93Dying is just a lot of crap. Only it\'92s wasteful. The attack is wrong and it\'92s wasteful. I can handle tanks good now. If I had time I could make good tankists too. And if we had tanks that were a little bit faster the anti-tanks wouldn\'92t bother them the way it does when you haven\'92t got the mobility. Listen, Hank, they aren\'92t what we thought they were though. Do you remember when everybody thought if we only had tanks?\'94 \'93They were good at Gaudalajara.\'94 \'93Sure. But those were the old boys. They were soldiers. And it was against Italians.\'94 \'93But what\'92s happened?\'94 \'93A lot of things. The mercenaries signed up for six months. Most of them were Frenchmen. They soldiered good for five but now all they want to do is live through the last month and go home. They aren\'92t worth a damn now. The Russians that came out as demonstrators when the government bought the tanks were perfect. But they\'92re pulling them back now for China they say. The new Spaniards are some of them good and some not. It takes six months to make a good tank man, I mean to know anything. And to be able to size up and work intelligently you have to have a talent. We\'92ve been having to make them in six weeks and there aren\'92t so many with a talent.\'94 \'93They make fine flyers.\'94 \'93They\'92ll make fine tank guys too. But you have to get the ones with a vocation for it. It\'92s sort of like being a priest. You have to be cut out for it. Especially now they\'92ve got so much anti-tank.\'94 They had pulled down the shutters in Chicote\'92s and now they were locking the door. No one would be allowed in now. But you had a half an hour more before they closed. \'93I like it here,\'94 said Al. \'93It isn\'92t so noisy now. Remember that time I met you in New Orleans when I was on a ship and we went in to have a drink in the Monteleone bar and that kid that looked just like Saint Sebastian was paging people with that funny voice like he was singing and I gave him a quarter to page Mr. B. F. Slob?\'94 \'93That\'92s the same way you said \'91Casa del Campo.\'92 \'94 \'93Yeah,\'94 he said. \'93I laugh every time I think of that.\'94 Then he went on, \'93You see, now, they\'92re not frightened of tanks any more. Nobody is. We aren\'92t either. But they\'92re still useful. Really useful. Only with the anti-tank now they\'92re so damn vulnerable. Maybe I ought to be in something else. Not really. Because they\'92re still useful. But the way they are now you\'92ve got to have a vocation for them. You got to have a lot of political development to be a good tank man now.\'94 \'93You\'92re a good tank man.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to be something else tomorrow,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m talking awfully wet but you have a right to talk wet if it isn\'92t going to hurt anybody else. You know I like tanks too, only we don\'92t use them right because the infantry don\'92t know enough yet. They just want the old tank ahead to give them some cover while they go. That\'92s no good. Then they get to depending on the tanks and they won\'92t move without them. Sometimes they won\'92t even deploy.\'94 \'93I know.\'94 \'93But you see if you had tankists that knew their stuff they\'92d go out ahead and develop the machine-gun fire and then drop back behind the infantry and fire on the gun and knock it out and give the infantry covering fire when they attacked. And other tanks could rush the machine-gun posts as though they were cavalry. And they could straddle a trench and enfilade and put flaking fire down it. And they could bring up infantry when it was right to or cover their advance when that was best.\'94 \'93But instead?\'94 \'93Instead it\'92s like it will be tomorrow. We have so damned few guns that we\'92re just used as slightly mobile armored artillery units. And as soon as you are standing still and being light artillery, you\'92ve lost your mobility and that\'92s your safety and they start sniping at you with the anti-tanks. And if we\'92re not that we\'92re just sort of iron perambulators to push ahead of the infantry. And lately you don\'92t know whether the perambulator will push or whether the guys inside will push them. And you never know if there\'92s going to be anybody behind you when you get there.\'94 \'93How many are you now to a brigade?\'94 \'93Six to a battalion. Thirty to a brigade. That\'92s in principle.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you come along now and get the bath and we\'92ll go and eat?\'94 \'93All right. But don\'92t you start taking care of me or thinking I\'92m worried or anything because I\'92m not. I\'92m just tired and I wanted to talk. And don\'92t give me any pep talk either because we\'92ve got a political commissar and I know what I\'92m fighting for and I\'92m not worried. But I\'92d like things to be efficient and used as intelligently as possible.\'94 \'93What made you think I was going to give you any pep talk?\'94 \'93You started to look like it.\'94 \'93All I tried to do was see if you wanted a girl and not to talk too wet about getting killed.\'94 \'93Well, I don\'92t want any girl tonight and I\'92ll talk just as wet as I please unless it does damage to others. Does it damage you?\'94 \'93Come on and get the bath,\'94 I said. \'93You can talk just as bloody wet as you want.\'94 \'93Who do you suppose that little guy was that talked as though he knew so much?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 I said. \'93But I\'92m going to find out.\'94 \'93He made me gloomy,\'94 said Al. \'93Come on. Let\'92s go.\'94 The old waiter with the bald head unlocked the outside door of Chicote\'92s and let us out into the street. \'93How is the offensive, comrades?\'94 he said at the door. \'93It\'92s O.K., comrade,\'94 said Al. \'93It\'92s all right.\'94 \'93I am happy,\'94 said the waiter. \'93My boy is in the One Hundred and Forty-fifth Brigade. Have you seen them?\'94 \'93I am of the tanks,\'94 said Al. \'93This comrade makes a cinema. Have you seen the Hundred and Forty-fifth?\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93They are up the Extremadura road,\'94 the old waiter said. \'93My boy is political commissar of the machine-gun company of his battalion. He is my youngest boy. He is twenty.\'94 \'93What party are you comrade?\'94 Al asked him. \'93I am of no party,\'94 the waiter said. \'93But my boy is a Communist.\'94 \'93So am I,\'94 said Al. \'93The offensive, comrade, has not yet reached a decision. It is very difficult. The fascists hold very strong positions. You, in the rear-guard, must be as firm as we will be at the front. We may not take these positions now but we have proved we now have an army capable of going on the offensive and you will see what it will do.\'94 \'93And the Extremadura road?\'94 asked the old waiter, still holding on to the door. \'93Is it very dangerous there?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Al. \'93It\'92s fine up there. You don\'92t need to worry about him up there.\'94 \'93God bless you,\'94 said the waiter. \'93God guard you and keep you.\'94 Outside in the dark street, Al said, \'93Jees he\'92s kind of confused politically, isn\'92t he?\'94 \'93He is a good guy,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ve known him for a long time.\'94 \'93He seems like a good guy,\'94 Al said. \'93But he ought to get wise to himself politically.\'94 The room at the Florida was crowded. They were playing the gramophone and it was full of smoke and there was a crap game going on the floor. Comrades kept coming in to use the bathtub and the room smelt of smoke, soap, dirty uniforms, and steam from the bathroom. The Spanish girl called Manolita, very neat, demurely dressed, with a sort of false French chic, with much joviality, much dignity and closely set cold eyes, was sitting on the bed talking with an English newspaper man. Except for the gramophone it wasn\'92t very noisy. \'93It is your room, isn\'92t it?\'94 the English newspaper man said. \'93It\'92s in my name at the desk,\'94 I said. \'93I sleep in it sometimes.\'94 \'93But whose is the whisky?\'94 he asked. \'93Mine,\'94 said Manolita. \'93They drank that bottle so I got another.\'94 \'93You\'92re a good girl, daughter,\'94 I said. \'93That\'92s three I owe you.\'94 \'93Two,\'94 she said. \'93The other was a present.\'94 There was a huge cooked ham, rosy and white edged in a half-opened tin on the table beside my typewriter and a comrade would reach up, cut himself a slice of ham with his pocket knife, and go back to the crap game. I cut myself a slice of ham. \'93You\'92re next on the tub,\'94 I said to Al. He had been looking around the room. \'93It\'92s nice here,\'94 he said. \'93Where did the ham come from?\'94 \'93We bought it from the intendencia of one of the brigades,\'94 she said. \'93Isn\'92t it beautiful?\'94 \'93Who\'92s we?\'94 \'93He and I,\'94 she said, turning her head toward the English correspondent. \'93Don\'92t you think he\'92s cute?\'94 \'93Manolita has been most kind,\'94 said the Englishman. \'93I hope we\'92re not disturbing you.\'94 \'93Not at all,\'94 I said. \'93Later on I might want to use the bed but that won\'92t be until much later.\'94 \'93We can have a party in my room,\'94 Manolita said. \'93You aren\'92t cross are you, Henry?\'94 \'93Never,\'94 I said. \'93Who are the comrades shooting craps?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said Manolita. \'93They came in for baths and then they stayed to shoot craps. Everyone has been very nice. You know my bad news?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93It\'92s very bad. You knew my fianc\'e9 who was in the police and went to Barcelona?\'94 \'93Yes. Sure.\'94 Al went into the bathroom. \'93Well, he was shot in an accident and I haven\'92t any one I can depend on in police circles and he never got me the papers he had promised me and today I heard I was going to be arrested.\'94 \'93Why?\'94 \'93Because I have no papers and they say I hang around with you people and with people from the brigades all the time so I am probably a spy. If my fianc\'e9 had not gotten himself shot it would have been all right. Will you help me?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 I said. \'93Nothing will happen to you if you\'92re all right.\'94 \'93I think I\'92d better stay with you to be sure.\'94 \'93And if you\'92re not all right that would be fine for me, wouldn\'92t it?\'94 \'93Can\'92t I stay with you?\'94 \'93No. If you get in trouble call me up. I never heard you ask anybody any military questions. I think you\'92re all right.\'94 \'93I\'92m really all right,\'94 she said then, leaning over, away from the Englishman. \'93You think it\'92s all right to stay with him? Is he all right?\'94 \'93How do I know?\'94 I said. \'93I never saw him before.\'94 \'93You\'92re being cross,\'94 she said. \'93Let\'92s not think about it now but everyone be happy and go out to dinner.\'94 I went over to the crap game. \'93You want to go out to dinner?\'94 \'93No, comrade,\'94 said the man handling the dice without looking up. \'93You want to get in the game?\'94 \'93I want to eat.\'94 \'93We\'92ll be here when you get back,\'94 said another crap shooter. \'93Come on, roll, I\'92ve got you covered.\'94 \'93If you run into any money bring it up here to the game.\'94 There was one in the room I knew besides Manolita. He was from the Twelfth Brigade and he was playing the gramophone. He was a Hungarian, a sad Hungarian, not one of the cheerful kind. \'93Salud camarade,\'94 he said. \'93Thank you for your hospitality.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you shoot craps?\'94 I asked him. \'93I haven\'92t that sort of money,\'94 he said. \'93They are aviators with contracts. Mercenaries \'85 They make a thousand dollars a month. They were on the Teruel front and now they have come here.\'94 \'93How did they come up here?\'94 \'93One of them knows you. But he had to go out to his field. They came for him in a car and the game had already started.\'94 \'93I\'92m glad you came up,\'94 I said. \'93Come up any time and make yourself at home.\'94 \'93I came to play the new discs,\'94 he said. \'93It does not disturb you?\'94 \'93No. It\'92s fine. Have a drink.\'94 \'93A little ham,\'94 he said. One of the crap shooters reached up and cut a slice of ham. \'93You haven\'92t seen this guy Henry around that owns the place, have you?\'94 he asked me. \'93That\'92s me.\'94 \'93Oh,\'94 he said. \'93Sorry. Want to get in the game?\'94 \'93Later on,\'94 I said. \'93O.K.,\'94 he said. Then his mouth full of ham, \'93Listen you tar heel bastid. Make your dice hit the wall and bounce.\'94 \'93Won\'92t make no difference to you, comrade,\'94 said the man handling the dice. Al came out of the bathroom. He looked all clean except for some smudges around his eyes. \'93You can take those off with a towel,\'94 I said. \'93What?\'94 \'93Look at yourself once more in the mirror.\'94 \'93It\'92s too steamy.\'94 he said. \'93To hell with it, I feel clean.\'94 \'93Let\'92s eat,\'94 I said. \'93Come on, Manolita. You know each other?\'94 I watched her eyes run over Al. \'93How are you?\'94 Manolita said. \'93I say that is a sound idea,\'94 the Englishman said. \'93Do let\'92s eat. But where?\'94 \'93Is that a crap game?\'94 Al said. \'93Didn\'92t you see it when you came in?\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93All I saw was the ham.\'94 \'93It\'92s a crap game.\'94 \'93You go and eat,\'94 Al said. \'93I\'92m staying here.\'94 As we went out there were six of them on the floor and Al Wagner was reaching up to cut a slice of ham. \'93What do you do, comrade?\'94 I heard one of the flyers say to Al. \'93Tanks.\'94 \'93Tell me they aren\'92t any good any more,\'94 said the flyer. \'93Tell you a lot of things,\'94 Al said. \'93What you got there? Some dice?\'94 \'93Want to look at them?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Al. \'93I want to handle them.\'94 We went down the hall, Manolita, me and the tall Englishman, and found the boys had left already for the Gran Via restaurant. The Hungarian had stayed behind to replay the new discs. I was very hungry and the food at the Gran Via was lousy. The two who were making the film had already eaten and gone back to work on the bad camera. This restaurant was in the basement and you had to pass a guard and go through the kitchen and down a stairs to get to it. It was a racket. They had a millet and water soup, yellow rice with horse meat in it, and oranges for dessert. There had been another dish of chickpeas with sausage in it that everybody said was terrible but it had run out. The newspaper men all sat at one table and the other tables were filled with officers and girls from Chicote\'92s, people from the censorship, which was then in the telephone building across the street, and various unknown citizens. The restaurant was run by an anarchist syndicate and they sold you wine that was all stamped with the label of the royal cellars and the date it had been put in the bins. Most of it was so old that it was either corked or just plain faded out and gone to pieces. You can\'92t drink labels and I sent three bottles back as bad before we got a drinkable one. There was a row about this. The waiters didn\'92t know the different wines. They just brought you a bottle of wine and you took your chances. They were as different from the Chicote\'92s waiters as black from white. These waiters were all snotty, all over-tipped and they regularly had special dishes such as lobster or chicken that they sold extra for gigantic prices. But these had all been bought up before we got there so we just drew the soup, the rice and the oranges. The place always made me angry because the waiters were a crooked lot of profiteers and it was about as expensive to eat in, if you had one of the special dishes, as 21 or the Colony in New York. We were sitting at the table with a bottle of wine that just wasn\'92t bad, you know you could taste it starting to go, but it wouldn\'92t justify making a row about, when Al Wagner came in. He looked around the room, saw us and came over. \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 I said. \'93They broke me,\'94 he said. \'93It didn\'92t take very long.\'94 \'93Not with those guys,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s a big game. What have they got to eat?\'94 I called a waiter over. \'93It\'92s too late,\'94 he said. \'93We can\'92t serve anything now.\'94 \'93This comrade is in the tanks,\'94 I said. \'93He has fought all day and he will fight tomorrow and he hasn\'92t eaten.\'94 \'93That\'92s not my fault,\'94 the waiter said. \'93It\'92s too late. There isn\'92t anything more. Why doesn\'92t the comrade eat with his unit? The army has plenty of food.\'94 \'93I asked him to eat with me.\'94 \'93You should have said something about it. It\'92s too late now. We are not serving anything any more.\'94 \'93Get the head waiter.\'94 The headwaiter said the cook had gone home and there was no fire in the kitchen. He went away. They were angry because we had sent the bad wine back. \'93The hell with it,\'94 said Al. \'93Let\'92s go somewhere else.\'94 \'93There\'92s no place you can eat at this hour. They\'92ve got food. I\'92ll just have to go over and suck up to the headwaiter and give him some more money.\'94 I went over and did just that and the sullen waiter brought a plate of cold sliced meats, then half a spiny lobster with mayonnaise, and a salad of lettuce and lentils. The headwaiter sold this out of his private stock which he was holding out either to take home, or sell to late comers. \'93Cost you much?\'94 Al asked. \'93No,\'94 I lied. \'93I\'92ll bet it did,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92ll fix up with you when I get paid.\'94 \'93What do you get now?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know yet. It was ten pesetas a day but they\'92ve raised it now I\'92m an officer. But we haven\'92t got it yet and I haven\'92t asked.\'94 \'93Comrade,\'94 I called the waiter. He came over, still angry that the headwaiter had gone over his head and served Al. \'93Bring another bottle of wine, please.\'94 \'93What kind?\'94 \'93Any that is not too old so that the red is faded.\'94 \'93It\'92s all the same.\'94 I said the equivalent of like hell it is in Spanish, and the waiter brought over a bottle of Ch\'e2teau Mouton-Rothschild 1906 that was just as good as the last claret we had was rotten. \'93Boy that\'92s wine,\'94 Al said. \'93What did you tell him to get that?\'94 \'93Nothing. He just made a lucky draw out of the bin.\'94 \'93Most of that stuff from the palace stinks.\'94 \'93It\'92s too old. This is a hell of a climate on wine.\'94 \'93There\'92s that wise comrade,\'94 Al nodded across at another table. The little man with the thick glasses that had talked to us about Largo Caballero was talking with some people I knew were very big shots indeed. \'93I guess he\'92s a big shot,\'94 I said. \'93When they\'92re high enough up they don\'92t give a damn what they say. But I wish he would have waited until after tomorrow. It\'92s kind of spoiled tomorrow for me.\'94 I filled his glass. \'93What he said sounded pretty sensible,\'94 Al went on. \'93I\'92ve been thinking it over. But my duty is to do what I\'92m ordered to do.\'94 \'93Don\'92t worry about it and get some sleep.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to get in that game again if you\'92ll let me take a thousand pesetas,\'94 Al said. \'93I\'92ve got a lot more than that coming to me and I\'92ll give you an order on my pay.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want any order. You can pay me when you get it.\'94 \'93I don\'92t think I\'92m going to draw it,\'94 Al said. \'93I certainly sound wet, don\'92t I? And I know gambling\'92s bohemianism too. But in a game like that is the only time I don\'92t think about tomorrow.\'94 \'93Did you like that Manolita girl? She liked you.\'94 \'93She\'92s got eyes like a snake.\'94 \'93She\'92s not a bad girl. She\'92s friendly and she\'92s all right.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want any girl. I want to get back in that crap game.\'94 Down the table Manolita was laughing at something the new Englishman had said in Spanish. Most of the people had left the table. \'93Let\'92s finish the wine and go,\'94 Al said. \'93Don\'92t you want to get in that game?\'94 \'93I\'92ll watch you for a while,\'94 I said and called the waiter over to bring us the bill. \'93Where you go?\'94 Manolita called down the table. \'93To the room.\'94 \'93We come by later on,\'94 she said. \'93This man is very funny.\'94 \'93She is making most awful sport of me,\'94 the Englishman said. \'93She picks up on my errors in Spanish. I say, doesn\'92t leche mean milk?\'94 \'93That\'92s one interpretation of it.\'94 \'93Does it mean something beastly too?\'94 \'93I\'92m afraid so,\'94 I said. \'93You know it is a beastly language,\'94 he said. \'93Now Manolita, stop pulling my leg. I say stop it.\'94 \'93I\'92m not pulling your leg,\'94 Manolita laughed. \'93I never touched your leg. I am just laughing about the leche.\'94 \'93But it does mean milk. Didn\'92t you just hear Edwin Henry say so?\'94 Manolita started to laugh again and we got up to go. \'93He\'92s a silly piece of work,\'94 Al said. \'93I\'92d almost like to take her away because he\'92s so silly.\'94 \'93You can never tell about an Englishman,\'94 I said. It was such a profound remark that I knew we had ordered too many bottles. Outside, in the street, it was turning cold and in the moonlight the clouds were passing very 