s very strange. I can\'92t remember that at all.\'94 \'93Can you remember the safari leaving?\'94 \'93I should. But I don\'92t. I remember the women going down the trail to the beach for the water with the pots on their heads and I remember the flock of geese the toto drove back and forth to the water. I remember how slowly they all went and they were always going down or coming up. There was a very big tide too and the flats were yellow and the channel ran by the far island. The wind blew all the time and there were no flies and no mosquitoes. There was a roof and a cement floor and the poles that held the roof up, and the wind blew through them all the time. It was cool all day and lovely and cool at night.\'94 \'93Do you remember when the big dhow came in and careened on the low tide?\'94 \'93Yes, I remember her and the crew coming ashore in her boats and coming up the path from the beach, and the geese were afraid of them and so were the women.\'94 \'93That was the day we caught so many fish but had to come in because it was rough.\'94 \'93I remember that.\'94 \'93You\'92re remembering well today,\'94 she said. \'93Don\'92t do it too much.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry you didn\'92t get to fly to Zanzibar,\'94 he said. \'93That upper beach from where we were was a fine place to land. You could have landed and taken off from there quite easily.\'94 \'93We can always go to Zanzibar. Don\'92t try to remember too much today. Would you like me to read to you? There\'92s always something in the old New Yorkers that we missed.\'94 \'93No, please don\'92t read,\'94 he said. \'93Just talk. Talk about the good days.\'94 \'93Do you want to hear about what it\'92s like outside?\'94 \'93It\'92s raining,\'94 he said. \'93I know that.\'94 \'93It\'92s raining a big rain,\'94 she told him. \'93There won\'92t be any tourists out with this weather. The wind is very wild and we can go down and sit by the fire.\'94 \'93We could anyway. I don\'92t care about them any more. I like to hear them