s were right along the left-hand wall as you came in and faced the bar. This gave him better control over them than he would have had at The Index where they were scattered on account it was a bigger place with more room. On this night it was really cold outside and he came in with icicles on his mustache and small pus icicles out of both eyes and he didn\'92t look really very good. Even his smell was froze but that wasn\'92t for very long and he started to put out almost as soon as the door was shut. It was always hard for me to look at him but I was looking at him carefully because I knew he always rode and I didn\'92t see how he would be frozen up so bad. Finally I asked him. \'93Where you walk from, Blindy?\'94 \'93Willie Sawyer put me out of his car down below the railway bridge. There weren\'92t no more cars come and I walked in.\'94 \'93What did he put you afoot for?\'94 somebody asked. \'93Said I smelled too bad.\'94 Someone had pulled the handle on a machine and Blindy started listening to the whirr. It came up nothing. \'93Any dudes playing?\'94 he asked me. \'93Can\'92t you hear?\'94 \'93Not yet.\'94 \'93No dudes, Blindy, and it\'92s a Wednesday.\'94 \'93I know what night it is. Don\'92t start telling me what night it is.\'94 Blindy went down the line of machines feeling in all of them to see if anything had been left in the cups by mistake. Naturally there wasn\'92t anything, but that was the first part of his pitch. He came back to the bar where we were and Al Chaney asked him to have a drink. \'93No,\'94 Blindy said. \'93I got to be careful on those roads.\'94 \'93What you mean those roads?\'94 somebody asked him. \'93You only go on one road. Between here and The Flats.\'94 \'93I been on lots of roads,\'94 Blindy said. \'93And any time I may have to take off and go on more.\'94 Somebody hit on a machine but it wasn\'92t any heavy hit. Blindy moved on it just the same. It was a quarter machine and the young fellow who was playing it gave him a quarter sort of reluctantly. Blindy felt it before he put it in his pocket. \'93Thank you,\'94 he said. \'93You\'92ll never miss it.\'94 The young fellow said, \'93Nice to know that,\'94 and put a quarter back in the machine and pulled down again. He hit again but this time pretty good and he scooped in the quarters and gave a quarter to Blindy.\'94 \'93Thanks,\'94 Blindy said. \'93You\'92re doing fine.\'94 \'93Tonight\'92s my night,\'94 the young fellow who was playing said. \'93Your night is my night,\'94 Blindy said and the young fellow went on playing but he wasn\'92t doing any good any more and Blindy was so strong standing by him and he looked so awful and finally the fellow quit playing and came over to the bar. Blindy had run him out but he had no way of noticing it because the fellow didn\'92t say anything, so Blindy just checked the machines again with his hand and stood there waiting for someone else to come in and make a play. There wasn\'92t any play at the wheel nor at the crap table and at the poker game there were just gamblers sitting there and cutting each other up. It was a quiet evening on a week night in town and there wasn\'92t any excitement. The place was not making a nickel except at the bar. But at the bar it was pleasant and the place had been nice until Blindy had come in. Now everybody was figuring they might as well go next door to The Index or else cut out and go home. \'93What will yours be, Tom?\'94 Frank the bartender asked me. \'93This is on the house.\'94 \'93I was figuring on shoving.\'94 \'93Have one first then.\'94 \'93The same with ditch,\'94 I said. Frank asked the young fellow, who was wearing heavy Oregon Cities and a black hat and was shaved clean and had a snow-burned face, what he would drink and the young fellow took the same. The whisky was Old Forester. I nodded to him and raised my drink and we both sipped at the drinks. Blindy was down at the far end of the machines. I think he figured maybe no one would come in if they saw 