he timber and kill both of those bastards while they\'92re on the dock and wire a piece of iron on them from the old mill and sink them in the channel.\'94 \'93And then what would you do?\'94 his sister asked. \'93Somebody sent them.\'94 \'93Nobody sent that first son of a bitch.\'94 \'93But you killed the moose and you sold the trout and you killed what they took from your boat.\'94 \'93That was all right to kill that.\'94 He did not like to mention what that was, because that was the proof they had. \'93I know. But you\'92re not going to kill people and that\'92s why I\'92m going with you.\'94 \'93Let\'92s stop talking about it. But I\'92d like to kill those two sons of bitches.\'94 \'93I know,\'94 she said. \'93So would I. But we\'92re not going to kill people, Nickie. Will you promise me?\'94 \'93No. Now I don\'92t know whether it\'92s safe to take her the trout.\'94 \'93I\'92ll take them to her.\'94 \'93No. They\'92re too heavy. I\'92ll take them through the swamp and to the woods in back of the hotel. You go straight to the hotel and see if she\'92s there and if everything\'92s all right. And if it is you\'92ll find me there by the big basswood tree.\'94 \'93It\'92s a long way there through the swamp, Nicky.\'94 \'93It\'92s a long way back from reform school, too.\'94 \'93Can\'92t I come with you through the swamp? I\'92ll go in then and see her while you stay out and come back out with you and take them in.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93But I wish you\'92d do it the other way.\'94 \'93Why, Nickie?\'94 \'93Because you\'92ll see them maybe on the road and you can tell me where they\'92ve gone. I\'92ll see you in the second-growth wood lot in back of the hotel where the big basswood is.\'94 Nick waited more than an hour in the second-growth timber and his sister had not come. When she came she was excited and he knew she was tired. \'93They\'92re at our house,\'94 she said. \'93They\'92re sitting out on the screen porch and drinking whiskey and ginger ale and they\'92ve unhitched and put their horses up. They say they\'92re going to wait till you come back. It was our mother told them you\'92d gone fishing at the creek. I don\'92t think she meant to. Anyway I hope not.\'94 \'93What about Mrs. Packard?\'94 \'93I saw her in the kitchen of the hotel and she asked me if I\'92d seen you and I said no. She said she was waiting for you to bring her some fish for tonight. She was worried. You might as well take them in.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 he said. \'93They\'92re nice and fresh. I repacked them in ferns.\'94 \'93Can I come in with you?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 Nick said. The hotel was a long wooden building with a porch that fronted on the lake. There were wide wooden steps that led down to the pier that ran far out into the water and there were natural cedar railings alongside the steps and natural cedar railings around the porch. There were chairs made of natural cedar on the porch and in them sat middle-aged people wearing white clothes. There were three pipes set on the lawn with spring water bubbling out of them, and little paths led to them. The water tasted like rotten eggs because these were mineral springs and Nick and his sister used to drink from them as a matter of discipline. Now coming toward the rear of the hotel, where the kitchen was, they crossed a plank bridge over a small brook running into the lake beside the hotel, and slipped into the back door of the kitchen. \'93Wash them and put them in the ice box, Nickie,\'94 Mrs. Packard said. \'93I\'92ll weigh them later.\'94 \'93Mrs. Packard,\'94 Nick said. \'93Could I speak to you a minute?\'94 \'93Speak up,\'94 she said. \'93Can\'92t you see I\'92m busy?\'94 \'93If I could have the money now.\'94 Mrs. Packard was a handsome woman in a gingham apron. She had a beautiful complexion and she was very busy and her kitchen help were there as well. \'93You don\'92t mean you want to sell trout. Don\'92t you know that\'92s against the law?\'94 \'93I know,\'94 Nick said. \'93I brought you the fish for a present. I mean my time for the wood I split and corded.\'94 \'93I\'92ll get it,\'94 she said. \'93I have to go to the annex.\'94 Nick and his sister followed her outside. On the board sidewalk that led to the icehouse from the kitchen she stopped and put her hands in her apron pocket and took out a pocketbook. \'93You get out of here,\'94 she said quickly and kindly. \'93And get out of here fast. How much do you need?\'94 \'93I\'92ve got sixteen dollars,\'94 Nick said. \'93Take twenty,\'94 she told him. \'93And keep that tyke out of trouble. Let her go home and keep an eye on them until you\'92re clear.\'94 \'93When did you hear about them?\'94 She shook her head at him. \'93Buying is as bad or worse than selling,\'94 she said. \'93You stay away until things quiet down. Nickie, you\'92re a good boy no matter what anybody says. You see Packard if things get bad. Come here nights if you need anything. I sleep light. Just knock on the window.\'94 \'93You aren\'92t going to serve them tonight are you, Mrs. Packard? You\'92re not going to serve them for the dinners?\'94 \'93No,\'94 she said. \'93But I\'92m not going to waste them. Packard can eat half a dozen and I know other people that can. Be careful, Nickie, and let it blow over. Keep out of sight.\'94 \'93Littless wants to go with me.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you dare take her,\'94 Mrs. Packard said. \'93You come by tonight and I\'92ll have some stuff made up for you.\'94 \'93Could you let me take a skillet?\'94 \'93I\'92ll have what you need. Packard knows what you need. I don\'92t give you any more money so you\'92ll keep out of trouble.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to see Mr. Packard about getting a few things.\'94 \'93He\'92ll get you anything you need. But don\'92t you go near the store, Nick.\'94 \'93I\'92ll get Littless to take him a note.\'94 \'93Anytime you need anything,\'94 Mrs. Packard said. \'93Don\'92t you worry. Packard will be studying things out.\'94 \'93Good-bye, Aunt Halley.\'94 \'93Good-bye,\'94 she said and kissed him. She smelt wonderful when she kissed him. It was the way the kitchen smelled when they were baking. Mrs. Packard smelled like her kitchen and her kitchen always smelled good. \'93Don\'92t worry and don\'92t do anything bad.\'94 \'93I\'92ll be all right.\'94 \'93Of course,\'94 she said. \'93And Packard will figure out something.\'94 They were in the big hemlocks on the hill behind the house now. It was evening and the sun was down beyond the hills on the other side of the lake. \'93I\'92ve found everything,\'94 his sister said. \'93It\'92s going to make a pretty big pack, Nickie.\'94 \'93I know it. What are they doing?\'94 \'93They ate a big supper and now they\'92re sitting out on the porch and drinking. They\'92re telling each other stories about how smart they are.\'94 \'93They aren\'92t very smart so far.\'94 \'93They\'92re going to starve you out,\'94 his sister said. \'93A couple of nights in the woods and you\'92ll be back. You hear a loon holler a couple of times when you got an empty stomach and you\'92ll be back.\'94 \'93What did our mother give them for supper?\'94 \'93Awful,\'94 his sister said. \'93Good.\'94 \'93I\'92ve located everything on the list. Our mother\'92s gone to bed with a sick headache. She wrote our father.\'94 \'93Did you see the letter?\'94 \'93No. It\'92s in her room with the list of stuff to get from the store tomorrow. She\'92s going to have to make a new list when she finds everything is gone in the morning.\'94 \'93How much are they drinking?\'94 \'93They\'92ve drunk about a bottle, I guess.\'94 \'93I wish we could put knockout drops in it.\'94 \'93I could put them in if you\'92ll tell me how. Do you put them in the bottle?\'94 \'93No. In the glass. But we haven\'92t got any.\'94 \'93Would there be any in the medicine cabinet?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93I could put paregoric in the bottle. They have another bottle. Or calomel. I know we\'92ve got those.\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Nick. \'93You try to get me about half the other bottle when they\'92re asleep. Put it in any old medicine bottle.\'94 \'93I better go and watch them,\'94 his sister said. \'93My, I wish we had knockout drops. I never even heard of them.\'94 \'93They aren\'92t really drops,\'94 Nick told her. \'93It\'92s chloral hydrate. Whores give it to lumberjacks in their drinks when they\'92re going to jack roll them.\'94 \'93It sounds pretty bad,\'94 his sister said. \'93But we probably ought to have some for in emergencies.\'94 \'93Let me kiss you,\'94 her brother said. \'93Just for in an emergency. Let\'92s go down and watch them drinking. I\'92d like to hear them talk sitting in our own house.\'94 \'93Will you promise not to get angry and do anything bad?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93Nor to the horses. It\'92s not the horses\'92 fault.\'94 \'93Not the horses either.\'94 \'93I wish we had knockout drops,\'94 his sister said loyally. \'93Well, we haven\'92t,\'94 Nick told her. \'93I guess there aren\'92t any this side of Boyne City.\'94 They sat in the woodshed and they watched the two men sitting at the table on the screen porch. The moon had not risen and it was dark, but the outlines of the men showed against the lightness that the lake made behind them. They were not talking now but were both leaning forward on the table. Then Nick heard the clink of ice against a bucket. \'93The ginger ale\'92s gone,\'94 one of the men said. \'93I said it wouldn\'92t last,\'94 the other said. \'93But you were the one said we had plenty.\'94 \'93Get some water. There\'92s a pail and a dipper in the kitchen.\'94 \'93I\'92ve drunk enough. I\'92m going to turn in.\'94 \'93Aren\'92t you going to stay up for that kid?\'94 \'93No. I\'92m going to get some sleep. You stay up.\'94 \'93Do you think he\'92ll come in tonight?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. I\'92m going to get some sleep. You wake me when you get sleepy.\'94 \'93I can stay up all night,\'94 the local warden said. \'93Many\'92s the night I\'92ve stayed up all night for jack lighters and never shut an eye.\'94 \'93Me, too,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93But now I\'92m going to get a little sleep.\'94 Nick and his sister watched him go in the door. Their mother had told the two men they could sleep in the bedroom next to the living room. They saw when he struck a match. Then the window was dark again. They watched the other warden sitting at the table until he put his head on his arms. Then they heard him snoring. \'93We\'92ll give him a little while to make sure he\'92s solid asleep. Then we\'92ll get the stuff,\'94 Nick said. \'93You get over outside the fence,\'94 his sister said. \'93It doesn\'92t matter if I\'92m moving around. But he might wake up and see you.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick agreed. \'93I\'92ll get everything out of here. Most of it\'92s here.\'94 \'93Can you find everything without a light?\'94 \'93Sure. Where\'92s the rifle?\'94 \'93Flat on the back upper rafter. Don\'92t slip or make the wood fall down. Nick.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you worry.\'94 She came out to the fence at the far corner where Nick was making up his pack beyond the big hemlock that had been struck by lightning the summer before and had fallen in a storm that autumn. The moon was just rising now behind the far hills and enough moonlight came through the trees for Nick to see clearly what he was packing. His sister put down the sack she was carrying and said, \'93They\'92re sleeping like pigs, Nickie.\'94 \'93Good.\'94 \'93The down-state one was snoring just like the one outside. I think I got everything.\'94 \'93You good old Littless.\'94 \'93I wrote a note to our mother and told her I was going with you to keep you out of trouble and not to tell anybody and that you\'92d take good care of me. I put it under her door. It\'92s locked.\'94 \'93Oh, shit,\'94 Nick said. Then he said, \'93I\'92m sorry, Littless.\'94 \'93Now it\'92s not your fault and I can\'92t make it worse for you.\'94 \'93You\'92re awful.\'94 \'93Can\'92t we be happy now?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93I brought the whiskey,\'94 she said hopefully. \'93I left some in the bottle. One of them can\'92t be sure the other didn\'92t drink it. Anyway they have another bottle.\'94 \'93Did you bring a blanket for you?\'94 \'93Of course.\'94 \'93We better get going.\'94 \'93We\'92re all right if we\'92re going where I think. The only thing that makes the pack bigger is my blanket. I\'92ll carry the rifle.\'94 \'93All right. What kind of shoes have you?\'94 \'93I\'92ve got my work-moccasins.\'94 \'93What did you bring to read?\'94 \'93Lorna Doone and Kidnapped and Wuthering Heights.\'94 \'93They\'92re all too old for you but Kidnapped.\'94 \'93Lorna Doone isn\'92t.\'94 \'93We\'92ll read it out loud,\'94 Nick said. \'93That way it lasts longer. But, Littless, you\'92ve made things sort of hard now and we better go. Those bastards can\'92t be as stupid as they act. Maybe it was just because they were drinking.\'94 Nick had rolled the pack now and tightened the straps and he sat back and put his moccasins on. He put his arm around his sister. \'93You sure you want to go?\'94 \'93I have to go, Nickie. Don\'92t be weak and indecisive now. I left the note.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93Let\'92s go. You can take the rifle until you get tired of it.\'94 \'93I\'92m all ready to go,\'94 his sister said. \'93Let me help you strap the pack.\'94 \'93You know you haven\'92t had any sleep at all and that we have to travel?\'94 \'93I know. I\'92m really like the snoring one at the table says he was.\'94 \'93Maybe he was that way once, too,\'94 Nick said. \'93But what you have to do is keep your feet in good shape. Do the moccasins chafe?\'94 \'93No. And my feet are tough from going barefoot all summer.\'94 \'93Mine are good, too,\'94 said Nick. \'93Come on. Let\'92s go.\'94 They started off walking on the soft hemlock needles and the trees were high and there was no brush between the tree trunks. They walked uphill and the moon came through the trees and showed Nick with the very big pack and his sister carrying the .22 rifle. When they were at the top of the hill they looked back and saw the lake in the moonlight. It was clear enough so they could see the dark point, and beyond were the high hills of the far shore. \'93We might as well say good-bye to it,\'94 Nick Adams said. \'93Good-bye, lake,\'94 Littless said. \'93I love you, too.\'94 They went down the hill and across the long field and through the orchard and then through a rail fence and into a field of stubble. Going through the stubble field they looked to the right and saw the slaughterhouse and the big barn in the hollow and the old log farmhouse on the other high land that overlooked the lake. The long road of Lombardy poplars that ran to the lake was in the moonlight. \'93Does it hurt your feet, Littless?\'94 Nick asked. \'93No,\'94 his sister said. \'93I came this way on account of the dogs,\'94 Nick said. \'93They\'92d shut up as soon as they knew it was us. But somebody might hear them bark.\'94 \'93I know,\'94 she said. \'93And as soon as they shut up afterwards they\'92d know it was us.\'94 Ahead they could see the dark of the rising line of hills beyond the road. They came to the end of one cut field of grain and crossed the little sunken creek that ran down to the springhouse. Then they climbed across the rise of another stubble field and there was another rail fence and the sandy road with the second-growth timber solid beyond it. \'93Wait till I climb over and I\'92ll help you,\'94 Nick said. \'93I want to look at the road.\'94 From the top of the fence he saw the roll of the country and the dark timber by their own house and the brightness of the lake in the moonlight Then he was looking at the road. \'93They can\'92t track us the way we\'92ve come and I don\'92t think they would notice tracks in this deep sand,\'94 he said to his sister. \'93We can keep to the two sides of the road if it isn\'92t too scratchy.\'94 \'93Nickie, honestly I don\'92t think they\'92re intelligent enough to track anybody. Look how they just waited for you to come back and then practically got drunk before supper and afterwards.\'94 \'93They came down to the dock,\'94 Nick said. \'93That was where I was. If you hadn\'92t told me they would have picked me up.\'94 \'93They didn\'92t have to be so intelligent to figure you would be on the big creek when our mother let them know you might have gone fishing. After I left they must have found all the boats were there and that would make them think you were fishing the creek. Everybody knows you usually fish below the grist mill and the cider mill. They were just slow thinking it out.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93But they were awfully close then.\'94 His sister handed him the rifle through the fence, butt toward him, and then crawled between the rails. She stood beside him on the road and he put his hand on her head and stroked it. \'93Are you awfully tired, Littless?\'94 \'93No. I\'92m fine. I\'92m too happy to be tired.\'94 \'93Until you\'92re too tired you walk in the sandy part of the road when; their horses made holes in the sand. It\'92s so soft and dry tracks won\'92t show and I\'92ll walk on the side where it\'92s hard.\'94 \'93I can walk on the side, too.\'94 \'93No. I don\'92t want you to get scratched.\'94 They climbed, but with constant small descents, toward the height of land that separated the two lakes. There was close, heavy, second-growth timber on both sides of the road and blackberry and raspberry bushes grew from the edge of the road to the timber. Ahead they could see the top of each hill as a notch in the timber. The moon was well on its way down now. \'93How do you feel, Littless?\'94 Nick asked his sister. \'93I feel wonderful. Nickie, is it always this nice when you run away from home?\'94 \'93No. Usually it\'92s lonesome.\'94 \'93How lonesome have you ever been?\'94 \'93Bad black lonesome. Awful.\'94 \'93Do you think you\'92ll get lonesome with me?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93You don\'92t mind you\'92re with me instead of going to Trudy?\'94 \'93What do you talk about her for all the time?\'94 \'93I haven\'92t been. Maybe you were thinking about her and you thought I was talking.\'94 \'93You\'92re too smart,\'94 Nick said. \'93I thought about her because you told me where she was and when I knew where she was I wondered what she would be doing and all that.\'94 \'93I guess I shouldn\'92t have come.\'94 \'93I told you that you shouldn\'92t have come.\'94 \'93Oh, hell,\'94 his sister said. \'93Are we going to be like the others and have fights? I\'92ll go back now. You don\'92t have to have me.\'94 \'93Shut up,\'94 Nick said. \'93Please don\'92t say that, Nickie. I\'92ll go back or I\'92ll stay just as you want. I\'92ll go back whenever you tell me to. But I won\'92t have fights. Haven\'92t we seen enough fights in families?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said Nick. \'93I know I forced you to take me. But I fixed it so you wouldn\'92t get in trouble about it. And I did keep them from catching you.\'94 They had reached the height of land and from here they could see the lake again although from here it looked narrow now and almost like a big river. \'93We cut across country here,\'94 Nick said. \'93Then we\'92ll hit that old logging road. Here\'92s where you go back from if you want to go back.\'94 He took off his pack and put it back into the timber and his sister leaned the rifle on it. \'93Sit down, Littless, and take a rest,\'94 he said. \'93We\'92re both tired.\'94 Nick lay with his head on the pack and his sister lay by him with her head on his shoulder. \'93I\'92m not going back, Nickie, unless you tell me to,\'94 she said. \'93I just don\'92t want fights. Promise me we won\'92t have fights?\'94 \'93Promise.\'94 \'93I won\'92t talk about Trudy.\'94 \'93The hell with Trudy.\'94 \'93I want to be useful and a good partner.\'94 \'93You are. You won\'92t mind if I get restless and mix it up with being lonesome?\'94 \'93No. We\'92ll take good care of each other and have fun. We can have a lovely time.\'94 \'93All right. We\'92ll start to have it now.\'94 \'93I\'92ve been having it all the time.\'94 \'93We just have one pretty hard stretch and then a really hard stretch and then we\'92ll be there. We might as well wait until it gets light to start. You go to sleep, Littless. Are you warm enough?\'94 \'93Oh, yes, Nickie. I\'92ve got my sweater.\'94 She curled up beside him and was asleep. In a little while Nick was sleeping, too. He slept for two hours until the morning light woke him. Nick had circled around through the second-growth timber until they had come onto the old logging road. \'93We couldn\'92t leave tracks going into it from the main road,\'94 he told his sister. The old road was so overgrown that he had to stoop many times to avoid hitting branches. \'93It\'92s like a tunnel,\'94 his sister said. \'93It opens up after a while.\'94 \'93Have I ever been here before?\'94 \'93No. This goes up way beyond where I ever took you hunting.\'94 \'93Does it come out on the secret place?\'94 \'93No, Littless. We have to go through some long bad slashings. Nobody gets in where we\'92re going.\'94 They kept on along the road and then took another road that was even more overgrown. Then they came out into a clearing. There was fireweed and brush in the clearing and the old cabins of the logging camp. They were very old and some of the roofs had fallen in. But there was a spring by the road and they both drank at it. The sun wasn\'92t up yet and they both felt hollow and empty in the early morning after the night of walking. \'93All this beyond was hemlock forest,\'94 Nick said. \'93They only cut it for the bark and they never used the logs.\'94 \'93But what happens to the road?\'94 \'93They must have cut up at the far end first and hauled and piled the bark by the road to snake it out. Then finally they cut everything right to the road and piled the bark here and then pulled out.\'94 \'93Is the secret place beyond all this slashing?\'94 \'93Yes. We go through the slashing and then some more road and then another slashing and then we come to virgin timber.\'94 \'93How did they leave it when they cut all this?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. It belonged to somebody that wouldn\'92t sell, I guess. They stole a lot from the edges and paid stumpage on it. But the good part\'92s still there and there isn\'92t any passable road into it.\'94 \'93But why can\'92t people go down the creek? The creek has to come from somewhere?\'94 They were resting before they started the bad traveling through the slashing and Nick wanted to explain. \'93Look, Littless. The creek crosses the main road we were on and it goes through a farmer\'92s land. The farmer has it fenced for a pasture and he runs people off that want to fish. So they stop at the bridge on his land. On the section of the creek where they would hit if they cut across his pasture on the other side from his house he runs a bull. The bull is mean and he really runs everybody off. He\'92s the meanest bull I ever saw and he just stays there, mean all the time, and hunts for people. Then after him the farmer\'92s land ends and there\'92s a section of cedar swamp with sink holes and you\'92d have to know it to get through. And then, even if you know it, it\'92s bad. Below that is the secret place. We\'92re going in over the hills and sort of in the back way. Then below the secret place there\'92s real swamp. Bad swamp that you can\'92t get through. Now we better start the bad part.\'94 The bad part and the part that was worse were behind them now. Nick had climbed over many logs that were higher than his head and others that were up to his waist. He would take the rifle and lay it down on the top of the log and pull his sister up and then she would slide down on the far side or he would lower himself down and take the rifle and help the girl down. They went over and around piles of brush and it was hot in the slashing, and the pollen from the ragweed and the fireweed dusted the girl\'92s hair and made her sneeze. \'93Damn slashings,\'94 she said to Nick. They were resting on top of a big log ringed where they sat by the cutting of the barkpeelers. The ring was gray in the rotting gray log and all around were other long gray trunks and gray brush and branches with the brilliant and worthless seeds growing. \'93This is the last one,\'94 Nick said. \'93I hate them,\'94 his sister said. \'93And the damn weeds are like flowers in a tree cemetery if nobody took care of it.\'94 \'93You see why I didn\'92t want to try to make it in the dark.\'94 \'93We couldn\'92t.\'94 \'93No. And nobody\'92s going to chase us through here. Now we come into the good part.\'94 They came from the hot sun of the slashings into the shade of the great trees. The slashings had run up to the top of a ridge and over and then the forest began. They were walking on the brown forest floor now and it was springy and cool under their feet. There was no underbrush and the trunks of the trees rose sixty feet high before there were any branches. It was cool in the shade of the trees and high up in them Nick could hear the breeze that was rising. No sun came through as they walked and Nick knew there would be no sun through the high top branches until nearly noon. His sister put her hand in his and walked close to him. \'93I\'92m not scared, Nickie. But it makes me feel very strange.\'94 \'93Me, too,\'94 Nick said. \'93Always.\'94 \'93I never was in woods like these.\'94 \'93This is all the virgin timber left around here.\'94 \'93Do we go through it very long?\'94 \'93Quite a way.\'94 \'93I\'92d be afraid if I were alone.\'94 \'93It makes me feel strange. But I\'92m not afraid.\'94 \'93I said that first.\'94 \'93I know. Maybe we say it because we are afraid.\'94 \'93No. I\'92m not afraid because I\'92m with you. But I know I\'92d be afraid alone. Did you ever come here with anyone else?\'94 \'93No. Only by myself.\'94 \'93And you weren\'92t afraid?\'94 \'93No. But I always feel strange. Like the way I ought to feel in church.\'94 \'93Nickie, where we\'92re going to live isn\'92t as solemn as this, is it?\'94 \'93No. Don\'92t you worry. There it\'92s cheerful. You just enjoy this, Littless. This is good for you. This is the way forests were in the olden days. This is about the last good country there is left. Nobody gets in here ever.\'94 \'93I love the olden days. But I wouldn\'92t want it all this solemn.\'94 \'93It wasn\'92t all solemn. But the hemlock forests were.\'94 \'93It\'92s wonderful walking. I thought behind our house was wonderful. But this is better. Nickie, do you believe in God? You don\'92t have to answer if you don\'92t want to.\'94 \'93I don\'92t know.\'94 \'93All right. You don\'92t have to say it. But you don\'92t mind if I say my prayers at night?\'94 \'93No. I\'92ll remind you if you forget.\'94 \'93Thank you. Because this kind of woods makes me feel awfully religious.\'94 \'93That\'92s why they build cathedrals to be like this.\'94 \'93You\'92ve never seen a cathedral, have you?\'94 \'93No. But I\'92ve read about them and I can imagine them. This is the best one we have around here.\'94 \'93Do you think we can go to Europe some time and see cathedrals?\'94 \'93Sure we will. But first I have to get out of this trouble and learn how to make some money.\'94 \'93Do you think you\'92ll ever make money writing?\'94 \'93If I get good enough.\'94 \'93Couldn\'92t you maybe make it if you wrote cheerfuller things? That isn\'92t my opinion. Our mother said everything you write is morbid.\'94 \'93It\'92s too morbid for the St. Nicholas,\'94 Nick said. \'93They didn\'92t say it. But they didn\'92t like it.\'94 \'93But the St. Nicholas is our favorite magazine.\'94 \'93I know,\'94 said Nick. \'93But I\'92m too morbid for it already. And I\'92m not even grown-up.\'94 \'93When is a man grown-up? When he\'92s married?\'94 \'93No. Until you\'92re grown-up they send you to reform school. After you\'92re grown-up they send you to the penitentiary.\'94 \'93I\'92m glad you\'92re not grown-up then.\'94 \'93They\'92re not going to send me anywhere,\'94 Nick said. \'93And let\'92s not talk morbid even if I write morbid.\'94 \'93I didn\'92t say it was morbid.\'94 \'93I know. Everybody else does, though.\'94 \'93Let\'92s be cheerful, Nickie,\'94 his sister said. \'93These woods make us too solemn.\'94 \'93We\'92ll be out of them pretty soon,\'94 Nick told her. \'93Then you\'92ll see where we\'92re going to live. Are you hungry, Littless?\'94 \'93A little.\'94 \'93I\'92ll bet,\'94 Nick said. \'93We\'92ll eat a couple of apples.\'94 They were coming down a long hill when they saw sunlight ahead through the tree trunks. Now, at the edge of the timber, there was wintergreen growing and some partridgeberries and the forest floor began to be alive with growing things. Through the tree trunks they saw an open meadow that sloped to where white birches grew along the stream. Below the meadow and the line of the birches there was the dark green of a cedar swamp and far beyond the swamp there were dark blue hills. There was an arm of the lake between the swamp and the hills. But from here they could not see it. They only felt from the distances that it was there. \'93Here\'92s the spring,\'94 Nick said to his sister. \'93And here\'92s the stones where I camped before.\'94 \'93It\'92s a beautiful, beautiful place, Nickie,\'94 his sister said. \'93Can we see the lake, too?\'94 \'93There\'92s a place where we can see it. But it\'92s better to camp here. I\'92ll get some wood and we\'92ll make breakfast.\'94 \'93The firestones are very old.\'94 \'93It\'92s a very old place,\'94 Nick said. \'93The firestones are Indian.\'94 \'93How did you come to it straight through the woods with no trail and no blazes?\'94 \'93Didn\'92t you see the direction sticks on the three ridges?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93I\'92ll show them to you sometime.\'94 \'93Are they yours?\'94 \'93No. They\'92re from the old days.\'94 \'93Why didn\'92t you show them to me?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Nick said. \'93I was showing off I guess.\'94 \'93Nickie, they\'92ll never find us here.\'94 \'93I hope not,\'94 Nick said. At about the time that Nick and his sister were entering the first of the slashings the warden who was sleeping on the screen porch of the house that stood in the shade of the trees above the lake was wakened by the sun that, rising above the slope of open land behind the house, shone full on his face. During the night the warden had gotten up for a drink of water and when he had come back from the kitchen he had lain down on the floor with a cushion from one of the chairs for a pillow. Now he waked, realized where he was, and got to his feet. He had slept on his right side because he had a .38 Smith and Wesson revolver in a shoulder holster under his left armpit. Now, awake, he felt for the gun, looked away from the sun, which hurt his eyes, and went into the kitchen where he dipped up a drink of water from the pail beside the kitchen table. The hired girl was building a fire in the stove and the warden said to her, \'93What about some breakfast?\'94 \'93No breakfast,\'94 she said. She slept in a cabin out behind the house and had come into the kitchen a half an hour before. The sight of the warden lying on the floor of the screen porch and the nearly empty bottle of whiskey on the table had frightened and disgusted her. Then it had made her angry. \'93What do you mean, no breakfast?\'94 the warden said, still holding the dipper. \'93Just that.\'94 \'93Why?\'94 \'93Nothing to eat.\'94 \'93What about coffee?\'94 \'93No coffee.\'94 \'93Tea?\'94 \'93No tea. No bacon. No corn meal. No salt. No pepper. No coffee. No Borden\'92s canned cream. No Aunt Jemima buckwheat flour. No nothing.\'94 \'93What are you talking about? There was plenty to eat last night.\'94 \'93There isn\'92t now. Chipmunks must have carried it away.\'94 The warden from down state had gotten up when he heard them talking and had come into the kitchen. \'93How do you feel this morning?\'94 the hired girl asked him. The warden ignored the hired girl and said, \'93What is it, Evans?\'94 \'93That son of a bitch came in here last night and got himself a pack load of grub.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you swear in my kitchen,\'94 the hired girl said. \'93Come out here,\'94 The down-state warden said. They both went out on the screen porch and shut the kitchen door. \'93What does that mean, Evans?\'94 The down-state man pointed at the quart of Old Green River which had less than a quarter left in it. \'93How skunk-drunk were you?\'94 \'93I drank the same as you. I sat up by the table\'97\'94 \'93Doing what?\'94 \'93Waiting for the goddam Adams boy if he showed.\'94 \'93And drinking.\'94 \'93Not drinking. Then I got up and went in the kitchen and got a drink of water about half past four and I lay down here in front of the door to take it easier.\'94 \'93Why didn\'92t you lie down in front of the kitchen door?\'94 \'93I could see him better from here if he came.\'94 \'93So what happened?\'94 \'93He must have come in the kitchen, through a window maybe, and loaded that stuff.\'94 \'93Bullshit.\'94 \'93What were you doing?\'94 the local warden asked. \'93I was sleeping the same as you.\'94 \'93Okay. Let\'92s quit fighting about it. That doesn\'92t do any good.\'94 \'93Tell that hired girl to come out here.\'94 The hired girl came out and the down-state man said to her, \'93You tell Mrs. Adams we want to speak to her.\'94 The hired girl did not say anything but went into the main part of the house, shutting the door after her. \'93You better pick up the full and the empty bottles,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93There isn\'92t enough of this to do any good. You want a drink of it?\'94 \'93No thanks. I\'92ve got to work today.\'94 \'93I\'92ll take one,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93It hasn\'92t been shared right.\'94 \'93I didn\'92t drink any of it after you left,\'94 the local warden said doggedly. \'93Why do you keep on with that bullshit?\'94 \'93It isn\'92t bullshit.\'94 The down-state man put the bottle down. \'93All right,\'94 he said to the hired girl, who had opened and shut the door behind her. \'93What did she say?\'94 \'93She has a sick headache and she can\'92t see you. She says you have a warrant. She says for you to search the place if you want to and then go.\'94 \'93What did she say about the boy?\'94 \'93She hasn\'92t seen the boy and she doesn\'92t know anything about him.\'94 \'93Where are the other kids?\'94 \'93They\'92re visiting at Charlevoix.\'94 \'93Who are they visiting?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. She doesn\'92t know. They went to the dance and they were going to stay over Sunday with friends.\'94 \'93Who was that kid that was around here yesterday?\'94 \'93I didn\'92t see any kid around here yesterday.\'94 \'93There was.\'94 \'93Maybe some friend of the children asking for them. Maybe some resorter\'92s kid. Was it a boy or a girl?\'94 \'93A girl about eleven or twelve. Brown hair and brown eyes. Freckles. Very tanned. Wearing overalls and a boy\'92s shirt. Barefooted.\'94 \'93Sounds like anybody,\'94 the girl said. \'93Did you say eleven or twelve years old?\'94 \'93Oh, shit,\'94 said the man from down state. \'93You can\'92t get anything out of these mossbacks.\'94 \'93If I\'92m a mossback what\'92s he?\'94 The hired girl looked at the local warden. \'93What\'92s Mr. Evans? His kids and me went to the same schoolhouse.\'94 \'93Who was the girl?\'94 Evans asked her. \'93Come on, Suzy. I can find out anyway.\'94 \'93I wouldn\'92t know,\'94 Suzy, the hired girl, said. \'93It seems like all kinds of people come by here now. I just feel like I\'92m in a big city.\'94 \'93You don\'92t want to get in any trouble, do you, Suzy?\'94 Evans said. \'93No, sir.\'94 \'93I mean it.\'94 \'93You don\'92t want to get in any trouble either, do you?\'94 Suzy asked him. Out at the barn after they were hitched up the down-state man said, \'93We didn\'92t do so good, did we?\'94 \'93He\'92s loose now,\'94 Evans said. \'93He\'92s got grub and he must have his rifle. But he\'92s still in the area. I can get him. Can you track?\'94 \'93No. Not really. Can you?\'94 \'93In snow,\'94 the other warden laughed. \'93But we don\'92t have to track. We have to think out where he\'92ll be.\'94 \'93He didn\'92t load up with all that stuff to go south. He\'92d just take a little something and head for the railway.\'94 \'93I couldn\'92t tell what was missing from the woodshed. But he had a big pack load from the kitchen. He\'92s heading in somewhere. I got to check on all his habits and his friends and where he used to go. You block him off at Charlevoix and Petoskey and St. Ignace and Sheboygan. Where would you go if you were him?\'94 \'93I\'92d go to the Upper Peninsula.\'94 \'93Me, too. He\'92s been up there, too. The ferry is the easiest place to pick him up. But there\'92s an awful big country between here and Sheboygan and he knows that country, too.\'94 \'93We better go down and see Packard. We were going to check that today.\'94 \'93What\'92s to prevent him going down by East Jordan and Grand Traverse?\'94 \'93Nothing. But that isn\'92t his country. He\'92ll go some place that he knows.\'94 Suzy came out when they were opening the gate in the fence. \'93Can I ride down to the store with you? I\'92ve got to get some groceries.\'94 \'93What makes you think we\'92re going to the store?\'94 \'93Yesterday you were talking about going to see Mr. Packard.\'94 \'93How are you going to get your groceries back?\'94 \'93I guess I can get a lift with somebody on the road or coming up the lake. This is Saturday.\'94 \'93All right. Climb up,\'94 the local warden said. \'93Thank you, Mr. Evans,\'94 Suzy said. At the general store and post office Evans hitched the team at the rack and he and the down-state man stood and talked before they went in. \'93I couldn\'92t say anything with that damned Suzy.\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93Packard\'92s a fine man. There isn\'92t anybody better-liked in this country. You\'92d never get a conviction on that trout business against him. Nobody\'92s going to scare him and we don\'92t want to antagonize him.\'94 \'93Do you think he\'92ll cooperate?\'94 \'93Not if you act rough.\'94 \'93We\'92ll go see him.\'94 Inside the store Suzy had gone straight through past the glass showcases, the opened barrels, the boxes, the shelves of canned goods, seeing nothing nor anyone until she came to the post office with its lockboxes and its general delivery and stamp window. The window was down and she went straight on to the back of the store. Mr. Packard was opening a packing box with a crowbar. He looked at her and smiled. \'93Mr. John,\'94 the hired girl said, speaking very fast. \'93There\'92s two wardens coming in that\'92s after Nickie. He cleared out last night and his kid sister\'92s gone with him. Don\'92t let on about that. His mother knows it and it\'92s all right. Anyhow she isn\'92t going to say anything.\'94 \'93Did he take all your groceries?\'94 \'93Most of them.\'94 \'93You pick out what you need and make a list and I\'92ll check it over with you.\'94 \'93They\'92re coming in now.\'94 \'93You go out the back and come in the front again. I\'92ll go and talk to them.\'94 Suzy walked around the long frame building and climbed the front steps again. This time she noticed everything as she came in. She knew the Indians who had brought in the baskets and she knew the two Indian boys who were looking at the fishing tackle in the first showcases on the left. She knew all the patent medicines in the next case and who usually bought them. She had clerked one summer in the store and she knew what the penciled code letters and numbers meant that were on the cardboard boxes that held shoes, winter overshoes, wool socks, mittens, caps and sweaters. She knew what the baskets were worth that the Indians had brought in and that it was too late in the season for them to bring a good price. \'93Why did you bring them in so late, Mrs. Tabeshaw?\'94 she asked. \'93Too much fun Fourth of July,\'94 the Indian woman laughed. \'93How\'92s Billy?\'94 Suzy asked. \'93I don\'92t know, Suzy. I no see him four weeks now.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you take them down to the hotel and try to sell them to the resorters?\'94 Suzy said. \'93Maybe,\'94 Mrs. Tabeshaw said. \'93I took once.\'94 \'93You ought to take them every day.\'94 \'93Long walk,\'94 Mrs. Tabeshaw said. While Suzy was talking to the people she knew and making a list of what she needed for the house the two wardens were in the back of the store with Mr. John Packard. Mr. John had gray-blue eyes and dark hair and a dark mustache and he always looked as though he had wandered into a general store by mistake. He had been away from northern Michigan once for eighteen years when he was a young man and he looked more like a peace officer or an honest gambler than a storekeeper. He had owned good saloons in his time and run them well. But when the country had been lumbered off he had stayed and bought farming land. Finally when the county had gone local option he had bought this store. He already owned the hotel. But he said he didn\'92t like a hotel without a bar and so he almost never went near it. Mrs. Packard ran the hotel. She was more ambitious than Mr. John and Mr. John said he didn\'92t want to waste time with people who had enough money to take a vacation anywhere in the country they wanted and then came to a hotel without a bar and spent their time sitting on the porch in rocking chairs. He called the resorters \'93change-of-lifers\'94 and he made fun of them to Mrs. Packard but she loved him and never minded when he teased her. \'93I don\'92t mind if you call them change-of-lifers,\'94 she told him one night in bed. \'93I had the damn thing but I\'92m still all the woman you can handle, aren\'92t I?\'94 She liked the resorters because some of them brought culture and Mr. John said she loved culture like a lumberjack loved Peerless, the great chewing tobacco. He really respected her love of culture because she said she loved it just like he loved good bonded whiskey and she said, \'93Packard, you don\'92t have to care about culture. I won\'92t bother you with it. But it makes me feel wonderful.\'94 Mr. John said she could have culture until hell wouldn\'92t hold it just so long as he never had to go to a Chautauqua or a Self-Betterment Course. He had been to camp meetings and a revival but he had never been to a Chautauqua. He said a camp meeting or a revival was bad enough but at least there was some sexual intercourse afterwards by those who got really aroused although he never knew anyone to pay their bills after a camp meeting or a revival. Mrs. Packard, he told Nick Adams, would get worried about the salvation of his immortal soul after she had been to a big revival by somebody like Gypsy Smith, that great evangelist, but finally it would turn out that he, Packard, looked like Gypsy Smith and everything would be fine finally. But a Chautauqua was something strange. Culture maybe was better than religion, Mr. John thought. But it was a cold proposition. Still they were crazy for it. He could see it was more than a fad, though. \'93It\'92s sure got a hold on them,\'94 he had told Nick Adams. \'93It must be sort of like the Holy Rollers only in the brain. You study it sometime and tell me what you think. You going to be a writer you ought to get in on it early. Don\'92t let them get too far ahead of you.\'94 Mr. John liked Nick Adams because he said he had original sin. Nick did not understand this but he was proud. \'93You\'92re going to have things to repent, boy,\'94 Mr. John had told Nick. \'93That\'92s one of the best things there is. You can always decide whether to repent them or not. But the thing is to have them.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to do anything bad,\'94 Nick had said. \'93I don\'92t want you to,\'94 Mr. John had said. \'93But you\'92re alive and you\'92re going to do things. Don\'92t you lie and don\'92t you steal. Everybody has to lie. But you pick out somebody you never lie to.\'94 \'93I\'92ll pick out you.\'94 \'93That\'92s right. Don\'92t you ever lie to me no matter what and I won\'92t lie to you.\'94 \'93I\'92ll try,\'94 Nick had said. \'93That isn\'92t it,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93It has to be absolute.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93I\'92ll never lie to you.\'94 \'93What became of your girl?\'94 \'93Somebody said she was working up at the Soo.\'94 \'93She was a beautiful girl and I always liked her,\'94 Mr. John had said. \'93So did I,\'94 Nick said. \'93Try and not feel too bad about it.\'94 \'93I can\'92t help it,\'94 Nick said. \'93None of it was her fault. She\'92s just built that way. If I ran into her again I guess I\'92d get mixed up with her again.\'94 \'93Maybe not.\'94 \'93Maybe too. I\'92d try not to.\'94 Mr. John was thinking about Nick when he went out to the back counter where the two men were waiting for him. He looked them over as he stood there and he didn\'92t like either of them. He had always disliked the local man Evans and had no respect for him but he sensed that the downstate man was dangerous. He had not analyzed it yet but he saw the man had very flat eyes and a mouth that was tighter than a simple tobacco chewer\'92s mouth needed to be. He had a real elk\'92s tooth too on his watch chain. It was a really fine tusk from about a five-year-old bull. It was a beautiful tusk and Mr. John looked at it again and at the over-large bulge the man\'92s shoulder holster made under his coat. \'93Did you kill that bull with that cannon you\'92re carrying around under your arm?\'94 Mr. John asked the down-state man. The down-state man looked at Mr. John unappreciatively. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I killed that bull out in the thoroughfare country in Wyoming with a Winchester 45-70.\'94 \'93You\'92re a big-gun man, eh?\'94 Mr. John said. He looked under the counter. \'93Have big feet, too. Do you need that big a cannon when you go out hunting kids?\'94 \'93What do you mean, kids,\'94 the down-state man said. He was one ahead. \'93I mean the kid you\'92re looking for.\'94 \'93You said kids,\'94 the down-state man said. Mr. John moved in. It was necessary. \'93What\'92s Evans carry when he goes after a boy who\'92s licked his own boy twice? You must be heavily armed, Evans. That boy could lick you, too.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you produce him and we could try it,\'94 Evans said. \'93You said kids, Mr. Jackson,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93What made you say that?\'94 \'93Looking at you, you cock-sucker,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93You splayfooted bastard.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you come out from behind that counter if you want to talk like that?\'94 the down-state man said. \'93You\'92re talking to the United States Postmaster,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93You\'92re talking without witnesses except for Turd-Face Evans. I suppose you know why they call him Turd-Face. You can figure it out. You\'92re a detective.\'94 He was happy now. He had drawn the attack and he felt now as he used to feel in the old days before he made a living from feeding and bedding resorters who rocked in rustic chairs on the front porch of his hotel while they looked out over the lake. \'93Listen, Splayfoot, I remember you very well now. Don\'92t you remember me, Splayzey?\'94 The down-state man looked at him. But he did not remember him. \'93I remember you in Cheyenne the day Tom Horn was hanged,\'94 Mr. John told him. \'93You were one of the ones that framed him with promises from the association. Do you remember now? Who owned the saloon in Medicine Bow when you worked for the people that gave it to Tom? Is that why you ended up doing what you\'92re doing? Haven\'92t you got any memory?\'94 \'93When did you come back here?\'94 \'93Two years after they dropped Tom.\'94 \'93I\'92ll be goddamned.\'94 \'93Do you remember when I gave you that bull tusk when we were packing out from Greybull?\'94 \'93Sure. Listen, Jim, I got to get this kid.\'94 \'93My name\'92s John,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93John Packard. Come on in back and have a drink. You want to get to know this other character. His name is Crut-Face Evans. We used to call him Turd-Face. I just changed it now out of kindness.\'94 \'93Mr. John,\'94 said Mr. Evans. \'93Why don\'92t you be friendly and cooperative.\'94 \'93I just changed your name, didn\'92t I?\'94 said Mr. John. \'93What kind of cooperation do you boys want?\'94 In the back of the store Mr. John took a bottle off a low shelf in the corner and handed it to the down-state man. \'93Drink up, Splayzey,\'94 he said. \'93You look like you need it.\'94 They each took a drink and then Mr. John asked, \'93What are you after this kid for?\'94 \'93Violation of the game laws,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93What particular violation?\'94 \'93He killed a buck deer the twelfth of last month.\'94 \'93Two men with guns out after a boy because he killed a deer the twelfth of last month,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93There\'92ve been other violations.\'94 \'93But this is the one you\'92ve got proof of.\'94 \'93That\'92s about it.\'94 \'93What were the other violations?\'94 \'93Plenty.\'94 \'93But you haven\'92t got proof.\'94 \'93I didn\'92t say that,\'94 Evans said. \'93But we\'92ve got proof on this.\'94 \'93And the date was the twelfth?\'94 \'93That\'92s right,\'94 said Evans. \'93Why don\'92t you ask some questions instead of answering them?\'94 the down-state man said to his partner. Mr. John laughed. \'93Let him alone, Splayzey,\'94 he said. \'93I like to see that great brain work.\'94 \'93How well do you know the boy?\'94 the down-state man asked. \'93Pretty well.\'94 \'93Ever do any business with him?\'94 \'93He buys a little stuff here once in a while. Pays cash.\'94 \'93Do you have any idea where he\'92d head for?\'94 \'93He\'92s got folks in Oklahoma.\'94 \'93When did you see him last?\'94 Evans asked. \'93Come on, Evans,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93You\'92re wasting our time. Thanks for the drink, Jim.\'94 \'93John,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93What\'92s your name, Splayzey?\'94 \'93Porter. Henry J. Porter.\'94 \'93Splayzey, you\'92re not going to do any shooting at that boy.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to bring him in.\'94 \'93You always were a murderous bastard.\'94 \'93Come on, Evans,\'94 the down-state man said. \'93We\'92re wasting time in here.\'94 \'93You remember what I said about the shooting,\'94 Mr. John said very quietly. \'93I heard you,\'94 the down-state man said. The two men went out through the store and unhitched their light wagon and drove off. Mr. John watched them go up the road. Evans was driving and the down-state man was talking to him. \'93Henry J. Porter,\'94 Mr. John thought. \'93The only name I can remember for him is Splayzey. He had such big feet he had to have made-to-order boots. Splayfoot they called him. Then Splayzey. It was his tracks by the spring where that Nester\'92s boy was shot that they hung Tom for. Splayzey. Splayzey what? Maybe I never did know. Splayfoot Splayzey. Splayfoot Porter? No, it wasn\'92t Porter.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry about those baskets, Mrs. Tabeshaw,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s too late in the season now and they don\'92t carry over. But if you\'92d be patient with them down at the hotel you\'92d get rid of them.\'94 \'93You buy them, sell at the hotel,\'94 Mrs. Tabeshaw suggested. \'93No. They\'92d buy them better from you,\'94 Mr. John told her. \'93You\'92re a fine looking woman.\'94 \'93Long time ago,\'94 Mrs. Tabeshaw said. \'93Suzy, I\'92d like to see you,\'94 Mr. John said. In the back of the store he said, \'93Tell me about it.\'94 \'93I told you already. They came for Nickie and they waited for him to come home. His youngest sister let him know they were waiting for him. When they were sleeping drunk Nickie got his stuff and pulled out. He\'92s got grub for two weeks easy and he\'92s got his rifle and young Littless went with him.\'94 \'93Why did she go?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know, Mr. John. I guess she wanted to look after him and keep him from doing anything bad. You know him.\'94 \'93You live up by Evans\'92s. How much do you think he knows about the country Nick uses?\'94 \'93All he can. But I don\'92t know how much.\'94 \'93Where do you think they went?\'94 \'93I wouldn\'92t know, Mr. John. Nickie knows a lot of country.\'94 \'93That man with Evans is no good. He\'92s really bad.\'94 \'93He isn\'92t very smart.\'94 \'93He\'92s smarter than he acts. The booze has him down. But he\'92s smart and he\'92s bad, I used to know him.\'94 \'93What do you want me to do.\'94 \'93Nothing, Suzy. Let me know about anything.\'94 \'93I\'92ll add up my stuff, Mr. John, and you can check it.\'94 \'93How are you going home?\'94 \'93I can get the boat up to Henry\'92s Dock and then get a rowboat from the cottage and row down and get the stuff. Mr. John, what will they do with Nickie?\'94 \'93That\'92s what I\'92m worried about.\'94 \'93They were talking about getting him put in the reform school.\'94 \'93I wish he hadn\'92t killed that buck.\'94 \'93So does he. He told me he was reading in a book about how you could crease something with a bullet and it wouldn\'92t do any harm. It would just stun it and Nickie wanted to try it. He said it was a damn fool thing to do. But he wanted to try it. Then he hit the buck and broke its neck. He felt awful about it. He felt awful about trying to crease it in the first place.\'94 \'93I know.\'94 \'93Then it must have been Evans found the meat where he had it hung up in the old springhouse. Anyway somebody took it.\'94 \'93Who could have told Evans?\'94 \'93I think it was just that boy of his found it. He trails around after Nick all the time. You never see him. He could have seen Nickie kill the buck. That boy\'92s no good, Mr. John. But he sure can trail around after anybody. He\'92s liable to be in this room right now.\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Mr. John. \'93But he could be listening outside.\'94 \'93I think he\'92s after Nick by now,\'94 the girl said. \'93Did you hear them say anything about him at the house?\'94 \'93They never mentioned him,\'94 Suzy said. \'93Evans must have left him home to do the chores. I don\'92t think we have to worry about him till they get home to Evans\'92s.\'94 \'93I can row up the lake to home this afternoon and get one of our kids to let me know if Evans hires anyone to do the chores. That will mean he\'92s turned that boy loose.\'94 \'93Both the men are too old to trail anybody.\'94 \'93But that boy\'92s terrible, Mr. John, and he knows too much about Nickie and where he would go. He\'92d find them and then bring the men up to them.\'94 \'93Come in back of the post office,\'94 Mr. John said. Back of the filing slits and the lockboxes and the registry book and the flat stamp books in place along with the cancellation stamps and their pads, with the General Delivery window down, so that Suzy felt again the glory of office that had been hers when she had helped out in the store, Mr. John said, \'93Where do you think they went, Suzy?\'94 \'93I wouldn\'92t know, true. Somewhere not too far or he wouldn\'92t take Littless. Somewhere that\'92s really good or he wouldn\'92t take her. They know about the trout for trout dinners, too, Mr. John.\'94 \'93That boy?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 \'93Maybe we better do something about the Evans boy.\'94 \'93I\'92d kill him. I\'92m pretty sure that\'92s why Littless went along. So Nickie wouldn\'92t kill him.\'94 \'93You fix it up so we keep track of them.\'94 \'93I will. But you have to think out something, Mr. John. Mrs. Adams, she\'92s just broke down. She just gets a sick headache like always. Here. You better take this letter.\'94 \'93You drop it in the box,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93That\'92s United States mail.\'94 \'93I wanted to kill them both last night when they were asleep.\'94 \'93No,\'94 Mr. John told her. \'93Don\'92t talk that way and don\'92t think that way.\'94 \'93Didn\'92t you ever want to kill anybody, Mr. John?\'94 \'93Yes. But it\'92s wrong and it doesn\'92t work out.\'94 \'93My father killed a man.\'94 \'93It didn\'92t do him any good.\'94 \'93He couldn\'92t help it.\'94 \'93You have to learn to help it,\'94 Mr. John said. \'93You get along now, Suzy.\'94 \'93I\'92ll see you tonight or in the morning,\'94 Suzy said. \'93I wish I still worked here, Mr. John.\'94 \'93So do I, Suzy. But Mrs. Packard doesn\'92t see it that way.\'94 \'93I know,\'94 said Suzy. \'93That\'92s the way everything is.\'94 Nick and his sister were lying on a browse bed under a lean-to that they had built together on the edge of the hemlock forest looking out over the slope of the hill to the cedar swamp and the blue hills beyond. \'93If it isn\'92t comfortable, Littless, we can feather in some more balsam on that hemlock. We\'92ll be tired tonight and this will do. But we can fix it up really good tomorrow.\'94 \'93It feels lovely,\'94 his sister said. \'93Lie loose and really feel it, Nickie.\'94 \'93It\'92s a pretty good camp,\'94 Nick said. \'93And it doesn\'92t show. We\'92ll only use little fires.\'94 \'93Would a fire show across to the hills?\'94 \'93It might,\'94 Nick said. \'93A fire shows a long way at night. But I\'92ll stake out a blanket behind it. That way it won\'92t show.\'94 \'93Nickie, wouldn\'92t it be nice if there wasn\'92t anyone after us and we were just here for fun?\'94 \'93Don\'92t start thinking that way so soon,\'94 Nick said. \'93We just started. Anyway if we were just here for fun we wouldn\'92t be here.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry, Nickie.\'94 \'93You don\'92t need to be,\'94 Nick told her. \'93Look, Littless, I\'92m going down to get a few trout for supper.\'94 \'93Can I come?\'94 \'93No. You stay here and rest. You had a tough day. You read a while or just be quiet.\'94 \'93It was tough in the slashings, wasn\'92t it? I thought it was really hard. Did I do all right?\'94 \'93You did wonderfully and you were wonderful making camp. But you take it easy now.\'94 \'93Have we got a name for this camp?\'94 \'93Let\'92s call it Camp Number One,\'94 Nick said. He went down the hill toward the creek and when he had come almost to the bank he stopped and cut himself a willow stick about four feet long and trimmed it, leaving the bark on. He could see the clear fast water of the stream. It was narrow and deep and the banks were mossy here before the stream entered the swamp. The dark clear water flowed fast and its rushing made bulges on the surface. Nick did not go close to it as he knew it flowed under the banks and he did not want to frighten a fish by walking on the bank. There must be quite a few up here in the open now, he thought. It\'92s pretty late in the summer. He took a coil of silk line out of a tobacco pouch he carried in the left breast pocket of his shirt and cut a length that was not quite as long as the willow stick and fastened it to the tip where he had notched it lightly. Then he fastened on a hook that he took from the pouch; then holding the shank of the hook he tested the pull of the line and the bend of the willow. He laid his rod down now and went back to where the trunk of a small birch tree, dead for several years, lay on its side in the grove of birches that bordered the cedars by the stream. He rolled the log over and found several earthworms under it. They were not big. But they were red and lively and he put them in a flat round tin with holes punched in the top that had once held Copenhagen snuff. He put some dirt over them and rolled the log back. This was the third year he had found bait at this same place and he had always replaced the log so that it was as he had found it. Nobody knows how big this creek is, he thought. It picks up an awful volume of water in that bad swamp up above. Now he looked up the creek and down it and up the hill to the hemlock forest where the camp was. Then he walked to where he had left the pole with the line and the hook and baited the hook carefully and spat on it for good luck. Holding the pole and the line with the baited hook in his right hand he walked very carefully and gently toward the bank of the narrow, heavy-flowing stream. It was so narrow here that his willow pole would have spanned it and as he came close to the bank he heard the turbulent rush of the water. He stopped by the bank, out of sight of anything in the stream, and took two lead shot, split down one side, out of the tobacco pouch and bent them on the line about a foot above the hook, clinching them with his teeth. He swung the hook on which the two worms curled out over the water and dropped it gently in so that it sank, swirling in the fast water, and he lowered the tip of the willow pole to let the current take the line and the baited hook under the bank. He felt the line straighten and a sudden heavy firmness. He swung up on the pole and it bent almost double in his hand. He felt the throbbing, jerking pull that did not yield as he pulled. Then it yielded, rising in the water with the line. There was a heavy wildness of movement in the narrow, deep current, and the trout was torn out of the water and, flopping in the air, sailed over Nick\'92s shoulder and onto the bank behind him. Nick saw him shine in the sun and then he found him where he was tumbling in the ferns. He was strong and heavy in Nick\'92s hands and he had a pleasant smell and Nick saw how dark his back was and how brilliant his spots were colored and how bright the edges of his fins were. They were white on the edge with a black line behind and then there was the lovely golden sunset color of his belly. Nick held him in his right hand and he could just reach around him. He\'92s pretty big for the skillet, he thought. But I\'92ve hurt him and I have to kill him. He knocked the trout\'92s head sharply against the handle of his hunting knife and laid him against the trunk of a birch tree. \'93Damn,\'94 he said. \'93He\'92s a perfect size for Mrs. Packard and her trout dinners. But he\'92s pretty big for Littless and me.\'94 I better go upstream and find a shallow and try to get a couple of small ones, he thought. Damn, didn\'92t he feel like something when I horsed him out though? They can talk all they want about playing them but people that have never horsed them out don\'92t know what they can make you feel. What if it only lasts that long? It\'92s the time when there\'92s no give at all and then they start to come and what they do to you on the way up and into the air. This is a strange creek, he thought. It\'92s funny when you have to hunt for small ones. He found his pole where he had thrown it. The hook was bent and he straightened it. Then he picked up the heavy fish and started up the stream. There\'92s one shallow, pebbly part just after she comes out of the upper swamp, he thought. I can get a couple of small ones there. Littless might not like this big one. If she gets homesick I\'92ll have to take her back. I wonder what those old boys are doing now? I don\'92t think that goddam Evans kid knows about this place. That son of a bitch. I don\'92t think anybody fished in here but Indians. You should have been an Indian, he thought. It would have saved you a lot of trouble. He made his way up the creek, keeping back from the stream but once stepping onto a piece of bank where the stream flowed underground. A big trout broke out in a violence that made a slashing wake in the water. He was a trout so big that it hardly seemed he could turn in the stream. \'93When did you come up?\'94 Nick said when the fish had gone under the bank again further upstream. \'93Boy, what a trout.\'94 At the pebbly shallow stretch he caught two small trout. They were beautiful fish, too, firm and hard and he gutted the three fish and tossed the guts into the stream, then washed the trout carefully in the cold water and then wrapped them in a small faded sugar sack from his pocket. It\'92s a good thing that girl likes fish, he thought. I