 and his sister sat on his lap and held her arms around his neck and rubbed her cropped head against his cheek. \'93I got them from the Queen of the Whores,\'94 she said. \'93And you know the name of the saloon?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93The Royal Ten Dollar Gold Piece Inn and Emporium.\'94 \'93What did you do there?\'94 \'93I was a whore\'92s assistant.\'94 \'93What\'92s a whore\'92s assistant do?\'94 \'93Oh, she carries the whore\'92s train when she walks and opens her carriage door and shows her to the right room. It\'92s like a lady in waiting I guess.\'94 \'93What\'92s she say to the whore?\'94 \'93She\'92ll say anything that comes into her mind as long as it\'92s polite.\'94 \'93Like what, brother?\'94 \'93Like, \'91Well ma\'92am, it must be pretty tiring on a hot day like today to be just a bird in a gilded cage.\'92 Things like that.\'94 \'93What\'92s the whore say?\'94 \'93She says, \'91Yes, indeedy. It sure is sweetness.\'92 Because this whore I was whore\'92s assistant to is of humble origin.\'94 \'93What kind of origin are you?\'94 \'93I\'92m the sister or the brother of a morbid writer and I\'92m delicately brought up. This makes me intensely desirable to the main whore and to all of her circle.\'94 \'93Did you get the knockout drops?\'94 \'93Of course. She said, \'91Hon, take these little old drops.\'92 \'91Thank you,\'92 I said! \'91Give my regards to your morbid brother and ask him to stop by the Emporium anytime he is at Sheboygan.\'92\'94 \'93Get off my lap,\'94 Nick said. \'93That\'92s just the way they talk in the Emporium,\'94 Littless said. \'93I have to get supper. Aren\'92t you hungry?\'94 \'93I\'92ll get supper.\'94 \'93No,\'94 Nick said. \'93You keep on talking.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you think we\'92re going to have fun, Nickie?\'94 \'93We\'92re having fun now.\'94 \'93Do you want me to tell you about the other thing I did for you?\'94 \'93You mean before you decided to do something practical and cut off your hair?\'94 \'93This was practical enough. Wait till you hear it. Can I kiss you while you\'92re making supper?\'94 \'93Wait a while and I\'92ll tell you. What was it you were going to do?\'94 \'93Well, I guess I was ruined morally last night when I stole the whiskey. Do you think you can be ruined morally by just one thing like that?\'94 \'93No. Anyway the bottle was open.\'94 \'93Yes. But I took the empty pint bottle and the quart bottle with the whiskey in it out to the kitchen and I poured the pint bottle full and some spilled on my hand and I licked it off and I thought that probably ruined me morally.\'94 \'93How\'92d it taste?\'94 \'93Awfully strong and funny and a little sick-making.\'94 \'93That wouldn\'92t ruin you morally.\'94 \'93Well, I\'92m glad because if I was ruined morally how could I exercise a good influence on you?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Nick said. \'93What was it you were going to do?\'94 He had his fire made and the skillet resting on it and he was laying strips of bacon in the skillet. His sister was watching and she had her hands folded across her knees and he watched her unclasp her hands and put one arm down and lean on it and put her legs out straight. She was practicing being a boy. \'93I\'92ve got to learn to put my hands right.\'94 \'93Keep them away from your head.\'94 \'93I know. It would be easy if there was some boy my own age to copy.\'94 \'93Copy me.\'94 \'93That would be natural, wouldn\'92t it? You won\'92t laugh, though?\'94 \'93Maybe.\'94 \'93Gee, I hope I won\'92t start to be a girl while we\'92re on the trip.\'94 \'93Don\'92t worry.\'94 \'93We have the same shoulders and the same kind of legs.\'94 \'93What was the other thing you were going to do?\'94 Nick was cooking the trout now. The bacon was curled brown on a fresh-cut chip of wood from the piece of fallen timber they were using for the fire and they both smelled the trout cooking in the bacon fat. Nick basted them and then turned them and basted them again. It was getting dark and he had rigged a piece of canvas behind the little fire so that it would not be seen. \'93What were you going to do?\'94 he asked again. Littless leaned forward and spat toward the fire. \'93How was that?\'94 \'93You missed the skillet anyway.\'94 \'93Oh, it\'92s pretty bad. I got it out of the Bible. I was going to take three spikes, one for each of them, and drive them into the temples of those two and that boy while they slept.\'94 \'93What were you going to drive them in with?\'94 \'93A muffled hammer.\'94 \'93How do you muffle a hammer?\'94 \'93I\'92d muffle it all right.\'94 \'93That nail thing\'92s pretty rough to try.\'94 \'93Well, that girl did it in the Bible and since I\'92ve seen armed men drunk and asleep and circulated among them at night and stolen their whiskey why shouldn\'92t I go the whole way, especially if I learned it in the Bible?\'94 \'93They didn\'92t have a muffled hammer in the Bible.\'94 \'93I guess I mixed it up with muffled oars.\'94 \'93Maybe. And we don\'92t want to kill anybody. That\'92s why you came along.\'94 \'93I know. But crime comes easy for you and me, Nickie. We\'92re different from the others. Then I thought if I was ruined morally I might as well be useful.\'94 \'93You\'92re crazy, Littless,\'94 he said. \'93Listen, does tea keep you awake?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know. I never had it at night. Only peppermint tea.\'94 \'93I\'92ll make it very weak and put canned cream in it.\'94 \'93I don\'92t need it, Nickie, if we\'92re short.\'94 \'93It will just give the milk a little taste.\'94 They were eating now. Nick had cut them each two slices of rye bread and he soaked one slice for each in the bacon fat in the skillet. They ate that and the trout that were crisp outside and cooked well and very tender inside. Then they put the trout skeletons in the fire and ate the bacon made in a sandwich with the other piece of bread, and then Littless drank the weak tea with the condensed milk in it and Nick tapped two slivers of wood into the holes he had punched in the can. \'93Did you have enough?\'94 \'93Plenty. The trout was wonderful and the bacon, too. Weren\'92t we lucky they had rye bread?\'94 \'93Eat an apple,\'94 he said. \'93Maybe we\'92ll have something good tomorrow. Maybe I should have made a bigger supper, Littless.\'94 \'93No. I had plenty.\'94 \'93You\'92re sure you\'92re not hungry?\'94 \'93No. I\'92m full. I\'92ve got some chocolate if you\'92d like some.\'94 \'93Where\'92d you get it?\'94 \'93From my savior.\'94 \'93Where?\'94 \'93My savior. Where I save everything.\'94 \'93Oh.\'94 \'93This is fresh. Some is the hard kind from the kitchen. We can start on that and save the other for sometime special. Look, my savior\'92s got a drawstring like a tobacco pouch. We can use it for nuggets and things like that. Do you think we\'92ll get out west, Nickie, on this trip?\'94 \'93I haven\'92t got it figured yet.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to get my savior packed full of nuggets worth sixteen dollars an ounce.\'94 Nick cleaned up the skillet and put the pack in at the head of the leanto. One blanket was spread over the browse bed and he put the other one on it and tucked it under on Littless\'92s side. He cleaned out the two-quart tin pail he\'92d made tea in and filled it with cold water from the spring. When he came back from the spring his sister was in the bed asleep, her head on the pillow she had made by rolling her blue jeans around her moccasins. He kissed her but she did not wake and he put on his old Mackinaw coat and felt in the packsack until he found the pint bottle of whiskey. He opened it and smelled it and it smelled very good. He dipped a half a cup of water out of the small pail he had brought from the spring and poured a little of the whiskey in it. Then he sat and sipped this very slowly, letting it stay under his tongue before he brought it slowly back over his tongue and swallowed it. He watched the small coals of the fire brighten with the light evening breeze and he tasted the whiskey and cold water and looked at the coals and thought. Then he finished the cup, dipped up some cold water and drank it and went to bed. The rifle was under his left leg and his head was on the good hard pillow his moccasins and the rolled trousers made and he pulled his side of the blanket tight around him and said his prayers and went to sleep. In the night he was cold and he spread his Mackinaw coat over his sister and rolled his back over closer to her so that there was more of his side of the blanket under him. He felt for the gun and tucked it under his leg again. The air was cold and sharp to breathe and he smelled the cut hemlock and balsam boughs. He had not realized how tired he was until the cold had waked him. Now he lay comfortable again feeling the warmth of his sister\'92s body against his back and he thought, I must take good care of her and keep her happy and get her back safely. He listened to her breathing and to the quiet of the night and then he was asleep again. It was just light enough to see the far hills beyond the swamp when he woke. He lay quietly and stretched the stiffness from his body. Then he sat up and pulled on his khaki trousers and put on his moccasins. He watched his sister sleeping with the collar of the warm Mackinaw coat under her chin and her high cheekbones and brown freckled skin light rose under the brown, her chopped-off hair showing the beautiful line of her head and emphasizing her straight nose and her close-set ears. He wished he could draw her face and he watched the way her long lashes lay on her cheeks. She looks like a small wild animal, he thought, and she sleeps like one. How would you say her head looks, he thought. I guess the nearest is that it looks as though someone had cut her hair off on a wooden block with an ax. It has a sort of a carved look. He loved his sister very much and she loved him too much. But, he thought, I guess those things straighten out. At least I hope so. There\'92s no sense waking anyone up, he thought. She must have been really tired if I\'92m as tired as I am. If we are all right here we are doing just what we should do: staying out of sight until things quiet down and that down-state man pulls out. I\'92ve got to feed her better, though. It\'92s a shame I couldn\'92t have outfitted really good. We\'92ve got a lot of things, though. The pack was heavy enough. But what we want to get today is berries. I better get a partridge or a couple if I can. We can get good mushrooms, too. We\'92ll have to be careful about the bacon but we won\'92t need it with the shortening. Maybe I fed her too light last night. She\'92s used to lots of milk, too, and sweet things. Don\'92t worry about it. We\'92ll feed good. It\'92s a good thing she likes trout. They were really good. Don\'92t worry about her. She\'92ll eat wonderfully. But, Nick, boy, you certainly didn\'92t feed her too much yesterday. Better to let her sleep than to wake her up now. There\'92s plenty for you to do. He started to get some things out of the pack very carefully and his sister smiled in her sleep. The brown skin came taut over her cheekbones when she smiled and the undercolor showed. She did not wake and he started to prepare to make breakfast and get the fire ready. There was plenty of wood cut and he built a very small fire and made tea while he waited to start breakfast. He drank his tea straight and ate three dried apricots and he tried to read in Lorna Doone. But he had read it and it did not have magic any more and he knew it was a loss on this trip. Late in the afternoon, when they had made camp, he had put some prunes in a tin pail to soak and he put them on the fire now to stew. In the pack he found the prepared buckwheat flour and he put it out with an enameled saucepan and a tin cup to mix the flour with water to make a batter. He had the tin of vegetable shortening and he cut a piece off the top of an empty flour sack and wrapped it around a cut stick and tied it tight with a piece of fish line. Littless had brought four old flour sacks and he was proud of her. He mixed the batter and put the skillet on the fire, greasing it with the shortening which he spread with the cloth on the stick. First it made the skillet shine darkly, then it sizzled and spat and he greased again and poured the batter smoothly and watched it bubble and then start to firm around the edges. He watched the rising and the forming of the texture and the gray color of the cake. He loosened it from the pan with a fresh clean chip and flipped it and caught it, the beautiful browned side up, the other sizzling. He could feel its weight but see it growing in buoyancy in the skillet. \'93Good morning,\'94 his sister said. \'93Did I sleep awfully late?\'94 \'93No, devil.\'94 She stood up with her shirt hanging down over her brown legs. \'93You\'92ve done everything.\'94 \'93No. I just started the cakes.\'94 \'93Doesn\'92t that one smell wonderful? I\'92ll go to the spring and wash and come and help.\'94 \'93Don\'92t wash in the spring.\'94 \'93I\'92m not white man,\'94 she said. She was gone behind the lean-to. \'93Where did you leave the soap?\'94 she asked. \'93It\'92s by the spring. There\'92s an empty lard bucket. Bring the butter, will you. It\'92s in the spring.\'94 \'93I\'92ll be right back.\'94 There was a half a pound of butter and she brought it wrapped in the oiled paper in the empty lard bucket. They ate the buckwheat cakes with butter and Log Cabin syrup out of a tin Log Cabin can. The top of the chimney unscrewed and the syrup poured from the chimney. They were both very hungry and the cakes were delicious with the butter melting on them and running down into the cut places with the syrup. They ate the prunes out of the tin cups and drank the juice. Then they drank tea from the same cups. \'93Prunes taste like a celebration,\'94 Littless said. \'93Think of that. How did you sleep, Nickie?\'94 \'93Good.\'94 \'93Thank you for putting the Mackinaw on me. Wasn\'92t it a lovely night, though?\'94 \'93Yes. Did you sleep all night?\'94 \'93I\'92m still asleep. Nickie, can we stay here always?\'94 \'93I don\'92t think so. You\'92d grow up and have to get married.\'94 \'93I\'92m going to get married to you anyway. I want to be your common-law wife. I read about it in the paper.\'94 \'93That\'92s where you read about the Unwritten Law.\'94 \'93Sure. I\'92m going to be your common-law wife under the Unwritten Law. Can\'92t I, Nickie?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93I will. I\'92ll surprise you. All you have to do is live a certain time as man and wife. I\'92ll get them to count this time now. It\'92s just like homesteading.\'94 \'93I won\'92t let you file.\'94 \'93You can\'92t help yourself. That\'92s the Unwritten Law. I\'92ve thought it out lots of times. I\'92ll get cards printed Mrs. Nick Adams, Cross Village, Michigan\'97common-law wife. I\'92ll hand these out to a few people openly each year until the time\'92s up.\'94 \'93I don\'92t think it would work.\'94 \'93I\'92ve got another scheme. We\'92ll have a couple of children while I\'92m a minor. Then you have to marry me under the Unwritten Law.\'94 \'93That\'92s not the Unwritten Law.\'94 \'93I get mixed up on it.\'94 \'93Anyway, nobody knows yet if it works.\'94 \'93It must,\'94 she said. \'93Mr. Thaw is counting on it.\'94 \'93Mr. Thaw might make a mistake.\'94 \'93Why Nickie, Mr. Thaw practically invented the Unwritten Law.\'94 \'93I thought it was his lawyer.\'94 \'93Well, Mr. Thaw put in the action anyway.\'94 \'93I don\'92t like Mr. Thaw,\'94 Nick Adams said. \'93That\'92s good. There\'92s things about him I don\'92t like either. But he certainly made the paper more interesting reading, didn\'92t he?\'94 \'93He gives the others something new to hate.\'94 \'93They hate Mr. Stanford White, too.\'94 \'93I think they\'92re jealous of both of them.\'94 \'93I believe that\'92s true, Nickie. Just like they\'92re jealous of us.\'94 \'93Think anybody is jealous of us now?\'94 \'93Not right now maybe. Our mother will think we\'92re fugitives from justice steeped in sin and iniquity. It\'92s a good thing she doesn\'92t know I got you that whiskey.\'94 \'93I tried it last night. It\'92s very good.\'94 \'93Oh, I\'92m glad. That\'92s the first whiskey I ever stole anywhere. Isn\'92t it wonderful that it\'92s good? I didn\'92t think anything about those people could be good.\'94 \'93I\'92ve got to think about them too much. Let\'92s not talk about them,\'94 Nick said. \'93All right. What are we going to do today?\'94 \'93What would you like to do?\'94 \'93I\'92d like to go to Mr. John\'92s store and get everything we need.\'94 \'93We can\'92t do that.\'94 \'93I know it. What do you plan to really do?\'94 \'93We ought to get some berries and I ought to get a partridge or some partridges. We\'92ve always got trout. But I don\'92t want you to get tired of trout.\'94 \'93Were you ever tired of trout?\'94 \'93No. But they say people get tired of them.\'94 \'93I wouldn\'92t get tired of them,\'94 Littless said. \'93You get tired of pike right away. But you never get tired of trout nor of perch. I know, Nickie. True.\'94 \'93You don\'92t get tired of walleyed pike either,\'94 Nick said. \'93Only of shovelnose. Boy, you sure get tired of them.\'94 \'93I don\'92t like the pitchfork bones,\'94 his sister said. \'93It\'92s a fish that surfeits you.\'94 \'93We\'92ll clean up here and I\'92ll find a place to cache the shells and we\'92ll make a trip for berries and try to get some birds.\'94 \'93I\'92ll bring two lard pails and a couple of the sacks,\'94 his sister said. \'93Littless,\'94 Nick said. \'93You remember about going to the bathroom, will you please?\'94 \'93Of course.\'94 \'93That\'92s important.\'94 \'93I know it. You remember, too.\'94 \'93I will.\'94 Nick went back into the timber and buried the carton of .22 long-rifles and the loose boxes of .22 shorts under the brown-needled floor at the base of a big hemlock. He put back the packed needles he had cut with his knife and made a small cut as far up as he could reach on the heavy bark of the tree. He took a bearing on the tree and then came out onto the hillside and walked down to the lean-to. It was a lovely morning now. The sky was high and clear blue and no clouds had come yet. Nick was happy with his sister and he thought, no matter how this thing comes out we might as well have a good happy time. He had already learned there was only one day at a time and that it was always the day you were in. It would be today until it was tonight and tomorrow would be today again. This was the main thing he had learned so far. Today was a good day and coming down to the camp with his rifle he was happy although their trouble was like a fishhook caught in his pocket that pricked him occasionally as he walked. They left the pack inside the lean-to. There were great odds against a bear bothering it in the daytime because any bear would be down below feeding on berries around the swamp. But Nick buried the bottle of whiskey up behind the spring. Littless was not back yet and Nick sat down on the log of the fallen tree they were using for firewood and checked his rifle. They were going after partridges so he pulled out the tube of the magazine and poured the long-rifle cartridges into his hand and then put them into a chamois pouch and filled the magazine with .22 shorts. They made less noise and would not tear the meat up if he could not get head shots. He was all ready now and wanted to start. Where\'92s that girl anyway, he thought. Then he thought, don\'92t get excited. You told her to take her time. Don\'92t get nervous. But he was nervous and it made him angry at himself. \'93Here I am,\'94 his sister said. \'93I\'92m sorry that I took so long. I went too far away, I guess.\'94 \'93You\'92re fine,\'94 Nick said. \'93Let\'92s go. You have the pails?\'94 \'93Uh huh, and covers, too.\'94 They started down across the hill to the creek. Nick looked carefully up the stream and along the hillside. His sister watched him. She had the pails in one of the sacks and carried it slung over her shoulder by the other sack. \'93Aren\'92t you taking a pole, Nickie?\'94 she asked him. \'93No. I\'92ll cut one if we fish.\'94 He moved ahead of his sister, holding the rifle in one hand, keeping a little way away from the stream. He was hunting now. \'93It\'92s a strange creek,\'94 his sister said. \'93It\'92s the biggest small stream I\'92ve ever known,\'94 Nick told her. \'93It\'92s deep and scary for a little stream.\'94 \'93It keeps having new springs,\'94 Nick said. \'93And it digs under the bank and it digs down. It\'92s awful cold water, Littless. Feel it.\'94 \'93Gee,\'94 she said. It was numbing cold. \'93The sun warms it a little,\'94 Nick said. \'93But not much. We\'92ll hunt along easy. There\'92s a berry patch down below.\'94 They went along down the creek. Nick was studying the banks. He had seen a mink\'92s track and shown it to his sister and they had seen tiny rubycrowned kinglets that were hunting insects and let the boy and girl come close as they moved sharply and delicately in the cedars. They had seen cedar waxwings so calm and gentle and distinguished moving in their lovely elegance with the magic wax touches on their wing coverts and their tails, and Littless had said, \'93They\'92re the most beautiful, Nickie. There couldn\'92t be more simply beautiful birds.\'94 \'93They\'92re built like your face,\'94 he said. \'93No, Nickie. Don\'92t make fun. Cedar waxwings make me so proud and happy that I cry.\'94 \'93When they wheel and light and then move so proud and friendly and gently,\'94 Nick said. They had gone on and suddenly Nick had raised the rifle and shot before his sister could see what he was looking at. Then she heard the sound of a big bird tossing and beating its wings on the ground. She saw Nick pumping the gun and shoot twice more and each time she heard another pounding of wings in the willow brush. Then there was the whirring noise of wings as large brown birds burst out of the willows and one bird flew only a little way and lit in the willows and with its crested head on one side looked down, bending the collar of feathers on his neck where the other birds were still thumping. The bird looking down from the red willow brush was beautiful, plump, heavy and looked so stupid with his head turned down and as Nick raised his rifle slowly, his sister whispered, \'93No, Nickie. Please no. We\'92ve got plenty.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93You want to take him?\'94 \'93No, Nickie. No.\'94 Nick went forward into the willows and picked up the three grouse and batted their heads against the butt of the rifle stock and laid them out on the moss. His sister felt them, warm and 7ullbreasted and beautifully feathered. \'93Wait till we eat them,\'94 Nick said. He was very happy. \'93I\'92m sorry for them now,\'94 his sister said. \'93They were enjoying the morning just like we were.\'94 She looked up at the grouse still in the tree. \'93It does look a little silly still staring down,\'94 she said. \'93This time of year the Indians call them fool hens. After they\'92ve been hunted they get smart. They\'92re not the real fool hens. Those never get smart. They\'92re willow grouse. These are ruffled grouse.\'94 \'93I hope we\'92ll get smart,\'94 his sister said. \'93Tell him to go away, Nickie.\'94 \'93You tell him.\'94 \'93Go away, partridge.\'94 The grouse did not move. Nick raised the rifle and the grouse looked at him. Nick knew he could not shoot the bird without making his sister sad and he made a noise blowing out so his tongue rattled and lips shook like a grouse bursting from cover and the bird looked at him fascinated. \'93We better not annoy him,\'94 Nick said. \'93I\'92m sorry, Nickie,\'94 his sister said. \'93He is stupid.\'94 \'93Wait till we eat them,\'94 Nick told her. \'93You\'92ll see why we hunt them.\'94 \'93Are they out of season, too?\'94 \'93Sure. But they are full grown and nobody but us would ever hunt them. I kill plenty of great horned owls and a great homed owl will kill a partridge every day if he can. They hunt all the time and they kill all the good birds.\'94 \'93He certainly could kill that one easy,\'94 his sister said. \'93I don\'92t feel bad any more. Do you want a bag to carry them in?\'94 \'93I\'92ll draw them and then pack them in the bag with some ferns. It isn\'92t so far to the berries now.\'94 They sat against one of the cedars and Nick opened the birds and took out their warm entrails and feeling the inside of the birds hot on his right hand he found the edible pans of the giblets and cleaned them and then washed them in the stream. When the birds were cleaned he smoothed their feathers and wrapped them in ferns and put them in the flour sack. He tied the mouth of the flour sack and two comers with a piece of fish line and slung it over his shoulder and then went back to the stream and dropped the entrails in and tossed some bright pieces of lung in to see the trout rise in the rapid heavy flow of the water. \'93They\'92d make good bait but we don\'92t need bait now,\'94 he said. \'93Our trout are all in the stream and we\'92ll take them when we need them.\'94 \'93This stream would make us rich if it was near home,\'94 his sister said. \'93It would be fished out then. This is the last really wild stream there is except in another awful country to get to beyond the foot of the lake. I never brought anybody here to fish.\'94 \'93Who ever fishes it?\'94 \'93Nobody I know.\'94 \'93Is it a virgin stream?\'94 \'93No. Indians fish it. But they\'92re gone now since they quit cutting hemlock bark and the camps closed down.\'94 \'93Does the Evans boy know?\'94 \'93Not him,\'94 Nick said. But then he thought about it and it made him feel sick. He could see the Evans boy. \'93What\'92re you thinking, Nickie?\'94 \'93I wasn\'92t thinking.\'94 \'93You were thinking. You tell me. We\'92re partners.\'94 \'93He might know,\'94 Nick said. \'93Goddam it. He might know.\'94 \'93But you don\'92t know that he knows?\'94 \'93No. That\'92s the trouble. If I did I\'92d get out.\'94 \'93Maybe he\'92s back at camp now,\'94 his sister said. \'93Don\'92t talk that way. Do you want to bring him?\'94 \'93No,\'94 she said. \'93Please, Nickie, I\'92m sorry I brought it up.\'94 \'93I\'92m not,\'94 Nick said. \'93I\'92m grateful. I knew it anyway. Only I\'92d stopped thinking about it. I have to think about things now the rest of my life.\'94 \'93You always thought about things.\'94 \'93Not like this.\'94 \'93Let\'92s go down and get the berries anyway,\'94 Littless said. \'93There isn\'92t anything we can do now to help, is there?\'94 \'93No,\'94 Nick said. \'93We\'92ll pick the berries and get back to camp.\'94 But Nick was trying to accept it now and think his way all the way through it. He must not get in a panic about it. Nothing had changed. Things were just as they were when he had decided to come here and let things blow over. The Evans boy could have followed him here before. But it was very unlikely. He could have followed him one time when he had gone in from the road through the Hodges\'92 place, but it was doubtful. Nobody had been fishing the stream. He could be sure of that. But the Evans boy did not care about fishing. \'93All that bastard cares about is trailing me,\'94 he said. \'93I know it, Nickie.\'94 \'93This is three times he\'92s made trouble.\'94 \'93I know it, Nickie. But don\'92t you kill him.\'94 That\'92s why she came along, Nick thought. That\'92s why she\'92s here. I can\'92t do it while she\'92s along. \'93I know I mustn\'92t kill him,\'94 he said. \'93There\'92s nothing we can do now. Let\'92s not talk about it.\'94 \'93As long as you don\'92t kill him,\'94 his sister said. \'93There\'92s nothing we can\'92t get out of and nothing that won\'92t blow over.\'94 \'93Let\'92s get back to camp,\'94 Nick said. \'93Without the berries?\'94 \'93We\'92ll get the berries another day.\'94 \'93Are you nervous, Nickie?\'94 \'93Yes. I\'92m sorry.\'94 \'93But what good will we be back at camp?\'94 \'93We\'92ll know quicker.\'94 \'93Can\'92t we just go along the way we were going?\'94 \'93Not now. I\'92m not scared, Littless. And don\'92t you be scared. But something\'92s made me nervous.\'94 Nick had cut up away from the stream into the edge of the timber and they were walking in the shade of the trees. They would come onto the camp now from above. From the timber they approached the camp carefully. Nick went ahead with the rifle. The camp had not been visited. \'93You stay here,\'94 Nick told his sister. \'93I\'92m going to have a look beyond.\'94 He left the sack with the birds and the berry pails with Littless and went well upstream. As soon as he was out of sight of his sister he changed the .22 shorts in the rifle for the long-rifles. I won\'92t kill him, he thought, but anyway it\'92s the right thing to do. He made a careful search of the country. He saw no sign of anyone and he went down to the stream and then downstream and back up to the camp. \'93I\'92m sorry I was nervous, Littless,\'94 he said. \'93We might as well have a good lunch and then we won\'92t have to worry about a fire showing at night.\'94 \'93I\'92m worried now, too,\'94 she said. \'93Don\'92t you be worried. It\'92s just like it was before.\'94 \'93But he drove us back from getting the berries without him even being here.\'94 \'93I know. But he\'92s not been here. Maybe he\'92s never even been to this creek ever. Maybe we\'92ll never see him again.\'94 \'93He makes me scared, Nickie, worse when he\'92s not here than when he\'92s here.\'94 \'93I know. But there isn\'92t any use being scared.\'94 \'93What are we going to do?\'94 \'93Well, we better wait to cook until night.\'94 \'93Why did you change?\'94 \'93He won\'92t be around here at night. He can\'92t come through the swamp in the dark. We don\'92t have to worry about him early in the mornings and late in the evening nor in the dark. We\'92ll have to be like the deer and only be out then. We\'92ll lay up in the daytime.\'94 \'93Maybe he\'92ll never come.\'94 \'93Sure. Maybe.\'94 \'93But I can stay though, can\'92t I?\'94 \'93I ought to get you home.\'94 \'93No. Please, Nickie. Who\'92s going to keep you from killing him then?\'94 \'93Listen, Littless, don\'92t ever talk about killing and remember I never talked about killing. There isn\'92t any killing nor ever going to be any.\'94 \'93True?\'94 \'93True.\'94 \'93I\'92m so glad.\'94 \'93Don\'92t even be that. Nobody ever talked about it.\'94 \'93 All right. I never thought about it nor spoke about it.\'94 \'93Me either.\'94 \'93Of course you didn\'92t.\'94 \'93I never even thought about it.\'94 No, he thought. You never even thought about it. Only all day and all night. But you mustn\'92t think about it in front of her because she can feel it because she is your sister and you love each other. \'93Are you hungry, Littless?\'94 \'93Not really.\'94 \'93Eat some of the hard chocolate and I\'92ll get some fresh water from the spring.\'94 \'93I don\'92t have to have anything.\'94 They looked across to where the big white clouds of the eleven o\'92clock breeze were coming up over the blue hills beyond the swamp. The sky was a high clear blue and the clouds came up white and detached themselves from behind the hills and moved high in the sky as the breeze freshened and the shadows of the clouds moved over the swamp and across the hillside. The wind blew in the trees now and was cool as they lay in the shade. The water from the spring was cold and fresh in the tin pail and the chocolate was not quite bitter but was hard and crunched as they chewed it. \'93It\'92s as good as the water in the spring where we were when we first saw them,\'94 his sister said. \'93It tastes even better after the chocolate.\'94 \'93We can cook if you\'92re hungry.\'94 \'93I\'92m not if you\'92re not.\'94 \'93I\'92m always hungry. I was a fool not to go on and get the berries.\'94 \'93No. You came back to find out.\'94 \'93Look, Littless. I know a good place back by the slashing we came through where we can get berries. I\'92ll cache everything and we can go in there through the timber all the way and pick a couple of pails full and then we\'92ll have them ahead for tomorrow. It isn\'92t a bad walk.\'94 \'93All right. But I\'92m fine.\'94 \'93Aren\'92t you hungry?\'94 \'93No. Not at all now after the chocolate. I\'92d love to just stay and read. We had a nice walk when we were hunting.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 Nick said. \'93Are you tired from yesterday?\'94 \'93Maybe a little.\'94 \'93We\'92ll take it easy. I\'92ll read Wuthering Heights.\'94 \'93Is it too old to read out loud to me?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Will you read it?\'94 \'93Sure.\'94 An African Story HE WAS WAITING FORTHE MOON TO RISE and he felt Kibo\'92s hair rise under his hand as he stroked him to be quiet and they both watched and listened as the moon came up and gave them shadows. His arm was around the dog\'92s neck now and he could feel him shivering. All of the night sounds had stopped. They did not hear the elephant and David did not see him until the dog turned his head and seemed to settle into David. Then the elephant\'92s shadow covered them and he moved past making no noise at all and they smelled him in the light wind that came down from the mountain. He smelled strong but old and sour and when he was past David saw that the left tusk was so long it seemed to reach the ground. They waited but no other elephants came by and then David and the dog started off running in the moonlight. The dog kept close behind him and when David stopped the dog pressed his muzzle into the back of his knee. David had to see the bull again and they came up on him at the edge of the forest. He was traveling toward the mountain and slowly moving into the steady night breeze. David came close enough to see him cut off the moon again and to smell the sour oldness but he could not see the right tusk. He was afraid to work closer with the dog and he took him back with the wind and pushed him down against the base of a tree and tried to make him understand. He thought the dog would stay and he did but when David moved up toward the bulk of the elephant again he felt the wet muzzle against the hollow of his knee. The two of them followed the elephant until he came to an opening in the trees. He stood there moving his huge ears. His bulk was in the shadow but the moonlight would be on his head. David reached behind him and closed the dog\'92s jaws gently with his hand and then moved softly and unbreathing to his right along the edge of the night breeze, feeling it on his cheek, edging with it, never letting it get between him and the bulk until he could see the elephant\'92s head and the great ears slowly moving. The right tusk was as thick as his own thigh and it curved down almost to the ground. He and Kibo moved back, the wind on his neck now, and they backtracked out of the forest and into the open park country. The dog was ahead of him now and he stopped where David had left the two hunting spears by the trail when they had followed the elephant. He swung them over his shoulder in their thong and leather cup harness and, with his best spear that he had kept with him all the time in his hand, they started on the trail for the shamba. The moon was high now and he wondered why there was no drumming from the shamba. Something was strange if his father was there and there was no drumming. David had felt the tiredness as soon as they had picked up the trail again. For a long time he had been fresher and in better shape than the two men and impatient with their slow trailing and the regular halts his father made each hour on the hour. He could have moved ahead much faster than Juma and his father but when he started to tire they were the same as ever and at noon they took only the usual five-minute rest and he had seen that Juma was increasing the pace a little. Perhaps he wasn\'92t. Perhaps it had only seemed faster but the elephant dung was fresher now although it was not warm yet to the touch. Juma gave him the rifle to carry after they came upon the last pile of dung but after an hour he looked at him and took it back.They had been climbing steadily across a slope of the mountain but now the trail went down and from a gap in the forest he saw broken country ahead. \'93Here\'92s where the tough part starts, Davey,\'94 his father said. It was then he knew that he should have been sent back to the shamba once he had put them on the trail. Juma had known it for a long time. His father knew it now and there was nothing to be done. It was another of his mistakes and there was nothing to do now except gamble. David looked down at the big flattened circle of the print of the elephant\'92s foot and saw where the bracken had been pressed down and where a broken stem of a weed was drying. Juma picked it up and looked at the sun. Juma handed the broken weed to David\'92s father and his father rolled it in his fingers. David noticed the white flowers that were drooped and dying. But they still had not dried in the sun nor shed their petals. \'93It\'92s going to be a bitch,\'94 his father said. \'93Let\'92s get going.\'94 Late in the afternoon they were still tracking through the broken country. He had been sleepy now for a long time and as he watched the two men he knew that sleepiness was his real enemy and he followed their pace and tried to move through and out of the sleep that deadened him. The two men relieved each other tracking on the hour and the one who was in second place looked back at him at regular intervals to check if he was with them. When they made a dry camp at dark in the forest he went to sleep as soon as he sat down and woke with Juma holding his moccasins and feeling his bare feet for blisters. His father had spread his coat over him and was sitting by him with a piece of cold cooked meat and two biscuits. He offered him a water bottle with cold tea. \'93He\'92ll have to feed, Davey,\'94 his father said. \'93Your feet are in good shape. They\'92re as sound as Juma\'92s. Eat this slowly and drink some tea and go to sleep again. We haven\'92t any problems.\'94 \'93I\'92m sorry I was so sleepy.\'94 \'93You and Kibo hunted and traveled all last night. Why shouldn\'92t you be sleepy? You can have a little more meat if you want it.\'94 \'93I\'92m not hungry.\'94 \'93Good. We\'92re good for three days. We\'92ll hit water again tomorrow. Plenty of creeks come off the mountain.\'94 \'93Where\'92s he going?\'94 \'93Juma thinks he knows.\'94 \'93Isn\'92t it bad?\'94 \'93Not too bad, Davey.\'94 \'93I\'92m going back to sleep,\'94 David had said. \'93I don\'92t need your coat.\'94 \'93Juma and I are all right,\'94 his father said. \'93I always sleep warm you know.\'94 David was asleep even before his father said good night. Then he woke once with the moonlight on his face and he thought of the elephant with his great ears moving as he stood in the forest, his head hung down with the weight of the tusks. David thought then in the night that the hollow way he felt as he remembered him was from waking hungry. But it was not and he found that out in the next three days. The next day was very bad because long before noon he knew that it was not just the need for sleep that made the difference between a boy and men. For the first three hours he was fresher than they were and he asked Juma for the .303 rifle to carry but Juma shook his head. He did not smile and he had always been David\'92s best friend and had taught him to hunt. He offered it to me yesterday, David thought, and I\'92m in better shape today than I was then. He was, too, but by ten o\'92clock he knew the day would be as bad or worse than the day before. It was as silly for him to think that he could trail with his father as to think he could fight with him. He knew too that it was not just that they were men. They were professional hunters and he knew now that was why Juma would not even waste a smile. They knew everything the elephant had done, pointed out the signs of it to each other without speaking, and when the tracking became difficult his father always yielded to Juma. When they stopped to fill the water bottles at a stream his father said, \'93Just last the day out, Davey.\'94 Then when they were past the broken country and climbing toward the forest the tracks of the elephant turned off to the right onto an old elephant trail. He saw his father and Juma talking and when he got up to them Juma was looking back over the way they had come and then at a far distant stony island of hills in the dry country and seemed to be taking a bearing of this against the peaks of three far blue hills on the horizon. \'93Juma knows where he\'92s going now,\'94 his father explained. \'93He thought he knew before but then he dropped down into this stuff.\'94 He looked back at the country they had come through all day. \'93Where he\'92s headed now is pretty good going but we\'92ll have to climb.\'94 They climbed until it was dark and then made another dry camp. David killed two spur fowl with his slingshot out of a small flock that had walked across the trail just before the sunset. The birds had come into the old elephant trail to dust, walking neatly and plumply, and when the pebble broke the back of one and the bird began to jerk and toss with its wings thumping, another bird ran forward to peck at it and David pouched another pebble and pulled it back and sent it against the ribs of the second bird. As he ran forward to put his hand on it the other birds whirred off. Juma had looked back and smiled this time and David picked up the two birds, warm and plump and smoothly feathered, and knocked their heads against the handle of his hunting knife. Now where they were camped for the night his father said, \'93I\'92ve never seen that type of francolin quite so high. You did very well to get a double on them.\'94 Juma cooked the birds spitted on a stick over the coals of a very small fire. His father drank a whiskey and water from the cup top on his flask as they lay and watched Juma cook. Afterward Juma gave them each a breast with the heart in it and ate the two necks and backs and the legs himself. \'93It makes a great difference, Davey,\'94 his father said. \'93We\'92re very well off on rations now.\'94 \'93How far are we behind him?\'94 David asked. \'93We\'92re quite close,\'94 his father said. \'93It depends on whether he travels when the moon comes up. It\'92s an hour later tonight and two hours later than when you found him.\'94 \'93Why does Juma think he knows where he\'92s going?\'94 \'93He wounded him and killed his askari not too far from here.\'94 \'93When?\'94 \'93Five years ago, he says. That may mean anytime. When you were still a toto he says.\'94 \'93Has he been alone since then?\'94 \'93He says so. He hasn\'92t seen him. Only heard of him.\'94 \'93How big does he say he is?\'94 \'93Close to two hundred. Bigger than anything I\'92ve ever seen. He says there\'92s only been one greater elephant and he came from near here too.\'94 \'93I\'92d better get to sleep,\'94 David said. \'93I hope I\'92ll be better tomorrow.\'94 \'93You were splendid today,\'94 his father said. \'93I was very proud of you. So was Juma.\'94 In the night when he woke after the moon was up he was sure they were not proud of him except perhaps for his dexterity in killing the two birds. He had found the elephant at night and followed him to see that he had both of his tusks and then returned to find the two men and put them on the trail. David knew they were proud of that. But once the deadly following started he was useless to them and a danger to their success just as Kibo had been to him when he had gone up close to the elephant in the night, and he knew they must each have hated themselves for not having sent him back when there was time. The tusks of the elephant weighed two hundred pounds apiece. Ever since these tusks had grown beyond their normal size the elephant had been hunted for them and now the three of them would kill him for them. David was sure that they would kill him now because he, David, had lasted through the day and kept up after the pace had destroyed him by noon. So they probably were proud of him doing that. But he had brought nothing useful to the hunt and they would have been far better off without him. Many times during the day he had wished that he had never betrayed the elephant and in the afternoon he remembered wishing that he had never seen him. Awake in the moonlight he knew that was not true. The next morning they were following the spoor of the elephant on an old elephant trail that was a hard-packed worn road through the forest. It looked as though elephants had traveled it ever since the lava had cooled from the mountain and the trees had first grown tall and close. Juma was very confident and they moved fast. Both his father and Juma seemed very sure of themselves and the going on the elephant road was so easy that Juma gave him the .303 to carry as they went on through the broken light of the forest. Then they lost the trail in smoking piles of fresh dung and the flat round prints of a herd of elephants that had come onto the elephant road from the heavy forest on the left of the trail. Juma had taken the .303 from David angrily. It was afternoon before they worked up to the herd and around it, seeing the gray bulks through the trees and the movement of the big ears and the searching trunks coiling and uncoiling, hearing the crash of branches broken, the crash of trees pushed over, the rumbling in the bellies of the elephants and the slap and thud of the dung falling. They had found the trail of the old bull finally and when it turned off onto a smaller elephant road Juma had looked at David\'92s father and grinned showing his filed teeth and his father had nodded his head. They looked as though they had a dirty secret, just as they had looked when he had found them that night at the shamba. It was not very long before they came on the secret. It was off to the right in the forest and the tracks of the old bull led to it. It was a skull as high as David\'92s chest and white from the sun and the rain. There was a deep depression in the forehead and a ridge ran from between the bare white eye sockets and flared out in empty broken holes where the tusks had been chopped away. Juma pointed out where the great elephant they were trailing had stood while he looked down at the skull and where his trunk had moved it a little way from the place it had rested on the ground and where the points of his tusks had touched the ground beside it. He showed David the single hole in the big depression in the white bone of the forehead and then the four holes close together in the bone around the earhole. He grinned at David and at his father and took a .303 solid from his pocket and fitted the nose into the hole in the bone of the forehead. \'93Here is where Juma wounded the big bull,\'94 his father said. \'93This was his askari. His friend, really, because he was a big bull too. He charged and Juma knocked him down and finished him in the ear.\'94 Juma was pointing out the scattered bones and how the big bull had walked among them. Juma and David\'92s father were both very pleased with what they had found. \'93How long do you suppose he and his friend had been together?\'94 David asked his father. \'93I haven\'92t the faintest idea,\'94 his father said. \'93Ask Juma.\'94 \'93You ask him, please.\'94 His father and Juma spoke together and Juma had looked at David and laughed. \'93Probably four or five times your life, he says,\'94 David\'92s father told him. \'93He doesn\'92t know or care really.\'94 I care, David thought. I saw him in the moonlight and he was alone but I had Kibo. Kibo has me too. The bull wasn\'92t doing any harm and now we\'92ve tracked him to where he came to see his dead friend and now we\'92re going to kill him. It\'92s my fault. I betrayed him. Now Juma had worked out the trail and motioned to his father and they started on. My father doesn\'92t need to kill elephants to live, David thought. Juma would not have found him if I had not seen him. He had his chance at him and all he did was wound him and kill his friend. Kibo and I found him and I never should have told them and I should have kept him secret and had him always and let them stay drunk at the beer shamba. Juma was so drunk we could not wake him. I\'92m going to keep everything a secret always. I\'92ll never tell them anything again. If they kill him Juma will drink his share of the ivory or just buy himself another goddamn wife. Why didn\'92t you help the elephant when you could? All you had to do was not go on the second day. No, that wouldn\'92t have stopped them. Juma would have gone on. You never should have told them. Never, never tell them. Try and remember that. Never tell anyone anything ever. Never tell anyone anything again. His father waited for him to come up and said very gently, \'93He rested here. He\'92s not traveling as he was. We\'92ll be up on him anytime now.\'94 \'93Fuck elephant hunting,\'94 David had said very quietly. \'93What\'92s that?\'94 his father asked. \'93Fuck elephant hunting,\'94 David said softly. \'93Be careful you don\'92t fuck it up,\'94 his father had said to him and looked at him flatly. That\'92s one thing, David had thought. He\'92s not stupid. He knows all about it now and he will never trust me again. That\'92s good. I don\'92t want him to because I\'92ll never ever tell him or anybody anything again, never anything again. Never ever never. In the morning he was on the far slope of the mountain again. The elephant was no longer traveling as he had been but was moving aimlessly now, feeding occasionally and David had known they were getting close to him. He tried to remember how he had felt. He had no love for the elephant yet. He must remember that. He had only a sorrow that had come from his own tiredness that had brought an understanding of age. Through being too young, he had learned how it must be to be too old. He was lonesome for Kibo and thinking of how Juma killing the elephant\'92s friend had turned him against Juma and made the elephant his brother. He knew then how much it meant to him to have seen the elephant in the moonlight and to have followed him and come close to him in the clearing so that he had seen the great tusks. But he did not know that nothing would ever be as good as that again. Now he knew they would kill the elephant and there was nothing he could do about it. He had betrayed the elephant when he had gone back to tell them at the shamba. They would kill me and they would kill Kibo if we had ivory, he had thought, and known it was untrue. Probably the elephant is going to find where he was born and they\'92ll kill him there. That\'92s all they\'92d need to make it perfect. They\'92d like to have killed him where they killed his friend. That would be a big joke. That would have pleased them. The goddamned friend killers. They had moved to the edge of thick cover now and the elephant was close ahead. David could smell him and they could all hear him pulling down branches and the snapping that they made. His father put his hand on David\'92s shoulder to move him back and have him wait outside and then he took a big pinch of ashes from the pouch in his pocket and tossed it in the air. The ash barely slanted toward them as it fell and his father nodded at Juma and bent down to follow him into the thick cover. David watched their backs and their asses go in and out of sight. He could not hear them move. David had stood still and listened to the elephant feeding. He could smell him as strongly as he had the night in the moonlight when he had worked up close to him and had seen his wonderful tusks. Then as he stood there it was silent and he could not smell the elephant. Then there had been a high squealing and smashing and a shot by the .303, then the heavy rocking double report of his father\'92s .450, then the smashing and crashing had gone on going steadily away and he had gone into the heavy growth and found Juma shaken and bleeding from his forehead all down over his face and his father white and angry. \'93He went for Juma and knocked him over,\'94 his father had said. \'93Juma hit him in the head.\'94 \'93Where did you hit him?\'94 \'93Where I fucking well could,\'94 his father had said. \'93Get on the blood spoor.\'94 There was plenty of blood. One stream as high as David\'92s head that had squirted bright on trunks and leaves and vines and another much lower that was dark and foul with stomach content. \'93Lung and gut shot,\'94 his father said. \'93We\'92ll find him down or anchored\'97I hope the hell,\'94 he added. They found him anchored, in such suffering and despair that he could no longer move. He had crashed through the heavy cover where he had been feeding and crossed a path of open forest and David and his father ran along the heavily splashed blood trail. Then the elephant had gone on into thick forest and David had seen him ahead standing gray and huge against the trunk of a tree. David could only see his stern and then his father moved ahead and he followed and they came alongside the elephant as though he was a ship and David saw the blood coming from his flanks and running down his sides and then his father raised his rifle and fired and the elephant turned his head with the great tusks moving heavy and slow and looked at them and when his father fired the second barrel the elephant seemed to sway like a felled tree and came smashing down toward them. But he was not dead. He had been anchored and now he was down with his shoulder broken. He did not move but his eye was alive and looked at David. He had very long eyelashes and his eye was the most alive thing David had ever seen. \'93Shoot him in the earhole with the three oh three,\'94 his father said. \'93Go on.\'94 \'93You shoot him,\'94 David had said. Juma had come up limping and bloody, the skin of his forehead hanging down over his left eye, the bone of his nose showing and one ear torn and had taken the rifle from David without speaking and pushed the muzzle almost into the earhole and fired twice, jerking the bolt and driving it forward angrily. The eye of the elephant had opened wide on the first shot and then started to glaze and blood came out of the ear and ran in two bright streams down the wrinkled gray hide. It was different colored blood and David had thought I must remember that and he had but it had never been of any use to him. Now all the dignity and majesty and all the beauty were gone from the elephant and he was a huge wrinkled pile. \'93Well, we got him, Davey, thanks to you,\'94 his father had said. \'93Now we\'92d better get a fire going so I can put Juma back together again. Come here, you bloody Humpty Dumpty. Those tusks will keep.\'94 Juma had come to him grinning, bringing the tail of the elephant that had no hairs on it at all. They had made a dirty joke and then his father had begun to speak rapidly in Swahili. How far to water? How far will you have to go to get people to get those tusks out of here? How are you, you worthless old pig fucker? What have you broken? With the answers known his father had said, \'93You and I will go back to get the packs where we dropped them. Juma can get wood and have the fire ready. The medical kit is in my pack. We have to get the packs before it\'92s dark. He won\'92t infect. It\'92s not like claw wounds. Let\'92s go.\'94 That evening as David had sat by the fire he had looked at Juma with his stitched-up face and his broken ribs and wondered if the elephant had recognized him when he had tried to kill him. He hoped he had. The elephant was his hero now as his father had been for a long time and he had thought, I didn\'92t believe he could do it when he was so old and tired. He would have killed Juma, too. But he didn\'92t look at me as though he wanted to kill me. He only looked sad the same way I felt. He visited his old friend on the day he died. David remembered how the elephant lost all dignity as soon as his eye had ceased to be alive and how when his father and he had returned with the packs the elephant had already started to swell, even in the cool evening. There was no more true elephant; only the gray wrinkled swelling dead body and the huge mottled brown and yellow tusks that they had killed him for. The tusks were stained with dried blood and he scraped some off with his thumbnail like a dried piece of sealing wax and put it in the pocket of his shirt. That was all he took from the elephant except the beginning of the knowledge of loneliness. After the butchery his father tried to talk to him that night by the fire. \'93He was a murderer you know, Davey,\'94 he had said. \'93Juma says nobody knows how many people he has killed.\'94 \'93They were all trying to kill him, weren\'92t they?\'94 \'93Naturally,\'94 his father had said, \'93with that pair of tusks.\'94 \'93How could he be a murderer then?\'94 \'93Just as you like,\'94 his father had said. \'93I\'92m sorry you got so mixed up about him.\'94 \'93I wish he\'92d killed Juma,\'94 David said. \'93I think that\'92s carrying it a little far,\'94 his father said. \'93Juma\'92s your friend, you know.\'94 \'93Not any more.\'94 \'93No need to tell him so.\'94 \'93He knows it,\'94 David had said. \'93I think you misjudge him,\'94 his father said and they had left it there. Then when they were finally back safely with the tusks after all the things that had happened and the tusks were propped against the wall of the stick and mud house, leaning there with their points touching, the tusks so tall and thick that no one could believe them even when they touched them and no one, not even his father, could reach to the top of the bend where they curved in for the points to meet, there when Juma and his father and he were heroes and Kibo was a hero\'92s dog and the men who had carried the tusks were heroes, already slightly drunk heroes and to be drunker, his father had said, \'93Do you want to make peace, Davey?\'94 \'93All right,\'94 he said because he knew this was the start of the never telling that he had decided on. \'93I\'92m so glad,\'94 his father said. \'93It\'92s so much simpler and better.\'94 Then they sat on old men\'92s stools under the shade of the fig tree with the tusks against the wall of the hut and drank beer from gourd cups that were brought by a young girl and her younger brother, the servant of heroes, sitting in the dust by the heroic dog of a hero who held an old cockerel, newly promoted to the standing of the heroes\'92 favorite rooster. They sat there and drank beer while the big drum started and the ngoma began to build. Part III Previously Unpublished Fiction \'93A Train Trip\'94 represents the first four chapters of an unfinished and untitled Lardneresque novel. These scenes form a fine short story in the vein of \'93The Battler\'94 and \'93Fifty Grand.\'94 A Train Trip MY FATHER TOUCHED ME AND I WAS awake. He stood by the bed in the dark. I felt his hand on me and I was wide awake in my head and saw and felt things but all the rest of me was asleep. \'93Jimmy,\'94 he said, \'93are you awake?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93Get dressed then.\'94 \'93All right.\'94 He stood there and I wanted to move but I was really still asleep. \'93Get dressed, Jimmy.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 I said but I lay there. Then the sleep was gone and I moved out of bed. \'93Good boy,\'94 my father said. I stood on the rug and felt for my clothes at the foot of the bed. \'93They\'92re on the chair,\'94 my father said. \'93Put on your shoes and stockings too.\'94 He went out of the room. It was cold and complicated getting dressed; I had not worn shoes and stockings all summer and it was not pleasant putting them on. My father came back in the room and sat on the bed. \'93Do the shoes hurt?\'94 \'93They pinch.\'94 \'93If the shoe pinches put it on.\'94 \'93I\'92m putting it on.\'94 \'93We\'92ll get some other shoes,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s not even a principle, Jimmy. It\'92s a proverb.\'94 \'93I see.\'94 \'93Like two against one is nigger fun. That\'92s a proverb too.\'94 \'93I like that one better than about the shoe,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s not so true,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s why you like it. The pleasanter proverbs aren\'92t so true.\'94 It was cold and I tied my other shoe and was finished dressing. \'93Would you like button shoes?\'94 my father asked. \'93I don\'92t care.\'94 \'93You can have them if you like,\'94 he said. \'93Everybody ought to have button shoes if they like.\'94 \'93I\'92m all ready.\'94 \'93Where are we going?\'94 \'93We\'92re going a long way.\'94 \'93Where to?\'94 \'93Canada.\'94 \'93We\'92ll go there too,\'94 he said. We went out to the kitchen. All the shutters were closed and there was a lamp on the table. In the middle of the room was a suitcase, a duffel bag, and two rucksacks. \'93Sit down at the table,\'94 my father said. He brought the frying pan and the coffee pot from the stove and sat down beside me and we ate ham and eggs and drank coffee with condensed cream in it. \'93Eat all you can.\'94 \'93I\'92m full.\'94 \'93Eat that other egg.\'94 He lifted the egg that was left in the pan with the pancake turner and put it on my plate. The edges were crisped from the bacon fat. I ate it and looked around the kitchen. If I was going away I wanted to remember it and say good-bye. In the corner the stove was rusty and half the lid was broken off the hot water reservoir. Above the stove there was a wooden-handled dish mop stuck in the edge of one of the rafters. My father threw it at a bat one evening. He left it there to remind him to get a new one and afterwards I think to remind him of the bat. I caught the bat in the landing net and kept him in a box with screen over it for a while. He had tiny eyes and tiny teeth and he kept himself folded in the box. We let him loose down on the shore of the lake in the dark and he flew out over the lake, flying very lightly and with flutters and flew down close over the water and then high and turned and flew over us and back into the trees in the dark. There were two kitchen tables, one that we ate on and one we did dishes on. They were both covered with oilcloth. There was a tin bucket for carrying lake water to fill the reservoir and a granite bucket for well water. There was a roller towel on the pantry door and dish towels on a rack over the stove. The broom was in the corner. The wood box was half full and all the pans were hanging against the wall. I looked all around the kitchen to remember it and I was awfully fond of it. \'93Well,\'94 said my father. \'93Do you think you\'92ll remember it?\'94 \'93I think so.\'94 \'93And what will you remember?\'94 \'93All the fun we\'92ve had.\'94 \'93Not just filling the wood box and hauling water?\'94 \'93That\'92s not hard.\'94 \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s not hard. Aren\'92t you sorry to go away?\'94 \'93Not if we\'92re going to Canada.\'94 \'93We won\'92t stay there.\'94 \'93Won\'92t we stay there a while?\'94 \'93Not very long.\'94 \'93Where do we go then?\'94 \'93We\'92ll see.\'94 \'93I don\'92t care where we go,\'94 I said. \'93Try and keep that way,\'94 my father said. He lit a cigarette and offered me the package. \'93You don\'92t smoke?\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93That\'92s good,\'94 he said. \'93Now you go outdoors and climb up on the ladder and put the bucket on the chimney and I\'92ll lock up.\'94 I went outside. It was still dark but along the edge of the hills it was lightening. The ladder was leaning against the roof and I found the old berry pail beside the woodshed and climbed the ladder. The leather soles of my shoes felt insecure and slippery on the rungs. I put the bucket over the top of the stove pipe to keep out the rain and to keep squirrels and chipmunks from climbing in. From the roof I looked down through the trees to the lake. Looking down on the other side was the woodshed roof, the fence and the hills. It was lighter than when I started to climb the ladder and it was cold and very early in the morning. I looked at the trees and the lake again to remember them and all around; at the hills in back and the woods off on the other side of the house and down again at the woodshed roof and I loved them all very much, the woodshed and the fence and the hills and the woods and I wished we were just going on a fishing trip and not going away. I heard the door shut and my father put all the bags out on the ground. Then he locked the door. I started down the ladder. \'93Jimmy,\'94 my father said. \'93Yes.\'94 \'93How is it up there on the roof?\'94 \'93I\'92m coming down.\'94 \'93Go on up. I\'92m coming up a minute,\'94 he said and climbed up very slowly and carefully. He looked all around the way I had done. \'93I don\'92t want to go either,\'94 he said. \'93Why do we have to go?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 he said. \'93But we do.\'94 We climbed down the ladder and my father put it in the woodshed. We carried the things down to the dock. The motor boat was tied beside the dock. There was dew on the oilcloth cover, the engine, and the seats were wet with dew. I took off the cover and wiped the seats dry with a piece of waste. My father lifted down the bags from the dock and put them in the stem of the boat. Then I untied the bow line and the stern line and got back in the boat and held onto the dock. My father primed the engine through a petcock, rocking the wheel twice to suck the gasoline into the cylinder, then he cranked the flywheel over and the engine started. I held the boat to the dock with a twist of the line around a spile. The propeller churned up the water and the boat pulled against the dock making the water swirl through the spiles