nd bigger and bigger. I stepped back from the tracks and looked back at the lake with the two grocery stores and the boat houses, the long docks going out into the water and close by the station the gravelled patch around the artesian well where the water came straight up in the sunlight out of a brown water-film covered pipe. The water was splashing in the fountain basin, in back was the lake with a breeze coming up, there were woods along the shore and the boat we had come in was tied to the dock. The train stopped, the conductor and the brakeman got down and my father said good-bye to Fred Cuthbert who was going to take care of the boat in his boat house. \'93When will you be back?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know, Fred,\'94 my father said. \'93Give her a coat of paint in the spring.\'94 \'93Good-bye, Jimmy,\'94 Fred said. \'93Take good care of yourself.\'94 \'93Good-bye, Fred.\'94 We shook hands with Fred and got on the train. The conductor got on in the car ahead and the brakeman picked up the little box we had stepped up on and swung aboard the train as it started. Fred stood there on the station platform and I watched the station, Fred standing there, then walking away, the water splashing up out of the pipe in the sun and then ties and the swamp and the station very small and the lake looking different and from a new angle and then we were out of sight and crossed the Bear River and went through a cut and there were only the ties and the rails running back and fireweed growing beside the track and nothing more to look at to remember. It was all new now looking out from the platform and the woods had that new look of woods you do not know and if you passed a lake it was the same way. It was just a lake and new and not like a lake you had lived on. \'93You\'92ll get all cinders out here,\'94 my father said. \'93I guess we\'92d better go in,\'94 I said. I felt funny with so much new country. I suppose it really looked just the same as the country where we lived but it did not feel the same. I suppose every patch of hardwood with the leaves turning looks alike but when you see a beech woods from the train it does not make you happy; it only makes you want the woods where you live. But I did not know that then. I thought it would all be like where we lived only more of it and that it would be just the same and give you the same feeling, but it didn\'92t. We did not have anything to do with it. The hills were worse than the woods. Perhaps all the hills in Michigan look the same but up in the car I looked out of the window and I would see woods and swamps and we would cross a stream and it was very interesting and then we would pass hills with a farmhouse and the woods behind them and they were the same hills but they were different and everything was a little different. I suppose, of course, that hills that a railroad runs by can not be the same. But it was not the way I had thought it was going to be. But it was a fine day early in the fall. The air was fine with the window open and in a little while I was hungry. We had been up since before it was light and now it was almost half past eight. My father came back down the car to our seat. \'93How do you feel, Jimmy?\'94 \'93Hungry.\'94 He gave me a bar of chocolate and an apple out of his pocket. \'93Come on up to the smoker,\'94 he said and I followed him through the car and into the next one ahead. We sat down in a seat, my father inside next to the window. It was dirty in the smoker and the black leather on the seats had been burned by cinders. \'93Look at the seats opposite us,\'94 my father said to me without looking toward them. Opposite us two men sat side by side. The man on the inside was looking out the window and his right wrist was handcuffed to the left wrist of the man who sat beside him. In the seat ahead of them were two other men. I could only see their backs but they sat the same way. The two men who sat on the aisle were talking. \'93In a day coach,\'94 the man opposite us said. The man who sat in front of him spoke without turning around. \'93Well why didn\'92t we take the night train?\'94 \'93Did you want to sleep with these?\'94 \'93Sure. Why not?\'94 \'93It\'92s more comfortable this way.\'94 \'93The hell it\'92s comfortable.\'94 The man who was looking out of the window looked at us and winked. He was a little man and he wore a cap. There was a bandage around his head under the cap. The man he was handcuffed to wore a cap also but his neck was thick, he was dressed in a blue suit and he wore a cap as though it was only for travelling. The two men on the next seat were about the same size and build but the one on the aisle had the thicker neck. \'93How about something to smoke, Jack?\'94 the man who had winked said to my father over the shoulder of the man he was handcuffed to. The thick-necked man turned and looked at my father and me. The man who had winked smiled. My father took out a package of cigarettes. \'93You want to give him a cigarette?\'94 asked the guard. My father reached the package across the aisle. \'93I\'92ll give it to him,\'94 said the guard. He took the package in his free hand, squeezed it, put it in his handcuffed hand and holding it there took out a cigarette with his free hand and gave it to the man beside him. The man next to the window smiled at us and the guard lit the cigarette for him. \'93You\'92re awfully sweet to me,\'94 he said to the guard. The guard reached the package of cigarettes back across the aisle. \'93Have one,\'94 my father said. \'93No thanks. I\'92m chewing.\'94 \'93Making a long trip?\'94 \'93Chicago.\'94 \'93So are we.\'94 \'93It\'92s a fine town,\'94 the little man next to the window said. \'93I was there once.\'94 \'93I\'92ll say you were,\'94 the guard said. \'93I\'92ll say you were.\'94 We moved up and sat in the seat directly opposite them. The guard in front looked around. The man with him looked down at the floor. \'93What\'92s the trouble,\'94 asked my father. \'93These gentlemen are wanted for murder.\'94 The man next to the window winked at me. \'93Keep it clean,\'94 he said. \'93We\'92re all gentlemen here.\'94 \'93Who was killed?\'94 asked my father. \'93An Italian,\'94 said the guard. \'93Who?\'94 asked the little man very brightly. \'93An Italian,\'94 the guard repeated to my father. \'93Who killed him?\'94 asked the little man looking at the sergeant and opening his eyes wide. \'93You\'92re pretty funny,\'94 the guard said. \'93No sir,\'94 the little man said. \'93I just asked you, Sergeant, who killed this Italian.\'94 \'93He killed this Italian,\'94 the prisoner on the front seat said looking toward the detective. \'93He killed this Italian with his bow and arrow.\'94 \'93Cut it out,\'94 said the detective. \'93Sergeant,\'94 the little man said. \'93I did not kill this Italian. I would not kill an Italian. I do not know an Italian.\'94 \'93Write it down and use it against him,\'94 the prisoner on the front seat said. \'93Everything he says will be used against him. He did not kill this Italian.\'94 \'93Sergeant,\'94 asked the little man, \'93who did kill this Italian?\'94 \'93You did,\'94 said the detective. \'93Sergeant,\'94 said the little man. \'93That is a falsehood. I did not kill this Italian. I refuse to repeat it. I did not kill this Italian.\'94 \'93Everything he says must be used against him,\'94 said the other prisoner. \'93Sergeant, why did you kill this Italian?\'94 \'93It was an error, Sergeant,\'94 the little prisoner said. \'93It was a grave error. You should never have killed this Italian.\'94 \'93Or that Italian,\'94 the other prisoner said. \'93Shut to hell up the both of you,\'94 said the sergeant. \'93They\'92re dope heads,\'94 he said to my father. \'93They\'92re crazy as bed bugs.\'94 \'93Bed bugs?\'94 said the little man, his voice rising. \'93There are no bed bugs on me, Sergeant.\'94 \'93He comes from a long line of English earls,\'94 said the other prisoner. \'93Ask the senator there,\'94 he