ulled. The other two ate as comfortably as they could. They were not as interesting to watch anyway. \'93Why don\'92t you take them off while we eat?\'94 the little man said to the sergeant. The sergeant did not say anything. He was reaching for his coffee and as he picked it up the little man jerked and he spilled it. Without looking toward the little man the sergeant jerked out with his arm and the steel cuffs yanked the little man\'92s wrist and the sergeant\'92s wrist hit the little man in the face. \'93Son of a bitch,\'94 the little man said. His lip was cut and he sucked it. \'93Who?\'94 asked the sergeant. \'93Not you,\'94 said the little man. \'93Not you with me chained to you. Certainly not.\'94 The sergeant moved his wrist under the table and looked at the little man\'92s face. \'93What do you say?\'94 \'93Not a thing,\'94 said the little man. The sergeant looked at his face and then reached for his coffee again with his handcuffed hand. The little man\'92s right hand was pulled out across the table as the sergeant reached. The sergeant lifted the coffee cup and as he raised it to drink it it jerked out of his hand and the coffee spilled all over everything. The sergeant brought the handcuffs up into the little man\'92s face twice without looking at him. The little man\'92s face was bloody and he sucked his lip and looked at the table. \'93You got enough?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said the little man. \'93I\'92ve got plenty.\'94 \'93You feel quieter now?\'94 \'93Very quiet,\'94 said the little man. \'93How do you feel?\'94 \'93Wipe your face off,\'94 said the sergeant. \'93Your mouth is bloody.\'94 We saw them get on the train two at a time and we got on too and went to our seats. The other detective, not the one they called Sergeant but the one handcuffed to the big prisoner, had not taken any notice of what happened at the table. He had watched it but he had not seemed to notice it. The big prisoner had not said anything but had watched everything. There were cinders in the plush of our seat in the train and my father brushed the seat with a newspaper. The train started and I looked out the open window and tried to see Cadillac but you could not see much, only the lake, and factories and a fine smooth road along near the tracks. There were a lot of sawdust piles along the lake shore. \'93Don\'92t put your head out, Jimmy,\'94 my father said. I sat down. There was nothing much to see anyway. \'93That is the town Al Moegast came from,\'94 my father said. \'93Oh,\'94 I said. \'93Did you see what happened at the table?\'94 my father asked. \'93Yes.\'94 \'93Did you see everything?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know.\'94 \'93What do you think the little one made that trouble for?\'94 \'93I guess he wanted to make it uncomfortable so they would take the handcuffs off.\'94 \'93Did you see anything else?\'94 \'93I saw him get hit three times in the face.\'94 \'93Where did you watch when he hit him?\'94 \'93I watched his face. I watched the sergeant hit him.\'94 \'93Well,\'94 my father said. \'93While the sergeant hit him in the face with the handcuff on his right hand he picked up a steel-bladed knife off the table with his left hand and put it in his pocket.\'94 \'93I didn\'92t see.\'94 \'93No,\'94 my father said. \'93Every man has two hands, Jimmy. At least to start with. You ought to watch both of them if you\'92re going to see things.\'94 \'93What did the other two do?\'94 I asked. My father laughed. \'93I didn\'92t watch them,\'94 he said. We sat there in the train after lunch and I looked out of the window and watched the country. It did not mean so much now because there was so much else going on and I had seen a lot of country but I did not want to suggest that we go up into the smoker until my father said to. He was reading and I guess my restlessness disturbed him. \'93Don\'92t you ever read, Jimmy?\'94 he asked me. \'93Not much,\'94 I said. \'93I don\'92t have time.\'94 \'93What are you doing now?\'94 \'93Waiting.\'94 \'93Do you want to go up there?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94 \'93Do you think we ought to tell the sergeant\'94 \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s an ethical problem,\'94 he said and shut the book. \'93Do you want to tell him?\'94 I asked. \'93No,\'94 my father said. \'93Besides a man is held to be innocent until the law has proved him guilty. He may not have killed that Italian.\'94 \'93Are they dope fiends?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know whether they use dope or not,\'94 my father said. \'93Many people use it. But using cocaine or morphine or heroin doesn\'92t make people talk the way they talked.\'94 \'93What does?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said my father. \'93What makes anyone talk the way they do?\'94 \'93Let\'92s go up there,\'94 I said. My father got the suitcase down, opened it up and put the book in it and something out of his pocket. He locked the suitcase and we went up to the smoker. Walking along the aisle of the smoker I saw the two detectives and the two prisoners sitting quietly. We sat down opposite them. The little man\'92s cap was down over the bandage around his head and his lips were swollen. He was awake and looking out of the window. The sergeant was sleepy, his eyes would shut and then open, stay open a while and then shut. His face looked very heavy and sleepy. Ahead on the next seat the other two were both sleepy. The prisoner leaned toward the window side of the seat and the detective toward the aisle. They were not comfortable that way and as they got sleepier, they both leaned toward each other. The little man looked at the sergeant and then across at us. He did not seem to recognize us and looked all down the car. He seemed to be looking at all the men in the smoker. There were not very many passengers. Then he looked at the sergeant again. My father had taken another book out of his pocket and was reading. \'93Sergeant,\'94 the little man said. The sergeant held his eyes open and looked at the prisoner. \'93I got to go to the can,\'94 the little man said. \'93Not now,\'94 the sergeant shut his eyes. \'93Listen, Sergeant,\'94 the little man said. \'93Didn\'92t you ever have to go to the can?\'94 \'93Not now,\'94 the sergeant said. He did not want to leave the half asleep half awake state he was in. He was breathing slowly and heavily but when he would open his eyes his breathing would stop. The little man looked across at us but did not seem to recognize us. \'93Sergeant,\'94 he said. The sergeant did not answer. The little man ran his tongue over his lips. \'93Listen Sergeant, I got to go to the can.\'94 \'93All right,\'94 the sergeant said. He stood up and the little man stood up and they walked down the aisle. I looked at my father. \'93Go on,\'94 he said, \'93if you want to.\'94 I walked after them down the aisle. They were standing at the door. \'93I want to go in alone,\'94 the prisoner said. \'93No you don\'92t.\'94 \'93Go on. Let me go in alone.\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Why not? You can keep the door locked.\'94 \'93I won\'92t take them off.\'94 \'93Go on, Sergeant. Let me go in alone.\'94 \'93We\'92ll take a look,\'94 the sergeant said. They went inside and the sergeant shut the door. I was sitting on the seat opposite the door to the toilet. I looked down the aisle at my father. Inside I could hear them talking but not what they were saying. Someone turned the handle inside the door to open it and then I heard something fall against it and hit twice against the door. Then it fell on the floor. Then there was a noise as when you pick a rabbit up by the hind legs and slap its head against a stump to kill it. I was looking at my father and motioning. There was that noise three times and then I saw something come out from under the door. It was blood and it came out very slowly and smoothly. I ran down the aisle to my father. \'93There\'92s blood coming out under the door.\'94 \'93Sit down there,\'94 my father said. He stood up, went across the aisle and touched the detective on the shoulder. The detective looked up. \'93Your partner went up to the washroom,\'94 my father said. \'93Sure,\'94 said the detective. \'93Why not?\'94 \'93My boy went up there and said he saw blood coming out from under the door.\'94 The detective jumped up and jerked the other prisoner over on the seat. The other prisoner looked at my father. \'93Come on,\'94 the detective said. The prisoner sat there. \'93Come on,\'94 the detective said and the prisoner did not move. \'93Come on or I\'92ll blow your can off.\'94 \'93What\'92s it all about, your excellency?\'94 the prisoner asked. \'93Come on, you bastard,\'94 the detective said. \'93Aw, keep it clean,\'94 the prisoner said. They were going down the aisle, the detective ahead holding a gun in his right hand and the prisoner handcuffed to him hanging back. The passengers were standing up to see. \'93Stay where you are,\'94 my father said. He took hold of me by the arm. The detective saw the blood under the door. He looked around at the prisoner. The prisoner saw him looking and stood still. \'93No,\'94 he said. The detective holding his gun in his right hand jerked down hard with his left hand and the prisoner slipped forward on his knees. \'93No,\'94 he said. The detective watching the door and the prisoner shifted the revolver so he held it by the muzzle and hit the prisoner suddenly at the side of the head. The prisoner slipped down with his head and hands on the floor. \'93No,\'94 he said shaking his head on the floor. \'93No. No. No.\'94 The detective hit him again and then again and he was quiet. He lay on the floor on his face with his head bent down on his chest. Watching the door, the detective laid the revolver down on the floor and leaning over unlocked the handcuff from the wrist of the prisoner. Then he picked up the revolver and stood up. Holding the revolver in his right hand he pulled the cord with his left to stop the train. Then he reached for the handle of the door. The train was starting to slow. \'93Get away from that door,\'94 we heard someone say inside the door. \'93Open it up,\'94 said the detective and stepped back. \'93Al,\'94 the voice said. \'93Al, are you all right?\'94 The detective stood just to one side of the door. The train was slowing down. \'93Al,\'94 said the voice again. \'93Answer me if you\'92re all right.\'94 There was no answer. The train stopped. The brakeman opened the door. \'93What the hell?\'94 he said. He looked at the man on the floor, the blood and the detective holding the revolver. The conductor was coming down from the other end of the car. \'93There\'92s a fellow in there that\'92s killed a man,\'94 the detective said. \'93The hell there is. He\'92s gone out the window,\'94 said the brakeman. \'93Watch that man,\'94 said the detective. He opened the door to the platform. I went across the aisle and looked out the window. Along the tracks there was a fence. Beyond the fence was the woods. I looked up and down the tracks. The detective came running by; then ran back. There was no one in sight. The detective came back in the car and they opened the door of the washroom. The door would not swing open because the sergeant was lying across it on the floor. The window was open about halfway. The sergeant was still breathing. They picked him up and carried him out into the car and they picked up the prisoner and put him in a seat. The detective put the handcuff through the handle of a big suitcase. Nobody seemed to know what to do or whether to look after the sergeant or try and find the little man or what. Everybody had gotten out of the train and looked down the tracks and in the edge of the woods. The brakeman had seen the little man run across the tracks and into the woods. The detective went into the woods a couple of times and then came out. The prisoner had taken the sergeant\'92s gun and nobody seemed to want to go very far into the woods after him. Finally they started the train to get to a station where they could send for the state constabulary and send out a descript