by the wind. Soon it was a rolling black cloud and in the greasy black smoke you could see the red flames. There was an explosion and a billowing of white smoke and then the black smoke rolled higher; but from a wider base. \'93That\'92s a tank,\'94 I said. \'93Burning.\'94 We stood and watched. Through the glasses you could see two men get out of an angle of the trench and start up a slant of the hill carrying a stretcher. They seemed to move slowly and ploddingly. As you watched the man in front sank onto his knees and then sat down. The man behind had dropped to the ground. He crawled forward. Then with his arm under the first man\'92s shoulder he started to crawl, dragging him toward the trench. Then he stopped moving and you saw that he was lying flat on his face. They both lay there not moving now. They had stopped shelling the house and it was quiet now. The big farmhouse and walled court showed clear and yellow against the green hillside that was scarred white with the dirt where the strong points had been fortified and the communication trenches dug. There was smoke from small fires rising now over the hillside where men were cooking. And up the slope toward the big farmhouse lay the casualties of the attack like many scattered bundles on the green slope. The tank was burning black and greasy in the trees. \'93It\'92s horrible,\'94 the girl said. \'93It\'92s the first time I\'92ve ever seen it. It\'92s really horrible.\'94 \'93It always has been.\'94 \'93Don\'92t you hate it?\'94 \'93I hate it and I always have hated it. But when you have to do it you ought to know how. That was a frontal attack. They are just murder.\'94 \'93Are there other ways to attack?\'94 \'93Oh sure. Lots of them. But you have to have knowledge and discipline and trained squad and section leaders. And most of all you ought to have surprise.\'94 \'93It makes now too dark to work,\'94 Johnny said putting the cap over his telephoto lens. \'93Hello you old lice. Now we go home to the hotel. Today we work pretty good.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 said the other one. \'93Today we have got something very good. It is too dom bad the attack is no good. Is better not to think about it. Sometime we film a successful attack. Only always with a successful attack it rains or snows.\'94 \'93I don\'92t want to see any more ever,\'94 the girl said. \'93I\'92ve seen it now. Nothing would ever make me see it for curiosity or to make money writing about it. Those are men as we are. Look at them there on that hillside.\'94 \'93You are not men,\'94 said Johnny. \'93You are a womans. Don\'92t make a confusion.\'94 \'93Comes now the steel hat man,\'94 said the other looking out of the window. \'93Comes now with much dignity. I wish I had bomb to throw to make suddenly a surprise.\'94 We were packing up the cameras and equipment when the steel-hatted Authority came in. \'93Hullo,\'94 he said. \'93Did you make some good pictures? I have a car in one of the back streets to take you home, Elizabeth.\'94 \'93I\'92m going home with Edwin Henry,\'94 the girl said. \'93Did the wind die down?\'94 I asked him conversationally. He let that go by and said to the girl, \'93You won\'92t come?\'94 \'93No,\'94 she said. \'93We are all going home together.\'94 \'93I\'92ll see you at the Club tonight,\'94 he said to me very pleasantly. \'93You don\'92t belong to the Club any more,\'94 I told him, speaking as nearly English as I could. We all started down the stairs together, being very careful about the holes in the marble, and walking over and around the new damage. It seemed a very long stairway. I picked up a brass nosecap flattened and plaster marked at the end and handed it to the girl called Elizabeth. \'93I don\'92t want it,\'94 she said and at the doorway we all stopped and let the steel-hatted man go on ahead alone. He walked with great dignity across the part of the street where you were sometimes fired on and continued on, with dignity, in the shelter of the wall opposite. Then, one at a time, we sprinted across to the lee of the wall. It is the third or fourth man to cross an open space who draws the fire, you learn after you have been around a while, and we were always pleased to be across that particular place. So we walked up the street now, protected by the wall, four abreast, carrying the cameras and stepping over the new iron fragments, the freshly broken bricks, and the blocks of stone, and watching the dignity of the walk of the steel-hatted man ahead who no longer belonged to the Club. \'93I hate to write a dispatch,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s not going to be an easy one to write. This offensive is gone.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter with you, boy?\'94 asked Johnny. \'93You must write what can be said,\'94 the other one said gently. \'93Certainly something can be said about a day so full of events.\'94 \'93When will they get the wounded back?\'94 the girl asked. She wore no hat and walked with a long loose stride and her hair, which was a dusty yellow in the fading light, hung over the collar of her short, fur-collared jacket. It swung as she turned her head. Her face was white and she looked ill. \'93I told you as soon as it gets dark.\'94 \'93God make it get dark quick,\'94 she said. \'93So that\'92s war. That\'92s what I\'92ve come here to see and write about. Were those two men killed who went out with the stretcher?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93Positively.\'94 \'93They moved so slowly,\'94 the girl said pitifully. \'93Sometime\'92s it\'92s very hard to make the legs move,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s like walking in deep sand or in a dream.\'94 Ahead of us the man in the steel hat was still walking up the street. There was a line of shattered houses on his left and the brick wall of the barracks on his right. His car was parked at the end of the street where ours was also standing in the lee of a house. \'93Let\'92s take him back to the Club,\'94 the girl said. \'93I don\'92t want anyone to be hurt tonight. Not their feelings nor anything. Heh!\'94 she called. \'93Wait for us. We\'92re coming.\'94 He stopped and looked back, the great heavy helmet looking ridiculous as he turned his head, like the huge horns on some harmless beast. He waited and we came up. \'93Can I help you with any of that?\'94 he asked. \'93No. The car\'92s just there ahead.\'94 \'93We\'92re all going to the Club,\'94 the girl said. She smiled at him. \'93Would you come and bring a bottle of something?\'94 \'93That would be so nice,\'94 he said. \'93What should I bring?\'94 \'93Anything,\'94 the girl said. \'93Bring anything you like. I have to do some work first. Make it seven thirtyish.\'94 \'93Will you ride home with me?\'94 he asked her. \'93I\'92m afraid the other car is crowded with all that bit.\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92d like to. Thank you.\'94 They got in one car and we loaded all the stuff into the other. \'93What\'92s the matter, boy?\'94 Johnny said. \'93Your girl go home with somebody else?\'94 \'93The attack upset her. She feels very badly.\'94 \'93A woman who doesn\'92t upset by an attack is no woman,\'94 said Johnny. \'93It was a very unsuccessful attack,\'94 said the other. \'93Fortunately she did not see it from too close. We must never let her see one from close regardless of the danger. It is too strong a thing. From where she saw it is only a picture. Like old-fashioned battle scene.\'94 \'93She has a kind heart,\'94 said Johnny. \'93Different than you, you old lice.\'94 \'93I have a kind heart,\'94 I said. \'93And it\'92s louse. Not lice. Lice is the plural.\'94 \'93I like lice better,\'94 said Johnny. \'93It sounds more determined.\'94 But he put up his hand and rubbed out the words written in lipstick on the window. \'93We make a new joke tomorrow,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s all right now about the writing on the mirror.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m glad.\'94 \'93You old lice,\'94 said Johnny and slapped me on the back. \'93Louse is the word.\'94 \'93No. Lice. I like much better. Is many times more determined.\'94 \'93Go to hell.\'94 \'93Good,\'94 said Johnny, smiling happily. \'93Now we are all good friends again. In a war we must all be careful not to hurt each other\'92s feelings.\'94 \'93I Guess Everything Reminds You of Something\'94 is a completed short story set in Cuba, where Hemingway made his home at the Finca Vig\'eda from 1939 to 1959. I Guess Everything Reminds You of Something \'93IT\'92S A VERY GOOD STORY ,\'94 THE BOY\'92S father said. \'93Do you know how good it is?\'94 \'93I didn\'92t want her to send it to you, Papa.\'94 \'93What else have you written?\'94 \'93That\'92s the only story. Truly I didn\'92t want her to send it to you. But when it won the prize\'97\'94 \'93She wants me to help you. But if you can write that well you don\'92t need anyone to help you. All you need is to write. How long did it take you to write that story?\'94 \'93Not very long.\'94 \'93Where did you learn about that type of gull?\'94 \'93In the Bahamas I guess.\'94 \'93You never went to the Dog Rocks nor to Elbow Key. There weren\'92t any gulls nor terns nested at Cat Key nor Bimini. At Key West you would only have seen least terns nesting.\'94 \'93Killem Peters. Sure. They nest on the coral rocks.\'94 \'93Right on the flats,\'94 his father said. \'93Where would you have known gulls like the one in the story?\'94 \'93Maybe you told me about them, Papa.\'94 \'93It\'92s a very fine story. It reminds me of a story I read a long time ago.\'94 \'93I guess everything reminds you of something,\'94 the boy said. That summer the boy read books that his father found for him in the library and when he would come over to the main house for lunch, if he had not been playing baseball or had not been down at the club shooting, he would often say he had been writing. \'93Show it to me when you want to or ask me about any trouble,\'94 his father said. \'93Write about something that you know.\'94 \'93I am,\'94 the boy said. \'93I don\'92t want to look over your shoulder or breathe down your neck,\'94 his father said. \'93If you want, though, I can set you some simple problems about things we both know. It would be good training.\'94 \'93I think I\'92m going all right.\'94 \'93Don\'92t show it to me until you want to then. How did you like \'91Far Away and Long Ago\'92?\'94 \'93I liked it very much.\'94 \'93The sort of problems I meant were: we could go into the market together or to the cockfight and then each of us write down what we saw. What it really was that you saw that stayed with you. Things like the handler opening the rooster\'92s bill and blowing in his throat when the referee would let them pick up and handle them before pitting again. The small things. To see what we each saw.\'94 The boy nodded and then looked down at his plate. \'93Or we can go into the caf\'e9 and shake a few rounds of poker dice and you write what it was in the conversation that you heard. Not try to write everything. Only what you heard that meant anything.\'94 \'93I\'92m afraid that I\'92m not ready for that yet, Papa. I think I\'92d better go on the way I did in the story.\'94 \'93Do that then. I don\'92t want to interfere or influence you. Those were just exercises. I\'92d have been glad to do them with you. They\'92re like five-finger exercises. Those weren\'92t especially good. We can make better ones.\'94 \'93Probably it\'92s better for me to go on the way it was in the story.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 his father said. I could not write that well when I was his age, his father thought. I never knew anyone else that could either. But I never knew anyone else that could shoot better at ten than this boy could; not just show-off shooting, but shooting in competition with grown men and professionals. He shot the same way in the field when he was twelve. He shot as though he had built-in radar. He never took a shot out of range nor let a driven bird come too close and he shot with beautiful style and an absolute timing and precision on high pheasants and in pass shooting at ducks. At live pigeons, in competition, when he walked out on the cement, spun the wheel and walked to the metal plaque that marked the black stripe of his yardage, the pros were silent and watching. He was the only shooter that the crowd became dead silent for. Some of the pros smiled as though at a secret when he put his gun to his shoulder and looked back to see where the heel of the stock rested against his shoulder. Then his cheek went down against the comb, his left hand was far forward, his weight was forward on his left foot. The muzzle of the gun rose and lowered, then swept to left, to right, and back to center. The heel of his right foot lifted gently as all of him leaned behind the two loads in the chambers. \'93Ready,\'94 he said in that low, hoarse voice that did not belong to a small boy. \'93Ready,\'94 answered the trapper. \'93Pull,\'94 said the hoarse voice and from whichever of the five traps the grey racing pigeon came out, and at whatever angle his wings drove him in full, low flight above the green grass toward the white, low fence, the load of the first barrel swung into him and the load from the second barrel drove through the first. As the bird collapsed in flight, his head falling forward, only the great shots saw the impact of the second load driving through onto the bird already dead in the air. The boy would break his gun and walk back in off the cement toward the pavilion, no expression on his face, his eyes down, never giving any recognition to applause and saying, \'93Thanks,\'94 in the strange hoarse voice if some pro said, \'93Good bird, Stevie.\'94 He would put his gun in the rack and wait to watch his father shoot and then the two of them would walk off together to the outdoor bar. \'93Can I drink a Coca-Cola, Papa?\'94 \'93Better not drink more than half a one.\'94 \'93All right. I\'92m sorry I was so slow. I shouldn\'92t have let the bird get hard.\'94 \'93He was a strong, low driver, Stevie.\'94 \'93Nobody\'92d