here be snakes?\'94 \'93I\'92m pretty sure there\'92d be a lot.\'94 \'93I\'92m afraid of them. Really afraid of them. But we could be careful couldn\'92t we?\'94 \'93Sure. We ought to do it in the winter time.\'94 \'93There are such wonderful places for us to go,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92ll always remember this river now and we saw it only like the lens clicking in a camera. We should have stopped.\'94 \'93Do you want to go back?\'94 \'93Not until we come to it going the other way. I want to go on and on and on.\'94 \'93We\'92re either going to have to stop to get something to eat or else get sandwiches and eat them while we drive.\'94 \'93Let\'92s have another drink,\'94 she said. \'93And then get some sandwiches. What kind do you think they\'92ll have?\'94 \'93They ought to have hamburgers and maybe barbecue.\'94 The second drink was like the first, icy cold but quick melting in the wind and Helena held the cup out of the rush of the air and handed it to him when he drank. \'93Daughter, are you drinking more than you usually do?\'94 \'93Of course. You didn\'92t think I drank a couple of cups of whisky and water every noon by myself before lunch did you?\'94 \'93I don\'92t want you to drink more than you should.\'94 \'93I won\'92t. But it\'92s fun. If I don\'92t want one I won\'92t take one. I never knew about driving across the country and having our drinks on the way.\'94 \'93We could have fun stopping and poking around. Going down to the coast and seeing the old places. But I want us to get out west.\'94 \'93So do I. I\'92ve never seen it. We can always come back.\'94 \'93It\'92s such a long way. But this is so much more fun than flying.\'94 \'93This is flying. Roger, will it be wonderful out west?\'94 \'93It always is to me.\'94 \'93Isn\'92t it lucky I\'92ve never been out so we\'92ll have it together?\'94 \'93We\'92ve got a lot of country to get through first.\'94 \'93It\'92s going to be fun though. Do you think we\'92ll come to the sandwich town pretty soon?\'94 \'93We\'92ll take the next town.\'94 The next town was a lumbering town with one long street of frame and brick buildings along the highway. The mills were by the railroad and lumber was piled high along the tracks and there was the smell of cypress and pine sawdust in the heat. While Roger filled the gas and had the water, oil and air checked Helena ordered hamburger sandwiches and barbecued pork sandwiches with hot sauce on them in a lunch counter and brought them to the car in a brown paper bag. She had beer in another paper sack. Back on the highway again, and out of the heat of the town, they ate the sandwiches and drank cold beer that the girl opened. \'93I couldn\'92t get any of our marriage beer,\'94 she said. \'93This was the only kind there was.\'94 \'93It\'92s good and cold. Wonderful after the barbecue.\'94 \'93The man said it was about like Regal. He said I\'92d never be able to tell it from Regal.\'94 \'93It\'92s better than Regal.\'94 \'93It had a funny name. It wasn\'92t a German name either. But the labels soaked off.\'94 \'93It\'92ll be on the caps.\'94 \'93I threw the caps away.\'94 \'93Wait till we get out west. They have better beer the further out you get.\'94 \'93I don\'92t think they could have any better sandwich buns or any better barbecue. Aren\'92t these good?\'94 \'93They\'92re awfully good. This isn\'92t a part of the country where you eat very good either.\'94 \'93Roger, will you mind terribly if I go to sleep for a little while after lunch? I won\'92t if you\'92re sleepy.\'94 \'93I\'92d love it if you went to sleep. I\'92m not sleepy at all really. I\'92d tell you if I was.\'94 \'93There\'92s another bottle of beer for you. Dammit I forgot to look at the cap.\'94 \'93That\'92s good. I like to drink it unknown.\'94 \'93But we could have remembered it for another time.\'94 \'93We\'92ll get another new one.\'94 \'93Roger, would you really not mind if I went to sleep?\'94 \'93No, beauty.\'94 \'93I can stay awake if you want.\'94 \'93Please sleep and you\'92ll wake up lonely and we can talk.\'94 \'93Good night, my dear Roger. Thank you very much for the trip and the two drinks and the sandwiches and the unknown beer and the way down upon the Swanee River and for where we are going.\'94 \'93You go to sleep, my baby.\'94 \'93I will. You wake me up if you want me.\'94 She slept curled up in the deep seat and Roger drove, watching the wide road ahead for stock, making fast time through the pine country, trying to keep around seventy to try to see how much he could get over sixty miles onto the speedometer in each hour. He had never been on this stretch of highway but he knew this part of the state and he was driving it now only to put it behind him. You shouldn\'92t have to waste country but on a long trip you have to. The monotony tires you, he thought. That and the fact there are no vistas. This would be a fine country on foot in cool weather but it is monotonous to drive through now. I have not been driving long enough to settle into it yet. But I should have more resiliency than I have. I\'92m not sleepy. My eyes are bored I guess as well as tired. I am not bored, he thought. It is just my eyes and the fact that it is a long time since I have been sitting still so long. It is another game and I\'92ll have to relearn it. About day after tomorrow we will start to make real distance and not be tired by it. I haven\'92t sat still this long for a long time. He reached forward and turned on the radio and tuned it. Helenadid not wake so he left it on and let it blur in with his thinking and his driving. It is awfully nice having her in the car asleep, he thought. She is good company even when she is asleep. You are a strange and lucky bastard, he thought. You are having much better luck than you deserve. You just thought you had learned something about being alone and you really worked at it and you did learn something. You got right to the edge of something. Then you backslid and ran with those worthless