g as starting it all over and you\'92ve been given a chance to and you can do it and you will do it. Will you make all the promises again? Yes. If necessary I will make all the promises and I will keep them. Not all the promises? Knowing you have broken them? He could not say anything to that. You mustn\'92t be a crook before you start . No. I mustn\'92t. Say what you can truly do each day and then do it. Each day. Do it a day at a time and keep each day\'92s promises to her and to yourself. That way I can start it all new, he thought, and still be straight. You\'92re getting to be an awful moralist, he thought. If you don\'92t watch out you will bore her. When weren\'92t you always a moralist? At different times. Don\'92t fool yourself. Well, at different places then. Don\'92t fool yourself. All right, Conscience, he said. Only don\'92t be so solemn and didactic. Get a load of this, Conscience old friend, I know how useful and important you are and how you could have kept me out of all the trouble I have been in but couldn\'92t you have a little lighter touch about it? I know that conscience speaks in italics but sometimes you seem to speak in very boldfaced Gothic script. I would take it just as well from you, Conscience, if you did not try to scare me; just as I would consider the Ten Commandments just as seriously if they were not presented as graven on stone tablets. You know. Conscience, it has been a long time since we were frightened by the thunder. Now with the lightning: There you have something. But the thunder doesn\'92t impress us so much any more. I\'92m trying to help you, you son of a bitch, his conscience said. The girl was still sleeping and they were coming up the hill into Tallahassee. She will probably wake when we stop at the first light, he thought. But she did not and he drove through the old town and turned off to the left on U.S. 319 straight south and into the beautiful wooded country that ran down toward the Gulf Coast. There\'92s one thing about you, daughter, he thought. Not only can you outsleep anybody I\'92ve ever known and have the best appetite I\'92ve ever seen linked with a build like yours but you have an absolutely heaven-given ability to not have to go to the bathroom. Their room was on the fourteenth floor and it was not very cool. But with the fans on and the windows open it was better and when the bellboy had gone out Helena said, \'93Don\'92t be disappointed, darling. Please. It\'92s lovely.\'94 \'93I thought I could get you an air-conditioned one.\'94 \'93They\'92re awful to sleep in really. Like being in a vault. This will be fine.\'94 \'93We could have tried the other two. But they know me there.\'94 \'93They\'92ll know us both here now. What\'92s our name?\'94 \'93Mr. and Mrs. Robert Harris.\'94 \'93That\'92s a splendid name. We must try to live up to it. Do you want to bathe first?\'94 \'93No. You.\'94 \'93All right. I\'92m going to really bathe though.\'94 \'93Go ahead. Go to sleep in the tub if you want.\'94 \'93I may. I didn\'92t sleep all day did I?\'94 \'93You were wonderful. There was some pretty dull going too.\'94 \'93It wasn\'92t bad. Lots of it was lovely. But New Orleans isn\'92t really the way I thought it would be. Did you always know it was so flat and dull? I don\'92t know what I expected. Marseilles I suppose. And to see the river.\'94 \'93It\'92s only to eat and drink in. The part right around here doesn\'92t look so bad at night. It\'92s really sort of nice.\'94 \'93Let\'92s not go out until it\'92s dark. It\'92s all right around here. Some of it is lovely.\'94 \'93We\'92ll have that and then, in the morning, we\'92ll be on our way.\'94 \'93That only leaves time for one meal.\'94 \'93That\'92s all right. We\'92ll come back in cold weather when we can really eat. Darling,\'94 she said. \'93This is the first sort of letdown we\'92ve had. So let\'92s not let it let us down. We\'92ll have long baths and some drinks and a meal twice as expensive as we can afford and