ry much, Roger. Don\'92t you think you ought to work more?\'94 \'93I\'92m going to work now as soon as we get out west.\'94 \'93Maybe we shouldn\'92t stay tomorrow then. I\'92ll be so happy when you work.\'94 \'93Happier than now?\'94 \'93Yes,\'94 she said. \'93Happier than now.\'94 \'93I\'92ll work hard. You\'92ll see.\'94 \'93Roger, do you think I\'92m bad for you? Do I make you drink or make love more than you should?\'94 \'93No, daughter.\'94 \'93I\'92m awfully glad if it\'92s true because I want to be good for you. I know it\'92s a weakness and silliness but I make up stories to myself in the daytime and in one of them I save your life. Sometimes it\'92s from drowning and sometimes from in from of a train and sometimes in a plane and sometimes in the mountains. You can laugh if you want. And then there is one where I come into your life when you are disgusted and disappointed with all women and you love me so much and I take such good care of you that you get an epoch of writing wonderfully. That\'92s a wonderful one. I was making it up again today in the car.\'94 \'93That\'92s one I\'92m pretty sure I\'92ve seen in the movies or read somewhere.\'94 \'93Oh I know. I\'92ve seen it there too. And I\'92m sure I\'92ve read it too. But don\'92t you think it happens? Don\'92t you think I could be good for you? Not in a wishy-washy way or by giving you a little baby but really good for you so you\'92d write better than you ever wrote and be happy at the same time?\'94 \'93They do it in pictures. Why shouldn\'92t we do it?\'94 The absinthe had come and from the saucers of cracked ice placed over the top of the glasses water, that Roger added from a small pitcher, was dripping down into the clear yellowish liquor turning it to an opalescent milkiness. \'93Try that,\'94 Roger said when it was the right cloudy color. \'93It\'92s very strange,\'94 the girl said. \'93And warming in the stomach. It tastes like medicine.\'94 \'93It is medicine. Pretty strong medicine.\'94 \'93I don\'92t really need medicine yet,\'94 the girl said. \'93But this is awfully good. When will we be tight?\'94 \'93Almost any time. I\'92m going to have three. You take what you want. But take them slow.\'94 \'93I\'92ll see how I do. I don\'92t know anything about it yet except that it\'92s like medicine. Roger?\'94 \'93Yes, daughter.\'94 He was feeling the warmth of the alchemist\'92s furnace starting at the pit of his stomach. \'93Roger, don\'92t you think I really could be good for you the way I was in the story I made up?\'94 \'93I think we could be good to each other and for each other. But I don\'92t like it to be on a basis of stories. I think the story business is bad.\'94 \'93But you see that\'92s the way I am. I\'92m a story-maker-upper and I\'92m romantic I know. But that\'92s how I am. If I was practical I\'92d never have come to Bimini.\'94 I don\'92t know, Roger thought to himself. If that was what you wanted to do that was quite practical. You didn\'92t just make up a story about it. And the other part of him thought: You must be slipping you bastard if the absinthe can bring the heel in you out that quickly. But what he said was, \'93I don\'92t know, daughter. I think the story business is dangerous. First you could make up stories about something innocuous, like me, and then there could be all sorts of other stories. There might be bad ones.\'94 \'93You\'92re not so innocuous.\'94 \'93Oh yes I am. Or the stories are anyway. Saving me is fairly innocuous. But first you might be saving me and then next you might be saving the world. Then you might start saving yourself.\'94 \'93I\'92d like to save the world. I always wished I could. That\'92s awfully big to make a story about. But I want to save you first.\'94 \'93I\'92m getting scared,\'94 Roger said. He drank some more of the absinthe and he felt better but he was worried. \'93Have you always made up the stories?\'94 \'93Since I can remember. I\'92ve made them up about you for twelve years. I didn\'92t tell you all the ones. There are hundreds of them.\'94 \'93Why don\'92t you write instead of making up the stories?\'94 \'93I do write. But it\'92s not as much fun as making up the stories and it\'92s much harder. Then they\'92re not nearly as good. The ones I make up are wonderful.\'94 \'93But you\'92re always the heroine in the stories you write?\'94 \'93No. It\'92s not that simple.\'94 \'93Well let\'92s not worry about it now.\'94 He took another sip of the absinthe and rolled it under his tongue. \'93I never worried about it at all,\'94 the girl said. \'93What I wanted, always, was you and now I\'92m with you. Now I want you to be a great writer.\'94 \'93Maybe we\'92d better not even stop for dinner,\'94 he said. He was still very worried and the absinthe warmth had moved up to his head now and he did not trust it there. He said to himself. What did you think could happen that would not have consequences? What woman in the world did you think could be as sound as a good secondhand Buick car? You\'92ve only known two sound women in your life and you lost them both. What will she want after that? And the other part of his brain said, Hail heel. The absinthe certainly brought you out early tonight. So he said, \'93Daughter, for now, let\'92s just try to be good to each other and love each other\'94 (he got the word out though the absinthe made it a difficult word for him to articulate) \'93and as soon as we get out where we are going I will work just as hard and as well as I can.\'94 \'93That\'92s lovely,\'94 she said. \'93And you don\'92t mind my telling you I made up stories?\'94 \'93No,\'94 he lied. \'93They were very nice stories.\'94 Which was true. \'93Can I have another?\'94 she asked. \'93Sure.\'94 He wished now they had never taken it although it was the drink he loved best of almost any in the world. But almost everything bad that had ever happened to him had happened when he was drinking absinthe; those bad things which were his own fault. He could tell that she knew something was wrong and he pulled hard against himself so that there would be nothing wrong. \'93I didn\'92t say something I shouldn\'92t did I?\'94 \'93No, daughter. Here\'92s to you.\'94 \'93Here\'92s to us.\'94 The second one always tastes better than the first because certain taste buds are numbed against the bitterness of the wormwood so that without becoming sweet, or even sweeter, it becomes less bitter and there are parts of the tongue that enjoy it more. \'93It is strange and wonderful. But all it does so far is just bring us to the edge of misunderstanding,\'94 the girl said. \'93I know,\'94 he said. \'93Let\'92s stick together through it.\'94 \'93Was it that you thought I was ambitious?\'94 \'93It\'92s all right about the stories.\'94 \'93No. It\'92s not all right with you. I couldn\'92t love you as much as I do and not know when you\'92re upset.\'94 \'93I\'92m not upset,\'94 he lied. \'93And I\'92m not going to be upset,\'94 he resolved. \'93Let\'92s talk about something else.\'94 \'93It will be wonderful when we\'92re out there and you can work.\'94 She is a little obtuse, he thought. Or maybe does it affect her that way? But he said, \'93It will be. But you won\'92t be bored?\'94 \'93Of course not.\'94 \'93I work awfully hard when I work.\'94 \'93I\'92ll work too.\'94 \'93That will be fun,\'94 he said. \'93Like Mr. and Mrs. Browning. I never saw the play.\'94 \'93Roger, do you have to make fun of it?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know.\'94 Now pull yourself together, he said to himself. Now is the time to pull yourself together. Be good now. \'93I make fun of everything,\'92 he said \'93I think it will be fine. And it\'92s much better for you to be working when \'92m writing.\'94 \'93Will you mind reading mine sometimes?\'94 \'93No. I\'92ll love to.\'94 \'91Really?\'94 \'93No. Of course. I\'92ll be really happy to. Really.\'94 \'91When you drink this it makes you feel as though you could do anything,\'94 the girl said. \'93I\'92m awfully glad